{"title_page": "Joaqu\u00edn \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n", "text_new": "{{for|the former president of El Salvador|Joaqu\u00edn Eufrasio Guzm\u00e1n}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{redirects|El Chapo}}\n{{short description|Mexican drug lord incarcerated in a US federal prison}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Spanish name|Guzm\u00e1n|Loera}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name        = Joaqu\u00edn \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n\n| birth_name  = Joaqu\u00edn Archivaldo Guzm\u00e1n Loera\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1957|4|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = La Tuna, [[Badiraguato Municipality]], [[Sinaloa]], Mexico\n| occupation  = Leader of [[Sinaloa Cartel]]\n| net worth   = U.S. $2\u2013$4 billion (2016 estimate)<ref name='Forbes2017'>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2017/01/25/does-mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-have-the-14-billion-the-u-s-wants-from-him/ Does Mexican Drug Lord El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n Have The $14 Billion The U.S. Wants From Him?] Dolia Estevez, ''Forbes''. 25 January 2017.</ref>\n| height      = {{convert|168|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[Miguel \u00c1ngel F\u00e9lix Gallardo]]\n| successor   = [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda]]\n| spouse      = {{Collapsible list\n | title       = At least 4\n | 1           = Alejandrina Mar\u00eda Salazar Hern\u00e1ndez (1977)\n | 2           = Estela Pe\u00f1a (date unknown)\n | 3           = Griselda L\u00f3pez P\u00e9rez (mid-1980s)\n | 4           = [[Emma Coronel Aispuro]] (2007)\n}}\n| relatives   = {{Collapsible list\n | title       = At least 10\n | 1           = Iv\u00e1n Archivaldo Guzm\u00e1n Salazar\n | 2           = Jes\u00fas Alfredo Guzm\u00e1n Salazar\n | 3           = C\u00e9sar Guzm\u00e1n Salazar\n | 4           = Alejandrina Gisselle Guzm\u00e1n Salazar\n | 5           = \u00c9dgar Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez (\u2020)\n | 6           = Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez\n | 7           = Victor Arael Hernandez Lopez\n | 8           = Griselda Guadalupe Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez\n | 9           = Mar\u00eda Joaquina Guzm\u00e1n Coronel\n | 10          = Emali Guadalupe Guzm\u00e1n\n}}\n| parents         =\n| criminal status = Incarcerated\n| conviction      = Murder, money laundering, drug trafficking, racketeering, organized crime\n| reward_amount   = Mexico: {{US$|3.8 million|link=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-33517118 |title=Mexico offers $3.8m reward in hunt for escaped drug lord |work=BBC News |date=13 July 2015 |accessdate=14 July 2015 }}</ref><br />United States: US$5 million<ref name=rewards>{{cite web| url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/115366.htm| title=Narcotics Rewards Program: Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n-Loera| year=2015| publisher=U.S. Department of State| accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n| capture_status  = 1st capture: 9 June 1993<br />2nd capture: 22 February 2014<br />3rd capture: 8 January 2016\n| wanted_by       = Attorney General of Mexico and the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration\n| escaped         = 1st escape: 19 January 2001<br />2nd escape: 11 July 2015\n| image_name      = Booking photo front GUZMAN JAQUIN% 20A S.jpg\n| image_alt       =\n| image_caption   = Booking photo from January 2017\n| alias           = {{unbulleted list\n| El Chapo (Shorty)\n| El R\u00e1pido (Speedy)}}|\n| charge          =\n| conviction_penalty = Life in prison plus 30 years, must forfeit assets worth more than $12.6 billion.<ref name=\"Hong\">{{Cite news|last=Hong|first=Nicole|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-sentenced-to-life-in-u-s-prison-11563373522|title=El Chapo Sentenced to Life in U.S. Prison|date=July 17, 2019|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| imprisoned = [[ADX Florence]] in [[Florence, Colorado|Florence]], [[Colorado]], US\n}}\n\n'''Joaqu\u00edn Archivaldo Guzm\u00e1n Loera''' ({{IPA-es|xoa\u02c8kin a\u027et\u0283i\u02c8\u03b2aldo \u0263uz\u02c8man lo\u02c8e\u027ea|lang}}; born 4 April 1957),<ref name=\"time-birth-date\">{{cite web |url=http://time.com/3963451/5-facts-el-chapo/ |title=5 Things You Didn't Know About El Chapo |last=Beith |first=Malcolm |website=time.com |date=17 July 2015 |accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref> commonly known as \"'''El Chapo'''\" (\"Shorty\", {{IPA-es|el \u02c8t\u0283apo|pron}}) because of his {{convert|168|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}  stature, is a Mexican drug lord and former leader of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]], an international crime syndicate. He is considered to have been the most powerful drug trafficker in the world.<ref name='Bryan Llenas'>[Manipulation, fear, snitches, and a new cell: Behind the scenes as El Chapo goes to trial]. ''Fox News''. 12 November 2018.</ref><ref name=\"El Universal\">{{cite news|last=Otero|first=Silvia|title=EU: \"El Chapo\" es el narco m\u00e1s poderoso del mundo|url=http://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/192801.html|accessdate=11 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n was born in Sinaloa and raised in a poor farming family. He endured physical abuse at the hands of his father, and also entered the drug trade through his father, helping him grow [[marijuana]] for local dealers during his early adulthood. Guzm\u00e1n began working with [[H\u00e9ctor Luis Palma Salazar]] by the late 1970s, one of the nation's rising drug lords. He helped Salazar map routes to move drugs through Sinaloa and into the United States. He later supervised logistics for [[Miguel \u00c1ngel F\u00e9lix Gallardo]], one of the nation's leading kingpins in the mid 1980s, but Guzm\u00e1n founded his own cartel in 1988 after Gallardo's arrest.\n\nGuzm\u00e1n oversaw operations whereby mass [[cocaine]], [[methamphetamine]], [[marijuana]],<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2014/02/26/where-7-mexican-drug-cartels-are-active-within-the-u-s/ |title=Where 7 Mexican drug cartels are active within the U.S. |work=Washington Post}}</ref> and [[heroin]] were produced, smuggled into, and distributed throughout the United States and Europe, the world's largest users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fusion.net/justice/story/mexican-cartel-presence-threatens-european-security-europol-22555%7ctitle=Justice%7cwork=Fusion|title=Justice|work=Fusion|accessdate=12 July 2015}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/02/25/powerful-sinaloa-cartel-business-unlikely-to-be-slowed-by-arrest-boss-el-chapo/|title=Powerful Sinaloa cartel's business unlikely to be slowed by arrest of boss 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n|work=Fox News|date=20 March 2015}}</ref> He achieved this by pioneering the use of distribution cells and long-range tunnels near borders,<ref name=rewards /> which enabled him to export more drugs to the United States than any other trafficker in history.<ref name=AParrest>{{cite news|last1=Partlow|first1=Joshua|last2=Miroff|first2=Nick|title=World's top drug trafficker arrested in Mexico, U.S. official says|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/worlds-top-drug-trafficker-arrested-in-mexico-us-official-says/2014/02/22/c001927c-9be0-11e3-ad71-e03637a299c0_story.html?wpisrc=al_national&clsrd|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|agency=Associated Press|date=5 July 2005}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n's leadership of the cartel also brought immense wealth and power; ''Forbes'' ranked him as one of the most powerful people in the world between 2009 and 2013,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/joaquin-guzman-loera/|title=Joaquin Guzman Loera|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref> while the Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) estimated that he matched the influence and wealth of [[Pablo Escobar]].<ref name=\"biggest ever\">{{cite news|last=Vardi|first=Nathan|title=Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n Has Become The Biggest Drug Lord Ever|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2011/06/15/joaquin-guzman-has-become-the-biggest-drug-lord-ever|newspaper=Forbes Magazine|date=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n was first captured in 1993 in [[Guatemala]] and was extradited and sentenced to 20 years in prison in Mexico for murder and drug trafficking.<ref name=rewards /><ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> He bribed prison guards and escaped from a federal maximum-security prison in 2001.<ref name=rewards /> His status as a fugitive resulted in an $8.8 million combined reward from Mexico and the U.S. for information leading to his capture,<ref name=rewards /> and he was arrested in Mexico in 2014.<ref name=AParrest /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/02/22/drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-captured-in-mexico-report-says|title=Drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n captured in Mexico| publisher=Fox News| date=1 December 2006| accessdate=24 February 2014}}</ref> He escaped prior to formal sentencing in 2015, through a tunnel under his jail cell.<ref name=bbc-2nd-escape>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-33497301| title=Mexican drug lord Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzman escapes jail|newspaper=BBC News|accessdate=12 July 2015| date=12 July 2015}}</ref> Mexican authorities recaptured him following a shoot-out in 2016<ref>{{cite news| last1=Ahmed| first1=Azam| title=El Chapo, Escaped Drug Lord, Has Been Recaptured, Mexican President Says| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/09/world/americas/El-Chapo-captured-mexico.html| work=The New York Times| accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> and extradited him to the U.S. a year later. In 2019, he was found guilty of a number of criminal charges related to his leadership of the Sinaloa Cartel,<ref name=\"ChapoExtradited\">{{cite web|title=Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzman Being Extradited to the US|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-extradited-us/story?id=44900091|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref> and is currently serving a life sentence at [[ADX Florence]].<ref name=\"SentenceBBC\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-49022208 \"El Chapo sentenced to life in prison.\"] BBC News 17 July 2019.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' begins life term in Colorado 'Supermax' prison|date=21 July 2019|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-mexico-el-chapo/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-begins-life-term-in-colorado-supermax-prison-idUSKCN1UE2GA\n|work=Reuters|access-date=22 July 2019|quote=\"We can confirm that Joaquin Guzman is in the custody of the Federal Bureau of Prisons at United States Penitentiary (USP) Administrative Maximum (ADX) Florence, located in Florence, Colorado,\" the U.S. Bureau of Prisons said in a statement.}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nJoaqu\u00edn Archivaldo Guzm\u00e1n Loera was born into a poor family in the rural community of La Tuna, [[Badiraguato Municipality|Badiraguato, Sinaloa]], Mexico.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=xvii}}{{sfn|Tuckman, Jo|2012|p=22}} He was born on 4 April 1957.{{efn|His date of birth used to be a point of contention prior to 2019, when his lover Lucero Guadalupe S\u00e1nchez L\u00f3pez testified in court and confirmed Guzm\u00e1n's date of birth. In previous years, his alternative date of birth was 25 December 1954.<ref>{{cite web|title=Narcotics Rewards Program: Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n-Loera| url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/115366.htm|publisher=[[Bureau for International Narcotics and Law Enforcement Affairs]] at the [[United States Department of State]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/17/nyregion/el-chapo-trial.html|title=How El Chapo Escaped in a Sewer, Naked With His Mistress|last=Feuer|first=Alan|date=2019-01-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Stephey |first=M.J. |title=Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n Loera: Billionaire Drug Lord |url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1884982,00.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=TIME magazine |date=13 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118080518/http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0%2C8599%2C1884982%2C00.html |archivedate=18 January 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> His parents were Emilio Guzm\u00e1n Bustillos and Mar\u00eda Consuelo Loera P\u00e9rez.<ref>{{cite news| title=Libre, cumple el 'Chapo' 56 a\u00f1os de edad| url=http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/libre-cumple-el-chapo-56-anos-de-edad| accessdate=22 February 2014| newspaper=[[R\u00edodoce]]| date=4 April 2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808184455/http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/libre-cumple-el-chapo-56-anos-de-edad| archivedate=8 August 2013| url-status=dead| language=Spanish| df=dmy-all}}</ref> His paternal grandparents were Juan Guzm\u00e1n and Otilia Bustillos, and his maternal grandparents were Ovidio Loera Cobret and Pomposa P\u00e9rez Uriarte. For many generations, his family lived at La Tuna.{{sfn|Hern\u00e1ndez, Anabel|2012|p=57}} His father was officially a cattle rancher, as were most in the area where he grew up; according to some sources, however, he might also have been a ''gomero'', an [[opium poppy]] farmer.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=50-54}} He has two younger sisters named Armida and Bernarda and four younger brothers named Miguel \u00c1ngel, Aureliano, Arturo, and Emilio. He had three unnamed older brothers who reportedly died of natural causes when he was very young.{{sfn|Hern\u00e1ndez, Anabel|2012|p=57}}\n\nFew details are known of Guzm\u00e1n's upbringing. As a child, he sold oranges and dropped out of school in third grade to work with his father.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\">{{cite news|last=De Cordoba|first=Jose|title=The Drug Lord Who Got Away|url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB124484177023110993| accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=13 June 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109201342/http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB124484177023110993| archivedate=9 November 2013| url-status=live}}</ref> He was known for being a practical joker and enjoyed playing pranks on his friends and family when he was young.<ref>Vorobyov, Niko (2019) ''Dopeworld.'' Hodder, UK. p. 228</ref> He was regularly beaten, and he sometimes fled to his maternal grandmother's house to escape such treatment. However, he stood up to his father to protect his younger siblings from being beaten.<ref name=univisionpg1>{{cite news|last=Reyes|first=Gerardo|title=The Eternal Fugitive: El Chapo Territory|url=http://www.univision.com/la-huella-digital/openpage/2013-11-08/el-chapo-special-ch-1-eng#viewVideo|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=Univision|year=2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123015236/http://www.univision.com/la-huella-digital/openpage/2013-11-08/el-chapo-special-ch-1-eng|archivedate=23 January 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=51}} It is possible that Guzm\u00e1n incurred his father's wrath for trying to stop him from beating them. His mother, however, was his \"foundation of emotional support\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Who Is El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n, Mexico's Most Elusive Drug Lord?|url=http://fusion.net/justice/story/univision-investigation-hunt-el-chapo-guzman-mexicos-elusive-181574|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=Fusion|year=2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202082511/https://fusion.net/justice/story/univision-investigation-hunt-el-chapo-guzman-mexicos-elusive-181574|archivedate=2 February 2014 |url-status=live |agency=Univision}}</ref> The nearest school to his home was about 60 miles (100&nbsp;km) away, and he was taught by traveling teachers during his early years. The teachers stayed for a few months before moving to other areas.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=51}} With few opportunities for employment in his hometown, he turned to the cultivation of opium poppy, a common practice among local residents.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=xvii-xx}} During harvest season, Guzm\u00e1n and his brothers hiked the hills of Badiraguato to cut the bud of the poppy. Once the plant was stacked in kilos, his father sold the harvest to other suppliers in [[Culiac\u00e1n]] and [[Guam\u00fachil]].{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=54-55}} He sold marijuana at commercial centers near the area while accompanied by Guzm\u00e1n. His father spent most of the profits on liquor and women and often returned home with no money. Tired of his mismanagement, Guzm\u00e1n cultivated his own marijuana plantation at age 15 with cousins [[Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva|Arturo]], [[Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva|Alfredo]], [[Carlos Beltr\u00e1n Leyva|Carlos]], and [[H\u00e9ctor Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]], and he supported his family with his marijuana production.<ref name=univisionpg1 /> \n\nWhen he was a teenager, however, his father kicked him out of the house, and he went to live with his grandfather.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=53}} It was during his adolescence that Guzm\u00e1n gained the nickname \"El Chapo\", Mexican slang for \"shorty\", for his {{convert|1.68|m}} stature and stocky physique.<ref>{{cite news| last=Hootsen|first=Jan-Albert| title=Drug war continues: 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n not dead after all| url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/americas/mexico/130226/drug-war-continues-joaquin-chapo-guzman-not-dead |accessdate=22 February 2014| newspaper=GlobalPost| date=26 February 2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220144411/http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/americas/mexico/130226/drug-war-continues-joaquin-chapo-guzman-not-dead |archivedate=20 February 2014 | url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Allen| first=Nick| title='Net closing' on Mexican drug lord Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/9141375/Net-closing-on-Mexican-drug-lord-Joaquin-El-Chapo-Guzman.html |accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314194220/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/9141375/Net-closing-on-Mexican-drug-lord-Joaquin-El-Chapo-Guzman.html |archivedate=14 March 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Most people in Badiraguato worked in the poppy fields of the [[Sierra Madre Occidental]] for most of their lives, but Guzm\u00e1n left his hometown in search of greater opportunities through his uncle [[Pedro Avil\u00e9s P\u00e9rez]], one of the pioneers of Mexican drug trafficking. He left Badiraguato in his 20s and joined organized crime.{{sfn|Longmire, Sylvia|2011|p=13-1}}\n\n== Early career ==\n[[File:Esparragoza-Moreno.jpeg|thumb|upright|Juan Jos\u00e9 Esparragoza Moreno]]\nDuring the 1980s, the leading crime syndicate in Mexico was the [[Guadalajara Cartel]],{{sfn|Edmonds-Poli|Shirk|2009|p=262}} which was headed by [[Miguel \u00c1ngel F\u00e9lix Gallardo]] (alias \"El Padrino\" or \"The Godfather\"), [[Rafael Caro Quintero]], [[Ernesto Fonseca Carrillo]] (alias \"Don Neto\"), [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Esparragoza Moreno]] (alias ''El Azul'', \"The Blue One\") and others.{{sfn|Edmonds-Poli|Shirk|2009|p=354}} In the 1970s, Guzm\u00e1n first worked for the drug lord [[H\u00e9ctor Luis Palma Salazar|H\u00e9ctor \"El G\u00fcero\" Palma]] by transporting drugs and overseeing their shipments from the Sierra Madre region to urban areas near the [[U.S.\u2013Mexico border]] by aircraft. Since his initial steps in organized crime, Guzm\u00e1n was ambitious and regularly pressed on his superiors to allow him to increase the share of narcotics that were smuggled across the border. He also favored a violent and serious approach when doing business; if any of his drug shipments were not on time, Guzm\u00e1n would simply kill the smuggler himself by shooting him in the head. Those around him learned that cheating him or going with other competitors\u2014even if they offered better prices\u2014was unwise. The leaders of the Guadalajara Cartel liked Guzm\u00e1n's business acumen, and in the early 1980s introduced him to F\u00e9lix Gallardo, one of the major drug lords in Mexico at that time.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=63\u201364}} Guzm\u00e1n worked as a chauffeur for F\u00e9lix Gallardo before he put him in charge of logistics,<ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo, de chofer a \"Se\u00f1or de la Monta\u00f1a\" |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/el-chapo-de-chofer-a-senior-de-la-montania-989885.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223190613/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/el-chapo-de-chofer-a-senior-de-la-montania-989885.html |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> where Guzm\u00e1n coordinated drug shipments from Colombia to Mexico by land, air, and sea. Palma ensured the deliveries arrived in the United States. Guzm\u00e1n earned enough standing and began working for F\u00e9lix Gallardo directly.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=63\u201364}}\n\nThroughout most of the late 1970s and early 1980s, the Mexican drug traffickers were also middlemen for the Colombian trafficking groups, and transported [[cocaine]] through the U.S.-Mexico border. Mexico, however, remained a secondary route for the Colombians, given that most of the drugs trafficked by their cartels were smuggled through the Caribbean and the Florida corridor.<ref name=startfor80s />{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=62-64}} F\u00e9lix Gallardo was the leading drug baron in Mexico and friend of [[Juan Matta-Ballesteros|Juan Ram\u00f3n Matta-Ballesteros]], but his operations were still limited by his counterparts in South America. In the mid-1980s, however, the U.S. government increased law enforcement surveillance and put pressure on the [[Medell\u00edn Cartel|Medell\u00edn]] and [[Cali Cartel]]s by effectively reducing the drug trafficking operations in the Caribbean corridor. Realizing it was more profitable to hand over the operations to their Mexican counterparts, the Colombian cartels gave F\u00e9lix Gallardo more control over their drug shipments.{{sfn|Bagley, Bruce|2012|p=6}}{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=66-68}} This power shift gave the Mexican organized crime groups more leverage over their Central American and South American counterparts.<ref name=startfor80s>{{cite web|title=Mexico's Cartels and the Economics of Cocaine |url=http://www.stratfor.com/weekly/mexicos-cartels-and-economics-cocaine |publisher=[[Stratfor]] |accessdate=23 February 2014 |date=3 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301031228/http://www.stratfor.com/weekly/mexicos-cartels-and-economics-cocaine |archivedate= 1 March 2013 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> During the 1980s, however, the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA) was conducting undercover groundwork in Mexico, where several of its agents worked as informants.\n\nOne DEA agent, [[Kiki Camarena|Enrique Camarena Salazar]], was working as an informant and grew close to many top drug barons, including F\u00e9lix Gallardo.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=69-70}} In November 1984, the Mexican military\u2014acting on the intelligence information provided by Camarena\u2014raided a large marijuana plantation owned by the Guadalajara Cartel and known as \"Rancho B\u00fafalo\".<ref name=nexos>{{cite news |last=Aguilar Cam\u00edn |first=H\u00e9ctor |title=Narco Historias extraordinarias |url=http://www.nexos.com.mx/?P=leerarticulo&Article=73 |accessdate=9 August 2013 |newspaper=Nexos |date=May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022053239/http://www.nexos.com.mx/?P=leerarticulo&Article=73 |archivedate=22 October 2013 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Angered by the suspected betrayal, F\u00e9lix Gallardo and his men exacted revenge when they kidnapped, tortured, and killed Camarena in February 1985.{{sfn|Cockburn, Alexander|1998|p=348}} The death of Camarena outraged Washington, and Mexico responded by carrying out a massive manhunt to arrest those involved in the incident.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vulliamy|first=Ed|title=Joaqu\u00edn \"Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n: the Mexican drug lord adept at playing the system|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/feb/22/joaquin-guzman-mexican-drug-lord|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 February 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223013033/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/feb/22/joaquin-guzman-mexican-drug-lord|archivedate=23 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n took advantage of the internal crisis to gain ground within the cartel and take over more drug trafficking operations.<ref name=univisionpg1 /> In 1989, F\u00e9lix Gallardo was arrested; while in prison and through a number of envoys, the drug lord called for a summit in [[Acapulco]], [[Guerrero]]. In the conclave, Guzm\u00e1n and others discussed the future of Mexico's drug trafficking and agreed to divide the territories previously owned by the Guadalajara Cartel.{{sfn|Grillo, Ioan|2012|p=78}} The Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers formed the [[Tijuana Cartel]], which controlled the [[Tijuana]] corridor and parts of [[Baja California]]; in [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] state, a group controlled by Carrillo Fuentes family formed the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]]; and the remaining faction left to Sinaloa and the Pacific Coast and formed the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] under the traffickers [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda|Ismael \"El Mayo\" Zambada]], Palma, and Guzm\u00e1n.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=72-73}}{{sfn|Edmonds-Poli|Shirk|2009|p=262}} Guzm\u00e1n was specifically in charge of the drug corridors of [[Tecate, Baja California]],{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=72-73}} and [[Mexicali]] and [[San Luis R\u00edo Colorado]], two border crossings that connect the states of [[Sonora]] and Baja California with the U.S. states of Arizona and California.{{sfn|Grayson, George W.|2011|p=56}}\n\nWhen F\u00e9lix Gallardo was arrested, Guzm\u00e1n reportedly lived in [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]] for some time. One of his other centers of operation, however, was in the border city of [[Agua Prieta]], [[Sonora]], where he coordinated drug trafficking activities more closely. Guzm\u00e1n had dozens of properties in various parts of the country. People he trusted purchased the properties for him and registered them under false names. Most of them were located in residential neighborhoods and served as stash houses for drugs, weapons, and cash. Guzm\u00e1n also owned several ranches across Mexico, but most of them were located in the states of Sinaloa, Durango, Chihuahua, and Sonora, where locals working for the drug lord grew opium and marijuana.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=83\u201384}} The first time Guzm\u00e1n was detected by U.S. authorities for his involvement in organized crime was in 1987, when several protected witnesses testified in a U.S. court that Guzm\u00e1n was in fact heading the Sinaloa Cartel. An indictment issued in the state of Arizona alleged that Guzm\u00e1n had coordinated the shipment of {{convert|2000|kg|abbr=on}} of marijuana and about {{convert|4700|kg|abbr=on}} of cocaine from 19 October 1987 to 18 May 1990, and had received roughly US$1.5 million in drug proceeds that were shipped back to his home state. Another indictment alleged that Guzm\u00e1n earned US$100,000 for trafficking 70,000&nbsp;lb (roughly 31,750&nbsp;kg) of cocaine and an unspecified amount of marijuana in a period of three years.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=93\u201394}} In the border areas between Tecate and San Luis R\u00edo Colorado, Guzm\u00e1n ordered his men to traffic most of the drugs overland, but also through a few aircraft. By using the so-called piecemeal strategy, in which traffickers kept drug quantities relatively low, risks were reduced. Guzm\u00e1n also pioneered the use of sophisticated tunnels to move drugs across the border and into the United States.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=70\u201373}} Aside from pioneering the tunnels, Palma and Guzm\u00e1n packed cocaine into chili pepper cans under the brand \"La Comadre\" before they were shipped to the U.S. by train.<ref>{{Citation | author = Sebastian Rotella | title = Food Company Owners Charged in Drug Tunnel Case : Smuggling: Indictment names executives of Reynoso Bros. in unfinished underground passage linking San Diego and Tijuana | newspaper = Los Angeles Times | page =   |  date = 29 September 1995 | url =https://articles.latimes.com/1995-09-29/local/me-51176_1_san-diego/2| accessdate = 11 January 2016}}</ref> In return, the drug lords were paid through large suitcases filled with millions of dollars in cash. These suitcases were flown from the U.S. to Mexico City, where corrupt customs agents at the airport made sure the deliveries were not inspected. Large sums of that money were reportedly used as bribes for members of the Attorney General's Office.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" />\n\n== Tijuana Cartel conflict: 1989\u20131993 ==\nWhen F\u00e9lix Gallardo was arrested, the Tijuana corridor was handed over to the Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers, Jes\u00fas Labra \u00c1viles (''alias'' \"El Chuy\"), and Javier Caro Pay\u00e1n (''alias'' \"El Doctor\"), cousin of the former Guadalajara Cartel leader Rafael Caro Quintero. In fears of a coup, however, Caro Pay\u00e1n fled to Canada and was later arrested. Guzm\u00e1n and the rest of the Sinaloa Cartel leaders consequently grew angry at the Arellano F\u00e9lix clan about this.{{sfn|Grayson, George W.|2011|p=81}} In 1989, Guzm\u00e1n sent Armando L\u00f3pez (alias \"El Rayo\"), one of his most trusted men, to speak with the Arellano F\u00e9lix clan in Tijuana. Before he had a chance to speak face-to-face with them, L\u00f3pez was killed by [[Ram\u00f3n Arellano F\u00e9lix]]. The corpse was disposed of in the outskirts of the city and the Tijuana Cartel ordered a hit on the remaining members of the L\u00f3pez family to prevent future reprisals.<ref name=elrayo /><ref name=elrayo2 /> That same year, the Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers sent the Venezuelan drug trafficker Enrique Rafael Clavel Moreno to infiltrate Palma's family and seduce his wife Guadalupe Leija Serrano.{{sfn|Richards, James R.|1998|p=23}} After convincing her to withdraw US$7 million from one of Palma's bank accounts in [[San Diego]], [[California]], Clavel beheaded her and sent her head to Palma in a box.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rotella |first=Sebastian |title=Fierce Mexican Drug Wars Drench Country In Blood And Corruption |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950702&slug=2129319 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2 July 1995 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226012256/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950702&slug=2129319 |archivedate=26 February 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was known as the first beheading linked to the drug trade in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moreno|first=Mart\u00edn|title=Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera, \"El Chapo\": Venganza, detonante de la batalla|url=http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/joaquin-guzman-loera-el-chapo-venganza-detonante-de-la-batalla|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=Z\u00f3calo Saltillo|date=18 June 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505082906/http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/joaquin-guzman-loera-el-chapo-venganza-detonante-de-la-batalla|archivedate=5 May 2010 |url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> Two weeks later, Clavel killed Palma's children, H\u00e9ctor (aged 5) and Nataly (aged 4), by throwing them off a bridge in [[Venezuela]]. Palma retaliated by sending his men to kill Clavel while he was in prison.<ref>{{subscription required}} {{cite news|last=Reynoso|first=Raymundo|title=Guerra de narcos mexicanos se hace tambien a esta parte|newspaper=[[La Opini\u00f3n]]|date=12 June 1993|agency=[[ImpreMedia]]|location=Los Angeles, California|language=Spanish|id={{ProQuest|368275091}}}}</ref> In 1991, Ram\u00f3n killed another Sinaloa Cartel associate, Rigoberto Campos Salcido (''alias'' \"El Rigo\"), and prompted bigger conflicts with Guzm\u00e1n.<ref name=elrayo>{{cite news|title=Todo empez\u00f3 en Tijuana|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/2013/01/08/nacional/878467|accessdate=19 October 2013|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=8 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211120741/http://www.excelsior.com.mx/2013/01/08/nacional/878467|archivedate=11 February 2013 |url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=elrayo2>{{cite news|title=La pugna entre el c\u00e1rtel de Sinaloa|url=http://www.zetatijuana.com/html/Edicion1922/Principal.html|accessdate=19 October 2013|newspaper=[[Zeta (magazine)|Zeta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020063705/http://www.zetatijuana.com/html/Edicion1922/Principal.html|archivedate=20 October 2012 |url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> In early 1992, a Tijuana Cartel-affiliated and San Diego-based gang known as Calle Treinta kidnapped six of Guzm\u00e1n's men in Tijuana, tortured them to obtain information, and then shot them in the back of their heads. Their bodies were dumped on the outskirts of the city. Shortly after the attack, a car bomb exploded outside one of Guzm\u00e1n's properties in Culiac\u00e1n. No injuries were reported, but the drug lord became fully aware of the intended message.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=97-99}}\n\nGuzm\u00e1n and Palma struck back against the Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers (Tijuana Cartel) with nine killings on 3 September 1992 in [[Iguala]];<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Andrade Jard\u00ed |first=Juli\u00e1n |title=Tormentas sobre Ju\u00e1rez |url=https://www.nexos.com.mx/?P=leerarticulo&Article=2099639 |accessdate=19 October 2013 |newspaper=Nexos |date=1 March 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020021737/https://www.nexos.com.mx/?P=leerarticulo&Article=2099639 |archivedate=20 October 2013 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref> among the dead were lawyers and family members of F\u00e9lix Gallardo, who was also believed to have orchestrated the attack against Palma's family.<ref>{{subscription required}} {{cite news |title=F\u00e9lix Gallardo se la deb\u00eda: mat\u00f3 a su mujer y dos hijos |url=http://hemeroteca.proceso.com.mx/?page_id=278958&a51dc26366d99bb5fa29cea4747565fec=160107&rl=wh |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]] |date=12 September 1992 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228014902/http://hemeroteca.proceso.com.mx/?page_id=278958&a51dc26366d99bb5fa29cea4747565fec=160107&rl=wh |archivedate=28 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Mexico's Attorney General formed a special unit to look into the killings, but the investigation was called off after the unit found that Guzm\u00e1n had paid off some of the top police officials in Mexico with $10 million, according to police reports and confessions of former police officers.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> In November 1992, gunmen of Arellano F\u00e9lix attempted to kill Guzm\u00e1n as he was traveling in a vehicle through the streets of Guadalajara. Ram\u00f3n and at least four of his henchmen shot at the moving vehicle with [[AK-47]] rifles, but the drug lord managed to escape unharmed. The attack forced Guzm\u00e1n to leave Guadalajara and live under a false name under fears of future attacks.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /><ref name=univisionpg1 /> He and Palma, however, responded to the assassination attempt in a similar fashion; several days later, on 8 November 1992, a large number of Sinaloa Cartel men posing as policemen stormed the Christine discoth\u00e8que in [[Puerto Vallarta]], spotted Ram\u00f3n and [[Francisco Javier Arellano F\u00e9lix]], and opened fire at them. The shooting lasted for at least eight minutes, and more than 1,000 rounds were fired by both Guzm\u00e1n's and Arellano F\u00e9lix's gunmen.<ref>{{cite news| last=Pliego| first=Roberto| title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n: Una vida breve| url=http://www.nexos.com.mx/?p=9921|accessdate=23 February 2014| newspaper=Nexos| date=1 March 2001| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223223140/http://www.nexos.com.mx/?p=9921| archivedate=23 February 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> Six people were killed in the shootout, but the Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers were in the restroom when the raid started and reportedly escaped through an air-conditioning duct before leaving the scene in one of their vehicles.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=98-99}}<ref>{{cite web| last=Goodman| first=Michael| title=Muerto, Inc.| url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/readings/muerto.html| publisher=[[PBS]], by [[Los Angeles (magazine)|PBS]], by [[Los Angeles]]| accessdate=23 February 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604143751/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/readings/muerto.html| archivedate=4 June 2009| year=1997}}</ref> On 9 and 10 December 1992, four alleged associates of F\u00e9lix Gallardo were killed. The antagonism between Guzm\u00e1n's Sinaloa Cartel and the Arellano F\u00e9lix clan left several more dead and was accompanied by more violent events in the states of Baja California, Sonora, Sinaloa, Durango, Jalisco, Guerrero, Michoac\u00e1n and Oaxaca.<ref>{{cite news| last=Lira Saade| first=Carmen| title=Buscar\u00e1 la DEA extradici\u00f3n de Arellano F\u00e9lix| url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2002/03/10/004n1pol.php?origen=politica.html| accessdate=19 October 2013 |newspaper=[[La Jornada]]| date=10 March 2002| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311092439/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2002/03/10/004n1pol.php?origen=politica.html| archivedate=11 March 2008| url-status=live| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe war between both groups continued for six more months, yet none of their respective leaders was killed. In mid-1993, the Arellano F\u00e9lix clan sent their top gunmen on a final mission to kill Guzm\u00e1n in Guadalajara, where he moved around frequently to avoid any possible attacks. Having no success, the Tijuana Cartel hitmen decided to return to Baja California on 24 May 1993. As Francisco Javier was at the [[Guadalajara International Airport]] booking his flight to Tijuana, informant tips notified him that Guzm\u00e1n was at the airport parking lot awaiting a flight to Puerto Vallarta.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=99-100}} Having spotted the white Mercury Grand Marquis car where Guzm\u00e1n was thought to be hiding, about 20 gunmen of the Tijuana Cartel descended from their vehicles and opened fire at around 4:10&nbsp;p.m. However, the drug lord was inside a green Buick sedan a short distance from the target. Inside the Mercury Grand Marquis was the cardinal and archbishop of Guadalajara [[Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo]], who died at the scene from fourteen gunshot wounds.<ref name=criminalactnyt>{{cite news| last=Golden| first=Tim| title=Cardinal in Mexico Killed in a Shooting Tied to Drug Battle| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/25/world/cardinal-in-mexico-killed-in-a-shooting-tied-to-drug-battle.html| accessdate=23 February 2014| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| date=25 May 1993| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625111428/http://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/25/world/cardinal-in-mexico-killed-in-a-shooting-tied-to-drug-battle.html| archivedate=25 June 2012}}</ref> Six other people, including the cardinal's chauffeur, were caught in the crossfire and killed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller |first=Marjorie |title=Mexico Cardinal Slain; Caught in Gun Battle: Violence: 6 others are killed at Guadalajara airport. Rival narcotics traffickers are believed responsible |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-25/news/mn-39567_1_gun-battle |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=25 May 1993 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223225319/http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-25/news/mn-39567_1_gun-battle |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Divany B\u00e1rcenas |first=Javier |title=Principales ejecuciones y atentados de los Arellano F\u00e9lix |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/53814.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]] |date=9 March 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219061517/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/53814.html |archivedate=19 February 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Amidst the shootout and confusion, Guzm\u00e1n escaped and headed to one of his safe houses in Bugambilias, a neighborhood 20 minutes away from the airport.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=99-100}}<ref name=univisionpg2>{{cite news| last=Ocando| first=Casto| title=The Eternal Fugitive: Leap to Fame |url=http://www.univision.com/la-huella-digital/openpage/2013-11-08/el-chapo-special-ch-2-eng| accessdate=23 February 2014| newspaper=[[Univision]]| year=2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123015240/http://www.univision.com/la-huella-digital/openpage/2013-11-08/el-chapo-special-ch-2-eng| archivedate=23 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Flight and arrest ===\nThe night the cardinal was killed, Mexican President [[Carlos Salinas de Gortari]] flew to Guadalajara and condemned the attack, stating it was \"a criminal act\" that targeted innocent civilians, but he did not give any indications of the involvement of organized crime.<ref name=criminalactnyt /> The death of Cardinal Posadas Ocampo, a high-profile religious figure, outraged the Mexican public, the Catholic Church, and many politicians. The government responded by carrying out a massive manhunt to arrest the people involved in the shootout, and offered about US$5 million bounties for each of them.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=100\u2013101}} Pictures of Guzm\u00e1n's face, previously unknown to the public, started to appear in newspapers and television across Mexico. Fearing his capture, Guzm\u00e1n fled to [[Tonal\u00e1, Jalisco]], where he reportedly owned a ranch. The drug lord then fled to [[Mexico City]] and stayed at a hotel for about ten days.<ref name=univisionpg2 /> He met with one of his associates in an unknown location and handed him US$200 million to provide for his family in case of his absence. He gave that same amount to another of his employees to make sure the Sinaloa Cartel ran its day-to-day activities smoothly in case he was gone for some time.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=100\u2013101}}\n\nAfter obtaining a passport with the fake name of Jorge Ramos P\u00e9rez, Guzm\u00e1n was transported to the southern state of [[Chiapas]] by one of his trusted associates before leaving the country and settling in [[Guatemala]] on 4 June 1993.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=100\u2013101}}  His plan was to move across Guatemala with his girlfriend Mar\u00eda del Roc\u00edo del Villar Becerra and several of his bodyguards and settle in [[El Salvador]].<ref name=univisionpg2 /> During his travel, Mexican and Guatemalan authorities were tracking his movements. Guzm\u00e1n paid a Guatemalan military official US$1.2 million to allow him to hide south of the Mexican border. The unnamed official, however, passed information about Guzm\u00e1n's whereabouts to law enforcement.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=101\u2013102}}<ref>{{cite news|title=En 1993 dirig\u00ed captura de El Chapo: Otto P\u00e9rez |url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2013/11/06/politica/020n2pol |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[La Jornada]] |date=6 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226012854/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2013/11/06/politica/020n2pol |archivedate=26 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> On 9 June 1993, Guzm\u00e1n was arrested by the [[Guatemalan Army]] at a hotel near [[Tapachula]], close to the [[Guatemala\u2013Mexico border]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Darling |first=Juanita |title=Mexico Arrests Reputed Top Drug Kingpin: Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n is believed to have been the target of the attack that killed cardinal. He is captured in Guatemala |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1993-06-11/news/mn-2027_1_top-drug-trafficker |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=11 June 1993 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226013039/http://articles.latimes.com/1993-06-11/news/mn-2027_1_top-drug-trafficker |archivedate=26 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A 'El Chapo' no lo agarran porque no quieren: Carrillo Olea |url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/aelchaponoloagarranporquenoquierencarrilloolea-1792446.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]] |date=22 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140206011457/http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/aelchaponoloagarranporquenoquierencarrilloolea-1792446.html |archivedate=6 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> He was extradited to Mexico two days later aboard a military airplane,<ref name=univisionpg2 /><ref>{{cite news |title=Chocan versiones sobre El Chapo| url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/905272.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]]| date=22 February 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225083534/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/905272.html |archivedate=25 February 2013 |url-status=live| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n, a 20 a\u00f1os de su captura en Guatemala |url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/seguridad/el-chapo-guzman-a-20-anos-de-su-captura-en-guatemala,6a08c0021023f310VgnVCM10000098cceb0aRCRD.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Terra Networks]] |year=2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615010258/http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/seguridad/el-chapo-guzman-a-20-anos-de-su-captura-en-guatemala%2C6a08c0021023f310VgnVCM10000098cceb0aRCRD.html |archivedate=15 June 2013 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> where he was immediately taken to the [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1]] (often referred to simply as \"La Palma\" or \"Altiplano\"), a maximum-security prison in [[Almoloya de Ju\u00e1rez]], [[State of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news| title=En la mira, recaptura de 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/325667.en-la-mira-recaptura-de-el-chapo-guzman.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n]]| date=19 January 2008| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621082949/http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/325667.en-la-mira-recaptura-de-el-chapo-guzman.html| archivedate=21 June 2009| url-status=live| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==== First arrest: 1993 ====\nGuzm\u00e1n was captured for the first time in [[Guatemala]] on 9 June 1993,<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> [[extradition|extradited]] to Mexico and sentenced to 20 years, nine months in prison on charges of drug trafficking, criminal association and bribery. He was jailed at Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1. On 22 November 1995, he was transferred to another maximum security prison, Federal Center for Social Rehabilitation No. 2 (also known as \"Puente Grande\") in [[Jalisco]], after being convicted of three crimes: possession of firearms, drug trafficking and the murder of Cardinal [[Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo]] (the charge would later be dismissed by another judge). He had been tried and sentenced inside the federal prison on the outskirts of [[Almoloya de Ju\u00e1rez]], Mexico State.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" />\n\nWhile he was in prison, Guzm\u00e1n's drug empire and cartel continued to operate unabated, run by his brother, Arturo Guzm\u00e1n Loera, known as ''El Pollo'', with Guzm\u00e1n himself still considered a major international drug trafficker by Mexico and the U.S. even while he was behind bars.<ref name=\"PBS cartels\" /> Associates brought him suitcases of cash to bribe prison workers and allow the drug lord to maintain his opulent lifestyle even in prison, with prison guards acting like his servants.<ref name=insight>{{cite news|title=El Chapo|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/personalities-mexico/joaquin-guzman-loera-el-chapo|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=Insight Crime}}</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\">{{cite news|title='El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n, Mexico's Most Powerful Drug Lord|url=http://www.newsweek.com/el-chapo-guzman-mexicos-most-powerful-drug-lord-64321|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> He met his longtime mistress and later Sinaloa associate, former police officer Zulema Hern\u00e1ndez, while in prison, where she was serving time for armed robbery.<ref name=LATwomen>{{cite news|last=Wilkinson|first=Tracy|title=Women play a bigger role in Mexico's drug war|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/10/world/fg-narco-women10|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=10 November 2009}}</ref> Hern\u00e1ndez later controlled Sinaloa's expansion into Mexico City, but in 2008 her body was found in a trunk, carved with multiple Zs, signifying [[Los Zetas]], Sinaloa's archrivals.<ref name=LATwomen />\n\n== Drug empire ==\n\n[[File:Mexico cartel map May 2010.svg|thumb|Map of Mexican drug cartels presence in Mexico based on a May 2010 [[Stratfor]] report\n{{legend|yellow|[[Sinaloa Cartel]]}}]]\nGuzm\u00e1n's [[Sinaloa Cartel]], at the time of his arrest, was the wealthiest and most powerful of Mexico's drug cartels. It smuggles multi-ton [[cocaine]] shipments from [[Colombia]] through Mexico to the United States by air, sea and road, and has distribution cells throughout the U.S.<ref name=rewards /><ref name=AParrest /> The organization has also been involved in the production, smuggling and distribution of Mexican [[methamphetamine]], [[marijuana]], and [[heroin]] from Southeast Asia.<ref name=\"PBS cartels\">{{cite news|title=Drug Cartels|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/etc/guzman.html|accessdate=22 February 2014|publisher=[[PBS]]}}</ref>\n\nWhen Palma was arrested by the Mexican Army on 23 June 1995, Guzm\u00e1n took leadership of the cartel.<ref name=\"Organized\">{{cite book|last=Bailey|first=John J.|author2=Roy Godson|title=Organized Crime and Democratic Governability: Mexico and the U.S.-Mexican Borderlands|publisher=Univ of Pittsburgh Press|year=2000|page=146|isbn=978-0-8229-5758-4|author2-link=Roy Godson}}</ref><ref name=\"Bordering\">{{cite book|last=Oppenheimer|first=Andres|title=Bordering on Chaos: Guerrillas, Stockbrokers, Politicians, and Mexico's Road to Prosperity|publisher=Little Brown & Co|year=1996|pages=202, 298, 300|isbn=978-0-316-65095-3}}</ref> Palma was later extradited to the United States, where he is in prison on charges of drug trafficking and conspiracy.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" />\n\nAfter Guzm\u00e1n's prison escape nearly a decade after his initial arrest, he and close associate [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda]] became Mexico's undisputed top drug kingpins after the 2003 arrest of their rival [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas]] of the [[Gulf Cartel]]. Until Guzm\u00e1n's arrest in 2014, he was considered the \"most powerful drug trafficker in the world\" by the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Department of the Treasury]].<ref name=\"El Universal\" /><ref name=\"Milenio\">{{cite news| title=Califica EU a \"El Chapo\" como el narco m\u00e1s poderoso del mundo| url=http://www.percepcion.com.mx/noticia/15541/eu-califica-a-el-chapo-guzman-como-el-narco-mas-poderoso-del-mundo| accessdate=15 January 2016| newspaper=Percepcion| date=10 January 2012}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n also had another close associate, his trusted friend [[Ignacio Coronel Villarreal|Ignacio \"Nacho\" Coronel Villarreal]].<ref name=\"Stratfor11/11/2008\"> {{cite news|url=http://www.stratfor.com/analysis/20081209_mexican_drug_cartels_government_progress_and_growing_violence|title=Mexican Drug Cartels: Government Progress and Growing Violence|date=11 December 2008|work=STRATFOR Global Intelligence|accessdate=25 August 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120013002/http://www.stratfor.com/analysis/20081209_mexican_drug_cartels_government_progress_and_growing_violence|archivedate=20 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Puro\">{{cite book|last=Crosthwaite|first=Luis Humberto|title=Puro Border: Dispatches, Snapshots & Graffiti from La Frontera|publisher=Cinco Puntos Press|page=115|isbn=978-0-938317-59-3|year=2002}}</ref>\n\nHis drug empire made Guzm\u00e1n a billionaire, and he was ranked the 10th richest man in Mexico and 1,140th in the world in 2011, with a net worth of roughly [[United States Dollar|US$]]1 billion.<ref name=\"forbes billionaire\">{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2010/10/billionaires-2010_Joaquin-Guzman-Loera_FS0Y.html| title=The World's Billionaires: 937 Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n Loera| accessdate=21 September 2010| date=10 March 2010|work=Forbes Magazine}}</ref> To assist his drug trafficking, the Sinaloa Cartel also built a shipping and transport empire.<ref name=AParrest /> Guzm\u00e1n has been referred to as the \"biggest drug lord of all time\",<ref name=\"cnn capture\">{{cite news|title=Major Mexican drug lord captured|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/09/19/world/americas/mexico-drug-lord/index.html|newspaper=CNN News|date=19 September 2011}}</ref> and the U.S. DEA considered him \"the godfather of the drug world\" and strongly estimates he surpassed the influence and reach of [[Pablo Escobar]]. In 2013, the Chicago Crime Commission named Guzm\u00e1n \"Public Enemy Number One\" for the influence of his criminal network in [[Chicago]] (however, there is no evidence Guzm\u00e1n has ever visited the city). The last person to receive such notoriety was [[Al Capone]] in 1930.\n\nAt the time of his 2014 arrest, Guzm\u00e1n imported more drugs into the United States than anyone else.<ref name=AParrest /> He took advantage of the power vacuum created by crackdowns on cartels in Colombia, gaining business and market share there as Colombia's own cartels were decimated.<ref name=\"market share\">{{cite news|last=Althaus|first=Dudley|title=Report: 'Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Grabs More Market Share in Colombia |url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-analysis/report-chapo-guzman-grabs-more-market-share-in-colombia|accessdate=22 February 2014|publisher=[[InSight Crime]]|agency=}}</ref> He took similar advantage of the situation when his rival cartels were brought down by an intense crackdown from the Mexican government, but the Sinaloa gang emerged largely unscathed.<ref name=\"AP AJC\">{{cite news|last=Spagat| first=Elliot| title=As allies fell, noose closed on 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=https://news.yahoo.com/allies-fell-noose-closed-39-el-chapo-39-050502264.html| accessdate=15 January 2016| newspaper= Yahoo News| agency=[[Associated Press]]| date=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Methamphetamine production ===\nAfter the fall of the Amezcua brothers&nbsp;\u2013 founders of the [[Colima Cartel]]&nbsp;\u2013 in 1999 on [[methamphetamine]] trafficking charges, there was a demand for leadership throughout Mexico to coordinate methamphetamine shipments north. Guzm\u00e1n saw an opportunity and seized it.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> Easily arranging precursor shipments, Guzm\u00e1n and [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda]] (\"El Mayo\") made use of their previous contacts on Mexico's Pacific coast. Importantly, for the first time, the Colombians would not have to be paid&nbsp;\u2013 they simply joined methamphetamine with cocaine shipments. This fact meant no additional money was needed for airplanes, pilots, boats and bribes; they used the existing infrastructure to pipeline the new product.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" />\n\nUntil this point, the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] had been a joint venture between Guzm\u00e1n and Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda; the methamphetamine business would be Guzm\u00e1n's alone. He cultivated his own ties to China, Thailand and India to import the necessary precursor chemicals. Throughout the mountains of the states of Sinaloa, [[Durango]], [[Jalisco]], [[Michoac\u00e1n]] and [[Nayarit]], Guzm\u00e1n constructed large [[clandestine chemistry|methamphetamine laboratories]] and rapidly expanded his organization.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" />\n\nHis nomadic existence allowed him to nurture contacts throughout the country. He was now operating in 17 of the 31 Mexican states. With his business expanding, he placed his trusted friend [[Ignacio Coronel Villarreal]] in charge of methamphetamine production; this way Guzm\u00e1n could continue being the boss of bosses. Coronel Villarreal proved so reliable in the Guzm\u00e1n business that he became known as the \"Crystal King\".<ref name=\"Grayson\">{{cite book |title=Mexico: Narco-Violence and a Failed State?| last=Grayson| first=George W. |year=2010 |publisher=[[Transaction Publishers]]| location=New Brunswick, NJ| isbn=978-1-4128-1151-4| lccn=2009029164|oclc=351324700| page=68| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ogjkeCd7RGoC&pg=PA68| accessdate=16 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== First escape and second arrest ==\n\n=== First escape: 2001 ===\nWhile still in prison in Mexico, Guzm\u00e1n was [[indictment|indicted]] in [[San Diego, California|San Diego]] on U.S. charges of [[money laundering]] and importing tons of cocaine into California, along with his Sinaloa attorney Humberto Loya-Castro, or ''Licenciado Perez'' (\"Lawyer Perez\"), who was charged with bribing Mexican officials on Sinaloa's behalf and making sure that any cartel members arrested were released from custody.<ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\" /><ref name=LAmaster>{{cite news|last=Boudreaux|first=Richard|title=Mexico's Master of Elusion|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2005/jul/05/world/fg-shorty5|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=5 July 2005}}</ref> After a ruling by the [[Supreme Court of Mexico]] made [[extradition]] between Mexico and the United States easier, Guzm\u00e1n bribed guards to aid his escape. On 19 January 2001, Francisco \"El Chito\" Camberos Rivera, a prison guard, opened Guzm\u00e1n's electronically operated cell door, and Guzm\u00e1n got into a laundry cart that maintenance worker Javier Camberos rolled through several doors and eventually out the front door. He was then transported in the trunk of a car driven by Camberos out of the town. At a petrol station, Camberos went inside, but when he came back, Guzm\u00e1n was gone on foot into the night. According to officials, 78 people have been implicated in his escape plan.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> Camberos is in prison for his assistance in the escape.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" />\n\nThe police say Guzm\u00e1n carefully masterminded his escape plan, wielding influence over almost everyone in the prison, including the facility's director, who is now in prison for aiding in the escape.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> One prison guard who came forward to report the situation at the prison disappeared 7 years later, and was presumed to have been killed on the orders of Guzm\u00e1n.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> Guzm\u00e1n allegedly had the prison guards on his payroll, smuggled contraband into the prison and received preferential treatment from the staff. In addition to the prison-employee accomplices, police in [[Jalisco]] were paid off to ensure he had at least 24 hours to get out of the state and stay ahead of the military manhunt. The story told to the guards being bribed not to search the laundry cart was that Guzm\u00e1n was smuggling gold, ostensibly extracted from rock at the inmate workshop, out of the prison. The escape allegedly cost Guzm\u00e1n $2.5&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amw.com/fugitives/case.cfm?id=25154|title=Guzm\u00e1n Escapes|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025095718/http://www.amw.com/fugitives/case.cfm?id=25154|archivedate=25 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Manhunt: 2001\u20132014 ===\n\n==== Mexican cartel wars ====\n{{Main|Mexican Drug War}}\n[[File:Drug-War Related Murders in Mexico 2006-2011.png|thumb|Drug-war related murders in Mexico, 2006\u20132011]]\nSince his 2001 escape from prison, Guzm\u00e1n had wanted to control the [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]] crossing points, which were in the hands of the Carrillo Fuentes family of the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]].<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> Despite a high degree of mistrust between the two organizations, the Sinaloa and Ju\u00e1rez cartels had a working agreement at the time. Guzm\u00e1n convened a meeting in [[Monterrey]] with [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda]] (\"El Mayo\"), [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Esparragoza Moreno]] (\"El Azul\") and [[Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]]. In this meeting, they discussed killing Rodolfo Carrillo Fuentes, who was in charge of the Ju\u00e1rez Cartel at the time. On 11 September 2004, Rodolfo, his wife and two young children were visiting a [[Culiac\u00e1n]] shopping mall. While leaving the mall, escorted by police commander Pedro P\u00e9rez L\u00f3pez, the family was ambushed by members of [[Los Negros]], assassins for the [[Sinaloa Cartel]]. Rodolfo and his wife were killed; the policeman survived.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" />\n\nThe city was no longer controlled only by the Carrillo Fuentes family. Instead, the city found itself as the front line in the [[Mexican Drug War]] and would see homicides skyrocket as rival cartels fought for control. With this act, Guzm\u00e1n was the first to break the nonaggression \"pact\" the major cartels had agreed to, setting in motion the fighting between cartels for drug routes that has claimed more than 60,000 lives since December 2006.<ref>{{cite news| title=Por crimen, 11% mas asesinatos en 2011| date=12 January 2012| url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/192833.html| work=El Universal| accessdate=15 January 2012| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Mendoza Hernandez| first=Enrique| title=Cinco a\u00f1os de guerra, 60 mil muertos| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=290774| accessdate=20 January 2012| newspaper=Proceso| date=10 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Quinto a\u00f1o de gobierno: 60 mil 420 ejecuciones| url=http://entranasdelnarco.com/?p=85| accessdate=15 January 2016| newspaper=Zeta Tijuana| date=12 December 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121234003/http://entranasdelnarco.com/?p=85| archive-date=21 November 2016| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhen Mexican President [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n]] took office in December 2006, he announced a crackdown on cartels by the Mexican military to stem the increasing violence.<ref name=\"LAT calderon\">{{cite news|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Tracy|last2=Ellingwood|first2=Ken|title=Mexico drug cartels thrive despite Calderon's offensive|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/aug/08/world/la-fg-mexico-cartels-20100808|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=8 August 2010}}</ref> After four years, the additional efforts had not slowed the flow of drugs or the killings tied to the drug war.<ref name=\"LAT calderon\" /> Of the 53,000 arrests made as of 2010, only 1,000 involved associates of the Sinaloa Cartel, which led to suspicions that Calder\u00f3n was intentionally allowing Sinaloa to win the drug war, a charge Calder\u00f3n denied in advertisements in Mexican newspapers, pointing to his administration's killing of top Sinaloa deputy \"Nacho\" Coronel as evidence.<ref name=\"LAT calderon\" /> Sinaloa's rival cartels saw their leaders killed and syndicates dismantled by the crackdown, but the Sinaloa gang was relatively unaffected and took over the rival gangs' territories, including the coveted Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez-El Paso corridor, in the wake of the power shifts.<ref name=\"market share\" />\n\n==== Conflict with Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel ====\n[[File:Alfredo BELTRAN LEYVA.jpg|thumb|Guzm\u00e1n's lieutenant [[Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]] (arrested)]]\nA ''[[Newsweek]]'' investigation alleges that one of Guzm\u00e1n's techniques for maintaining his dominance among cartels included giving information to the DEA and [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] that led to the arrests of his enemies in the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]], in addition to information that led to the arrests of some of the top Sinaloa leaders.<ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\" /> The arrests were speculated by some to have been part of a deal Guzm\u00e1n struck with Calder\u00f3n and the DEA, in which he intentionally gave up some of his purported Sinaloa colleagues to U.S. agents in exchange for immunity from prosecution, while perpetuating the idea that the Calder\u00f3n government was heavily pursuing his organization during the cartel crackdown.<ref name=\"war won\">{{cite book |last= Payan|first= Tony|title= A War that Can't Be Won: Binational Perspectives on the War on Drugs|url= |page=42|location= |publisher= University of Arizona Press|isbn= 978-0-8165-3034-2|date= 2013-10-17}}</ref>\n\nThis became a key factor influencing the break between the Sinaloa Cartel and the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel|Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers]], five brothers who served as Guzm\u00e1n's top lieutenants, primarily working for the cartel in the northern region of Sinaloa.<ref name=\"Mexico raids\">{{cite news|title=Mexico raids net alleged drug cartel figures |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/22785423 |accessdate=3 March 2014 |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=22 January 2008 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"LAT zetas\">{{cite news|last=Wilkinson |first=Tracy |title=Sinaloa cartel, Zetas push Mexico's drug violence to new depths |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/27/world/la-fg-mexico-cartel-war-20120528/2 |accessdate=3 March 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=27 May 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101074757/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/27/world/la-fg-mexico-cartel-war-20120528/2 |archivedate=1 November 2012 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Sinaloa lawyer Loya-Castro, who like Guzm\u00e1n had been wanted on federal charges in the United States since 1993, voluntarily approached the DEA offering them information in 1998, eventually signing paperwork as a formal informant in 2005, and his U.S. indictment was thrown out in 2008.<ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\" /> Loya-Castro's leaks to the DEA led to the dismantling of the Tijuana Cartel, as well as the Mexican Army's arrest of Guzm\u00e1n's lieutenant and the top commander of the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva organization, [[Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]] (also known as ''El Mochomo'', or \"Desert Ant\"), in Culiac\u00e1n in January 2008, with Guzm\u00e1n believed to have given up El Mochomo for various reasons.<ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\" /><ref name=\"war won\" /><ref name=\"LAT zetas\" /> Guzm\u00e1n had expressed concerns with Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n's lifestyle and high-profile actions for some time before his arrest. After El Mochomo's arrest, authorities said he was in charge of two hit squads, money laundering, transporting drugs and bribing officials.<ref name=\"Mexico raids\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico arrests top drugs suspect |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7201571.stm |accessdate=3 March 2014 |newspaper=[[BBC News]] |date=21 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203210808/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7201571.stm |archivedate=3 December 2012 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nThat high-profile arrest was followed by the arrest of 11 Beltr\u00e1n Leyva hit squad members in Mexico City, with police noting that the arrests were the first evidence that Sinaloa had expanded into the capital city.<ref name=\"Mexico raids\" /><ref name=\"cnn leyva\">{{cite news |title=Major Mexican drug cartel suspects arrested, officials say| date=20 January 2002| url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/americas/05/20/mexico.narco.arrest/index.html| work=CNN| accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> U.S. Ambassador to Mexico [[Tony Garza]] called the arrests a \"significant victory\" in the drug war.<ref name=\"Mexico raids\" /> With Alfredo in custody, his brother [[Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]] took over as the brothers' top commander, but he was killed in a shootout with Mexican marines the next year.<ref name=\"LAT zetas\" />\n\nWhether Guzm\u00e1n was responsible for Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n's arrest is not known. However, the Beltr\u00e1n Leyvas and their allies suspected he was behind it,<ref name=\"LAT zetas\" /> and after Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n's arrest, a formal \"war\" was declared. An attempt on the life of cartel head Zambada's son [[Vicente Zambada Niebla]] (''El Vincentillo'') was made only hours after the declaration. Dozens of killings followed in retaliation for that attempt.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> The Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers ordered the assassination of Guzm\u00e1n's son, \u00c9dgar Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez, on 8 May 2008, in Culiac\u00e1n, which brought massive retaliation from Guzm\u00e1n. They were also in conflict over the allegiance of the Flores brothers, Margarito and Pedro, leaders of a major, highly lucrative cell in [[Chicago]] responsible for distributing over two tons of cocaine every month.<ref name=\"ChicagoFBI\">{{cite web| title=Three Alleged Mexican Drug Cartel Leaders and Twin Brothers Who Ran Chicago-Based Distribution Crew Among Dozens Indicted in Chicago as Part of Coordinated Strike Against Drug Traffickers| url=http://chicago.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel09/cg082009.htm| publisher=FBI Chicago| accessdate=28 November 2010| url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129064526/http://chicago.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel09/cg082009.htm| archivedate=29 November 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Mexican military claims that Guzm\u00e1n and the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers were at odds over Guzm\u00e1n's relationship with the [[Milenio Cartel|Valencia brothers]] in Michoac\u00e1n.<ref name=\"LastNarco\">{{cite book| last=Beith| first=Malcolm| title=The Last Narco| url=https://archive.org/details/lastnarcoinsideh00beit| url-access=registration| year=2010}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the killing of Guzm\u00e1n's son \u00c9dgar, violence increased. From 8 May through the end of the month, over 116 people were murdered in Culiac\u00e1n, 26 of them police officers. In June 2008, over 128 were killed; in July, 143 were slain.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> An additional deployment of 2,000 troops to the area failed to stop the turf war. The wave of violence spread to other cities such as [[Guam\u00fachil]], [[Guasave]] and Mazatl\u00e1n.\n\nHowever, the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers were involved in some double-dealing of their own. Arturo and Alfredo had met with leading members of [[Los Zetas]] in [[Cuernavaca]], where they agreed to form an alliance to fill the power vacuum. They would not necessarily go after the main strongholds, such as the Sinaloa and Gulf Cartel; instead, they would seek control of southern states like [[Guerrero]] (where the Beltr\u00e1n Leyvas already had a big stake), [[Oaxaca]], [[Yucat\u00e1n (state)|Yucat\u00e1n]] and [[Quintana Roo]]. They worked their way into the center of the country, where no single group had control.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> The Beltr\u00e1n Leyva organization allied with the Gulf Cartel and its hit squad [[Los Zetas]] against Sinaloa.<ref name=\"cnn leyva\" />\n\nThe split was officially recognized by the U.S. government on 30 May 2008. On that day, it recognized the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers as leaders of their own cartel. President [[George W. Bush]] designated Marcos Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva and the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Organization as subject to sanction under the [[Foreign Narcotics Kingpin Designation Act]] (\"Kingpin Act\"),<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /><ref>{{cite news| last=Garza| first=Antonio O.| title=President Bush Designates Beltran Leyva and his Organization Under Kingpin Act| date=30 May 2008| publisher=Embassy of the U.S. in Mexico| url=http://www.usembassy-mexico.gov/eng/releases/ep080530kingpin.html| accessdate=3 August 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827010930/http://usembassy-mexico.gov/eng/releases/ep080530kingpin.html| archive-date=27 August 2009| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref> which prohibits people and corporations in the U.S. from conducting businesses with them and freezes their U.S. assets.\n\n==== First manhunt ====\n{{Main|Manhunt of Joaqu\u00edn \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n}}\nGuzm\u00e1n was known among drug lords for his longevity and evasion of authorities, assisted by alleged bribes to federal, state and local Mexican officials.<ref name=AParrest /><ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /><ref name=\"cnn arrest\">{{cite news| last1=Sanchez| first1=Ray| last2=Perez| first2=Evan |last3=Labott| first3=Elise| title=Sinaloa Cartel chief 'Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n arrested |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/22/world/americas/mexico-cartel-chief-arrest/index.html |accessdate=22 February 2014| newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=22 February 2014}}</ref> Despite the progress made in arresting others in the aftermath of Guzm\u00e1n's escape, including a handful of his foremost logistics and security men, the huge military and federal police manhunt failed to capture Guzm\u00e1n for years. In the years between his escape and capture, he was Mexico's most-wanted man.<ref name=\"wbur\">{{cite news| last=Beaubien| first=Jason| title=Smugglers' Hero Status Hampers Cartel Crackdown| url=http://www.wbur.org/npr/91303968| accessdate=22 February 2014| publisher=[[WBUR]]|date=9 June 2008}}</ref> His elusiveness from law enforcement made him a near-legendary figure in Mexico's narcotics folklore; stories abounded that Guzm\u00e1n sometimes strolled into restaurants, his bodyguards confiscating peoples' cellphones, he ate his meal, and then left after paying everyone's tab.<ref>{{cite news| last=Wilkinson| first=Tracy| title=Guzm\u00e1n's rise to power made him a living legend in Mexico's drug world| url=http://m.themonitor.com/news/local/article_6faa3de8-9c2a-11e3-8994-0017a43b2370.html?mode=jqm| accessdate=20 May 2014| newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)]]| date=February 2014}}</ref> Rumors circulated of Guzm\u00e1n being seen in different parts of Mexico and abroad.<ref name=mostwantedSA /> For more than thirteen years, Mexican security forces coordinated many operations to re-arrest him, but their efforts were largely in vain as Guzm\u00e1n appeared to be steps ahead from his captors.<ref>{{cite news| last=Wilkinson| first=Tracy| title=Mexican drug lord hid in mountains, homes, sewers| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2014/feb/23/world/la-fg-mexico-guzman-capture-20140224| accessdate=21 May 2014| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlthough his whereabouts were unknown, the authorities thought that he was likely hiding in the \"Golden Triangle\" (Spanish: ''Tri\u00e1ngulo Dorado''), an area that encompasses parts of Sinaloa, Durango, and Chihuahua in the [[Sierra Madre Oriental|Sierra Madre]] region. The region is a major producer of marijuana and opium poppies in Mexico,<ref>{{cite news| last=Blancas Madrigal| first=Daniel| title=El Tri\u00e1ngulo Dorado, zona m\u00e1s disputada por el narco| url=http://www.cronica.com.mx/notas/2008/369892.html|accessdate=4 May 2014| newspaper=[[La Cr\u00f3nica de Hoy]]| date=2008| language=Spanish}}</ref> and its remoteness from the urban areas makes it an attractive territory for the production of synthetic drugs in clandestine laboratories and for its mountains that offer potential hideouts.<ref>{{cite news| last=Lawson| first=Guy| title=The War Next Door| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/the-war-next-door-20110418| accessdate=4 May 2014| newspaper=[[The Rolling Stone]]| date=11 April 2011}}</ref>{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=21}}<ref>{{cite news| last=Dudley| first=Steven| title=In Battle for Sierra Madre, Old Allies, New Foes Displace Thousands| url=http://www.insightcrime.org/investigations/in-battle-for-sierra-madre-old-allies-new-foes-displace-hundreds| accessdate=20 May 2014| newspaper=[[InSight Crime]]| date=1 June 2012}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n reportedly commanded a sophisticated security circle of at least 300 informants and gunmen resembling the manpower equivalent to those of a [[head of state]]. His inner circle would help him move around through several isolated ranches in the mountainous area to avoid capture.<ref name=mostwantedSA>{{cite news| last=Schiller| first=Dane|title=Mexico's most wanted man|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/enie/article/Mexico-s-most-wanted-man-1363669.php| accessdate=4 May 2014| newspaper=[[San Antonio Express News]]| date=3 May 2011| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208060720/http://www.mysanantonio.com/enie/article/Mexico-s-most-wanted-man-1363669.php| archivedate=8 February 2014| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=chapostronger /> He usually escaped from law enforcement using armored cars, aircraft, and all-terrain vehicles, and was known to employ sophisticated communications gadgetry and counterespionage practices.<ref name=chapostronger /><ref>{{cite news| title=High-Tech Gizmos Helped Joaqu\u00edn 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Avoid Cops, But Also Led To Arrest| url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2014/02/26/high-tech-gizmos-helped-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-avoid-cops-but-also-led-to/| accessdate=4 May 2014| newspaper=[[Fox News]]| date=26 February 2014}}</ref> Since many of these locations in the Golden Triangle are only accessible via single-track dirt roads, local residents easily detected the arrival of law enforcement or any outsiders. Their distrust towards non-residents and their aversion towards the government, alongside a combination of bribery and intimidation, helped keep the locals loyal to Guzm\u00e1n and the Sinaloa Cartel in the area. According to law enforcement intelligence, attempting to have launched an attack to capture Guzm\u00e1n by air would have had similar results; his security circle would have warned him of the presence of an aircraft 10 minutes away from Guzm\u00e1n's location, giving him ample time to escape the scene and avoid arrest. In addition, his gunmen reportedly carried surface-to-air missiles that may bring down aircraft in the area.<ref name=chapostronger>{{cite news|last=Booth |first=William |title=El Chapo, wanted drug lord, grows stronger in Mexico's Sierra Madre |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/americas/el-chapo-wanted-drug-lord-grows-stronger-in-mexicos-sierra-madre/2011/10/14/gIQAfcUDNM_story.html |accessdate=4 May 2014 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=14 October 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525094936/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/americas/el-chapo-wanted-drug-lord-grows-stronger-in-mexicos-sierra-madre/2011/10/14/gIQAfcUDNM_story.html |archivedate=25 May 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n=== Second arrest: 2014 ===\nAlthough Guzm\u00e1n had hidden for long periods in remote areas of the Sierra Madre mountains without being captured, the arrested members of his security team told the military he had begun venturing out to Culiac\u00e1n and the beach town of Mazatl\u00e1n.<ref name=\"AP AJC\" /> A week before he was caught, Guzm\u00e1n and Zambada were reported to have attended a family reunion in Sinaloa.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n y \"El Mayo\" Zambada escaparon de un operativo militar |url=http://noticias.univision.com/article/1856093/2014-02-18/mexico/noticias/el-chapo-guzman-y-el-mayo-zambada-escaparon-de-un-operativo-militar |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Univision]] |date=18 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221155449/http://noticias.univision.com/article/1856093/2014-02-18/mexico/noticias/el-chapo-guzman-y-el-mayo-zambada-escaparon-de-un-operativo-militar |archivedate=21 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> On 16 February 2014, the Mexican military followed the bodyguards' tips to Guzm\u00e1n's former wife's house, but they had trouble ramming the steel-reinforced front door, which allowed Guzm\u00e1n to escape through a system of secret tunnels that connected six houses, eventually moving south to Mazatl\u00e1n.<ref name=\"AP AJC\" /> He had planned to stay a few days in Mazatl\u00e1n to see his twin baby daughters before retreating to the mountains.<ref>{{cite news| last=Loret de Mola| first=Carlos| title=El Chapo habl\u00f3 en el avi\u00f3n| url=http://www.eluniversalmas.com.mx/columnas/2014/02/105771.php| accessdate=25 February 2014| newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]]| date=25 February 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225182449/http://www.eluniversalmas.com.mx/columnas/2014/02/105771.php| archivedate=25 February 2014| url-status=dead| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February 2014, at around 6:40 AM,<ref>{{cite news|title=Capturan a 'El Chapo'; se mov\u00eda por t\u00faneles entre siete casas |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-arrestan_al_Chapo_Guzman-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_250175141.html |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228073126/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-arrestan_al_Chapo_Guzman-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_250175141.html |archivedate=28 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> Mexican authorities arrested Guzm\u00e1n at a hotel in a beachfront area in [[Mazatl\u00e1n]], following an operation by the [[Mexican Navy]], with joint intelligence from the DEA and the [[United States Marshals Service|U.S. Marshals Service]].<ref name=\"cnn arrest\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Washington Valdez |first=Diana |title=US Officials: Sinaloa drug kingpin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n arrested in Mexico |url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/news/ci_25204120/officials-chapo-guzman-arrested-last-night-mexico?source=rss |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Paso Times]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NajwvvNs?url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/news/ci_25204120/officials-chapo-guzman-arrested-last-night-mexico?source=rss |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A few days before his capture, Mexican authorities had been raiding several properties owned by members of the Sinaloa Cartel who were close to Guzm\u00e1n throughout the state of Sinaloa.<ref name=\"To Snitch on a Trap God\">{{cite web|url=http://dondivamag.com/to-snitch-on-the-trap-god/|title=To Snitch On The Trap God|author=Ryan K. Smith|date=19 August 2015|publisher=|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wilkinson |first=Tracy |title=Mexico's most wanted drug lord captured, U.S. official says |url=https://latimes.com/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-mexico-drug-arrest-20140222,0,4503693.story#axzz2u4ZpjqXL |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222215639/http://www.latimes.com/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-mexico-drug-arrest-20140222%2C0%2C4503693.story |archivedate=22 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's Sinaloa Drug Chief Arrested |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/mexicos-sinaloa-drug-chief-arrested |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[The Associated Press]] |date=22 February 2014 |author=Caldwell, Alicia A. |author2=Corcoran, Catherine |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223030727/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/mexicos-sinaloa-drug-chief-arrested |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> The operation leading to his capture began at 3:45 AM, when ten pickup trucks of the Mexican Navy carrying over 65 marines made their way to the resort area. Guzm\u00e1n was hiding at the Miramar condominiums, located at #608 on Avenida del Mar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mazatl\u00e1n ve la ca\u00edda de 'El Chapo' |url=http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1402/operativo-mazatlan-termina-dos-detenidos/ |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Televisa]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303170116/http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1402/operativo-mazatlan-termina-dos-detenidos/ |archivedate=3 March 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref><ref name=cronicamilenio /> Mexican and U.S. federal agents had leads that the drug lord had been at that location for at least two days, and that he was staying on the condominium's fourth floor, in Room 401. When the Mexican authorities arrived at the location, they quickly subdued [[Carlos Manuel Hoo Ram\u00edrez]], one of Guzm\u00e1n's bodyguards, before quietly making their way to the fourth floor by the elevators and stairs. Once they were at Guzm\u00e1n's front door, they broke into the apartment and stormed its two rooms. In one of the rooms was Guzm\u00e1n, lying in bed with his wife (former beauty queen [[Emma Coronel Aispuro]]).<ref name=cronicamilenio /><ref>{{cite news| title=Su esposa, la reina de belleza Emma Coronel, estaba con El Chapo cuando cay\u00f3| url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/2014/02/24/945415| accessdate=24 February 2014| newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=24 February 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224190057/http://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/2014/02/24/945415 |archivedate=24 February 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> Their two daughters were reported to have been at the condominium during the arrest.<ref>{{cite news| title=Defensa de Guzm\u00e1n Loera frena con amparo su posible extradici\u00f3n a EU |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365777| accessdate=25 February 2014| newspaper=Proceso|date=24 February 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n tried to resist arrest physically,<ref name=cronicamilenio /> but he did not attempt to grab a rifle he had close to him.<ref>{{cite news | title=Celular, pieza clave para el arresto de \"El Chapo\" | url=http://www.aztecanoticias.com.mx/notas/mexico/183614/celular-pieza-clave-para-el-arresto-de-el-chapo | accessdate=25 February 2014 | newspaper=[[TV Azteca|Azteca Noticias]] | date=23 February 2014 | language=Spanish | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303023352/http://www.aztecanoticias.com.mx/notas/mexico/183614/celular-pieza-clave-para-el-arresto-de-el-chapo | archive-date=3 March 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Gomez Licon| first=Adriana| title=Celular llev\u00f3 a arresto de \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n| url=https://news.yahoo.com/celular-llev-arresto-quot-el-chapo-quot-guzm-010440185.html |accessdate=25 February 2014| newspaper=[[Yahoo! News]]| date=23 February 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> Amid the quarrel with the marines, the drug lord was hit four times. By 6:40 AM, he was arrested, taken to the ground floor, and walked to the condominium's parking lot, where the first photos of his capture were taken.<ref name=cronicamilenio>{{cite news |last=Becerra Acosta |first=Juan Pablo |title=El se\u00f1or del cuerno de chivo junto la cama no lo alcanzaba a coger ... |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-arrestan_al_Chapo_Guzman-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_250175210.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227182130/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-arrestan_al_Chapo_Guzman-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_250175210.html |archivedate=27 February 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Althaus |first=Dudley |title=Marines take down drug kingpin Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/americas/mexico/140222/drug-kingpin-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-caught |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[GlobalPost]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223020248/http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/americas/mexico/140222/drug-kingpin-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-caught |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> His identity was confirmed through a [[fingerprint]] examination immediately following his capture.<ref>{{cite news|last=Esquivel |first=Jes\u00fas |title=Detienen a \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n en hotel de Mazatl\u00e1n |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365562 |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223031155/http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365562 |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> He was then flown to Mexico City, the country's capital, for formal identification.<ref>{{cite news| last=H.T.| title=Arrest of a drug lord: Got Shorty| url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/02/arrest-drug-lord| accessdate=22 February 2014| newspaper=[[The Economist]]| date=22 February 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222220116/https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/02/arrest-drug-lord |archivedate=22 February 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> According to the Mexican government, no shots were fired during the operation.<ref name=\"To Snitch on a Trap God\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Lara |first=Carlos |title=Operativo para capturar a \"El Chapo\" fue puro y sin ning\u00fan disparo: PGR |url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldemexico/notas/n3300539.htm |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=El Sol de M\u00e9xico |date=23 February 2014 |agency=[[Organizaci\u00f3n Editorial Mexicana]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301154708/http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldemexico/notas/n3300539.htm |archivedate=1 March 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n was presented in front of cameras during a press conference at the [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez International Airport|Mexico City International Airport]] that afternoon,<ref>{{cite news|title=Blindan el Aeropuerto para la presentaci\u00f3n de \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/blindan-el-aeropuerto-para-la-presentacion-de-el-chapo-guzman |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[R\u00edodoce]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223031824/http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/blindan-el-aeropuerto-para-la-presentacion-de-el-chapo-guzman |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> and then he was transferred to the [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1]], a maximum-security prison in [[Almoloya de Ju\u00e1rez]], State of Mexico, on a [[Federal Police (Mexico)|Federal Police]] Black Hawk helicopter. The helicopter was escorted by two Navy helicopters and one from the Mexican Air Force.<ref>{{cite news|last=Monroy |first=Jorge |title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n fue trasladado al penal del Altiplano |url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/sociedad/2014/02/22/chapo-guzman-fue-trasladado-penal-altiplano |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Economista (Mexico)|El Economista]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223032105/http://eleconomista.com.mx/sociedad/2014/02/22/chapo-guzman-fue-trasladado-penal-altiplano |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Alzaga |first=Ignacio |title=Encarcelan a 'El Chapo' en penal del Altiplano |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Chapo_penal_Altiplano_0_250175186.html |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301214232/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Chapo_penal_Altiplano_0_250175186.html |archivedate=1 March 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> Surveillance inside the penitentiary and surrounding areas was increased by a large contingent of law enforcement.<ref>{{cite news |last=D\u00e1vila |first=Israel |title=Regresa El Chapo al penal de alta seguridad de El Altiplano |url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2014/02/22/regresa-el-chapo-al-penal-de-alta-seguridad-de-el-altiplano-1622.html |accessdate=6 November 2016 |newspaper=[[La Jornada]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223043606/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2014/02/22/regresa-el-chapo-al-penal-de-alta-seguridad-de-el-altiplano-1622.html |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Reactions ====\nMexican President [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]] confirmed the arrest through [[Twitter]] and congratulated the [[Secretariat of National Defense (Mexico)|Secretariat of National Defense]] (SEDENA), [[Secretariat of the Navy (Mexico)|Secretariat of the Navy]] (SEMAR), [[Procuradur\u00eda General de la Rep\u00fablica|Office of the General Prosecutor]] (PGR), the Federal Police, and the [[Centro de Investigaci\u00f3n y Seguridad Nacional (M\u00e9xico)|Centro de Investigaci\u00f3n y Seguridad Nacional]] (CISEN) for Guzm\u00e1n's capture.<ref name=AParrest /><ref>{{cite news|title=Cae 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n, el narcotraficante m\u00e1s buscado |url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2014/02/22/el-lider-del-cartel-de-sinaloa-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-es-detenido |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222201220/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2014/02/22/el-lider-del-cartel-de-sinaloa-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-es-detenido |archivedate=22 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Felicitan a EPN por detenci\u00f3n de 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1402/felicitan-epn-detencion-el-chapo-guzman/ |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Televisa]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713092042/http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1402/felicitan-epn-detencion-el-chapo-guzman/ |archivedate=13 July 2015 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> In the United States, [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Eric Holder]] said Guzm\u00e1n had caused \"death and destruction of millions of lives across the globe\" and called the arrest \"a landmark achievement, and a victory for the citizens of both Mexico and the United States\".<ref name=\"cnn arrest\" /> [[Colombia]]'s President [[Juan Manuel Santos]] telephoned Pe\u00f1a Nieto and congratulated him for the arrest of Guzm\u00e1n, highlighting its importance in the international efforts against drug trafficking.<ref>{{cite news|title=Presidente de Colombia felicita a EPN por captura de 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/965521.presidente-de-colombia-felicita-a-epn-por-captura-de-el-chapo.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225192138/http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/965521.presidente-de-colombia-felicita-a-epn-por-captura-de-el-chapo.html |archivedate=25 February 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Colombia's Defense Minister, [[Juan Carlos Pinz\u00f3n]], congratulated Mexico on Guzm\u00e1n's arrest and stated that his capture \"contributes to eradicate this crime ([[drug trafficking]]) in the region\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Colombia felicita a M\u00e9xico por captura de El Chapo |url=http://www.debate.com.mx/eldebate/noticias/default.asp?IdArt=14085260&IdCat=6103 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=El Debate |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223052541/http://www.debate.com.mx/eldebate/noticias/default.asp?IdArt=14085260&IdCat=6103 |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Guatemalan President [[Otto P\u00e9rez Molina]] congratulated the Mexican government for the arrest.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se suma Guatemala a felicitaciones por detenci\u00f3n |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/guatemala-detencion-felicitaciones-mexico-chapo-989805.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223032813/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/guatemala-detencion-felicitaciones-mexico-chapo-989805.html |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> [[Costa Rica]]'s President [[Laura Chinchilla]] congratulated the Mexican government through Twitter for the capture too.<ref>{{cite news |title=Autoridades internacionales felicitan a M\u00e9xico por captura de \"El Chapo\" |url=http://noticias.prodigy.msn.com/internacional/autoridades-internacionales-felicitan-a-m%C3%A9xico-por-captura-de-%E2%80%9Cel-chapo%E2%80%9D |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=MSN |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Nar5RVpl?url=http://noticias.prodigy.msn.com/internacional/autoridades-internacionales-felicitan-a-m%C3%A9xico-por-captura-de-%E2%80%9Cel-chapo%E2%80%9D |archivedate=23 February 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The French government extended its congratulations on 24 February and supported the Mexican security forces in their combat against organized crime.<ref>{{cite news|title=Francia felicita a M\u00e9xico por captura de 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.milenio.com/politica/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Francia_0_251374926.html |accessdate=24 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=24 February 2014 |agency=24 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228044524/http://www.milenio.com/politica/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Francia_0_251374926.html |archivedate=28 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> News of Guzm\u00e1n's capture made it to the headlines of many media outlets across the U.S., Latin America, and Europe.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pantoja |first=Sara |title=Prensa internacional resalta la captura del capo \"m\u00e1s buscado en el mundo\" |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365663 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223051712/http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365663 |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Captura de 'El Chapo' acapara medios internacionales |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman_0_250175132.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303081340/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman_0_250175132.html |archivedate=3 March 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> On Twitter, Mexico and Guzm\u00e1n's capture were [[trending topics]] throughout most of 22 February 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vivas |first=Mar\u00eda Luisa |title=Reaprehensi\u00f3n del capo, Trending Topic mundial |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365664 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223051900/http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365664 |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref>\n\nBob Nardoza, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York|District Court for the Eastern District of New York]], announced that U.S. authorities plan to seek the extradition of Guzm\u00e1n for several cases pending against him in New York and other United States jurisdictions.<ref>{{cite press release|last1=Shoichet |first1=Catherine |last2=Prokupecz |first2=Shimon |title=They got 'Shorty' -- now what? Cases pending against drug boss in several US jurisdictions |url=http://www.kcci.com/national/They-got-Shorty-now-what/24629878 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |publisher=CNN |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224050832/http://www.kcci.com/national/They-got-Shorty-now-what/24629878 |archivedate=24 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n==== Charges and imprisonment ====\nGuzm\u00e1n was imprisoned at [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1]], area #20, Hallway #1, on the same day of his capture on 22 February 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo ya tiene abogado|url=http://www.razon.com.mx/spip.php?article206605|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=La Raz\u00f3n|date=23 February 2014|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227081101/http://www.razon.com.mx/spip.php?article206605|archive-date=27 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The area where he lived was highly restricted; the cells are without windows, inmates are not allowed to interact with each other, and they are not permitted to contact their family members.<ref>{{cite news |last=G\u00f3mora| first=Doris|title=Primera noche en prisi\u00f3n, sin antecedentes| url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/impreso/primera-noche-en-prision-sin-incidentes-213395.html|accessdate=24 February 2014|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]]|date=24 February 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref> His cell was close to those of Jos\u00e9 Jorge Balderas (''alias'' \"El JJ\"), former lieutenant of the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel, and [[Jaime Gonz\u00e1lez Dur\u00e1n]] (''alias'' \"El Hummer\"), a former leader of [[Los Zetas]] drug cartel. Miguel \u00c1ngel Guzm\u00e1n Loera, one of his brothers, was in one of the other units.<ref name=carcelmilenio /><ref>{{cite news|title=Abogado se acredita formalmente como defensor de 'El Chapo'|url=http://www.adnpolitico.com/gobierno/2014/02/23/abogado-se-acredita-formalmente-como-abogado-de-el-chapo|accessdate=25 February 2014|newspaper=ADNPol\u00edtico|date=24 February 2014|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224163011/http://www.adnpolitico.com/gobierno/2014/02/23/abogado-se-acredita-formalmente-como-abogado-de-el-chapo|archive-date=24 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n was alone in his cell, and had one bed, one shower, and a single toilet. His lawyer was \u00d3scar Quirarte. Guzm\u00e1n was allowed to receive visits from members of his family every nine days from 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to 5:00&nbsp;p.m. (if approved by a judge), and was granted by law the right to receive MXN$638 (about US$48) every month to buy products for personal hygiene.<ref name=carcelmilenio>{{cite news|last=Valdez |first=Blanca |title=\u00d3scar Quirarte es el abogado de 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-penal_de_maxima_seguridad_del_Altiplano-Almoloya_de_Juarez_0_250775087.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301214236/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-penal_de_maxima_seguridad_del_Altiplano-Almoloya_de_Juarez_0_250775087.html |archivedate=1 March 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=aislamiento /> He lived under 23 hours of [[solitary confinement]] with one hour of outdoor exposure. He was only allowed to speak with people during his judicial hearings (the prison guards that secured his cell were not allowed to speak with him). Unlike the other inmates, Guzm\u00e1n was prohibited from practicing sport or cultural activities. These conditions were court-approved and could only be changed if a federal judge decided to amend them.<ref name=aislamiento>{{cite news |title=\"El Chapo\": 23 horas de aislamiento por una de sol |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=370779| accessdate=27 April 2014| newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=27 April 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February, the Mexican government formally charged Guzm\u00e1n for drug trafficking, a process that slowed down his possible extradition to the U.S. The decision to initially file only one charge against him showed that the Mexican government was working on preparing more formal charges against Guzm\u00e1n, and possibly including the charges he faced before his escape from prison in 2001. The kingpin also faces charges in at least seven U.S. jurisdictions, and U.S. officials filed for his extradition.<ref>{{cite news |title=Joaquin \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n formally charged in Mexico, likely slowing extradition to U.S. |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-formally-charged-in-mexico-likely-slowing-extradition/| accessdate=24 February 2014| newspaper=[[CBS News]]| date=24 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mexican drug kingpin seeks to block US extradition |url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/mexican-drug-kingpin-seeks-block-us-extradition-214230238.html| accessdate=24 February 2014| newspaper=[[Yahoo News]]| date=24 February 2014}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n was initially granted an [[injunction]] preventing immediate extradition to the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title='Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n arrest: Mexican corrido singer chronicles capture| date=26 February 2014| first=Diana| last=Washington Valdez| work=El Paso Times |url=http://www.willitsnews.com/general-news/20140226/chapo-guzman-arrest-mexican-corrido-singer-chronicles-capture| accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref> On 25 February, a Mexican federal judge set the trial in motion for drug-related and organized crime charges,<ref>{{cite news |last=Stevenson| first=Mark| title=Judge Sets Mexican Trial for 'El Chapo' in Motion |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/el-chapo-stay-strong-inside-mexican-prison-22669323| accessdate=25 February 2014| newspaper=[[ABC News]]| date=25 February 2014}}<br /></ref> On 4 March 2014, a Mexican federal court issued a formal charge against Guzm\u00e1n for his involvement in organized crime.<ref>{{cite news |last=Castillo| first=Gustavo| title=Dictan tercer auto de formal prisi\u00f3n contra 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2014/03/04/dictan-quinto-auto-de-formal-prision-contra-el-chapo-1781.html| accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=[[La Jornada]]| date=4 March 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306013744/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2014/03/04/dictan-quinto-auto-de-formal-prision-contra-el-chapo-1781.html| archivedate=6 March 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gandaria|first=Manrique|title=Dictan el cuarto auto de formal prisi\u00f3n contra \"El Chapo\" |url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldemexico/notas/n3313041.htm|accessdate=6 March 2014|newspaper=El Sol de M\u00e9xico|date=5 March 2014|agency=[[Organizaci\u00f3n Editorial Mexicana]]|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2014, a Mexico City federal court rejected Guzm\u00e1n's injunction against extradition to the U.S. on the grounds that the U.S. officials had not formally requested his extradition from Mexico. The court said that if the U.S. files a request in the future, Guzm\u00e1n can petition for another injunction.<ref>{{cite news |title=El Chapo denied petition against U.S. extradition| url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/el-chapo-denied-petition-against-us-extradition| accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=[[The Associated Press]]| date=6 March 2014| location=Mexico City}}</ref> The court had until 9 April 2014 to issue a formal declaration of the injunction's rejection, and Guzm\u00e1n's lawyers could appeal the court's decision in the meantime.<ref>{{cite news |title=Se complica la situaci\u00f3n jur\u00eddica de El Chapo| url=http://noticias.univision.com/article/1873670/2014-03-05/mexico/noticias/el-chapo-pierde-un-amparo-para-evitar-una-posible-extradicion| accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=[[Univision]]|date=5 March 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> The same day that the injunction was rejected, another federal court issued formal charges against Guzm\u00e1n, totaling up to five different Mexican federal courts where he was wanted for drug trafficking and organized crime charges.<ref>{{cite news |title=Un juez emite la quinta orden de formal prisi\u00f3n contra 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2014/03/05/un-juez-emite-la-cuarta-orden-de-formal-prision-contra-el-chapo-guzman|accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico| date=5 March 2014| agency=[[Turner Broadcasting System]]|language=Spanish}}</ref> The court explained that although Guzm\u00e1n faces charges in several different courts, he cannot be sentenced for the same crime twice because that would violate [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 23|Article 23]] of the [[Constitution of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Carrasco Araizaga| first=Jorge| title=Suman 5 autos de formal prisi\u00f3n contra \"El Chapo\"; le niegan amparo contra extradici\u00f3n| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=366493| accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=5 March 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April 2014, the Attorney General of Mexico, [[Jes\u00fas Murillo Karam]], said that Mexico had no intention of extraditing Guzm\u00e1n to the U.S. even if a formal request were to be presented. He said he wished to see Guzm\u00e1n face charges in Mexico, and expressed his disagreement with how the U.S. cuts deals with extradited Mexican criminals by reducing their sentences (as in [[Vicente Zambada Niebla]]'s case) in exchange for information.<ref>{{cite news |last=Estevez| first=Dolia| title=Upset About A Controversial Narco Deal, Mexico Reaffirms It Will Not Extradite Drug Kingpin El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n To The U.S.| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2014/04/17/upset-about-a-controversial-narco-deal-mexico-reaffirms-it-will-not-extradite-drug-kingpin-el-chapo-guzman-to-the-u-s/| accessdate=20 April 2014| newspaper=[[Forbes]]| date=17 April 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419044704/http://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2014/04/17/upset-about-a-controversial-narco-deal-mexico-reaffirms-it-will-not-extradite-drug-kingpin-el-chapo-guzman-to-the-u-s/| archivedate=19 April 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 July 2014, Guzm\u00e1n reportedly helped organize a five-day hunger strike in the prison in cooperation with inmate and former drug lord [[Edgar Valdez Villarreal]] (''alias'' \"La Barbie\"). Over 1,000 prisoners reportedly participated in the protest and complained of the prison's poor hygiene, food, and medical treatment. The Mexican government confirmed that the strike took place and that the prisoners' demands were satisfied, but denied that Guzm\u00e1n or Valdez Villarreal were involved in it given their status as prisoners in solitary confinement.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hern\u00e1ndez| first1=Anabel| title='El Chapo' y 'La Barbie' ponen de cabeza el penal del Altiplano| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=377621| accessdate=2 September 2014| magazine=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=19 July 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720183503/http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=377621| archivedate=20 July 2014| url-status=live| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Partlow |first1=Joshua |title=The Mexican drug lord Chapo Guzm\u00e1n is in prison. But he might live by his own rules |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/the-mexican-drug-lord-chapo-guzman-is-in-prison-but-he-might-live-by-his-own-rules/2014/08/28/1878a689-aeaf-4d4f-a8bc-fca2dab3a02e_story.html |accessdate=2 September 2014 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=31 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140829191149/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/the-mexican-drug-lord-chapo-guzman-is-in-prison-but-he-might-live-by-his-own-rules/2014/08/28/1878a689-aeaf-4d4f-a8bc-fca2dab3a02e_story.html |archivedate=29 August 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 2014, Guzm\u00e1n and his former business partner Zambada were indicted by the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York]] in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cawley |first1=Marguerite |title=US Indictment Shows Escalating Political Battle for Mexico's 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.insightcrime.com/news-briefs/us-indictment-shows-escalating-political-battle-mexicos-el-chapo |accessdate=9 October 2014 |publisher=[[InSight Crime]] |date=9 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009183722/http://www.insightcrime.com/news-briefs/us-indictment-shows-escalating-political-battle-mexicos-el-chapo |archivedate= 9 October 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> According to the court documents, both of them conspired to kill Mexican law enforcement officers, government officials, and members of the Mexican Armed Forces. Among the people killed under the alleged orders of Guzm\u00e1n were Roberto Velasco Bravo (2008), the chief of Mexico's organized crime investigatory division; Rafael Ram\u00edrez Jaime (2008), the chief of the arrest division of the Attorney General's Office; Rodolfo Carrillo Fuentes (2004), former leader of the Ju\u00e1rez Cartel, among other criminals from the Tijuana, Los Zetas, Beltr\u00e1n Leyva, and Ju\u00e1rez crime syndicates.<ref name=forbesindictment /> The court alleged that Guzm\u00e1n used professional assassins to carry out \"hundreds of acts of violence, including murders, assaults, kidnappings, assassinations and acts of torture\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marzulli| first1=John| title=EXCLUSIVE: Mexican druglord Joaquin (El Chapo) Guzm\u00e1n charged with 12 murders in new indictment| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/exclusive-druglord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-charged-12-murders-article-1.1965623| accessdate=8 October 2014| newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]| date=8 October 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008145312/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/exclusive-druglord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-charged-12-murders-article-1.1965623| archivedate=8 October 2014|  url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, it alleged that he oversaw a drug-trafficking empire that transported multi-ton shipments of narcotics from South America, through Central America and Mexico, and then to the U.S., and that his network was facilitated by corrupt law enforcement and public officials.<ref name=forbesindictment>{{cite news |last1=Estevez| first1=Dolia| title=Mexican Drug Lords El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n, Ismael Zambada Charged With A Dozen Killings In New U.S. Indictment| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2014/10/07/mexican-drug-lords-el-chapo-guzman-ismael-zambada-charged-with-a-dozen-killings-in-new-u-s-indictment/| accessdate=8 October 2014| work=[[Forbes]]|date=8 October 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008013626/http://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2014/10/07/mexican-drug-lords-el-chapo-guzman-ismael-zambada-charged-with-a-dozen-killings-in-new-u-s-indictment/| archivedate=8 October 2014}}</ref> It also alleged that Guzm\u00e1n laundered more than US$14 billion in drug proceeds along with several other high-ranking drug lords.<ref name='Forbes2017'/><ref name='FoxLatino'>{{cite news |title=Notorious Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n indicted in New York, opening door to possible extradition| url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2014/10/07/notorious-mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-indicted-in-new-york-opening-door/| accessdate=8 October 2014| publisher=[[Fox News]]| date=8 October 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008014044/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2014/10/07/notorious-mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-indicted-in-new-york-opening-door/| archivedate=8 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 November 2014, a federal court in Sinaloa granted Guzm\u00e1n an injunction for weaponry charges after the judge determined that the arrest was not carried out the way the Mexican Navy reported it.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ram\u00edrez de Aguilar|first1=Fernando| title=Otorgan un amparo al \"Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n|url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/sociedad/otorgan-un-amparo-al-chapo-guzman.html| accessdate=13 November 2014| publisher=El Financiero| date=13 November 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> According to law enforcement, the Navy apprehended Guzm\u00e1n after they received an anonymous tip on an armed individual in the hotel where he was staying. However, no evidence of the anonymous tip was provided. The judge also determined that the investigations leading to his arrest were not presented in court. He determined that law enforcement's version of the arrest had several irregularities because the Navy did not have a raid warrant when they entered the premises and arrested Guzm\u00e1n (when he was not the subject matter of the anonymous tip in the first place).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mosso |first1=Rub\u00e9n |title=Tribunal ampara a 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-captura_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_407959393.html |accessdate=13 November 2014 |publisher=[[Milenio]] |date=13 November 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113103315/http://www.milenio.com/policia/Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-captura_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_407959393.html |archivedate=13 November 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2015, Guzm\u00e1n requested another injunction through his lawyer Andr\u00e9s Granados Flores to prevent his extradition to the U.S.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vela| first1=David Sa\u00fal| title='El Chapo' tramita amparo ante posible extradici\u00f3n a EU| url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/el-chapo-tramita-amparo-ante-posible-extradicion-a-eu.html| accessdate=24 January 2015| publisher=El Financiero| date=23 January 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> His defense argued that if he were to be extradited and judged in a foreign court, his constitutional rights expressed in [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 1|Articles 1]], [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 14|14]], [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 16|16]], [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 17|17]], [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 18|18]] and [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 20|20]] of the Constitution of Mexico would be violated.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alzaga| first1=Ignacio|title=Promueve El Chapo amparo para evitar extradici\u00f3n a EU| url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/promueve_amparo_chapo-amparo_extradicion_chapo-el_chapo_guzman_0_451155237.html| accessdate=24 January 2015| publisher=[[Milenio]]| date=23 January 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> The decision of his defense was made after Attorney General Murillo Karam said at a press conference that the U.S. was pushing to formally request his extradition.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuevo amparo del \"Chapo\" contra extradici\u00f3n| url=http://zetatijuana.com/noticias/generalez/17105/nuevo-amparo-del-chapo-contra-extradicion| accessdate=24 January 2015| magazine=[[Zeta (magazine)|Zeta]]| date=23 January 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> The PGR and Mexico's [[Secretariat of Foreign Affairs (Mexico)|Secretariat of Foreign Affairs]] stated that Guzm\u00e1n had a provisional arrest with extradition purposes from the U.S. government since 17 February 2001, but that the formal proceedings to officiate the extradition were not realized because investigators considered that the request was outdated and believed it would have been difficult to gather potential witnesses.<ref>{{cite news |title=Busca 'El Chapo' amparo para evitar extradici\u00f3n a Estados Unidos|url=http://diario.mx/Nacional/2015-01-23_995ad1a0/busca-el-chapo-amparo-para-evitar-extradicion-a-estados-unidos-|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=Diario de Ju\u00e1rez|date=23 January 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Murillo Karam said that the Mexican government would process the request when they deemed it appropriate.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Estevez|first1=Dolia|title=Confirmed: U.S. Will Request That Mexico Extradite Drug Lord Joaqu\u00edn El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2015/01/21/confirmed-u-s-will-request-that-mexico-extradite-drug-lord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman/|accessdate=24 January 2015|work=[[Forbes]]|date=21 January 2015}}</ref> He asked for a second injunction preventing his extradition on 26 January. Mexico City federal judge Fabricio Villegas asked federal authorities to confirm in 24 hours if there was a pending extradition request against Guzm\u00e1n.<ref>{{cite news|last1=M\u00e9ndez|first1=Alfredo|title=Otorgan a 'El Chapo' segundo amparo contra extradici\u00f3n a EU|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2015/01/26/otorgan-suspension-de-amparo-a-el-chapo-contra-extradicion-a-eu-594.html|accessdate=29 January 2015|publisher=[[La Jornada]]|date=26 January 2015|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801102231/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2015/01/26/otorgan-suspension-de-amparo-a-el-chapo-contra-extradicion-a-eu-594.html|archive-date=1 August 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a press conference the following day, Murillo Karam said that he was expecting a request from Washington, but said that they would not extradite him until he faces charges and completes his sentences in Mexico. If all the charges are added up, Guzm\u00e1n may receive a sentence between 300 and 400 years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Verza|first1=Maria |title=Mexico: Captured drug lord 'Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n to stay put |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/0fbcdfcab6f94b268c74cd651a35b932/mexico-ag-captured-drug-lord-chapo-guzman-stay-put |accessdate=29 January 2015 |work=Associated Press |date=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=reuters-2nd-escape>{{cite news |last1=Stargardter|first1=Gabriel |title=Mexico says drug lord 'Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n escapes from prison |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/12/us-mexcio-guzman-idUSKCN0PM07020150712 |accessdate=12 July 2015 |publisher=Reuters |date=12 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Second escape and third arrest ==\n\n=== Second escape: 2015 ===\nOn 11 July 2015, Guzm\u00e1n escaped from [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1]], a maximum-security prison.<ref name=reuters-2nd-escape /> After receiving medication,<ref name=reformafuga>{{cite news|last1=Mart\u00ednez|first1=C\u00e9sar|title=Escap\u00f3 'Chapo' por t\u00fanel de 1.5 km|url=http://www.reforma.com/aplicacioneslibre/articulo/default.aspx?id=589370&md5=fff66622e1862e9b295ee653b4ff13be&ta=0dfdbac11765226904c16cb9ad1b2efe#ixzz3fggfMYlD|publisher=[[Reforma]]|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n was last seen by security cameras at 20:52 hours near the shower area in his cell. The shower area was the only part of his cell that was not visible through the security camera.<ref name=laescape>{{cite news|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Tracy|title=Drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzman escapes from Mexico prison -- again|url=https://latimes.com/world/mexico-americas/la-fg-drug-lord-escapes-mexico-prison-20150711-story.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> After the guards did not see him for twenty-five minutes on surveillance video, personnel went looking for him.<ref name=CNNElChapo>{{cite news|last1=Hanna|first1=Jason|title=Seven prison workers charged in connection with 'El Chapo' escape|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/07/17/americas/mexico-el-chapo-escape/|publisher=CNN|date=18 July 2015|language=}}</ref> When they reached his cell, Guzm\u00e1n was gone. It was discovered he had [[Escape tunnel|escaped through a tunnel]] leading from the shower area to a house construction site {{convert|1.5|km|abbr=on}} away in a Santa Juanita neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news| title=Se escapa \"El Chapo\" por un t\u00fanel de 1.5 kil\u00f3metros| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=410392| magazine=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=12 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Castillo| first1=Eduardo E. |last2=Corcoran| first2=Katherine| title=Mexico: Drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzman escapes through tunnel| url=https://news.yahoo.com/mexico-top-drug-lord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-064113154.html |agency=[[The Associated Press]]| publisher=Yahoo News| date=12 July 2015}}</ref> The tunnel lay {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}} deep underground, and Guzm\u00e1n used a ladder to climb to the bottom. The tunnel was {{convert|1.7|m|abbr=on}} tall and {{convert|75|cm|abbr=on}} in width. It was equipped with artificial light, air ducts, and high-quality construction materials.<ref name=reformafuga /> In addition, a [[motorcycle]] was found in the tunnel, which authorities think was used to transport materials and possibly Guzm\u00e1n himself.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dudley|first1=Steven|title=El Chapo's 2nd Escape Could Paralyze Mexico's National Security Plans|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-analysis/el-chapo-s-2nd-escape-could-paralyze-mexico-s-already-reeling-security-strategy|publisher=[[InSight Crime]]|date=12 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Notorious Mexican Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Escapes Prison for Second Time|url = https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/mexican-drug-lord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-escapes-prison-second-n390706|website = NBC News| accessdate = 9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Second runaway and manhunt: 2015\u20132016 ===\nThe escape of Guzm\u00e1n triggered a wide-range manhunt.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Partlow| first1=Joshua| last2=Miroff| first2=Nick|title=Huge manhunt in Mexico as drug lord Chapo Guzm\u00e1n tunnels out of prison| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/drug-lord-chapo-guzman-tunnels-out-of-maximum-security-prison/2015/07/12/90279efe-666a-49fb-aba4-4177bb36f0a0_story.html| newspaper=The Washington Post| date=12 July 2015}}</ref> According to Mexico's National Security Commissioner Monte Alejandro Rubido&nbsp;Garc\u00eda, the manhunt was instituted immediately in the surrounding area by putting up several checkpoints and air searches by helicopter.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Alzag |first1=Ignacio| title=El Chapo se fug\u00f3 \u2026 otra vez| url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/fuga-nuevamente-Chapo-Guzman-Altiplano-Penal-Federal-CNS-Joaquin_0_553144682.html| publisher=[[Milenio]]| date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> The entire prison was put on lockdown and no one was allowed to enter or leave.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Partlow| first1=Joshua| last2=Miroff| first2=Nick| title=Drug lord Chapo Guzman tunnels out of maximum-security Mexico prison| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/drug-lord-chapo-guzman-tunnels-out-of-maximum-security-prison/2015/07/12/90279efe-666a-49fb-aba4-4177bb36f0a0_story.html| newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> The search was then extended to other federal entities: Mexico City, the State of Mexico, [[Morelos]], [[Puebla]], [[Guerrero]], [[Michoac\u00e1n]], [[Quer\u00e9taro]], [[Hidalgo (state)|Hidalgo]] and [[Tlaxcala]]. However, most of the military officers involved in the search were sent to the State of Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jim\u00e9nez|first1=Benito|title=Buscan al 'Chapo' en 9 entidades|url=http://www.reforma.com/aplicacioneslibre/articulo/default.aspx?id=589374&md5=1c521e6ad138567d1f7521e754eb78e7&ta=0dfdbac11765226904c16cb9ad1b2efe#ixzz3fgpNCJQQ|publisher=[[Reforma]]|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> The Mexican government also issued an international warning to prevent Guzm\u00e1n from escaping the country through airports, border checkpoints, or ports. Interpol and other security organizations were alerted to the possibility of him escaping into another country.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mosso|first1=Rub\u00e9n|title=Emiten alerta internacional por fuga de El Chapo|url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/alerta_internacional_chapo-fuga_el_chapo_guzman-joaquin_chapo_guzman_0_553144757.html|publisher=[[Milenio]]|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Flights at the [[Toluca International Airport]] were cancelled, while soldiers occupied parts of [[Mexico City International Airport]].<ref name=laescape /> Out of the 120 employees that were working at the prison that night, eighteen that worked in the area of Guzm\u00e1n's cell were initially detained for questioning.<ref name=procesofuga1>{{cite news| last1=Mendoza| first1=Veneranda| title=\"El Chapo\" tuvo dos horas para escapar; sobrevol\u00f3 la zona un \"helic\u00f3ptero peque\u00f1o\"| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=410421| magazine=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=12 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> By the afternoon, a total of 31 people had been called in for questioning. The director of the prison, Valent\u00edn C\u00e1rdenas Lerma, was among those detained.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Mosso| first1=Rub\u00e9n| title=Declaran 31 por fuga de el Chapo, entre ellos el director del penal |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/arely_gomex_penal_altiplano-fuga_chapo_guzman-joaquin_chapo_guzman_0_553144770.html| accessdate=12 July 2015|publisher=[[Milenio]]| date=12 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nWhen the news of the escape broke, President Pe\u00f1a Nieto was heading to a state visit in France along with several top officials from his cabinet and many others.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harrup|first1=Anthony|last2=Althaus|first2=Dudley|title=Mexican Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Escapes From Prison|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-escapes-from-prison-1436703513|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> The [[Secretariat of the Interior (Mexico)|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Osorio Chong]], who was already in France waiting for them, returned to Mexico after learning of Guzm\u00e1n's prison break.<ref>{{cite news|title=Una noticia congel\u00f3 el vuelo presidencial a Francia|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/articulo/nacion/politica/2015/07/12/una-noticia-congelo-el-vuelo-presidencial-francia|publisher=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]]|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Osorio Chong regresa a M\u00e9xico por fuga del Chapo|url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/osorio-chong-regresa-a-mexico-por-fuga-del-chapo.html|publisher=El Financiero|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> Pe\u00f1a Nieto returned to Mexico on 17 July.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rivera|first1=Carolina|title=Osorio Chong regresa a M\u00e9xico por fuga de 'El Chapo'|url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/Osorio_Chong_regresa_Mexico_fuga_-El_Chapo-fuga_chapo_guzman-guzman_loera_0_553144725.html|publisher=[[Milenio]]|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> In a press conference, Pe\u00f1a Nieto said he was shocked by Guzm\u00e1n's escape, and promised that the government would carry out an intensive investigation to see if officials had collaborated in the prison break. In addition, he claimed that Guzm\u00e1n's escape was an \"affront\" to the Mexican government, and that they would not spare any resources in trying to recapture him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fuga de 'el Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n es una \"afrenta\" al Estado mexicano: Pe\u00f1a|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2015/07/12/la-fuga-de-el-chapo-guzman-es-lamentable-e-indigna-pena|agency=[[Turner Broadcasting System]]|publisher=CNNM\u00e9xico|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Pe\u00f1a Nieto, however, was severely criticized for the incident, and media outlets pointed out that this incident was among the administration's most embarrassing episodes. Critics stated that Guzm\u00e1n's escape highlighted the high levels of corruption within the government, and questioned the government's ability to combat the country's organized crime groups.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Neuman|first1=William|last2=Ahmed|first2=Azam|title=Stunning Escape of Joaqu\u00edn 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Fuels Mexicans' Cynicism|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/14/world/americas/mexico-joaquin-guzman-loera-el-chapo-prison-escape.html|work=The New York Times|date=13 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Barrett|first1=Devlin|title=U.S. Officials Cite Intelligence Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Was Plotting Escape|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-officials-cite-intelligence-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-was-plotting-escape-1436807234|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=13 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July 2015, Osorio Chong met with members of the cabinet that specialize in security and law enforcement intelligence to discuss the escape of Guzm\u00e1n, and scheduled a press conference that day. The objective of the meeting and the conference was to analyze the actions the government employed to recapture him. Among them were Rubido Garc\u00eda, [[Arely G\u00f3mez Gonz\u00e1lez]], the Attorney General of Mexico and Eugenio Imaz Gispert, head of the [[Centro de Investigaci\u00f3n y Seguridad Nacional (M\u00e9xico)|Center for Research and National Security]].<ref>{{cite news| title=Osorio Chong encabeza reuniones para recapturar a Guzm\u00e1n| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=410463| magazine=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=13 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Osorio encabezar\u00e1 reuni\u00f3n de seguridad para buscar a 'El Chapo'| url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-fuga_Chapo_Guzman_0_553744723.html| publisher=[[Milenio]]| date=13 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> At the press conference, the government placed a $60 million MXN bounty (approximately US$3.8 million) for information that leads to Guzm\u00e1n's arrest.<ref>{{cite news| title=PGR ofrece 60 mdp de recompensa por 'El Chapo'| url=http://noticieros.televisa.com/coberturas/chapo-guzman/1507/pgr-ofrece-60-mdp-recompensa-chapo/| publisher=[[Televisa]]| date=13 July 2015| location=Mexico City| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nA number of officials were indicted; of these, three were police officers employed within the Division of Intelligence, and another two were employed by [[CISEN]].<ref>Business Insider \u2013 [http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/world/heres-why-el-chapo-probably-wont-be-recaptured-any-time-soon/ar-AAdIhbM news] published by [[msn]] 30 July 2015 [Retrieved 1 August 2015]</ref>\n\n==== Colombian assistance ====\nOfficials of the Mexican government appealed to three Colombian Police retired generals for assistance in the closure of issues relating to Guzm\u00e1n, according to a report dated to 1 August 2015.<ref name=\"Manhunters\">A. Dawber \u2013 [http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/world/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-manhunters-who-caught-pablo-escobar-are-tasked-with-tracking-down-escaped-mexican-drug-lord/ar-BBlgTbI Article:''Manhunters tasked with capture''] published by [[The Independent]] via msn [Retrieved 1 August 2015]</ref> Among them is [[Rosso Jos\u00e9 Serrano]], a decorated officer and one of the masterminds behind the dismantling of the [[Cali Cartel]] and [[Medell\u00edn Cartel]] and Luis Enrique Montenegro, protagonist in the arrests of [[Miguel Rodr\u00edguez Orejuela|Miguel]] and [[Gilberto Rodr\u00edguez Orejuela]]. They suggested particular Colombian strategies like creation of special search units (\"Bloques de B\u00fasqueda\" or [[Search Bloc]]s), specialized investigation and intelligence units, like [[DIJIN]] (Directorate of Criminal Investigation and Interpol) and DIPOL (Directorate of Police Intelligence) and new laws about [[money laundering]] and [[asset forfeiture]].<ref name=\"Manhunters\"/><ref>{{cite web|title = Luis Enrique Montenegro Rinco|url = http://www.semana.com/enfoque/articulo/luis-enrique-montenegro-rinco/126394-3|website = www.semana.com|accessdate = 9 January 2016}}</ref> After the third capture of Guzm\u00e1n, it was revealed that the [[Government of Colombia]] had sent a team of 12 officials to assist the Mexican authorities on tracking down Guzm\u00e1n.<ref>{{cite web| title=La asesor\u00eda en Colombia para la captura de 'El Chapo'| url=http://cnnespanol.cnn.com/video/cnnee-pkg-ramos-colombian-expertise-help-mexico-chapo/| accessdate=9 January 2016| date=9 January 2016}} (Spanish)</ref>\n\n==== Kate del Castillo meeting ====\nMexican actress [[Kate del Castillo]] was first approached by Guzm\u00e1n's lawyers in 2014,<ref name=Littleton10Jan>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2016/biz/news/kate-del-castillo-el-chapo-sean-penn-1201676183/| title=Kate del Castillo: Meet the Star Playing a Big Part in El Chapo's Real-Life Drama| first1=Cynthia| last1=Littleton| first2=John| last2=Hopewell| work=Variety| date=10 January 2016| accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref> after having published an open letter to Guzm\u00e1n in 2012 in which she expressed her sympathy and requested him to \"traffic in love\" instead of in drugs; Guzm\u00e1n reached out again to del Castillo after his 2015 escape,<ref name=\"extradition 2016\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/11/chapo-guzman-kate-del-castillo-letter_n_1199024.html |title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n, 'World's Most Powerful Drug Trafficker,' Receives Special Request From Mexican Actress, Kate Del Castillo |work=The Huffington Post |date=1 November 2012 |accessdate=2016-01-11 }}</ref> and allegedly sought to cooperate with her in making a film about his life.<ref name=Littleton10Jan/><ref name=Penn9Jan/> American actor [[Sean Penn]] heard about the connection with Ms. del Castillo through a mutual acquaintance, and asked if he might come along to do an interview.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/world/americas/el-chapo-mexican-drug-lord-interview-with-sean-penn.html Sean Penn Met With \u2018El Chapo\u2019 for Interview in His Hide-Out].  Ravi Somaiya, ''The New3 York Times''. 9 January 2016.</ref>\n\nOn 2 October, del Castillo and Penn visited Guzm\u00e1n for seven hours at his hideout in the mountains, with Penn interviewing the fugitive for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine.<ref name=Penn9Jan>{{cite news| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/el-chapo-speaks-40784/| title=El Chapo Speaks| work=Rolling Stone| first=Sean| last=Penn| date=9 January 2016| accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n, who had never before acknowledged his drug trafficking to a journalist, told Penn he had a \"fleet of [[narco-submarine]]s, airplanes, trucks and boats\" and that he supplied \"more heroin, methamphetamine, cocaine and marijuana than anybody else in the world\".<ref name=Penn9Jan />\n\nGuzm\u00e1n had a close call in early October 2015, several days after the meeting with Penn and Kate del Castillo.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan/><ref name=\"extradition 2016\"/> An unnamed Mexican official confirmed that the meeting helped authorities locate Guzm\u00e1n,<ref name=BBC10Jan>{{cite news| work=BBC| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-35276894| title='El Chapo' Guzman: Sean Penn interview provokes US scorn| date=10 January 2016| accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref> with cell phone interceptions and information from American authorities<ref name=Ahmed16Jan/> directing Mexican Marines to a ranch near [[Tamazula de Victoria|Tamazula]], [[Durango]], in the [[Sierra Madre Occidental|Sierra Madre]] mountains in western Mexico.<ref name=Castillo10Jan>{{cite news| url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/L/LT_MEXICO_DRUG_LORD?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-01-10-01-33-52| title= Sean Penn interview helped locate drug lord |date=10 January 2016| accessdate=10 January 2016| work=Associated Press| first1=E. Eduardo| last1=Castillo| first2=Katherine| last2=Corcoran}}</ref> The raid on the ranch was met with heavy gunfire and Guzm\u00e1n was able to flee. The [[Attorney General of Mexico|Attorney General of M\u00e9xico]] declared that \"El Chapo ran away through a gully and, although he was found by a helicopter, he was with two women and a girl and it was decided not to shoot\".<ref>{{cite web| title = Cellphone Signals Suggest 'El Chapo' Hid in Mexican Mountains: Sources| url = https://www.nbcnews.com/news/mexico/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-may-have-hid-mexican-mountains-sources-n444206| website = NBC News| accessdate = 9 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = 'El Chapo' en el momento de la detenci\u00f3n: \"\u00a1Pinches federales, ya nos atraparon!\"| url = http://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2016/01/09/56909b6e46163f45048b4591.html| website = El Mundo |accessdate =10 January 2016| date = 9 January 2016}}</ref> The two women were later revealed to be Guzm\u00e1n's personal chefs, who had traveled with him to multiple safe houses. At one point, Guzm\u00e1n reportedly carried a child on his arms \"obscuring himself as a target\".<ref name=Ahmed16Jan>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/17/world/americas/mexico-el-chapo-sinaloa.html| title=The Manhunt for the Drug Kingpin El Chapo|work=The New York Times|date=16 January 2016|accessdate=16 January 2016| first=Azam| last=Ahmed}}</ref>\n\n=== Third arrest: 2016 ===\n[[File:Mensaje a los medios de comunicaci\u00f3n, 8 Enero 2016.jpg|thumbnail|President [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]], accompanied by [[Cabinet of Mexico|Cabinet members]], holds a press conference in the [[National Palace (Mexico)|Palacio Nacional]] announcing the capture of Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n]]\nAccording to the official report published by the [[Mexican Navy]], citizens reported \"armed people\" in a house at the coastal city of [[Los Mochis]] in northern Sinaloa, which was then placed under surveillance for one month.<ref name=\"surveillance\">{{cite news |last=Martinez |first=Michael |last2=Karimi |first2=Faith |last3=Romo |first3=Rafael |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/09/americas/el-chapo-captured-mexico/index.html |title='El Chapo' dreamed of biopic; it helps lead to recapture, extradition process |publisher=CNN |date=9 January 2016 |accessdate=10 January 2016 }}</ref> Monitored communications indicated the home was being prepared for the arrival of \"Grandma\" or \"Aunt\", which authorities suspected was code for a high-priority potential target.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan /> After the gunmen returned to the house, placing a large order for tacos at a nearby restaurant and picking up the order in a white van after midnight,<ref name=Ahmed16Jan /> the residence was raided in the early hours of 8 January 2016,<ref name=\"surveillance\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Marina de M\u00e9xico emite comunicado oficial sobre \"El Chapo\" |url=http://www.latribuna.hn/?p=11707853 |website=Diario La Tribuna Honduras |accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> in [[Operation Black Swan]], by 17 marines from the [[Fuerzas Especiales|Mexican Navy's Special Forces]] with support from the Mexican Army and the Federal Police<ref name=\"2016 capture\">{{cite news |last=Schuppe |first=Jon |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/el-chapo-notorious-mexican-drug-kingpin-captured-authorities-n492956 |title=El Chapo: Notorious Mexican Drug Kingpin Captured by Authorities |publisher=NBC News |date=8 January 2016 |accessdate=8 January 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Recapturan a \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/especiales/nacion/2016/01/8/260967/nota/261085/0/capturan-el-cholo-junto-el-chapo#info |website=El Universal |accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> \u2013 but Guzm\u00e1n and a lieutenant escaped through a secret tunnel, emerging 1.5&nbsp;km away and stealing a vehicle at gunpoint.\n\nA statewide alert was issued for the stolen vehicle, and the Federal Police located and intercepted it about 20&nbsp;km south of Los Mochis near the town of [[Juan Jos\u00e9 R\u00edos, Sinaloa|Juan Jos\u00e9 R\u00edos]].<ref name=\"bribe offered\">{{cite news |last=Valencia |first=Alejandro |url=http://tamaulipaszonadeguerra.com/cartel-de-sinaloa/se-van-a-morir-todos-ustedes-no-saben-quien-soy-dijo-el-chapo-a-federales-hasta-selfies-se-tomaron/ |title=\"\u00a1Se van a morir todos ustedes! \u00bfNo saben qui\u00e9n soy?\" dijo El Chapo a Federales, hasta selfies se tomaron |work=Zona de Guerra |language=Spanish |date=11 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115090448/http://tamaulipaszonadeguerra.com/cartel-de-sinaloa/se-van-a-morir-todos-ustedes-no-saben-quien-soy-dijo-el-chapo-a-federales-hasta-selfies-se-tomaron/ |archive-date=15 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n attempted to bribe the officers with offers of cash, properties, and offers of jobs.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan /><ref name=\"bribe offered\" /> When the officers refused, Guzm\u00e1n told them \"you are all going to die\". The four police officers sent pictures of Guzm\u00e1n to their superiors, who were tipped that 40 assassins were on their way to free Guzm\u00e1n.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan /> To avoid this counter-attack by cartel members, the policemen were told to take their prisoners to a motel on the outskirts of town to wait for reinforcements,<ref name=\"bribe offered\" /><ref>{{cite web| title=As\u00ed se captur\u00f3 a Joaqu\u00edn Loera Guzm\u00e1n, 'El Chapo', el pr\u00f3fugo m\u00e1s buscado del mundo| url=http://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2016/01/09/56909b6e46163f45048b4591.html| publisher=El Mundo| accessdate=9 January 2016| date=9 January 2016}}</ref> and later, hand over the prisoners to the marines.<ref>{{cite news |last=P\u00e1ez |first=Hugo |url=http://impacto.mx/opinion/policia-federal-enfrenta-a-marinos-y-entrega-al-chapo |title=Polic\u00eda Federal enfrenta a marinos y entrega al 'Chapo' |language=Spanish |work=Impacto |date=13 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117175816/http://impacto.mx/opinion/policia-federal-enfrenta-a-marinos-y-entrega-al-chapo |archive-date=17 January 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> They were subsequently taken to Los Mochis airport for transport to Mexico City, where Guzm\u00e1n was presented to the press at the Mexico City airport and then flown by a Navy helicopter to the same maximum-security prison from which he escaped in July 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-captured-1452278572 |title=Mexican Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Recaptured |date=9 January 2016 |access-date=9 January 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\nDuring the raid, five gunmen were killed, six others arrested, and one Marine was wounded.<ref name=\"2016 capture\" /> The Mexican Navy said that they found two [[Armored car (VIP)|armored cars]], eight assault rifles, including two [[Barrett M82]] sniper rifles, two [[M16 rifle]]s with [[grenade launchers]] and a loaded [[rocket-propelled grenade]] launcher.<ref>{{cite web| title=Recapturan a \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n| url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/especiales/nacion/2016/01/8/260967/nota/261004/0/incautan-vehiculos-en-recaptura-del-el-chapo#info| website=El Universal| accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Reactions ====\nSecretary of the Interior [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Osorio Chong]] was hosting a reunion with Mexico's ambassadors and consuls when he received a notice from the President on Guzm\u00e1n's capture.<ref name=\"Noticieros Televisa 2016\">{{cite web|last1=Madrigal|first1=Guadalupe|title=Osorio Chong recibi\u00f3 una tarjeta, se apart\u00f3 y llam\u00f3 a EPN|url=http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1601/osorio-chong-recibio-tarjeta-se-aparto-llamo-epn/|publisher=Noticieros Televisa|accessdate=9 January 2016|date=8 January 2016}}</ref> He returned a few moments later with Secretary of National Defense [[Salvador Cienfuegos Zepeda]], Secretary of Navy [[Vidal Francisco Sober\u00f3n Sanz]] and Secretary of Foreign Affairs [[Claudia Ruiz Massieu]].<ref name=\"Noticieros Televisa 2016\" /> Osorio Chong then announced the capture to the diplomats by reading the President's tweet which resulted in applause and chants of ''Viva M\u00e9xico'', ''Viva el Presidente Pe\u00f1a'' and ''Viva las Fuerzas Armadas'' (Long live Mexico, Long live President Pe\u00f1a, Long live our Military Forces).<ref name=\"Once Noticias 2016\">{{cite web|title=Once Noticias \u2013 Embajadores y c\u00f3nsules aplauden la reaprehensi\u00f3n de \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=sv2XLeCBRrE|via=YouTube|publisher=[[Canal Once (Mexico)|Canal Once]]|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> This was followed by a spontaneous rendition of the [[Himno Nacional Mexicano|National Anthem]] by the crowd.<ref name=\"Noticieros Televisa 2016\" /><ref name=\"Once Noticias 2016\" />\n\nColombian President [[Juan Manuel Santos]] congratulated Mexican President [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]] for the capture of Guzm\u00e1n. Santos stated that \"Guzm\u00e1n's capture is a success, a great blow against organized crime, and drug trafficking\", adding that \"finally, this individual (Guzm\u00e1n), like all criminals, will find what he deserves in the eyes of justice, and we celebrate that the Mexican authorities have recaptured this criminal\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Santos felicita a Pe\u00f1a Nieto por recaptura de \"El Chapo\", importante socio de las Farc| url=http://www.elespectador.com/noticias/elmundo/santos-felicita-pena-nieto-recaptura-de-el-chapo-import-articulo-609603|work=El Espectador|accessdate=9 January 2016| date=9 January 2016}} (Spanish)</ref> [[Loretta Lynch]], United States Attorney General, praised Mexican authorities \"who have worked tirelessly in recent months to bring Guzm\u00e1n to justice\".\n\n== United States extradition and prosecution ==\n{{Main|United States of America v. Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera}}\n\n[[File:El Chapo in U.S. 1.jpg|thumb|Guzm\u00e1n in U.S. custody when extradited on 19 January 2017.]]\n[[File:Booking photo of Joaquin \u201cEl Chapo\u201c Guzman (side and front).jpg|thumb|[[Mugshot]] taken shortly after Guzm\u00e1n was extradited.]]\nMexico formally launched a renewed process of extradition to the United States two days after Guzm\u00e1n was recaptured on 8 January 2016 after his second prison escape.<ref name=\"extradition 2016\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35278176 |title=El Chapo Guzman: Extradition to US could take 'at least year' |work=CNN News |date=11 January 2015 |accessdate=2016-01-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world |title=Mexico moves to extradite 'El Chapo' |work=BBC News |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=9 January 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Almasy |first=Steve |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/08/us/el-chapo-us-extradition/index.html |title=U.S. indicates Washington wants 'El Chapo' extradited |work=CNN News |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=9 January 2016 }}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n's lawyers mounted \"numerous and creative injunctions\" to prevent extradition.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan/><ref>{{cite news |last=Pestano |first=Andrew V. |url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/01/11/Mexico-El-Chapo-extradition-could-take-up-to-six-years/7891452529818/ |title=Mexico: 'El Chapo' extradition could take up to six years |work=UPI |date=11 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-13 }}</ref> [[Murder of Vicente Berm\u00fadez Zacar\u00edas|Vicente Antonio Berm\u00fadez Zacar\u00edas]] was a federal judge involved in Guzm\u00e1n's extradition proceedings, and he was assassinated on 17 October 2016 while jogging near Mexico City.<ref>{{cite news |title=A federal judge who ruled on some of Mexico's highest profile criminal cases was gunned down in broad daylight |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=18 October 2016 |author=Patrick J. McDonnell |url=https://latimes.com/world/mexico-americas/la-fg-mexico-judge-20161018-snap-story.html |accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n was wanted in Chicago, San Diego, New York City, New Hampshire, Miami, and Texas, in addition to having indictments in at least seven different U.S. federal courts.<ref name=\"Process 2016\">{{cite news |url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-briefs/el-chapo-the-extradition-process-briefly-explained |title='El Chapo': Mexico's Extradition Process Briefly Explained |work=InSight Crime |date=11 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-13 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.businessinsider.com/ap-a-look-at-the-extradition-process-for-el-chapo-guzman-2016-1 A look at the extradition process for 'El Chapo' Guzman]. Eric Tucker and Alicia A. Caldwell, ''Business Insider''. 12 January 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2016/01/11/coming-america-el-chapo-could-fight-extradition-years/78622760/ Coming to America: Why the El Chapo extradition could take years]. John Bacon, ''USA Today''. 13 January 2016.</ref> Charges in the United States include drug trafficking with intent to distribute, conspiracy association, organized crime against health, money laundering, homicide, illegal possession of firearms,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/el-chapos-extradition-process-set-to-begin/ |title=El Chapo's extradition process set to begin |work=Mexico News Daily |date=12 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-13 }}</ref> kidnapping, and murder in Chicago, Miami, New York, and other cities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-faces-life-sentence-u-s-n709556|title=Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' faces life sentence in U.S. prison|publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-court-york/story?id=44915563|title='El Chapo' Pleads Not Guilty in 1st Appearance in New York Courtroom|date=20 January 2017|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/opa/legacy/2009/08/20/chapo-mayo-indictment.pdf|title=Chapo-Mayo Superseding Infictment|last=News|date=20 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref> A critical requirement for extradition was that the U.S. must guarantee that they would not sentence Guzm\u00e1n to death if he were found guilty of homicide charges.<ref name=\"Process 2016\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Estados Unidos no ejecutar\u00e1 a El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n si es extraditado |url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/actualidad/estados-unidos-ejecutara-chapo-guzman-extraditado-208432 |website=El Comercio |language=es |date=12 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo, if convicted, would likely do time in 'Supermax' prison|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mexico-crime-chapo-prison-idUSKBN1550E0?il=0|accessdate=21 January 2017|work=Reuters|date=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 January 2017, Guzm\u00e1n was extradited to the U.S. to face the charges and turned over to the custody of HSI and DEA agents.<ref name=\"ChapoExtradited\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/el-chapo-mexico-extradites-drug-lord-joaquin-guzman-to-us/|title=Mexico says it has extradited drug lord Joaquin \"El Chapo\" Guzman to U.S.|publisher=CBS News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://europe.newsweek.com/el-chapo-mexico-drug-lord-mexican-drug-cartels-544940|title=Top Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' extradited to U.S.|magazine=Newsweek}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/mexico-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzaman-extradited-us-44900272|title=Mexico Says Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Guzman Extradited to US|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> He was housed at the maximum-security wing of the [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York]] located in Manhattan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-headed-new-york-jail-article-1.2950794|title=Drug lord 'El Chapo' headed to New York jail from Mexico|newspaper=New York Daily News}}</ref> He pled not guilty on 20 January to a 17-count indictment in the United States District Court in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/20/us/el-chapo-guzman-extradition/index.html|title='El Chapo' Guzman pleads not guilty in US to 17 counts|author1=Ray Sanchez |author2=Phil Gast |author3=Catherine E. Shoichet |author4=Evan Perez|publisher=CNN}}</ref> U.S. District Judge [[Brian Cogan]] scheduled his trial for 5 November 2018, when jury selection began.<ref>[https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2018/07/16/Judge-delays-start-of-El-Chapo-trial-by-two-months/9811531782964/ Judge delays start of 'El Chapo' trial by two months]. Daniel Uria, UPI. July 16, 2018.</ref> According to the prosecutors, juror anonymity and an armed escort are necessary even if Guzm\u00e1n is in isolation due to his history of having jurors and witnesses murdered.<ref name=lawyer>[http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/01/25/el-chapo-promises-not-to-kill-any-jurors.html 'El Chapo' promises not to kill any jurors, lawyer says]. ''Fox News''. January 25, 2018</ref><ref>[http://www.ladbible.com/news/news-el-chapo-promises-he-wont-have-jurors-swimming-with-the-fishes-20180125 El Chapo Promises He Won\u2019t Have Jurors Swimming With The Fishes]. Mischa Pearlman. 25 January 2018.</ref> The judge agreed to keep jurors anonymous and to have Guzm\u00e1n transported to and from the courthouse by U.S. Marshals and sequestered from the public while in the courthouse.<ref>[http://www.businessinsider.com/juror-identities-el-chapo-guzman-federal-trial-secret-2018-2 The identities of the jurors in Mexican cartel kingpin 'El Chapo' Guzman's federal trial will be kept secret]. Christopher Woody. ''Business Insider''. 7 February 2018.</ref> Opening arguments began Tuesday November 13,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/05/nyregion/el-chapo-trial-jury.html Wanted: 12 People Willing to Serve as Jurors in El Chapo Trial]. Alan Feuer, ''The New York Times''. November 2018.</ref> and closing arguments took place on 31 January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/01/31/690468846/closing-arguments-heard-in-trial-of-joaquin-el-chapo-guzm-n|title=Closing Arguments Heard In Trial Of Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n was found guilty of all counts on 12 February 2019, and was sentenced on 17 July 2019 to life in prison plus 30 years<ref name=\"SentenceBBC\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/1d5b01e6b8ee4dd29319349bcebc1dcd|title=Mexico's El Chapo sentenced to life in prison|website=apnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=El Chapo trial: Mexican drug lord Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n gets life in prison|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-49022208|work=BBC News|date=17 July 2019 |accessdate=17 July 2019 }}</ref> and ordered to forfeit more than $12.6 billion.<ref name=\"Hong\"/> He is now serving his sentence at [[ADX Florence]], the nation's most secure supermax prison under Federal Register Number 89914-053.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wkzo.com/news/articles/2019/jul/19/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-at-supermax-prison-in-colorado/919764/|title=Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' begins life term in Colorado 'Supermax' prison|first=Midwest Communications|last=Inc|website=WKZO}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=After two escapes, 'El Chapo' may go to 'Supermax' prison to avoid a third|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-mexico-el-chapo-supermax/after-two-escapes-el-chapo-may-go-to-supermax-prison-to-avoid-a-third-idUSKCN1UC142|work=Reuters|date=17 July 2019 |accessdate=17 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal and family criminal activities ==\nGuzm\u00e1n's family is heavily involved in drug trafficking. Several members of his family, including his brother, one of his sons, and a nephew were killed by Sinaloa's archrival cartels, [[Los Zetas]] and the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Organization.<ref name=insight />\n\nIn 1977, Guzm\u00e1n married Alejandrina Mar\u00eda Salazar Hern\u00e1ndez in a small ceremony in the town of Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda, Sinaloa. The couple had at least three children: C\u00e9sar, Iv\u00e1n Archivaldo, and Jes\u00fas Alfredo. He set them up in a ranch home in Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda.\n\nWhen he was 30 years old, El Chapo fell in love with a bank clerk, Estela Pe\u00f1a of [[Nayarit]], whom he kidnapped and with whom he had sexual relations. They later married.\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Guzm\u00e1n married once more, to Griselda L\u00f3pez P\u00e9rez, with whom he had four more children: \u00c9dgar, Joaqu\u00edn, [[Ovidio Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez|Ovidio]], and Griselda Guadalupe.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Women, the Achilles heel of 'El Chapo' Guzman |url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/2014/02/22/945140 |accessdate=12 January 2016 |newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n's sons followed him into the drug business, and his third wife, L\u00f3pez P\u00e9rez, was arrested in 2010, in [[Culiac\u00e1n]].<ref name=\"LAT daughter\">{{cite news| title=Wife of Fugitive Mexican Drug Lord Arrested, Press Says| url=http://www.laht.com/article.asp?CategoryId=14091&ArticleId=356911| accessdate=22 February 2012|newspaper=[[Latin American Herald Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, Guzm\u00e1n married an 18-year-old American beauty queen, [[Emma Coronel Aispuro]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dailyentertainmentnews.com/breaking-news/emma-coronel-guzman-joaquin-el-chapo-guzmans-wife/| title=Emma Coronel- El Chapo's young American Wife |accessdate=22 February 2014|date=February 2014}}</ref> the daughter of one of his top deputies, In\u00e9s Coronel Barreras, in Canelas, Durango.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7938904.stm |work=BBC News| title=Mexican 'drug lord' on rich list|date=12 March 2009| accessdate=6 May 2010| first=Stephen|last=Gibbs}}</ref><ref name=\"In\u00e9s Coronel\">{{cite news|last=Barros |first=Guillermo |title=Mexican police detain drug kingpin's father-in-law |url=http://uk.news.yahoo.com/mexican-police-detain-drug-kingpins-father-law-001528438.html#DOt3euy |accessdate=2 May 2013 |newspaper=[[Yahoo! News]] |date=1 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714170607/https://uk.news.yahoo.com/mexican-police-detain-drug-kingpins-father-law-001528438.html |url-status=live |archivedate= 14 July 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>Revista Proceso, Mexico DF, 2007</ref> In August 2011, she gave birth to twin girls, Maria Joaquina and Emali Guadalupe, in [[Los Angeles County Hospital]], in California.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2011/09/mexico-el-chapo-guzman-emma-coronel-twins-lancaster-antelope-valley.html |work=Los Angeles Times| title=Drug lord's wife has twins in Los Angeles County hospital| date=26 September 2011| accessdate=27 September 2011| first=Tracy| last=Wilkinson}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/quienes-son-las-esposas-e-hijos-de-el-chapo-guzman-fotos-y-videos,76b9ca117d14c179a815cc4306f99530gzy9RCRD.html| work=Terra Networks| title=Mujeres de 'El Chapo': Las seduce con dinero y amenaza con armas\n| date=12 July 2015| accessdate=12 January 2016| first=Anna| last=Lagos| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2013, Guzm\u00e1n's father-in-law, [[In\u00e9s Coronel Barreras]], was captured by Mexican authorities in [[Agua Prieta]], Sonora, with no gunfire exchanged. U.S. authorities believe Coronel Barreras was a \"key operative\" of the Sinaloa Cartel who grew and smuggled marijuana through the Arizona border area.<ref name=\"In\u00e9s Coronel\" />\n\nOn 15 February 2005, Guzm\u00e1n's son Iv\u00e1n Archivaldo, known as \"El Chapito\", was arrested in Guadalajara on [[money laundering]] charges.<ref name=\"Beltran Leon\">{{cite news|last=Gomez Licon|first=Adriana|title=Jesus Alfredo Guzm\u00e1n Salazar Arrested? Identity Of Capo's Son Questioned In Mexico|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/22/jesus-alfredo-guzman-salazar-arrested_n_1619373.html|accessdate=23 February 2014|work=The Huffington Post|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=22 June 2012}}</ref> He was sentenced to five years in a federal prison but released in April 2008, after a Mexican federal judge, Jes\u00fas Guadalupe Luna, ruled that there was no proof his cash came from drugs other than that he was a drug lord's son.<ref name=\"Mexican judges\">{{cite news| last=Gomez Licon|first=Adriana| title=Mexico Drug Cases Federal Judges Suspended For Possible Irregularities |url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/02/mexico-drug-cases-judges-_n_1565262.html |accessdate=22 February 2014|work=The Huffington Post| agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=6 June 2012}}</ref> Luna and another judge were later suspended on suspicion of unspecified irregularities in their decisions, including Luna's decision to release \"El Chapito\".<ref name=\"Mexican judges\" />\n\nGuzm\u00e1n's son \u00c9dgar Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez died after a 2008 ambush in a shopping center parking lot, in Culiac\u00e1n, Sinaloa.<ref name=\"AP El Gordo\">{{cite news |title=Mexico marines detain suspected son of drug lord| url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/story/2012-06-22/mexico-detains-drug-lord-son/55754648/1| accessdate=22 February 2012| newspaper=[[USA Today]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=22 June 2012}}</ref> Afterwards, police found more than 500 [[AK-47]] bullet casings at the scene.<ref name=\"AP El Gordo\" /> Guzm\u00e1n's brother Arturo, known as \"El Pollo\", was killed in prison in 2004.<ref name=insight />\n\nAnother of Guzm\u00e1n's sons, Jes\u00fas Alfredo Guzm\u00e1n Salazar, known as \"El Gordo\" (\"The Fat One\"), then 23 years old, was suspected of being a member of the cartel and was indicted on federal charges of drug trafficking in 2009 with Guzm\u00e1n, by the U.S. District Court of Northern Illinois, which oversees Chicago.<ref name=\"Beltran Leon\" /><ref name=\"BBC El Gordo\">{{cite news| title=Mexico arrests son of top drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-18543635| accessdate=22 February 2012 |newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=22 June 2012}}</ref> Authorities described Guzm\u00e1n Salazar as a growing force within his father's organization and directly responsible for Sinaloa's drug trade between the U.S. and Mexico and for managing his billionaire father's growing list of properties. Guzm\u00e1n Salazar and his mother, Guzm\u00e1n's former wife Mar\u00eda Alejandrina Salazar Hern\u00e1ndez, were both described as key operatives in the Sinaloa Cartel and added to the U.S.'s financial sanction list under the [[Kingpin Act]] on 7 June 2012.<ref name=\"BBC El Gordo\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Otero|first=Silvia|title=Esposa e hijo de 'El Chapo' en lista de narcos de EU| url=http://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/852073.html| accessdate=7 June 2012| newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]| date=7 June 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=\"salazar sanctions\">{{cite web|url= http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg1609.aspx|title=Treasury Targets Operatives of Sinaloa Cartel|author=Staff |date=7 June 2012| publisher=United States Department of the Treasury| accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. Treasury Department described Salazar as Guzm\u00e1n's wife, in its sanction against her, and described Guzm\u00e1n as her husband.<ref name=\"salazar sanctions\" /> The month before, the U.S. Treasury Department had announced sanctions against Guzm\u00e1n's sons Iv\u00e1n Guzm\u00e1n Salazar and [[Ovidio Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez]] under the Kingpin Act.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/world/2012/05/08/us-targets-2-sons-sinaloa-cartel-leader US targets 2 sons of Sinaloa cartel leader] ''Fox News''; 8 May 2012.</ref> Guzm\u00e1n's second wife, Griselda L\u00f3pez P\u00e9rez, was also sanctioned by the U.S. under the Kingpin Act and described as Guzm\u00e1n's wife.<ref name=\"Forbes daughter\">{{cite news| last=Carlyle|first=Erin|title=Alleged Daughter Of Mexican Billionaire Druglord El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n Arrested Trying To Cross Border, Won't Talk |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erincarlyle/2012/10/17/alleged-daughter-of-mexican-billionaire-druglord-el-chapo-guzman-arrested-trying-to-cross-border-wont-talk| accessdate=22 February 2012 |newspaper=[[Forbes]]| date=17 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nJes\u00fas Guzm\u00e1n Salazar was reported to have been detained by Mexican Marines in an early morning raid, in the western state of [[Jalisco]] on 21 June 2012.<ref>{{cite news| last=Allen|first=Nick| title=Son of Sinaloa drug cartel's Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n captured| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/9347880/Son-of-Sinaloa-drug-cartels-Joaquin-El-Chapo-Guzman-captured.html |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[The Sunday Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=21 June 2012}}</ref> Months later, however, the Mexican Attorney General's Office announced the Marines had arrested the wrong man and that the man captured was actually F\u00e9lix Beltr\u00e1n Le\u00f3n, who said he was a used-car dealer, not the drug lord's son.<ref name=\"Beltran Leon\" /> U.S. and Mexican authorities blamed each other for providing the inaccurate information that led to the arrest.<ref name=\"Beltran Leon\" />\n\nIn 2012, Alejandrina Gisselle Guzm\u00e1n Salazar, a 31-year-old pregnant physician and Mexican citizen from Guadalajara, was said to have claimed she was Guzm\u00e1n's daughter as she crossed the U.S. border into San Diego.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|last1=Marosi|first1=Richard|last2=Wilkinson|first2=Tracy|title=Woman claiming to be drug trafficker's daughter is arrested| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/16/local/la-me-chapo-daughter-20121016|accessdate=22 February 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=16 October 2012}}</ref> She was arrested on fraud charges for entering the country with a false visa.<ref name=\"LAT daughter\" /> Unnamed officials said the woman was the daughter of Mar\u00eda Alejandrina Salazar Hern\u00e1ndez but did not appear to be a major figure in the cartel. She had planned to meet the father of her child in Los Angeles and give birth in the United States.<ref name=\"LAT daughter\" />\n\nOn the night of 17 June 2012, Obied Cano Zepeda, a nephew of Guzm\u00e1n's, was gunned down by unknown assailants at his home in the state capital of [[Culiac\u00e1n]], while hosting a [[Father's Day]] celebration.<ref name=diadelpadre /> The gunmen, who were reportedly carrying [[AK-47]] rifles, also killed two other guests and left another seriously injured.<ref name=diadelpadre>{{cite news|title=Asesinan a sobrino de El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=311451|accessdate=20 June 2012|newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=19 June 2012|language=es}}</ref>\n\nObied was a brother of Luis Alberto Cano Zepeda (''alias'' \"El Blanco\")'s, another nephew of Guzm\u00e1n's who worked as a pilot drug transporter for the Sinaloa cartel.<ref name=elblanco>{{cite news| last=Torres|first=Rub\u00e9n| title=Asesinan al sobrino de El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/seguridad-publica/2012/06/19/ejecutan-sobrino-chapo-sinaloa|accessdate=20 June 2012|newspaper=[[El Economista (Mexico)|El Economista]]|date=19 June 2012|language=es}}</ref> The latter was arrested by the Mexican military in August 2006.<ref name=elblanco /> ''InSight Crime'' notes that Obied's murder may have been either a retaliation attack by [[Los Zetas]], for Guzm\u00e1n's incursions into their territory, or a brutal campaign heralding Los Zetas' presence in [[Sinaloa]].<ref>{{cite news| last=Knott|first=Tracey| title=El Chapo Nephew Gunned Down at Family Party| url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-briefs/el-chapo-nephew-gunned-down-at-family-party| accessdate=2 March 2014| newspaper=[[InSight Crime]]|date=20 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nEven after Guzman's arrest, the Sinaloa Cartel remained the primary drug distributor (in 2018) in the U.S. among Mexican cartels, according to the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/ny-mexico-guzman-sentence-1.5214643 |title=Drug kingpin Joaquin (El Chapo) Guzman gets life sentence, says jail has been 'mental torture' |date=July 17, 2019 |work=Fortune |access-date=July 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n=== Literature ===\nMartin Corona, the chief assassin for a rival cartel of Sinaloa's who mistakenly killed a priest when aiming at Guzm\u00e1n, published a tell-all memoir titled ''Confessions of a Cartel Hit Man'' in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|author=Connelly, Sherryl|date=15 July 2017|work=New York Daily News|title=Executioner for Sinaloa rival details how he almost took out El Capo in 'Confessions of a Cartel Hit Man'}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nSeveral Mexican ''[[narcocorrido]]s'' (narco ballads) narrate the exploits of Guzm\u00e1n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnnmexico.com/nacional/2015/07/13/la-segunda-fuga-de-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-ya-tiene-dos-narcocorridos|title=La segunda fuga de Joaqu\u00edn 'el Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n ya tiene dos narcocorridos|date=13 July 2015|work=CNN|language=Spanish|location=Mexico|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/2015/07/13/1034501|title=De Lupillo Rivera a Regulo\u2026 los corridos sobre la fuga de 'El Chapo'|work=Exc\u00e9lsior|language=Spanish|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chilango.com/cultura/nota/2014/02/24/11-narcos-y-sus-corridos|title=12 narcos y sus corridos (Canciones de sangre, violencia y crimen)|language=Spanish|date=9 October 2014|website=chilango.com|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/el-regreso-del-chapo-mt0003041507|title=El Regreso del Chapo|website=AllMusic|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/11-narcocorridos-que-inspiro-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman|language=Spanish||title=11 narcocorridos que inspir\u00f3 Joaqu\u00edn \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n|work=People en Espanol|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/el-comandante-antrax-mt0048963603|title=El Comandante Antrax|website=AllMusic|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> and his organization. Additionally, some [[Americans|American]] artists have made songs with references to Guzm\u00e1n, such as the rappers [[Uncle Murda]], [[Skrillex]], [[YG (rapper)|YG]], [[Gucci Mane]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/12/world/americas/mexico-el-chapo-profile/|title=The legend of 'El Chapo': Hiding in plain sight? | author1=Shoichet, Catherine E. |author2=Melvin, Don  |author3=Castillo, Mariano  |date=12 July 2015|work=CNN| accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref> and [[The Game (rapper)|The Game]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://noisey.vice.com/es_mx/blog/the-game-acaba-de-lanzar-una-cancin-dedicada-al-chapo|title=The Game y Skrillex acaban de lanzar una canci\u00f3n dedicada al Chapo|work=NOISEY|language=Spanish|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://espectaculos.televisa.com/musica/noticias/865919/chapo-joaquin-guzman-loera-tambien-tiene-hip-hop-corridos/|title=No s\u00f3lo corridos, 'El Chapo' tambi\u00e9n tiene su hip hop|author=Televisa TIM|language=Spanish|work=Televisa Entretenimiento|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\nIn 2017, [[Netflix]] and [[Univision]] began co-producing the series ''[[El Chapo (TV series)|El Chapo]]'' about the life of Guzm\u00e1n.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/univision-netflix-el-chapo-series-sets-april-premiere-w463155|title=Univision, Netflix 'El Chapo' Series Sets April Premiere|first=Jon|last=Blistein|date=26 January 2017|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> The series premiered on Sunday, 23 April 2017 at 8PM/7C on Univision and was followed by a 20-minute [[Facebook]] Live after-show titled \"El Chapo Ilimitado\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elchapotheseries.kinja.com/the-story-of-el-chapo-comes-to-univision-1794468954|title=The story of \"El Chapo\" comes to Univision|last=|first=|date=|website=kinja.com|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fmg.kinja.com/univision-launches-el-chapo-ilimitado-first-live-a-1794544950|title=Univision Launches 'El Chapo Ilimitado' -- First Live After-Show for New Series 'El Chapo'|last=|first=|date=|website=kinja.com|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n is also portrayed by Alejandro Edda in the [[Netflix]] television series ''[[Narcos: Mexico]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of Mexico's 37 most-wanted drug lords]]\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}<!-- NB. When indent option is used,  please use a colon (:) instead of asterisk (*) for bullet markers in the references list -->\n\n: {{cite book|author=Bagley, Bruce  |title=Drug trafficking and organized crime in the Americas & he was the drug lord: Major trends in the twenty-first century|year=2012|publisher=Woodrow Wilson Center Latin American Program|isbn=978-1-56000-752-4|url=http://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/BB%20Final.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117130542/http://wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/BB%20Final.pdf|archivedate=17 January 2013 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|author=Beith, Malcolm  |title=The Last Narco: Inside the Hunt for El Chapo, the World's Most Wanted Drug Lord|year=2010|publisher=[[Grove Press]]|isbn=978-0-8021-9622-4|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Last_Narco.html?id=Jmid9oCEz04C|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book|author=Cockburn, Alexander  |title=Whiteout: The CIA, Drugs, and the Press|year=1998|publisher=Verso|isbn=978-1-85984-139-6|url=https://archive.org/details/whiteoutciadrugs00cock|url-access=registration  |quote=Whiteout: The CIA, Drugs, and the Press.  |ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book|last=Edmonds-Poli|first= Emily  | last2=Shirk|first2=David A.| title=Contemporary Mexican Politics|year=2009|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|isbn=978-0-7425-4049-1|url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarymexi0000edmo|url-access=registration|quote=El Chapo Guzman.|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|author=Hern\u00e1ndez, Anabel  |title=Los Se\u00f1ores del Narco|year=2012|publisher=[[Random House]]|isbn=978-6073108485|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Los_se%C3%B1ores_del_narco.html?id=oVLXjMuUrTgC|language=Spanish|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book|author=Grayson, George W.  |title=Mexico: Narco-Violence and a Failed State?|year=2011|publisher=[[Transaction Publishers]]|isbn=978-1-4128-1551-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ogjkeCd7RGoC&dq=El+Narco:+Inside+Mexico%27s+Criminal+Insurgency|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book|author=Longmire, Sylvia  |title=Cartel: The Coming Invasion of Mexico's Drug Wars|year=2011|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]|isbn=978-0-230-11137-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=B9fge8lQpcYC&dq=El+Narco:+Inside+Mexico%27s+Criminal+Insurgency|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book|author=Richards, James R.  |title=Transnational Criminal Organizations, Cybercrime, and Money Laundering: A Handbook for Law Enforcement Officers, Auditors, and Financial Investigators|year=1998|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|isbn=978-1-4200-4872-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RmGi5zDus7gC&dq=Enrique+Rafael+Clavel+Moreno+arellano+felix|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book|author=Tuckman, Jo  |title=Mexico: Democracy Interrupted|date=2012|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|isbn=978-0-300-16031-4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RCpYG10O30AC&dq=El+Chapo+Guzman|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Refend}} <!--close biblio/reference style options -->\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera}}\n* [https://www.forbes.com/profile/joaquin-guzman-loera/ Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera's profile] at [[Forbes]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150524012151/https://www.dea.gov/fugitives/elp/8EAD6E56-C8D6-42C6-8797-75D7ED3E6315.shtml Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera's profile] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20151031235736/http://www.dea.gov/resources/img/Ads/guzman-e.html wanted poster] from the [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150924051405/http://www.interpol.int/en/layout/set/print/notice/search/wanted/1993-25358 Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera's profile] at the [[INTERPOL]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131025051559/http://www.chicagocrimecommission.org/content.aspx?page_id=22&club_id=783436&module_id=142291 Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera's profile] at the [[Chicago Crime Commission]]\n* [https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/115366.htm Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera's profile] at the [[United States Department of State]]\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-sinaloa-cartel-leader-convicted-running-continuing-criminal|title=Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzman, Sinaloa Cartel Leader, Convicted of Running a Continuing Criminal Enterprise and Other Drug-Related Charges|publisher=[[United States Department of Justice]]|date=2019-02-12}}\n\n{{Mexican Drug War}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Mexico}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guzman, Joaquin El Chapo}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:21st-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Escapees from Mexican detention]]\n[[Category:Inmates of ADX Florence]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement scandals]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:Mexican escapees]]\n[[Category:Mexican mob bosses]]\n[[Category:Mexican money launderers]]\n[[Category:Mexican people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:People extradited to Mexico]]\n[[Category:People extradited from Guatemala]]\n[[Category:People extradited from Mexico to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Badiraguato]]\n[[Category:People from Badiraguato Municipality]]\n[[Category:People of the Mexican Drug War]]\n[[Category:People sanctioned under the Foreign Narcotics Kingpin Designation Act]]\n[[Category:Political scandals]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:Sinaloa Cartel traffickers]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the former president of El Salvador|Joaqu\u00edn Eufrasio Guzm\u00e1n}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{redirects|El Chapo}}\n{{short description|Mexican drug lord incarcerated in a US federal prison}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Spanish name|Guzm\u00e1n|Loera}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name        = Joaqu\u00edn \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n\n| birth_name  = Joaqu\u00edn Archivaldo Guzm\u00e1n Loera\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1957|4|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = La Tuna, [[Badiraguato Municipality]], [[Sinaloa]], Mexico\n| occupation  = Leader of [[Sinaloa Cartel]]\n| net worth   = U.S. $2\u2013$4 billion (2016 estimate)<ref name='Forbes2017'>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2017/01/25/does-mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-have-the-14-billion-the-u-s-wants-from-him/ Does Mexican Drug Lord El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n Have The $14 Billion The U.S. Wants From Him?] Dolia Estevez, ''Forbes''. 25 January 2017.</ref>\n| height      = {{convert|168|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[Miguel \u00c1ngel F\u00e9lix Gallardo]]\n| successor   = [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda]]\n| spouse      = {{Collapsible list\n | title       = At least 4\n | 1           = Alejandrina Mar\u00eda Salazar Hern\u00e1ndez (1977)\n | 2           = Estela Pe\u00f1a (date unknown)\n | 3           = Griselda L\u00f3pez P\u00e9rez (mid-1980s)\n | 4           = [[Emma Coronel Aispuro]] (2007)\n}}\n| relatives   = {{Collapsible list\n | title       = At least 10\n | 1           = Iv\u00e1n Archivaldo Guzm\u00e1n Salazar\n | 2           = Jes\u00fas Alfredo Guzm\u00e1n Salazar\n | 3           = C\u00e9sar Guzm\u00e1n Salazar\n | 4           = Alejandrina Gisselle Guzm\u00e1n Salazar\n | 5           = \u00c9dgar Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez (\u2020)\n | 6           = Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez\n | 7           = Victor Arael Hernandez Lopez\n | 8           = Griselda Guadalupe Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez\n | 9           = Mar\u00eda Joaquina Guzm\u00e1n Coronel\n | 10          = Emali Guadalupe Guzm\u00e1n\n}}\n| parents         =\n| criminal status = Incarcerated\n| conviction      = Murder, money laundering, drug trafficking, racketeering, organized crime\n| reward_amount   = Mexico: {{US$|3.8 million|link=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-33517118 |title=Mexico offers $3.8m reward in hunt for escaped drug lord |work=BBC News |date=13 July 2015 |accessdate=14 July 2015 }}</ref><br />United States: US$5 million<ref name=rewards>{{cite web| url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/115366.htm| title=Narcotics Rewards Program: Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n-Loera| year=2015| publisher=U.S. Department of State| accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n| capture_status  = 1st capture: 9 June 1993<br />2nd capture: 22 February 2014<br />3rd capture: 8 January 2016\n| wanted_by       = Attorney General of Mexico and the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration\n| escaped         = 1st escape: 19 January 2001<br />2nd escape: 11 July 2015\n| image_name      = Booking photo front GUZMAN JAQUIN% 20A S.jpg\n| image_alt       =\n| image_caption   = Booking photo from January 2017\n| alias           = {{unbulleted list\n| El Chapo (Shorty)\n| El R\u00e1pido (Speedy)}}|\n| charge          =\n| conviction_penalty = Life in prison plus 30 years, must forfeit assets worth more than $12.6 billion.<ref name=\"Hong\">{{Cite news|last=Hong|first=Nicole|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-sentenced-to-life-in-u-s-prison-11563373522|title=El Chapo Sentenced to Life in U.S. Prison|date=July 17, 2019|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| imprisoned = At [[ADX Florence]] in [[Florence, Colorado|Florence]], [[Colorado]], US\n}}\n\n'''Joaqu\u00edn Archivaldo Guzm\u00e1n Loera''' ({{IPA-es|xoa\u02c8kin a\u027et\u0283i\u02c8\u03b2aldo \u0263uz\u02c8man lo\u02c8e\u027ea|lang}}; born 4 April 1957),<ref name=\"time-birth-date\">{{cite web |url=http://time.com/3963451/5-facts-el-chapo/ |title=5 Things You Didn't Know About El Chapo |last=Beith |first=Malcolm |website=time.com |date=17 July 2015 |accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref> commonly known as \"'''El Chapo'''\" (\"Shorty\", {{IPA-es|el \u02c8t\u0283apo|pron}}) because of his {{convert|168|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}  stature, is a Mexican drug lord and former leader of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]], an international crime syndicate. He is considered to have been the most powerful drug trafficker in the world.<ref name='Bryan Llenas'>[Manipulation, fear, snitches, and a new cell: Behind the scenes as El Chapo goes to trial]. ''Fox News''. 12 November 2018.</ref><ref name=\"El Universal\">{{cite news|last=Otero|first=Silvia|title=EU: \"El Chapo\" es el narco m\u00e1s poderoso del mundo|url=http://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/192801.html|accessdate=11 January 2012|newspaper=El Universal}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n was born in Sinaloa and raised in a poor farming family. He endured physical abuse at the hands of his father, and also entered the drug trade through his father, helping him grow [[marijuana]] for local dealers during his early adulthood. Guzm\u00e1n began working with [[H\u00e9ctor Luis Palma Salazar]] by the late 1970s, one of the nation's rising drug lords. He helped Salazar map routes to move drugs through Sinaloa and into the United States. He later supervised logistics for [[Miguel \u00c1ngel F\u00e9lix Gallardo]], one of the nation's leading kingpins in the mid 1980s, but Guzm\u00e1n founded his own cartel in 1988 after Gallardo's arrest.\n\nGuzm\u00e1n oversaw operations whereby mass [[cocaine]], [[methamphetamine]], [[marijuana]],<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/govbeat/wp/2014/02/26/where-7-mexican-drug-cartels-are-active-within-the-u-s/ |title=Where 7 Mexican drug cartels are active within the U.S. |work=Washington Post}}</ref> and [[heroin]] were produced, smuggled into, and distributed throughout the United States and Europe, the world's largest users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fusion.net/justice/story/mexican-cartel-presence-threatens-european-security-europol-22555%7ctitle=Justice%7cwork=Fusion|title=Justice|work=Fusion|accessdate=12 July 2015}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/02/25/powerful-sinaloa-cartel-business-unlikely-to-be-slowed-by-arrest-boss-el-chapo/|title=Powerful Sinaloa cartel's business unlikely to be slowed by arrest of boss 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n|work=Fox News|date=20 March 2015}}</ref> He achieved this by pioneering the use of distribution cells and long-range tunnels near borders,<ref name=rewards /> which enabled him to export more drugs to the United States than any other trafficker in history.<ref name=AParrest>{{cite news|last1=Partlow|first1=Joshua|last2=Miroff|first2=Nick|title=World's top drug trafficker arrested in Mexico, U.S. official says|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/worlds-top-drug-trafficker-arrested-in-mexico-us-official-says/2014/02/22/c001927c-9be0-11e3-ad71-e03637a299c0_story.html?wpisrc=al_national&clsrd|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|agency=Associated Press|date=5 July 2005}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n's leadership of the cartel also brought immense wealth and power; ''Forbes'' ranked him as one of the most powerful people in the world between 2009 and 2013,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/joaquin-guzman-loera/|title=Joaquin Guzman Loera|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref> while the Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) estimated that he matched the influence and wealth of [[Pablo Escobar]].<ref name=\"biggest ever\">{{cite news|last=Vardi|first=Nathan|title=Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n Has Become The Biggest Drug Lord Ever|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2011/06/15/joaquin-guzman-has-become-the-biggest-drug-lord-ever|newspaper=Forbes Magazine|date=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n was first captured in 1993 in [[Guatemala]] and was extradited and sentenced to 20 years in prison in Mexico for murder and drug trafficking.<ref name=rewards /><ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> He bribed prison guards and escaped from a federal maximum-security prison in 2001.<ref name=rewards /> His status as a fugitive resulted in an $8.8 million combined reward from Mexico and the U.S. for information leading to his capture,<ref name=rewards /> and he was arrested in Mexico in 2014.<ref name=AParrest /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/02/22/drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-captured-in-mexico-report-says|title=Drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n captured in Mexico| publisher=Fox News| date=1 December 2006| accessdate=24 February 2014}}</ref> He escaped prior to formal sentencing in 2015, through a tunnel under his jail cell.<ref name=bbc-2nd-escape>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-33497301| title=Mexican drug lord Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzman escapes jail|newspaper=BBC News|accessdate=12 July 2015| date=12 July 2015}}</ref> Mexican authorities recaptured him following a shoot-out in 2016<ref>{{cite news| last1=Ahmed| first1=Azam| title=El Chapo, Escaped Drug Lord, Has Been Recaptured, Mexican President Says| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/09/world/americas/El-Chapo-captured-mexico.html| work=The New York Times| accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> and extradited him to the U.S. a year later. In 2019, he was found guilty of a number of criminal charges related to his leadership of the Sinaloa Cartel,<ref name=\"ChapoExtradited\">{{cite web|title=Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzman Being Extradited to the US|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-extradited-us/story?id=44900091|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref> and is currently serving a life sentence at [[ADX Florence]].<ref name=\"SentenceBBC\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-49022208 \"El Chapo sentenced to life in prison.\"] BBC News 17 July 2019.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' begins life term in Colorado 'Supermax' prison|date=21 July 2019|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-mexico-el-chapo/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-begins-life-term-in-colorado-supermax-prison-idUSKCN1UE2GA\n|work=Reuters|access-date=22 July 2019|quote=\"We can confirm that Joaquin Guzman is in the custody of the Federal Bureau of Prisons at United States Penitentiary (USP) Administrative Maximum (ADX) Florence, located in Florence, Colorado,\" the U.S. Bureau of Prisons said in a statement.}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nJoaqu\u00edn Archivaldo Guzm\u00e1n Loera was born into a poor family in the rural community of La Tuna, [[Badiraguato Municipality|Badiraguato, Sinaloa]], Mexico.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=xvii}}{{sfn|Tuckman, Jo|2012|p=22}} He was born on 4 April 1957.{{efn|His date of birth used to be a point of contention prior to 2019, when his lover Lucero Guadalupe S\u00e1nchez L\u00f3pez testified in court and confirmed Guzm\u00e1n's date of birth. In previous years, his alternative date of birth was 25 December 1954.<ref>{{cite web|title=Narcotics Rewards Program: Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n-Loera| url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/115366.htm|publisher=[[Bureau for International Narcotics and Law Enforcement Affairs]] at the [[United States Department of State]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/17/nyregion/el-chapo-trial.html|title=How El Chapo Escaped in a Sewer, Naked With His Mistress|last=Feuer|first=Alan|date=2019-01-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Stephey |first=M.J. |title=Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n Loera: Billionaire Drug Lord |url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1884982,00.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=TIME magazine |date=13 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118080518/http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0%2C8599%2C1884982%2C00.html |archivedate=18 January 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> His parents were Emilio Guzm\u00e1n Bustillos and Mar\u00eda Consuelo Loera P\u00e9rez.<ref>{{cite news| title=Libre, cumple el 'Chapo' 56 a\u00f1os de edad| url=http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/libre-cumple-el-chapo-56-anos-de-edad| accessdate=22 February 2014| newspaper=[[R\u00edodoce]]| date=4 April 2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808184455/http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/libre-cumple-el-chapo-56-anos-de-edad| archivedate=8 August 2013| url-status=dead| language=Spanish| df=dmy-all}}</ref> His paternal grandparents were Juan Guzm\u00e1n and Otilia Bustillos, and his maternal grandparents were Ovidio Loera Cobret and Pomposa P\u00e9rez Uriarte. For many generations, his family lived at La Tuna.{{sfn|Hern\u00e1ndez, Anabel|2012|p=57}} His father was officially a cattle rancher, as were most in the area where he grew up; according to some sources, however, he might also have been a ''gomero'', an [[opium poppy]] farmer.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=50-54}} He has two younger sisters named Armida and Bernarda and four younger brothers named Miguel \u00c1ngel, Aureliano, Arturo, and Emilio. He had three unnamed older brothers who reportedly died of natural causes when he was very young.{{sfn|Hern\u00e1ndez, Anabel|2012|p=57}}\n\nFew details are known of Guzm\u00e1n's upbringing. As a child, he sold oranges and dropped out of school in third grade to work with his father.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\">{{cite news|last=De Cordoba|first=Jose|title=The Drug Lord Who Got Away|url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB124484177023110993| accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=13 June 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109201342/http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB124484177023110993| archivedate=9 November 2013| url-status=live}}</ref> He was known for being a practical joker and enjoyed playing pranks on his friends and family when he was young.<ref>Vorobyov, Niko (2019) ''Dopeworld.'' Hodder, UK. p. 228</ref> He was regularly beaten, and he sometimes fled to his maternal grandmother's house to escape such treatment. However, he stood up to his father to protect his younger siblings from being beaten.<ref name=univisionpg1>{{cite news|last=Reyes|first=Gerardo|title=The Eternal Fugitive: El Chapo Territory|url=http://www.univision.com/la-huella-digital/openpage/2013-11-08/el-chapo-special-ch-1-eng#viewVideo|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=Univision|year=2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123015236/http://www.univision.com/la-huella-digital/openpage/2013-11-08/el-chapo-special-ch-1-eng|archivedate=23 January 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=51}} It is possible that Guzm\u00e1n incurred his father's wrath for trying to stop him from beating them. His mother, however, was his \"foundation of emotional support\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Who Is El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n, Mexico's Most Elusive Drug Lord?|url=http://fusion.net/justice/story/univision-investigation-hunt-el-chapo-guzman-mexicos-elusive-181574|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=Fusion|year=2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202082511/https://fusion.net/justice/story/univision-investigation-hunt-el-chapo-guzman-mexicos-elusive-181574|archivedate=2 February 2014 |url-status=live |agency=Univision}}</ref> The nearest school to his home was about 60 miles (100&nbsp;km) away, and he was taught by traveling teachers during his early years. The teachers stayed for a few months before moving to other areas.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=51}} With few opportunities for employment in his hometown, he turned to the cultivation of opium poppy, a common practice among local residents.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=xvii-xx}} During harvest season, Guzm\u00e1n and his brothers hiked the hills of Badiraguato to cut the bud of the poppy. Once the plant was stacked in kilos, his father sold the harvest to other suppliers in [[Culiac\u00e1n]] and [[Guam\u00fachil]].{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=54-55}} He sold marijuana at commercial centers near the area while accompanied by Guzm\u00e1n. His father spent most of the profits on liquor and women and often returned home with no money. Tired of his mismanagement, Guzm\u00e1n cultivated his own marijuana plantation at age 15 with cousins [[Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva|Arturo]], [[Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva|Alfredo]], [[Carlos Beltr\u00e1n Leyva|Carlos]], and [[H\u00e9ctor Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]], and he supported his family with his marijuana production.<ref name=univisionpg1 /> \n\nWhen he was a teenager, however, his father kicked him out of the house, and he went to live with his grandfather.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=53}} It was during his adolescence that Guzm\u00e1n gained the nickname \"El Chapo\", Mexican slang for \"shorty\", for his {{convert|1.68|m}} stature and stocky physique.<ref>{{cite news| last=Hootsen|first=Jan-Albert| title=Drug war continues: 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n not dead after all| url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/americas/mexico/130226/drug-war-continues-joaquin-chapo-guzman-not-dead |accessdate=22 February 2014| newspaper=GlobalPost| date=26 February 2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220144411/http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/americas/mexico/130226/drug-war-continues-joaquin-chapo-guzman-not-dead |archivedate=20 February 2014 | url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Allen| first=Nick| title='Net closing' on Mexican drug lord Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/9141375/Net-closing-on-Mexican-drug-lord-Joaquin-El-Chapo-Guzman.html |accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314194220/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/9141375/Net-closing-on-Mexican-drug-lord-Joaquin-El-Chapo-Guzman.html |archivedate=14 March 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Most people in Badiraguato worked in the poppy fields of the [[Sierra Madre Occidental]] for most of their lives, but Guzm\u00e1n left his hometown in search of greater opportunities through his uncle [[Pedro Avil\u00e9s P\u00e9rez]], one of the pioneers of Mexican drug trafficking. He left Badiraguato in his 20s and joined organized crime.{{sfn|Longmire, Sylvia|2011|p=13-1}}\n\n== Early career ==\n[[File:Esparragoza-Moreno.jpeg|thumb|upright|Juan Jos\u00e9 Esparragoza Moreno]]\nDuring the 1980s, the leading crime syndicate in Mexico was the [[Guadalajara Cartel]],{{sfn|Edmonds-Poli|Shirk|2009|p=262}} which was headed by [[Miguel \u00c1ngel F\u00e9lix Gallardo]] (alias \"El Padrino\" or \"The Godfather\"), [[Rafael Caro Quintero]], [[Ernesto Fonseca Carrillo]] (alias \"Don Neto\"), [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Esparragoza Moreno]] (alias ''El Azul'', \"The Blue One\") and others.{{sfn|Edmonds-Poli|Shirk|2009|p=354}} In the 1970s, Guzm\u00e1n first worked for the drug lord [[H\u00e9ctor Luis Palma Salazar|H\u00e9ctor \"El G\u00fcero\" Palma]] by transporting drugs and overseeing their shipments from the Sierra Madre region to urban areas near the [[U.S.\u2013Mexico border]] by aircraft. Since his initial steps in organized crime, Guzm\u00e1n was ambitious and regularly pressed on his superiors to allow him to increase the share of narcotics that were smuggled across the border. He also favored a violent and serious approach when doing business; if any of his drug shipments were not on time, Guzm\u00e1n would simply kill the smuggler himself by shooting him in the head. Those around him learned that cheating him or going with other competitors\u2014even if they offered better prices\u2014was unwise. The leaders of the Guadalajara Cartel liked Guzm\u00e1n's business acumen, and in the early 1980s introduced him to F\u00e9lix Gallardo, one of the major drug lords in Mexico at that time.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=63\u201364}} Guzm\u00e1n worked as a chauffeur for F\u00e9lix Gallardo before he put him in charge of logistics,<ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo, de chofer a \"Se\u00f1or de la Monta\u00f1a\" |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/el-chapo-de-chofer-a-senior-de-la-montania-989885.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223190613/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/el-chapo-de-chofer-a-senior-de-la-montania-989885.html |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> where Guzm\u00e1n coordinated drug shipments from Colombia to Mexico by land, air, and sea. Palma ensured the deliveries arrived in the United States. Guzm\u00e1n earned enough standing and began working for F\u00e9lix Gallardo directly.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=63\u201364}}\n\nThroughout most of the late 1970s and early 1980s, the Mexican drug traffickers were also middlemen for the Colombian trafficking groups, and transported [[cocaine]] through the U.S.-Mexico border. Mexico, however, remained a secondary route for the Colombians, given that most of the drugs trafficked by their cartels were smuggled through the Caribbean and the Florida corridor.<ref name=startfor80s />{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=62-64}} F\u00e9lix Gallardo was the leading drug baron in Mexico and friend of [[Juan Matta-Ballesteros|Juan Ram\u00f3n Matta-Ballesteros]], but his operations were still limited by his counterparts in South America. In the mid-1980s, however, the U.S. government increased law enforcement surveillance and put pressure on the [[Medell\u00edn Cartel|Medell\u00edn]] and [[Cali Cartel]]s by effectively reducing the drug trafficking operations in the Caribbean corridor. Realizing it was more profitable to hand over the operations to their Mexican counterparts, the Colombian cartels gave F\u00e9lix Gallardo more control over their drug shipments.{{sfn|Bagley, Bruce|2012|p=6}}{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=66-68}} This power shift gave the Mexican organized crime groups more leverage over their Central American and South American counterparts.<ref name=startfor80s>{{cite web|title=Mexico's Cartels and the Economics of Cocaine |url=http://www.stratfor.com/weekly/mexicos-cartels-and-economics-cocaine |publisher=[[Stratfor]] |accessdate=23 February 2014 |date=3 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301031228/http://www.stratfor.com/weekly/mexicos-cartels-and-economics-cocaine |archivedate= 1 March 2013 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> During the 1980s, however, the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA) was conducting undercover groundwork in Mexico, where several of its agents worked as informants.\n\nOne DEA agent, [[Kiki Camarena|Enrique Camarena Salazar]], was working as an informant and grew close to many top drug barons, including F\u00e9lix Gallardo.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=69-70}} In November 1984, the Mexican military\u2014acting on the intelligence information provided by Camarena\u2014raided a large marijuana plantation owned by the Guadalajara Cartel and known as \"Rancho B\u00fafalo\".<ref name=nexos>{{cite news |last=Aguilar Cam\u00edn |first=H\u00e9ctor |title=Narco Historias extraordinarias |url=http://www.nexos.com.mx/?P=leerarticulo&Article=73 |accessdate=9 August 2013 |newspaper=Nexos |date=May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022053239/http://www.nexos.com.mx/?P=leerarticulo&Article=73 |archivedate=22 October 2013 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Angered by the suspected betrayal, F\u00e9lix Gallardo and his men exacted revenge when they kidnapped, tortured, and killed Camarena in February 1985.{{sfn|Cockburn, Alexander|1998|p=348}} The death of Camarena outraged Washington, and Mexico responded by carrying out a massive manhunt to arrest those involved in the incident.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vulliamy|first=Ed|title=Joaqu\u00edn \"Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n: the Mexican drug lord adept at playing the system|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/feb/22/joaquin-guzman-mexican-drug-lord|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 February 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223013033/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/feb/22/joaquin-guzman-mexican-drug-lord|archivedate=23 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n took advantage of the internal crisis to gain ground within the cartel and take over more drug trafficking operations.<ref name=univisionpg1 /> In 1989, F\u00e9lix Gallardo was arrested; while in prison and through a number of envoys, the drug lord called for a summit in [[Acapulco]], [[Guerrero]]. In the conclave, Guzm\u00e1n and others discussed the future of Mexico's drug trafficking and agreed to divide the territories previously owned by the Guadalajara Cartel.{{sfn|Grillo, Ioan|2012|p=78}} The Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers formed the [[Tijuana Cartel]], which controlled the [[Tijuana]] corridor and parts of [[Baja California]]; in [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] state, a group controlled by Carrillo Fuentes family formed the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]]; and the remaining faction left to Sinaloa and the Pacific Coast and formed the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] under the traffickers [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda|Ismael \"El Mayo\" Zambada]], Palma, and Guzm\u00e1n.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=72-73}}{{sfn|Edmonds-Poli|Shirk|2009|p=262}} Guzm\u00e1n was specifically in charge of the drug corridors of [[Tecate, Baja California]],{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=72-73}} and [[Mexicali]] and [[San Luis R\u00edo Colorado]], two border crossings that connect the states of [[Sonora]] and Baja California with the U.S. states of Arizona and California.{{sfn|Grayson, George W.|2011|p=56}}\n\nWhen F\u00e9lix Gallardo was arrested, Guzm\u00e1n reportedly lived in [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]] for some time. One of his other centers of operation, however, was in the border city of [[Agua Prieta]], [[Sonora]], where he coordinated drug trafficking activities more closely. Guzm\u00e1n had dozens of properties in various parts of the country. People he trusted purchased the properties for him and registered them under false names. Most of them were located in residential neighborhoods and served as stash houses for drugs, weapons, and cash. Guzm\u00e1n also owned several ranches across Mexico, but most of them were located in the states of Sinaloa, Durango, Chihuahua, and Sonora, where locals working for the drug lord grew opium and marijuana.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=83\u201384}} The first time Guzm\u00e1n was detected by U.S. authorities for his involvement in organized crime was in 1987, when several protected witnesses testified in a U.S. court that Guzm\u00e1n was in fact heading the Sinaloa Cartel. An indictment issued in the state of Arizona alleged that Guzm\u00e1n had coordinated the shipment of {{convert|2000|kg|abbr=on}} of marijuana and about {{convert|4700|kg|abbr=on}} of cocaine from 19 October 1987 to 18 May 1990, and had received roughly US$1.5 million in drug proceeds that were shipped back to his home state. Another indictment alleged that Guzm\u00e1n earned US$100,000 for trafficking 70,000&nbsp;lb (roughly 31,750&nbsp;kg) of cocaine and an unspecified amount of marijuana in a period of three years.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=93\u201394}} In the border areas between Tecate and San Luis R\u00edo Colorado, Guzm\u00e1n ordered his men to traffic most of the drugs overland, but also through a few aircraft. By using the so-called piecemeal strategy, in which traffickers kept drug quantities relatively low, risks were reduced. Guzm\u00e1n also pioneered the use of sophisticated tunnels to move drugs across the border and into the United States.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=70\u201373}} Aside from pioneering the tunnels, Palma and Guzm\u00e1n packed cocaine into chili pepper cans under the brand \"La Comadre\" before they were shipped to the U.S. by train.<ref>{{Citation | author = Sebastian Rotella | title = Food Company Owners Charged in Drug Tunnel Case : Smuggling: Indictment names executives of Reynoso Bros. in unfinished underground passage linking San Diego and Tijuana | newspaper = Los Angeles Times | page =   |  date = 29 September 1995 | url =https://articles.latimes.com/1995-09-29/local/me-51176_1_san-diego/2| accessdate = 11 January 2016}}</ref> In return, the drug lords were paid through large suitcases filled with millions of dollars in cash. These suitcases were flown from the U.S. to Mexico City, where corrupt customs agents at the airport made sure the deliveries were not inspected. Large sums of that money were reportedly used as bribes for members of the Attorney General's Office.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" />\n\n== Tijuana Cartel conflict: 1989\u20131993 ==\nWhen F\u00e9lix Gallardo was arrested, the Tijuana corridor was handed over to the Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers, Jes\u00fas Labra \u00c1viles (''alias'' \"El Chuy\"), and Javier Caro Pay\u00e1n (''alias'' \"El Doctor\"), cousin of the former Guadalajara Cartel leader Rafael Caro Quintero. In fears of a coup, however, Caro Pay\u00e1n fled to Canada and was later arrested. Guzm\u00e1n and the rest of the Sinaloa Cartel leaders consequently grew angry at the Arellano F\u00e9lix clan about this.{{sfn|Grayson, George W.|2011|p=81}} In 1989, Guzm\u00e1n sent Armando L\u00f3pez (alias \"El Rayo\"), one of his most trusted men, to speak with the Arellano F\u00e9lix clan in Tijuana. Before he had a chance to speak face-to-face with them, L\u00f3pez was killed by [[Ram\u00f3n Arellano F\u00e9lix]]. The corpse was disposed of in the outskirts of the city and the Tijuana Cartel ordered a hit on the remaining members of the L\u00f3pez family to prevent future reprisals.<ref name=elrayo /><ref name=elrayo2 /> That same year, the Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers sent the Venezuelan drug trafficker Enrique Rafael Clavel Moreno to infiltrate Palma's family and seduce his wife Guadalupe Leija Serrano.{{sfn|Richards, James R.|1998|p=23}} After convincing her to withdraw US$7 million from one of Palma's bank accounts in [[San Diego]], [[California]], Clavel beheaded her and sent her head to Palma in a box.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rotella |first=Sebastian |title=Fierce Mexican Drug Wars Drench Country In Blood And Corruption |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950702&slug=2129319 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2 July 1995 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226012256/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950702&slug=2129319 |archivedate=26 February 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was known as the first beheading linked to the drug trade in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moreno|first=Mart\u00edn|title=Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera, \"El Chapo\": Venganza, detonante de la batalla|url=http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/joaquin-guzman-loera-el-chapo-venganza-detonante-de-la-batalla|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=Z\u00f3calo Saltillo|date=18 June 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505082906/http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/joaquin-guzman-loera-el-chapo-venganza-detonante-de-la-batalla|archivedate=5 May 2010 |url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> Two weeks later, Clavel killed Palma's children, H\u00e9ctor (aged 5) and Nataly (aged 4), by throwing them off a bridge in [[Venezuela]]. Palma retaliated by sending his men to kill Clavel while he was in prison.<ref>{{subscription required}} {{cite news|last=Reynoso|first=Raymundo|title=Guerra de narcos mexicanos se hace tambien a esta parte|newspaper=[[La Opini\u00f3n]]|date=12 June 1993|agency=[[ImpreMedia]]|location=Los Angeles, California|language=Spanish|id={{ProQuest|368275091}}}}</ref> In 1991, Ram\u00f3n killed another Sinaloa Cartel associate, Rigoberto Campos Salcido (''alias'' \"El Rigo\"), and prompted bigger conflicts with Guzm\u00e1n.<ref name=elrayo>{{cite news|title=Todo empez\u00f3 en Tijuana|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/2013/01/08/nacional/878467|accessdate=19 October 2013|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=8 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211120741/http://www.excelsior.com.mx/2013/01/08/nacional/878467|archivedate=11 February 2013 |url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=elrayo2>{{cite news|title=La pugna entre el c\u00e1rtel de Sinaloa|url=http://www.zetatijuana.com/html/Edicion1922/Principal.html|accessdate=19 October 2013|newspaper=[[Zeta (magazine)|Zeta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020063705/http://www.zetatijuana.com/html/Edicion1922/Principal.html|archivedate=20 October 2012 |url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> In early 1992, a Tijuana Cartel-affiliated and San Diego-based gang known as Calle Treinta kidnapped six of Guzm\u00e1n's men in Tijuana, tortured them to obtain information, and then shot them in the back of their heads. Their bodies were dumped on the outskirts of the city. Shortly after the attack, a car bomb exploded outside one of Guzm\u00e1n's properties in Culiac\u00e1n. No injuries were reported, but the drug lord became fully aware of the intended message.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=97-99}}\n\nGuzm\u00e1n and Palma struck back against the Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers (Tijuana Cartel) with nine killings on 3 September 1992 in [[Iguala]];<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Andrade Jard\u00ed |first=Juli\u00e1n |title=Tormentas sobre Ju\u00e1rez |url=https://www.nexos.com.mx/?P=leerarticulo&Article=2099639 |accessdate=19 October 2013 |newspaper=Nexos |date=1 March 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020021737/https://www.nexos.com.mx/?P=leerarticulo&Article=2099639 |archivedate=20 October 2013 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref> among the dead were lawyers and family members of F\u00e9lix Gallardo, who was also believed to have orchestrated the attack against Palma's family.<ref>{{subscription required}} {{cite news |title=F\u00e9lix Gallardo se la deb\u00eda: mat\u00f3 a su mujer y dos hijos |url=http://hemeroteca.proceso.com.mx/?page_id=278958&a51dc26366d99bb5fa29cea4747565fec=160107&rl=wh |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]] |date=12 September 1992 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228014902/http://hemeroteca.proceso.com.mx/?page_id=278958&a51dc26366d99bb5fa29cea4747565fec=160107&rl=wh |archivedate=28 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Mexico's Attorney General formed a special unit to look into the killings, but the investigation was called off after the unit found that Guzm\u00e1n had paid off some of the top police officials in Mexico with $10 million, according to police reports and confessions of former police officers.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> In November 1992, gunmen of Arellano F\u00e9lix attempted to kill Guzm\u00e1n as he was traveling in a vehicle through the streets of Guadalajara. Ram\u00f3n and at least four of his henchmen shot at the moving vehicle with [[AK-47]] rifles, but the drug lord managed to escape unharmed. The attack forced Guzm\u00e1n to leave Guadalajara and live under a false name under fears of future attacks.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /><ref name=univisionpg1 /> He and Palma, however, responded to the assassination attempt in a similar fashion; several days later, on 8 November 1992, a large number of Sinaloa Cartel men posing as policemen stormed the Christine discoth\u00e8que in [[Puerto Vallarta]], spotted Ram\u00f3n and [[Francisco Javier Arellano F\u00e9lix]], and opened fire at them. The shooting lasted for at least eight minutes, and more than 1,000 rounds were fired by both Guzm\u00e1n's and Arellano F\u00e9lix's gunmen.<ref>{{cite news| last=Pliego| first=Roberto| title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n: Una vida breve| url=http://www.nexos.com.mx/?p=9921|accessdate=23 February 2014| newspaper=Nexos| date=1 March 2001| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223223140/http://www.nexos.com.mx/?p=9921| archivedate=23 February 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> Six people were killed in the shootout, but the Arellano F\u00e9lix brothers were in the restroom when the raid started and reportedly escaped through an air-conditioning duct before leaving the scene in one of their vehicles.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=98-99}}<ref>{{cite web| last=Goodman| first=Michael| title=Muerto, Inc.| url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/readings/muerto.html| publisher=[[PBS]], by [[Los Angeles (magazine)|PBS]], by [[Los Angeles]]| accessdate=23 February 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604143751/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/readings/muerto.html| archivedate=4 June 2009| year=1997}}</ref> On 9 and 10 December 1992, four alleged associates of F\u00e9lix Gallardo were killed. The antagonism between Guzm\u00e1n's Sinaloa Cartel and the Arellano F\u00e9lix clan left several more dead and was accompanied by more violent events in the states of Baja California, Sonora, Sinaloa, Durango, Jalisco, Guerrero, Michoac\u00e1n and Oaxaca.<ref>{{cite news| last=Lira Saade| first=Carmen| title=Buscar\u00e1 la DEA extradici\u00f3n de Arellano F\u00e9lix| url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2002/03/10/004n1pol.php?origen=politica.html| accessdate=19 October 2013 |newspaper=[[La Jornada]]| date=10 March 2002| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311092439/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2002/03/10/004n1pol.php?origen=politica.html| archivedate=11 March 2008| url-status=live| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe war between both groups continued for six more months, yet none of their respective leaders was killed. In mid-1993, the Arellano F\u00e9lix clan sent their top gunmen on a final mission to kill Guzm\u00e1n in Guadalajara, where he moved around frequently to avoid any possible attacks. Having no success, the Tijuana Cartel hitmen decided to return to Baja California on 24 May 1993. As Francisco Javier was at the [[Guadalajara International Airport]] booking his flight to Tijuana, informant tips notified him that Guzm\u00e1n was at the airport parking lot awaiting a flight to Puerto Vallarta.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=99-100}} Having spotted the white Mercury Grand Marquis car where Guzm\u00e1n was thought to be hiding, about 20 gunmen of the Tijuana Cartel descended from their vehicles and opened fire at around 4:10&nbsp;p.m. However, the drug lord was inside a green Buick sedan a short distance from the target. Inside the Mercury Grand Marquis was the cardinal and archbishop of Guadalajara [[Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo]], who died at the scene from fourteen gunshot wounds.<ref name=criminalactnyt>{{cite news| last=Golden| first=Tim| title=Cardinal in Mexico Killed in a Shooting Tied to Drug Battle| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/25/world/cardinal-in-mexico-killed-in-a-shooting-tied-to-drug-battle.html| accessdate=23 February 2014| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| date=25 May 1993| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625111428/http://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/25/world/cardinal-in-mexico-killed-in-a-shooting-tied-to-drug-battle.html| archivedate=25 June 2012}}</ref> Six other people, including the cardinal's chauffeur, were caught in the crossfire and killed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller |first=Marjorie |title=Mexico Cardinal Slain; Caught in Gun Battle: Violence: 6 others are killed at Guadalajara airport. Rival narcotics traffickers are believed responsible |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-25/news/mn-39567_1_gun-battle |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=25 May 1993 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223225319/http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-25/news/mn-39567_1_gun-battle |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Divany B\u00e1rcenas |first=Javier |title=Principales ejecuciones y atentados de los Arellano F\u00e9lix |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/53814.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]] |date=9 March 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219061517/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/53814.html |archivedate=19 February 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Amidst the shootout and confusion, Guzm\u00e1n escaped and headed to one of his safe houses in Bugambilias, a neighborhood 20 minutes away from the airport.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=99-100}}<ref name=univisionpg2>{{cite news| last=Ocando| first=Casto| title=The Eternal Fugitive: Leap to Fame |url=http://www.univision.com/la-huella-digital/openpage/2013-11-08/el-chapo-special-ch-2-eng| accessdate=23 February 2014| newspaper=[[Univision]]| year=2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123015240/http://www.univision.com/la-huella-digital/openpage/2013-11-08/el-chapo-special-ch-2-eng| archivedate=23 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Flight and arrest ===\nThe night the cardinal was killed, Mexican President [[Carlos Salinas de Gortari]] flew to Guadalajara and condemned the attack, stating it was \"a criminal act\" that targeted innocent civilians, but he did not give any indications of the involvement of organized crime.<ref name=criminalactnyt /> The death of Cardinal Posadas Ocampo, a high-profile religious figure, outraged the Mexican public, the Catholic Church, and many politicians. The government responded by carrying out a massive manhunt to arrest the people involved in the shootout, and offered about US$5 million bounties for each of them.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=100\u2013101}} Pictures of Guzm\u00e1n's face, previously unknown to the public, started to appear in newspapers and television across Mexico. Fearing his capture, Guzm\u00e1n fled to [[Tonal\u00e1, Jalisco]], where he reportedly owned a ranch. The drug lord then fled to [[Mexico City]] and stayed at a hotel for about ten days.<ref name=univisionpg2 /> He met with one of his associates in an unknown location and handed him US$200 million to provide for his family in case of his absence. He gave that same amount to another of his employees to make sure the Sinaloa Cartel ran its day-to-day activities smoothly in case he was gone for some time.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=100\u2013101}}\n\nAfter obtaining a passport with the fake name of Jorge Ramos P\u00e9rez, Guzm\u00e1n was transported to the southern state of [[Chiapas]] by one of his trusted associates before leaving the country and settling in [[Guatemala]] on 4 June 1993.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=100\u2013101}}  His plan was to move across Guatemala with his girlfriend Mar\u00eda del Roc\u00edo del Villar Becerra and several of his bodyguards and settle in [[El Salvador]].<ref name=univisionpg2 /> During his travel, Mexican and Guatemalan authorities were tracking his movements. Guzm\u00e1n paid a Guatemalan military official US$1.2 million to allow him to hide south of the Mexican border. The unnamed official, however, passed information about Guzm\u00e1n's whereabouts to law enforcement.{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|pp=101\u2013102}}<ref>{{cite news|title=En 1993 dirig\u00ed captura de El Chapo: Otto P\u00e9rez |url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2013/11/06/politica/020n2pol |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[La Jornada]] |date=6 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226012854/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2013/11/06/politica/020n2pol |archivedate=26 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> On 9 June 1993, Guzm\u00e1n was arrested by the [[Guatemalan Army]] at a hotel near [[Tapachula]], close to the [[Guatemala\u2013Mexico border]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Darling |first=Juanita |title=Mexico Arrests Reputed Top Drug Kingpin: Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n is believed to have been the target of the attack that killed cardinal. He is captured in Guatemala |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1993-06-11/news/mn-2027_1_top-drug-trafficker |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=11 June 1993 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226013039/http://articles.latimes.com/1993-06-11/news/mn-2027_1_top-drug-trafficker |archivedate=26 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A 'El Chapo' no lo agarran porque no quieren: Carrillo Olea |url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/aelchaponoloagarranporquenoquierencarrilloolea-1792446.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]] |date=22 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140206011457/http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/aelchaponoloagarranporquenoquierencarrilloolea-1792446.html |archivedate=6 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> He was extradited to Mexico two days later aboard a military airplane,<ref name=univisionpg2 /><ref>{{cite news |title=Chocan versiones sobre El Chapo| url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/905272.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]]| date=22 February 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225083534/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/905272.html |archivedate=25 February 2013 |url-status=live| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n, a 20 a\u00f1os de su captura en Guatemala |url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/seguridad/el-chapo-guzman-a-20-anos-de-su-captura-en-guatemala,6a08c0021023f310VgnVCM10000098cceb0aRCRD.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Terra Networks]] |year=2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615010258/http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/seguridad/el-chapo-guzman-a-20-anos-de-su-captura-en-guatemala%2C6a08c0021023f310VgnVCM10000098cceb0aRCRD.html |archivedate=15 June 2013 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> where he was immediately taken to the [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1]] (often referred to simply as \"La Palma\" or \"Altiplano\"), a maximum-security prison in [[Almoloya de Ju\u00e1rez]], [[State of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news| title=En la mira, recaptura de 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/325667.en-la-mira-recaptura-de-el-chapo-guzman.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n]]| date=19 January 2008| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621082949/http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/325667.en-la-mira-recaptura-de-el-chapo-guzman.html| archivedate=21 June 2009| url-status=live| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==== First arrest: 1993 ====\nGuzm\u00e1n was captured for the first time in [[Guatemala]] on 9 June 1993,<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> [[extradition|extradited]] to Mexico and sentenced to 20 years, nine months in prison on charges of drug trafficking, criminal association and bribery. He was jailed at Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1. On 22 November 1995, he was transferred to another maximum security prison, Federal Center for Social Rehabilitation No. 2 (also known as \"Puente Grande\") in [[Jalisco]], after being convicted of three crimes: possession of firearms, drug trafficking and the murder of Cardinal [[Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo]] (the charge would later be dismissed by another judge). He had been tried and sentenced inside the federal prison on the outskirts of [[Almoloya de Ju\u00e1rez]], Mexico State.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" />\n\nWhile he was in prison, Guzm\u00e1n's drug empire and cartel continued to operate unabated, run by his brother, Arturo Guzm\u00e1n Loera, known as ''El Pollo'', with Guzm\u00e1n himself still considered a major international drug trafficker by Mexico and the U.S. even while he was behind bars.<ref name=\"PBS cartels\" /> Associates brought him suitcases of cash to bribe prison workers and allow the drug lord to maintain his opulent lifestyle even in prison, with prison guards acting like his servants.<ref name=insight>{{cite news|title=El Chapo|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/personalities-mexico/joaquin-guzman-loera-el-chapo|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=Insight Crime}}</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\">{{cite news|title='El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n, Mexico's Most Powerful Drug Lord|url=http://www.newsweek.com/el-chapo-guzman-mexicos-most-powerful-drug-lord-64321|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> He met his longtime mistress and later Sinaloa associate, former police officer Zulema Hern\u00e1ndez, while in prison, where she was serving time for armed robbery.<ref name=LATwomen>{{cite news|last=Wilkinson|first=Tracy|title=Women play a bigger role in Mexico's drug war|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/10/world/fg-narco-women10|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=10 November 2009}}</ref> Hern\u00e1ndez later controlled Sinaloa's expansion into Mexico City, but in 2008 her body was found in a trunk, carved with multiple Zs, signifying [[Los Zetas]], Sinaloa's archrivals.<ref name=LATwomen />\n\n== Drug empire ==\n\n[[File:Mexico cartel map May 2010.svg|thumb|Map of Mexican drug cartels presence in Mexico based on a May 2010 [[Stratfor]] report\n{{legend|yellow|[[Sinaloa Cartel]]}}]]\nGuzm\u00e1n's [[Sinaloa Cartel]], at the time of his arrest, was the wealthiest and most powerful of Mexico's drug cartels. It smuggles multi-ton [[cocaine]] shipments from [[Colombia]] through Mexico to the United States by air, sea and road, and has distribution cells throughout the U.S.<ref name=rewards /><ref name=AParrest /> The organization has also been involved in the production, smuggling and distribution of Mexican [[methamphetamine]], [[marijuana]], and [[heroin]] from Southeast Asia.<ref name=\"PBS cartels\">{{cite news|title=Drug Cartels|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/mexico/etc/guzman.html|accessdate=22 February 2014|publisher=[[PBS]]}}</ref>\n\nWhen Palma was arrested by the Mexican Army on 23 June 1995, Guzm\u00e1n took leadership of the cartel.<ref name=\"Organized\">{{cite book|last=Bailey|first=John J.|author2=Roy Godson|title=Organized Crime and Democratic Governability: Mexico and the U.S.-Mexican Borderlands|publisher=Univ of Pittsburgh Press|year=2000|page=146|isbn=978-0-8229-5758-4|author2-link=Roy Godson}}</ref><ref name=\"Bordering\">{{cite book|last=Oppenheimer|first=Andres|title=Bordering on Chaos: Guerrillas, Stockbrokers, Politicians, and Mexico's Road to Prosperity|publisher=Little Brown & Co|year=1996|pages=202, 298, 300|isbn=978-0-316-65095-3}}</ref> Palma was later extradited to the United States, where he is in prison on charges of drug trafficking and conspiracy.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" />\n\nAfter Guzm\u00e1n's prison escape nearly a decade after his initial arrest, he and close associate [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda]] became Mexico's undisputed top drug kingpins after the 2003 arrest of their rival [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas]] of the [[Gulf Cartel]]. Until Guzm\u00e1n's arrest in 2014, he was considered the \"most powerful drug trafficker in the world\" by the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Department of the Treasury]].<ref name=\"El Universal\" /><ref name=\"Milenio\">{{cite news| title=Califica EU a \"El Chapo\" como el narco m\u00e1s poderoso del mundo| url=http://www.percepcion.com.mx/noticia/15541/eu-califica-a-el-chapo-guzman-como-el-narco-mas-poderoso-del-mundo| accessdate=15 January 2016| newspaper=Percepcion| date=10 January 2012}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n also had another close associate, his trusted friend [[Ignacio Coronel Villarreal|Ignacio \"Nacho\" Coronel Villarreal]].<ref name=\"Stratfor11/11/2008\"> {{cite news|url=http://www.stratfor.com/analysis/20081209_mexican_drug_cartels_government_progress_and_growing_violence|title=Mexican Drug Cartels: Government Progress and Growing Violence|date=11 December 2008|work=STRATFOR Global Intelligence|accessdate=25 August 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120013002/http://www.stratfor.com/analysis/20081209_mexican_drug_cartels_government_progress_and_growing_violence|archivedate=20 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Puro\">{{cite book|last=Crosthwaite|first=Luis Humberto|title=Puro Border: Dispatches, Snapshots & Graffiti from La Frontera|publisher=Cinco Puntos Press|page=115|isbn=978-0-938317-59-3|year=2002}}</ref>\n\nHis drug empire made Guzm\u00e1n a billionaire, and he was ranked the 10th richest man in Mexico and 1,140th in the world in 2011, with a net worth of roughly [[United States Dollar|US$]]1 billion.<ref name=\"forbes billionaire\">{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2010/10/billionaires-2010_Joaquin-Guzman-Loera_FS0Y.html| title=The World's Billionaires: 937 Joaquin Guzm\u00e1n Loera| accessdate=21 September 2010| date=10 March 2010|work=Forbes Magazine}}</ref> To assist his drug trafficking, the Sinaloa Cartel also built a shipping and transport empire.<ref name=AParrest /> Guzm\u00e1n has been referred to as the \"biggest drug lord of all time\",<ref name=\"cnn capture\">{{cite news|title=Major Mexican drug lord captured|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/09/19/world/americas/mexico-drug-lord/index.html|newspaper=CNN News|date=19 September 2011}}</ref> and the U.S. DEA considered him \"the godfather of the drug world\" and strongly estimates he surpassed the influence and reach of [[Pablo Escobar]]. In 2013, the Chicago Crime Commission named Guzm\u00e1n \"Public Enemy Number One\" for the influence of his criminal network in [[Chicago]] (however, there is no evidence Guzm\u00e1n has ever visited the city). The last person to receive such notoriety was [[Al Capone]] in 1930.\n\nAt the time of his 2014 arrest, Guzm\u00e1n imported more drugs into the United States than anyone else.<ref name=AParrest /> He took advantage of the power vacuum created by crackdowns on cartels in Colombia, gaining business and market share there as Colombia's own cartels were decimated.<ref name=\"market share\">{{cite news|last=Althaus|first=Dudley|title=Report: 'Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Grabs More Market Share in Colombia |url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-analysis/report-chapo-guzman-grabs-more-market-share-in-colombia|accessdate=22 February 2014|publisher=[[InSight Crime]]|agency=}}</ref> He took similar advantage of the situation when his rival cartels were brought down by an intense crackdown from the Mexican government, but the Sinaloa gang emerged largely unscathed.<ref name=\"AP AJC\">{{cite news|last=Spagat| first=Elliot| title=As allies fell, noose closed on 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=https://news.yahoo.com/allies-fell-noose-closed-39-el-chapo-39-050502264.html| accessdate=15 January 2016| newspaper= Yahoo News| agency=[[Associated Press]]| date=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Methamphetamine production ===\nAfter the fall of the Amezcua brothers&nbsp;\u2013 founders of the [[Colima Cartel]]&nbsp;\u2013 in 1999 on [[methamphetamine]] trafficking charges, there was a demand for leadership throughout Mexico to coordinate methamphetamine shipments north. Guzm\u00e1n saw an opportunity and seized it.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> Easily arranging precursor shipments, Guzm\u00e1n and [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda]] (\"El Mayo\") made use of their previous contacts on Mexico's Pacific coast. Importantly, for the first time, the Colombians would not have to be paid&nbsp;\u2013 they simply joined methamphetamine with cocaine shipments. This fact meant no additional money was needed for airplanes, pilots, boats and bribes; they used the existing infrastructure to pipeline the new product.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" />\n\nUntil this point, the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] had been a joint venture between Guzm\u00e1n and Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda; the methamphetamine business would be Guzm\u00e1n's alone. He cultivated his own ties to China, Thailand and India to import the necessary precursor chemicals. Throughout the mountains of the states of Sinaloa, [[Durango]], [[Jalisco]], [[Michoac\u00e1n]] and [[Nayarit]], Guzm\u00e1n constructed large [[clandestine chemistry|methamphetamine laboratories]] and rapidly expanded his organization.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" />\n\nHis nomadic existence allowed him to nurture contacts throughout the country. He was now operating in 17 of the 31 Mexican states. With his business expanding, he placed his trusted friend [[Ignacio Coronel Villarreal]] in charge of methamphetamine production; this way Guzm\u00e1n could continue being the boss of bosses. Coronel Villarreal proved so reliable in the Guzm\u00e1n business that he became known as the \"Crystal King\".<ref name=\"Grayson\">{{cite book |title=Mexico: Narco-Violence and a Failed State?| last=Grayson| first=George W. |year=2010 |publisher=[[Transaction Publishers]]| location=New Brunswick, NJ| isbn=978-1-4128-1151-4| lccn=2009029164|oclc=351324700| page=68| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ogjkeCd7RGoC&pg=PA68| accessdate=16 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== First escape and second arrest ==\n\n=== First escape: 2001 ===\nWhile still in prison in Mexico, Guzm\u00e1n was [[indictment|indicted]] in [[San Diego, California|San Diego]] on U.S. charges of [[money laundering]] and importing tons of cocaine into California, along with his Sinaloa attorney Humberto Loya-Castro, or ''Licenciado Perez'' (\"Lawyer Perez\"), who was charged with bribing Mexican officials on Sinaloa's behalf and making sure that any cartel members arrested were released from custody.<ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\" /><ref name=LAmaster>{{cite news|last=Boudreaux|first=Richard|title=Mexico's Master of Elusion|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2005/jul/05/world/fg-shorty5|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=5 July 2005}}</ref> After a ruling by the [[Supreme Court of Mexico]] made [[extradition]] between Mexico and the United States easier, Guzm\u00e1n bribed guards to aid his escape. On 19 January 2001, Francisco \"El Chito\" Camberos Rivera, a prison guard, opened Guzm\u00e1n's electronically operated cell door, and Guzm\u00e1n got into a laundry cart that maintenance worker Javier Camberos rolled through several doors and eventually out the front door. He was then transported in the trunk of a car driven by Camberos out of the town. At a petrol station, Camberos went inside, but when he came back, Guzm\u00e1n was gone on foot into the night. According to officials, 78 people have been implicated in his escape plan.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> Camberos is in prison for his assistance in the escape.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" />\n\nThe police say Guzm\u00e1n carefully masterminded his escape plan, wielding influence over almost everyone in the prison, including the facility's director, who is now in prison for aiding in the escape.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> One prison guard who came forward to report the situation at the prison disappeared 7 years later, and was presumed to have been killed on the orders of Guzm\u00e1n.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /> Guzm\u00e1n allegedly had the prison guards on his payroll, smuggled contraband into the prison and received preferential treatment from the staff. In addition to the prison-employee accomplices, police in [[Jalisco]] were paid off to ensure he had at least 24 hours to get out of the state and stay ahead of the military manhunt. The story told to the guards being bribed not to search the laundry cart was that Guzm\u00e1n was smuggling gold, ostensibly extracted from rock at the inmate workshop, out of the prison. The escape allegedly cost Guzm\u00e1n $2.5&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amw.com/fugitives/case.cfm?id=25154|title=Guzm\u00e1n Escapes|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025095718/http://www.amw.com/fugitives/case.cfm?id=25154|archivedate=25 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Manhunt: 2001\u20132014 ===\n\n==== Mexican cartel wars ====\n{{Main|Mexican Drug War}}\n[[File:Drug-War Related Murders in Mexico 2006-2011.png|thumb|Drug-war related murders in Mexico, 2006\u20132011]]\nSince his 2001 escape from prison, Guzm\u00e1n had wanted to control the [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]] crossing points, which were in the hands of the Carrillo Fuentes family of the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]].<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> Despite a high degree of mistrust between the two organizations, the Sinaloa and Ju\u00e1rez cartels had a working agreement at the time. Guzm\u00e1n convened a meeting in [[Monterrey]] with [[Ismael Zambada Garc\u00eda]] (\"El Mayo\"), [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Esparragoza Moreno]] (\"El Azul\") and [[Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]]. In this meeting, they discussed killing Rodolfo Carrillo Fuentes, who was in charge of the Ju\u00e1rez Cartel at the time. On 11 September 2004, Rodolfo, his wife and two young children were visiting a [[Culiac\u00e1n]] shopping mall. While leaving the mall, escorted by police commander Pedro P\u00e9rez L\u00f3pez, the family was ambushed by members of [[Los Negros]], assassins for the [[Sinaloa Cartel]]. Rodolfo and his wife were killed; the policeman survived.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" />\n\nThe city was no longer controlled only by the Carrillo Fuentes family. Instead, the city found itself as the front line in the [[Mexican Drug War]] and would see homicides skyrocket as rival cartels fought for control. With this act, Guzm\u00e1n was the first to break the nonaggression \"pact\" the major cartels had agreed to, setting in motion the fighting between cartels for drug routes that has claimed more than 60,000 lives since December 2006.<ref>{{cite news| title=Por crimen, 11% mas asesinatos en 2011| date=12 January 2012| url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/192833.html| work=El Universal| accessdate=15 January 2012| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Mendoza Hernandez| first=Enrique| title=Cinco a\u00f1os de guerra, 60 mil muertos| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=290774| accessdate=20 January 2012| newspaper=Proceso| date=10 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Quinto a\u00f1o de gobierno: 60 mil 420 ejecuciones| url=http://entranasdelnarco.com/?p=85| accessdate=15 January 2016| newspaper=Zeta Tijuana| date=12 December 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121234003/http://entranasdelnarco.com/?p=85| archive-date=21 November 2016| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhen Mexican President [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n]] took office in December 2006, he announced a crackdown on cartels by the Mexican military to stem the increasing violence.<ref name=\"LAT calderon\">{{cite news|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Tracy|last2=Ellingwood|first2=Ken|title=Mexico drug cartels thrive despite Calderon's offensive|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/aug/08/world/la-fg-mexico-cartels-20100808|accessdate=22 February 2014|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=8 August 2010}}</ref> After four years, the additional efforts had not slowed the flow of drugs or the killings tied to the drug war.<ref name=\"LAT calderon\" /> Of the 53,000 arrests made as of 2010, only 1,000 involved associates of the Sinaloa Cartel, which led to suspicions that Calder\u00f3n was intentionally allowing Sinaloa to win the drug war, a charge Calder\u00f3n denied in advertisements in Mexican newspapers, pointing to his administration's killing of top Sinaloa deputy \"Nacho\" Coronel as evidence.<ref name=\"LAT calderon\" /> Sinaloa's rival cartels saw their leaders killed and syndicates dismantled by the crackdown, but the Sinaloa gang was relatively unaffected and took over the rival gangs' territories, including the coveted Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez-El Paso corridor, in the wake of the power shifts.<ref name=\"market share\" />\n\n==== Conflict with Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel ====\n[[File:Alfredo BELTRAN LEYVA.jpg|thumb|Guzm\u00e1n's lieutenant [[Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]] (arrested)]]\nA ''[[Newsweek]]'' investigation alleges that one of Guzm\u00e1n's techniques for maintaining his dominance among cartels included giving information to the DEA and [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] that led to the arrests of his enemies in the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]], in addition to information that led to the arrests of some of the top Sinaloa leaders.<ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\" /> The arrests were speculated by some to have been part of a deal Guzm\u00e1n struck with Calder\u00f3n and the DEA, in which he intentionally gave up some of his purported Sinaloa colleagues to U.S. agents in exchange for immunity from prosecution, while perpetuating the idea that the Calder\u00f3n government was heavily pursuing his organization during the cartel crackdown.<ref name=\"war won\">{{cite book |last= Payan|first= Tony|title= A War that Can't Be Won: Binational Perspectives on the War on Drugs|url= |page=42|location= |publisher= University of Arizona Press|isbn= 978-0-8165-3034-2|date= 2013-10-17}}</ref>\n\nThis became a key factor influencing the break between the Sinaloa Cartel and the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel|Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers]], five brothers who served as Guzm\u00e1n's top lieutenants, primarily working for the cartel in the northern region of Sinaloa.<ref name=\"Mexico raids\">{{cite news|title=Mexico raids net alleged drug cartel figures |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/22785423 |accessdate=3 March 2014 |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=22 January 2008 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"LAT zetas\">{{cite news|last=Wilkinson |first=Tracy |title=Sinaloa cartel, Zetas push Mexico's drug violence to new depths |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/27/world/la-fg-mexico-cartel-war-20120528/2 |accessdate=3 March 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=27 May 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101074757/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/27/world/la-fg-mexico-cartel-war-20120528/2 |archivedate=1 November 2012 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Sinaloa lawyer Loya-Castro, who like Guzm\u00e1n had been wanted on federal charges in the United States since 1993, voluntarily approached the DEA offering them information in 1998, eventually signing paperwork as a formal informant in 2005, and his U.S. indictment was thrown out in 2008.<ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\" /> Loya-Castro's leaks to the DEA led to the dismantling of the Tijuana Cartel, as well as the Mexican Army's arrest of Guzm\u00e1n's lieutenant and the top commander of the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva organization, [[Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]] (also known as ''El Mochomo'', or \"Desert Ant\"), in Culiac\u00e1n in January 2008, with Guzm\u00e1n believed to have given up El Mochomo for various reasons.<ref name=\"Newsweek DEA\" /><ref name=\"war won\" /><ref name=\"LAT zetas\" /> Guzm\u00e1n had expressed concerns with Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n's lifestyle and high-profile actions for some time before his arrest. After El Mochomo's arrest, authorities said he was in charge of two hit squads, money laundering, transporting drugs and bribing officials.<ref name=\"Mexico raids\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico arrests top drugs suspect |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7201571.stm |accessdate=3 March 2014 |newspaper=[[BBC News]] |date=21 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203210808/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7201571.stm |archivedate=3 December 2012 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nThat high-profile arrest was followed by the arrest of 11 Beltr\u00e1n Leyva hit squad members in Mexico City, with police noting that the arrests were the first evidence that Sinaloa had expanded into the capital city.<ref name=\"Mexico raids\" /><ref name=\"cnn leyva\">{{cite news |title=Major Mexican drug cartel suspects arrested, officials say| date=20 January 2002| url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/americas/05/20/mexico.narco.arrest/index.html| work=CNN| accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> U.S. Ambassador to Mexico [[Tony Garza]] called the arrests a \"significant victory\" in the drug war.<ref name=\"Mexico raids\" /> With Alfredo in custody, his brother [[Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]] took over as the brothers' top commander, but he was killed in a shootout with Mexican marines the next year.<ref name=\"LAT zetas\" />\n\nWhether Guzm\u00e1n was responsible for Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n's arrest is not known. However, the Beltr\u00e1n Leyvas and their allies suspected he was behind it,<ref name=\"LAT zetas\" /> and after Alfredo Beltr\u00e1n's arrest, a formal \"war\" was declared. An attempt on the life of cartel head Zambada's son [[Vicente Zambada Niebla]] (''El Vincentillo'') was made only hours after the declaration. Dozens of killings followed in retaliation for that attempt.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> The Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers ordered the assassination of Guzm\u00e1n's son, \u00c9dgar Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez, on 8 May 2008, in Culiac\u00e1n, which brought massive retaliation from Guzm\u00e1n. They were also in conflict over the allegiance of the Flores brothers, Margarito and Pedro, leaders of a major, highly lucrative cell in [[Chicago]] responsible for distributing over two tons of cocaine every month.<ref name=\"ChicagoFBI\">{{cite web| title=Three Alleged Mexican Drug Cartel Leaders and Twin Brothers Who Ran Chicago-Based Distribution Crew Among Dozens Indicted in Chicago as Part of Coordinated Strike Against Drug Traffickers| url=http://chicago.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel09/cg082009.htm| publisher=FBI Chicago| accessdate=28 November 2010| url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129064526/http://chicago.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel09/cg082009.htm| archivedate=29 November 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Mexican military claims that Guzm\u00e1n and the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers were at odds over Guzm\u00e1n's relationship with the [[Milenio Cartel|Valencia brothers]] in Michoac\u00e1n.<ref name=\"LastNarco\">{{cite book| last=Beith| first=Malcolm| title=The Last Narco| url=https://archive.org/details/lastnarcoinsideh00beit| url-access=registration| year=2010}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the killing of Guzm\u00e1n's son \u00c9dgar, violence increased. From 8 May through the end of the month, over 116 people were murdered in Culiac\u00e1n, 26 of them police officers. In June 2008, over 128 were killed; in July, 143 were slain.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> An additional deployment of 2,000 troops to the area failed to stop the turf war. The wave of violence spread to other cities such as [[Guam\u00fachil]], [[Guasave]] and Mazatl\u00e1n.\n\nHowever, the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers were involved in some double-dealing of their own. Arturo and Alfredo had met with leading members of [[Los Zetas]] in [[Cuernavaca]], where they agreed to form an alliance to fill the power vacuum. They would not necessarily go after the main strongholds, such as the Sinaloa and Gulf Cartel; instead, they would seek control of southern states like [[Guerrero]] (where the Beltr\u00e1n Leyvas already had a big stake), [[Oaxaca]], [[Yucat\u00e1n (state)|Yucat\u00e1n]] and [[Quintana Roo]]. They worked their way into the center of the country, where no single group had control.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /> The Beltr\u00e1n Leyva organization allied with the Gulf Cartel and its hit squad [[Los Zetas]] against Sinaloa.<ref name=\"cnn leyva\" />\n\nThe split was officially recognized by the U.S. government on 30 May 2008. On that day, it recognized the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva brothers as leaders of their own cartel. President [[George W. Bush]] designated Marcos Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva and the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Organization as subject to sanction under the [[Foreign Narcotics Kingpin Designation Act]] (\"Kingpin Act\"),<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /><ref>{{cite news| last=Garza| first=Antonio O.| title=President Bush Designates Beltran Leyva and his Organization Under Kingpin Act| date=30 May 2008| publisher=Embassy of the U.S. in Mexico| url=http://www.usembassy-mexico.gov/eng/releases/ep080530kingpin.html| accessdate=3 August 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827010930/http://usembassy-mexico.gov/eng/releases/ep080530kingpin.html| archive-date=27 August 2009| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref> which prohibits people and corporations in the U.S. from conducting businesses with them and freezes their U.S. assets.\n\n==== First manhunt ====\n{{Main|Manhunt of Joaqu\u00edn \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n}}\nGuzm\u00e1n was known among drug lords for his longevity and evasion of authorities, assisted by alleged bribes to federal, state and local Mexican officials.<ref name=AParrest /><ref name=\"online.wsj.com\" /><ref name=\"cnn arrest\">{{cite news| last1=Sanchez| first1=Ray| last2=Perez| first2=Evan |last3=Labott| first3=Elise| title=Sinaloa Cartel chief 'Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n arrested |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/22/world/americas/mexico-cartel-chief-arrest/index.html |accessdate=22 February 2014| newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=22 February 2014}}</ref> Despite the progress made in arresting others in the aftermath of Guzm\u00e1n's escape, including a handful of his foremost logistics and security men, the huge military and federal police manhunt failed to capture Guzm\u00e1n for years. In the years between his escape and capture, he was Mexico's most-wanted man.<ref name=\"wbur\">{{cite news| last=Beaubien| first=Jason| title=Smugglers' Hero Status Hampers Cartel Crackdown| url=http://www.wbur.org/npr/91303968| accessdate=22 February 2014| publisher=[[WBUR]]|date=9 June 2008}}</ref> His elusiveness from law enforcement made him a near-legendary figure in Mexico's narcotics folklore; stories abounded that Guzm\u00e1n sometimes strolled into restaurants, his bodyguards confiscating peoples' cellphones, he ate his meal, and then left after paying everyone's tab.<ref>{{cite news| last=Wilkinson| first=Tracy| title=Guzm\u00e1n's rise to power made him a living legend in Mexico's drug world| url=http://m.themonitor.com/news/local/article_6faa3de8-9c2a-11e3-8994-0017a43b2370.html?mode=jqm| accessdate=20 May 2014| newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)]]| date=February 2014}}</ref> Rumors circulated of Guzm\u00e1n being seen in different parts of Mexico and abroad.<ref name=mostwantedSA /> For more than thirteen years, Mexican security forces coordinated many operations to re-arrest him, but their efforts were largely in vain as Guzm\u00e1n appeared to be steps ahead from his captors.<ref>{{cite news| last=Wilkinson| first=Tracy| title=Mexican drug lord hid in mountains, homes, sewers| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2014/feb/23/world/la-fg-mexico-guzman-capture-20140224| accessdate=21 May 2014| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlthough his whereabouts were unknown, the authorities thought that he was likely hiding in the \"Golden Triangle\" (Spanish: ''Tri\u00e1ngulo Dorado''), an area that encompasses parts of Sinaloa, Durango, and Chihuahua in the [[Sierra Madre Oriental|Sierra Madre]] region. The region is a major producer of marijuana and opium poppies in Mexico,<ref>{{cite news| last=Blancas Madrigal| first=Daniel| title=El Tri\u00e1ngulo Dorado, zona m\u00e1s disputada por el narco| url=http://www.cronica.com.mx/notas/2008/369892.html|accessdate=4 May 2014| newspaper=[[La Cr\u00f3nica de Hoy]]| date=2008| language=Spanish}}</ref> and its remoteness from the urban areas makes it an attractive territory for the production of synthetic drugs in clandestine laboratories and for its mountains that offer potential hideouts.<ref>{{cite news| last=Lawson| first=Guy| title=The War Next Door| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/the-war-next-door-20110418| accessdate=4 May 2014| newspaper=[[The Rolling Stone]]| date=11 April 2011}}</ref>{{sfn|Beith, Malcolm|2010|p=21}}<ref>{{cite news| last=Dudley| first=Steven| title=In Battle for Sierra Madre, Old Allies, New Foes Displace Thousands| url=http://www.insightcrime.org/investigations/in-battle-for-sierra-madre-old-allies-new-foes-displace-hundreds| accessdate=20 May 2014| newspaper=[[InSight Crime]]| date=1 June 2012}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n reportedly commanded a sophisticated security circle of at least 300 informants and gunmen resembling the manpower equivalent to those of a [[head of state]]. His inner circle would help him move around through several isolated ranches in the mountainous area to avoid capture.<ref name=mostwantedSA>{{cite news| last=Schiller| first=Dane|title=Mexico's most wanted man|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/enie/article/Mexico-s-most-wanted-man-1363669.php| accessdate=4 May 2014| newspaper=[[San Antonio Express News]]| date=3 May 2011| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208060720/http://www.mysanantonio.com/enie/article/Mexico-s-most-wanted-man-1363669.php| archivedate=8 February 2014| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=chapostronger /> He usually escaped from law enforcement using armored cars, aircraft, and all-terrain vehicles, and was known to employ sophisticated communications gadgetry and counterespionage practices.<ref name=chapostronger /><ref>{{cite news| title=High-Tech Gizmos Helped Joaqu\u00edn 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Avoid Cops, But Also Led To Arrest| url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2014/02/26/high-tech-gizmos-helped-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-avoid-cops-but-also-led-to/| accessdate=4 May 2014| newspaper=[[Fox News]]| date=26 February 2014}}</ref> Since many of these locations in the Golden Triangle are only accessible via single-track dirt roads, local residents easily detected the arrival of law enforcement or any outsiders. Their distrust towards non-residents and their aversion towards the government, alongside a combination of bribery and intimidation, helped keep the locals loyal to Guzm\u00e1n and the Sinaloa Cartel in the area. According to law enforcement intelligence, attempting to have launched an attack to capture Guzm\u00e1n by air would have had similar results; his security circle would have warned him of the presence of an aircraft 10 minutes away from Guzm\u00e1n's location, giving him ample time to escape the scene and avoid arrest. In addition, his gunmen reportedly carried surface-to-air missiles that may bring down aircraft in the area.<ref name=chapostronger>{{cite news|last=Booth |first=William |title=El Chapo, wanted drug lord, grows stronger in Mexico's Sierra Madre |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/americas/el-chapo-wanted-drug-lord-grows-stronger-in-mexicos-sierra-madre/2011/10/14/gIQAfcUDNM_story.html |accessdate=4 May 2014 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=14 October 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525094936/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/americas/el-chapo-wanted-drug-lord-grows-stronger-in-mexicos-sierra-madre/2011/10/14/gIQAfcUDNM_story.html |archivedate=25 May 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n=== Second arrest: 2014 ===\nAlthough Guzm\u00e1n had hidden for long periods in remote areas of the Sierra Madre mountains without being captured, the arrested members of his security team told the military he had begun venturing out to Culiac\u00e1n and the beach town of Mazatl\u00e1n.<ref name=\"AP AJC\" /> A week before he was caught, Guzm\u00e1n and Zambada were reported to have attended a family reunion in Sinaloa.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n y \"El Mayo\" Zambada escaparon de un operativo militar |url=http://noticias.univision.com/article/1856093/2014-02-18/mexico/noticias/el-chapo-guzman-y-el-mayo-zambada-escaparon-de-un-operativo-militar |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Univision]] |date=18 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221155449/http://noticias.univision.com/article/1856093/2014-02-18/mexico/noticias/el-chapo-guzman-y-el-mayo-zambada-escaparon-de-un-operativo-militar |archivedate=21 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> On 16 February 2014, the Mexican military followed the bodyguards' tips to Guzm\u00e1n's former wife's house, but they had trouble ramming the steel-reinforced front door, which allowed Guzm\u00e1n to escape through a system of secret tunnels that connected six houses, eventually moving south to Mazatl\u00e1n.<ref name=\"AP AJC\" /> He had planned to stay a few days in Mazatl\u00e1n to see his twin baby daughters before retreating to the mountains.<ref>{{cite news| last=Loret de Mola| first=Carlos| title=El Chapo habl\u00f3 en el avi\u00f3n| url=http://www.eluniversalmas.com.mx/columnas/2014/02/105771.php| accessdate=25 February 2014| newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]]| date=25 February 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225182449/http://www.eluniversalmas.com.mx/columnas/2014/02/105771.php| archivedate=25 February 2014| url-status=dead| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February 2014, at around 6:40 AM,<ref>{{cite news|title=Capturan a 'El Chapo'; se mov\u00eda por t\u00faneles entre siete casas |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-arrestan_al_Chapo_Guzman-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_250175141.html |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228073126/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-arrestan_al_Chapo_Guzman-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_250175141.html |archivedate=28 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> Mexican authorities arrested Guzm\u00e1n at a hotel in a beachfront area in [[Mazatl\u00e1n]], following an operation by the [[Mexican Navy]], with joint intelligence from the DEA and the [[United States Marshals Service|U.S. Marshals Service]].<ref name=\"cnn arrest\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Washington Valdez |first=Diana |title=US Officials: Sinaloa drug kingpin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n arrested in Mexico |url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/news/ci_25204120/officials-chapo-guzman-arrested-last-night-mexico?source=rss |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Paso Times]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NajwvvNs?url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/news/ci_25204120/officials-chapo-guzman-arrested-last-night-mexico?source=rss |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A few days before his capture, Mexican authorities had been raiding several properties owned by members of the Sinaloa Cartel who were close to Guzm\u00e1n throughout the state of Sinaloa.<ref name=\"To Snitch on a Trap God\">{{cite web|url=http://dondivamag.com/to-snitch-on-the-trap-god/|title=To Snitch On The Trap God|author=Ryan K. Smith|date=19 August 2015|publisher=|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wilkinson |first=Tracy |title=Mexico's most wanted drug lord captured, U.S. official says |url=https://latimes.com/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-mexico-drug-arrest-20140222,0,4503693.story#axzz2u4ZpjqXL |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222215639/http://www.latimes.com/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-mexico-drug-arrest-20140222%2C0%2C4503693.story |archivedate=22 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's Sinaloa Drug Chief Arrested |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/mexicos-sinaloa-drug-chief-arrested |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[The Associated Press]] |date=22 February 2014 |author=Caldwell, Alicia A. |author2=Corcoran, Catherine |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223030727/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/mexicos-sinaloa-drug-chief-arrested |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> The operation leading to his capture began at 3:45 AM, when ten pickup trucks of the Mexican Navy carrying over 65 marines made their way to the resort area. Guzm\u00e1n was hiding at the Miramar condominiums, located at #608 on Avenida del Mar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mazatl\u00e1n ve la ca\u00edda de 'El Chapo' |url=http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1402/operativo-mazatlan-termina-dos-detenidos/ |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Televisa]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303170116/http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1402/operativo-mazatlan-termina-dos-detenidos/ |archivedate=3 March 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref><ref name=cronicamilenio /> Mexican and U.S. federal agents had leads that the drug lord had been at that location for at least two days, and that he was staying on the condominium's fourth floor, in Room 401. When the Mexican authorities arrived at the location, they quickly subdued [[Carlos Manuel Hoo Ram\u00edrez]], one of Guzm\u00e1n's bodyguards, before quietly making their way to the fourth floor by the elevators and stairs. Once they were at Guzm\u00e1n's front door, they broke into the apartment and stormed its two rooms. In one of the rooms was Guzm\u00e1n, lying in bed with his wife (former beauty queen [[Emma Coronel Aispuro]]).<ref name=cronicamilenio /><ref>{{cite news| title=Su esposa, la reina de belleza Emma Coronel, estaba con El Chapo cuando cay\u00f3| url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/2014/02/24/945415| accessdate=24 February 2014| newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=24 February 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224190057/http://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/2014/02/24/945415 |archivedate=24 February 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> Their two daughters were reported to have been at the condominium during the arrest.<ref>{{cite news| title=Defensa de Guzm\u00e1n Loera frena con amparo su posible extradici\u00f3n a EU |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365777| accessdate=25 February 2014| newspaper=Proceso|date=24 February 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n tried to resist arrest physically,<ref name=cronicamilenio /> but he did not attempt to grab a rifle he had close to him.<ref>{{cite news | title=Celular, pieza clave para el arresto de \"El Chapo\" | url=http://www.aztecanoticias.com.mx/notas/mexico/183614/celular-pieza-clave-para-el-arresto-de-el-chapo | accessdate=25 February 2014 | newspaper=[[TV Azteca|Azteca Noticias]] | date=23 February 2014 | language=Spanish | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303023352/http://www.aztecanoticias.com.mx/notas/mexico/183614/celular-pieza-clave-para-el-arresto-de-el-chapo | archive-date=3 March 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Gomez Licon| first=Adriana| title=Celular llev\u00f3 a arresto de \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n| url=https://news.yahoo.com/celular-llev-arresto-quot-el-chapo-quot-guzm-010440185.html |accessdate=25 February 2014| newspaper=[[Yahoo! News]]| date=23 February 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> Amid the quarrel with the marines, the drug lord was hit four times. By 6:40 AM, he was arrested, taken to the ground floor, and walked to the condominium's parking lot, where the first photos of his capture were taken.<ref name=cronicamilenio>{{cite news |last=Becerra Acosta |first=Juan Pablo |title=El se\u00f1or del cuerno de chivo junto la cama no lo alcanzaba a coger ... |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-arrestan_al_Chapo_Guzman-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_250175210.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227182130/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-arrestan_al_Chapo_Guzman-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_250175210.html |archivedate=27 February 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Althaus |first=Dudley |title=Marines take down drug kingpin Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/americas/mexico/140222/drug-kingpin-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-caught |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[GlobalPost]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223020248/http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/americas/mexico/140222/drug-kingpin-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-caught |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> His identity was confirmed through a [[fingerprint]] examination immediately following his capture.<ref>{{cite news|last=Esquivel |first=Jes\u00fas |title=Detienen a \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n en hotel de Mazatl\u00e1n |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365562 |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223031155/http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365562 |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> He was then flown to Mexico City, the country's capital, for formal identification.<ref>{{cite news| last=H.T.| title=Arrest of a drug lord: Got Shorty| url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/02/arrest-drug-lord| accessdate=22 February 2014| newspaper=[[The Economist]]| date=22 February 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222220116/https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/02/arrest-drug-lord |archivedate=22 February 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> According to the Mexican government, no shots were fired during the operation.<ref name=\"To Snitch on a Trap God\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Lara |first=Carlos |title=Operativo para capturar a \"El Chapo\" fue puro y sin ning\u00fan disparo: PGR |url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldemexico/notas/n3300539.htm |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=El Sol de M\u00e9xico |date=23 February 2014 |agency=[[Organizaci\u00f3n Editorial Mexicana]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301154708/http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldemexico/notas/n3300539.htm |archivedate=1 March 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n was presented in front of cameras during a press conference at the [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez International Airport|Mexico City International Airport]] that afternoon,<ref>{{cite news|title=Blindan el Aeropuerto para la presentaci\u00f3n de \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/blindan-el-aeropuerto-para-la-presentacion-de-el-chapo-guzman |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[R\u00edodoce]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223031824/http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/blindan-el-aeropuerto-para-la-presentacion-de-el-chapo-guzman |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> and then he was transferred to the [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1]], a maximum-security prison in [[Almoloya de Ju\u00e1rez]], State of Mexico, on a [[Federal Police (Mexico)|Federal Police]] Black Hawk helicopter. The helicopter was escorted by two Navy helicopters and one from the Mexican Air Force.<ref>{{cite news|last=Monroy |first=Jorge |title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n fue trasladado al penal del Altiplano |url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/sociedad/2014/02/22/chapo-guzman-fue-trasladado-penal-altiplano |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Economista (Mexico)|El Economista]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223032105/http://eleconomista.com.mx/sociedad/2014/02/22/chapo-guzman-fue-trasladado-penal-altiplano |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Alzaga |first=Ignacio |title=Encarcelan a 'El Chapo' en penal del Altiplano |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Chapo_penal_Altiplano_0_250175186.html |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301214232/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Chapo_penal_Altiplano_0_250175186.html |archivedate=1 March 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> Surveillance inside the penitentiary and surrounding areas was increased by a large contingent of law enforcement.<ref>{{cite news |last=D\u00e1vila |first=Israel |title=Regresa El Chapo al penal de alta seguridad de El Altiplano |url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2014/02/22/regresa-el-chapo-al-penal-de-alta-seguridad-de-el-altiplano-1622.html |accessdate=6 November 2016 |newspaper=[[La Jornada]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223043606/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2014/02/22/regresa-el-chapo-al-penal-de-alta-seguridad-de-el-altiplano-1622.html |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Reactions ====\nMexican President [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]] confirmed the arrest through [[Twitter]] and congratulated the [[Secretariat of National Defense (Mexico)|Secretariat of National Defense]] (SEDENA), [[Secretariat of the Navy (Mexico)|Secretariat of the Navy]] (SEMAR), [[Procuradur\u00eda General de la Rep\u00fablica|Office of the General Prosecutor]] (PGR), the Federal Police, and the [[Centro de Investigaci\u00f3n y Seguridad Nacional (M\u00e9xico)|Centro de Investigaci\u00f3n y Seguridad Nacional]] (CISEN) for Guzm\u00e1n's capture.<ref name=AParrest /><ref>{{cite news|title=Cae 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n, el narcotraficante m\u00e1s buscado |url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2014/02/22/el-lider-del-cartel-de-sinaloa-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-es-detenido |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222201220/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2014/02/22/el-lider-del-cartel-de-sinaloa-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-es-detenido |archivedate=22 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Felicitan a EPN por detenci\u00f3n de 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1402/felicitan-epn-detencion-el-chapo-guzman/ |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Televisa]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713092042/http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1402/felicitan-epn-detencion-el-chapo-guzman/ |archivedate=13 July 2015 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> In the United States, [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Eric Holder]] said Guzm\u00e1n had caused \"death and destruction of millions of lives across the globe\" and called the arrest \"a landmark achievement, and a victory for the citizens of both Mexico and the United States\".<ref name=\"cnn arrest\" /> [[Colombia]]'s President [[Juan Manuel Santos]] telephoned Pe\u00f1a Nieto and congratulated him for the arrest of Guzm\u00e1n, highlighting its importance in the international efforts against drug trafficking.<ref>{{cite news|title=Presidente de Colombia felicita a EPN por captura de 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/965521.presidente-de-colombia-felicita-a-epn-por-captura-de-el-chapo.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225192138/http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/965521.presidente-de-colombia-felicita-a-epn-por-captura-de-el-chapo.html |archivedate=25 February 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Colombia's Defense Minister, [[Juan Carlos Pinz\u00f3n]], congratulated Mexico on Guzm\u00e1n's arrest and stated that his capture \"contributes to eradicate this crime ([[drug trafficking]]) in the region\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Colombia felicita a M\u00e9xico por captura de El Chapo |url=http://www.debate.com.mx/eldebate/noticias/default.asp?IdArt=14085260&IdCat=6103 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=El Debate |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223052541/http://www.debate.com.mx/eldebate/noticias/default.asp?IdArt=14085260&IdCat=6103 |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=dead |language=Spanish |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Guatemalan President [[Otto P\u00e9rez Molina]] congratulated the Mexican government for the arrest.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se suma Guatemala a felicitaciones por detenci\u00f3n |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/guatemala-detencion-felicitaciones-mexico-chapo-989805.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223032813/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/guatemala-detencion-felicitaciones-mexico-chapo-989805.html |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> [[Costa Rica]]'s President [[Laura Chinchilla]] congratulated the Mexican government through Twitter for the capture too.<ref>{{cite news |title=Autoridades internacionales felicitan a M\u00e9xico por captura de \"El Chapo\" |url=http://noticias.prodigy.msn.com/internacional/autoridades-internacionales-felicitan-a-m%C3%A9xico-por-captura-de-%E2%80%9Cel-chapo%E2%80%9D |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=MSN |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Nar5RVpl?url=http://noticias.prodigy.msn.com/internacional/autoridades-internacionales-felicitan-a-m%C3%A9xico-por-captura-de-%E2%80%9Cel-chapo%E2%80%9D |archivedate=23 February 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The French government extended its congratulations on 24 February and supported the Mexican security forces in their combat against organized crime.<ref>{{cite news|title=Francia felicita a M\u00e9xico por captura de 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.milenio.com/politica/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Francia_0_251374926.html |accessdate=24 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=24 February 2014 |agency=24 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228044524/http://www.milenio.com/politica/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman-Francia_0_251374926.html |archivedate=28 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> News of Guzm\u00e1n's capture made it to the headlines of many media outlets across the U.S., Latin America, and Europe.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pantoja |first=Sara |title=Prensa internacional resalta la captura del capo \"m\u00e1s buscado en el mundo\" |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365663 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223051712/http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365663 |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Captura de 'El Chapo' acapara medios internacionales |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman_0_250175132.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303081340/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-Cartel_de_Sinaloa-Cae_Chapo_Guzman_0_250175132.html |archivedate=3 March 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref> On Twitter, Mexico and Guzm\u00e1n's capture were [[trending topics]] throughout most of 22 February 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vivas |first=Mar\u00eda Luisa |title=Reaprehensi\u00f3n del capo, Trending Topic mundial |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365664 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]] |date=22 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223051900/http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=365664 |archivedate=23 February 2014 |url-status=live |language=Spanish |df= }}</ref>\n\nBob Nardoza, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York|District Court for the Eastern District of New York]], announced that U.S. authorities plan to seek the extradition of Guzm\u00e1n for several cases pending against him in New York and other United States jurisdictions.<ref>{{cite press release|last1=Shoichet |first1=Catherine |last2=Prokupecz |first2=Shimon |title=They got 'Shorty' -- now what? Cases pending against drug boss in several US jurisdictions |url=http://www.kcci.com/national/They-got-Shorty-now-what/24629878 |accessdate=23 February 2014 |publisher=CNN |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224050832/http://www.kcci.com/national/They-got-Shorty-now-what/24629878 |archivedate=24 February 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n==== Charges and imprisonment ====\nGuzm\u00e1n was imprisoned at [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1]], area #20, Hallway #1, on the same day of his capture on 22 February 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo ya tiene abogado|url=http://www.razon.com.mx/spip.php?article206605|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=La Raz\u00f3n|date=23 February 2014|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227081101/http://www.razon.com.mx/spip.php?article206605|archive-date=27 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The area where he lived was highly restricted; the cells are without windows, inmates are not allowed to interact with each other, and they are not permitted to contact their family members.<ref>{{cite news |last=G\u00f3mora| first=Doris|title=Primera noche en prisi\u00f3n, sin antecedentes| url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion-mexico/2014/impreso/primera-noche-en-prision-sin-incidentes-213395.html|accessdate=24 February 2014|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]]|date=24 February 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref> His cell was close to those of Jos\u00e9 Jorge Balderas (''alias'' \"El JJ\"), former lieutenant of the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel, and [[Jaime Gonz\u00e1lez Dur\u00e1n]] (''alias'' \"El Hummer\"), a former leader of [[Los Zetas]] drug cartel. Miguel \u00c1ngel Guzm\u00e1n Loera, one of his brothers, was in one of the other units.<ref name=carcelmilenio /><ref>{{cite news|title=Abogado se acredita formalmente como defensor de 'El Chapo'|url=http://www.adnpolitico.com/gobierno/2014/02/23/abogado-se-acredita-formalmente-como-abogado-de-el-chapo|accessdate=25 February 2014|newspaper=ADNPol\u00edtico|date=24 February 2014|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224163011/http://www.adnpolitico.com/gobierno/2014/02/23/abogado-se-acredita-formalmente-como-abogado-de-el-chapo|archive-date=24 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n was alone in his cell, and had one bed, one shower, and a single toilet. His lawyer was \u00d3scar Quirarte. Guzm\u00e1n was allowed to receive visits from members of his family every nine days from 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to 5:00&nbsp;p.m. (if approved by a judge), and was granted by law the right to receive MXN$638 (about US$48) every month to buy products for personal hygiene.<ref name=carcelmilenio>{{cite news|last=Valdez |first=Blanca |title=\u00d3scar Quirarte es el abogado de 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-penal_de_maxima_seguridad_del_Altiplano-Almoloya_de_Juarez_0_250775087.html |accessdate=23 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=23 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301214236/http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Guzman_Loera-penal_de_maxima_seguridad_del_Altiplano-Almoloya_de_Juarez_0_250775087.html |archivedate=1 March 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=aislamiento /> He lived under 23 hours of [[solitary confinement]] with one hour of outdoor exposure. He was only allowed to speak with people during his judicial hearings (the prison guards that secured his cell were not allowed to speak with him). Unlike the other inmates, Guzm\u00e1n was prohibited from practicing sport or cultural activities. These conditions were court-approved and could only be changed if a federal judge decided to amend them.<ref name=aislamiento>{{cite news |title=\"El Chapo\": 23 horas de aislamiento por una de sol |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=370779| accessdate=27 April 2014| newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=27 April 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February, the Mexican government formally charged Guzm\u00e1n for drug trafficking, a process that slowed down his possible extradition to the U.S. The decision to initially file only one charge against him showed that the Mexican government was working on preparing more formal charges against Guzm\u00e1n, and possibly including the charges he faced before his escape from prison in 2001. The kingpin also faces charges in at least seven U.S. jurisdictions, and U.S. officials filed for his extradition.<ref>{{cite news |title=Joaquin \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n formally charged in Mexico, likely slowing extradition to U.S. |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-formally-charged-in-mexico-likely-slowing-extradition/| accessdate=24 February 2014| newspaper=[[CBS News]]| date=24 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mexican drug kingpin seeks to block US extradition |url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/mexican-drug-kingpin-seeks-block-us-extradition-214230238.html| accessdate=24 February 2014| newspaper=[[Yahoo News]]| date=24 February 2014}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n was initially granted an [[injunction]] preventing immediate extradition to the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title='Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n arrest: Mexican corrido singer chronicles capture| date=26 February 2014| first=Diana| last=Washington Valdez| work=El Paso Times |url=http://www.willitsnews.com/general-news/20140226/chapo-guzman-arrest-mexican-corrido-singer-chronicles-capture| accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref> On 25 February, a Mexican federal judge set the trial in motion for drug-related and organized crime charges,<ref>{{cite news |last=Stevenson| first=Mark| title=Judge Sets Mexican Trial for 'El Chapo' in Motion |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/el-chapo-stay-strong-inside-mexican-prison-22669323| accessdate=25 February 2014| newspaper=[[ABC News]]| date=25 February 2014}}<br /></ref> On 4 March 2014, a Mexican federal court issued a formal charge against Guzm\u00e1n for his involvement in organized crime.<ref>{{cite news |last=Castillo| first=Gustavo| title=Dictan tercer auto de formal prisi\u00f3n contra 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2014/03/04/dictan-quinto-auto-de-formal-prision-contra-el-chapo-1781.html| accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=[[La Jornada]]| date=4 March 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306013744/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2014/03/04/dictan-quinto-auto-de-formal-prision-contra-el-chapo-1781.html| archivedate=6 March 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gandaria|first=Manrique|title=Dictan el cuarto auto de formal prisi\u00f3n contra \"El Chapo\" |url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldemexico/notas/n3313041.htm|accessdate=6 March 2014|newspaper=El Sol de M\u00e9xico|date=5 March 2014|agency=[[Organizaci\u00f3n Editorial Mexicana]]|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2014, a Mexico City federal court rejected Guzm\u00e1n's injunction against extradition to the U.S. on the grounds that the U.S. officials had not formally requested his extradition from Mexico. The court said that if the U.S. files a request in the future, Guzm\u00e1n can petition for another injunction.<ref>{{cite news |title=El Chapo denied petition against U.S. extradition| url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/el-chapo-denied-petition-against-us-extradition| accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=[[The Associated Press]]| date=6 March 2014| location=Mexico City}}</ref> The court had until 9 April 2014 to issue a formal declaration of the injunction's rejection, and Guzm\u00e1n's lawyers could appeal the court's decision in the meantime.<ref>{{cite news |title=Se complica la situaci\u00f3n jur\u00eddica de El Chapo| url=http://noticias.univision.com/article/1873670/2014-03-05/mexico/noticias/el-chapo-pierde-un-amparo-para-evitar-una-posible-extradicion| accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=[[Univision]]|date=5 March 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> The same day that the injunction was rejected, another federal court issued formal charges against Guzm\u00e1n, totaling up to five different Mexican federal courts where he was wanted for drug trafficking and organized crime charges.<ref>{{cite news |title=Un juez emite la quinta orden de formal prisi\u00f3n contra 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2014/03/05/un-juez-emite-la-cuarta-orden-de-formal-prision-contra-el-chapo-guzman|accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico| date=5 March 2014| agency=[[Turner Broadcasting System]]|language=Spanish}}</ref> The court explained that although Guzm\u00e1n faces charges in several different courts, he cannot be sentenced for the same crime twice because that would violate [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 23|Article 23]] of the [[Constitution of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Carrasco Araizaga| first=Jorge| title=Suman 5 autos de formal prisi\u00f3n contra \"El Chapo\"; le niegan amparo contra extradici\u00f3n| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=366493| accessdate=6 March 2014| newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=5 March 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April 2014, the Attorney General of Mexico, [[Jes\u00fas Murillo Karam]], said that Mexico had no intention of extraditing Guzm\u00e1n to the U.S. even if a formal request were to be presented. He said he wished to see Guzm\u00e1n face charges in Mexico, and expressed his disagreement with how the U.S. cuts deals with extradited Mexican criminals by reducing their sentences (as in [[Vicente Zambada Niebla]]'s case) in exchange for information.<ref>{{cite news |last=Estevez| first=Dolia| title=Upset About A Controversial Narco Deal, Mexico Reaffirms It Will Not Extradite Drug Kingpin El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n To The U.S.| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2014/04/17/upset-about-a-controversial-narco-deal-mexico-reaffirms-it-will-not-extradite-drug-kingpin-el-chapo-guzman-to-the-u-s/| accessdate=20 April 2014| newspaper=[[Forbes]]| date=17 April 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419044704/http://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2014/04/17/upset-about-a-controversial-narco-deal-mexico-reaffirms-it-will-not-extradite-drug-kingpin-el-chapo-guzman-to-the-u-s/| archivedate=19 April 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 July 2014, Guzm\u00e1n reportedly helped organize a five-day hunger strike in the prison in cooperation with inmate and former drug lord [[Edgar Valdez Villarreal]] (''alias'' \"La Barbie\"). Over 1,000 prisoners reportedly participated in the protest and complained of the prison's poor hygiene, food, and medical treatment. The Mexican government confirmed that the strike took place and that the prisoners' demands were satisfied, but denied that Guzm\u00e1n or Valdez Villarreal were involved in it given their status as prisoners in solitary confinement.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hern\u00e1ndez| first1=Anabel| title='El Chapo' y 'La Barbie' ponen de cabeza el penal del Altiplano| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=377621| accessdate=2 September 2014| magazine=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=19 July 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720183503/http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=377621| archivedate=20 July 2014| url-status=live| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Partlow |first1=Joshua |title=The Mexican drug lord Chapo Guzm\u00e1n is in prison. But he might live by his own rules |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/the-mexican-drug-lord-chapo-guzman-is-in-prison-but-he-might-live-by-his-own-rules/2014/08/28/1878a689-aeaf-4d4f-a8bc-fca2dab3a02e_story.html |accessdate=2 September 2014 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=31 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140829191149/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/the-mexican-drug-lord-chapo-guzman-is-in-prison-but-he-might-live-by-his-own-rules/2014/08/28/1878a689-aeaf-4d4f-a8bc-fca2dab3a02e_story.html |archivedate=29 August 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 2014, Guzm\u00e1n and his former business partner Zambada were indicted by the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York]] in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cawley |first1=Marguerite |title=US Indictment Shows Escalating Political Battle for Mexico's 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.insightcrime.com/news-briefs/us-indictment-shows-escalating-political-battle-mexicos-el-chapo |accessdate=9 October 2014 |publisher=[[InSight Crime]] |date=9 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009183722/http://www.insightcrime.com/news-briefs/us-indictment-shows-escalating-political-battle-mexicos-el-chapo |archivedate= 9 October 2014 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> According to the court documents, both of them conspired to kill Mexican law enforcement officers, government officials, and members of the Mexican Armed Forces. Among the people killed under the alleged orders of Guzm\u00e1n were Roberto Velasco Bravo (2008), the chief of Mexico's organized crime investigatory division; Rafael Ram\u00edrez Jaime (2008), the chief of the arrest division of the Attorney General's Office; Rodolfo Carrillo Fuentes (2004), former leader of the Ju\u00e1rez Cartel, among other criminals from the Tijuana, Los Zetas, Beltr\u00e1n Leyva, and Ju\u00e1rez crime syndicates.<ref name=forbesindictment /> The court alleged that Guzm\u00e1n used professional assassins to carry out \"hundreds of acts of violence, including murders, assaults, kidnappings, assassinations and acts of torture\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marzulli| first1=John| title=EXCLUSIVE: Mexican druglord Joaquin (El Chapo) Guzm\u00e1n charged with 12 murders in new indictment| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/exclusive-druglord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-charged-12-murders-article-1.1965623| accessdate=8 October 2014| newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]| date=8 October 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008145312/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/exclusive-druglord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-charged-12-murders-article-1.1965623| archivedate=8 October 2014|  url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, it alleged that he oversaw a drug-trafficking empire that transported multi-ton shipments of narcotics from South America, through Central America and Mexico, and then to the U.S., and that his network was facilitated by corrupt law enforcement and public officials.<ref name=forbesindictment>{{cite news |last1=Estevez| first1=Dolia| title=Mexican Drug Lords El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n, Ismael Zambada Charged With A Dozen Killings In New U.S. Indictment| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2014/10/07/mexican-drug-lords-el-chapo-guzman-ismael-zambada-charged-with-a-dozen-killings-in-new-u-s-indictment/| accessdate=8 October 2014| work=[[Forbes]]|date=8 October 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008013626/http://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2014/10/07/mexican-drug-lords-el-chapo-guzman-ismael-zambada-charged-with-a-dozen-killings-in-new-u-s-indictment/| archivedate=8 October 2014}}</ref> It also alleged that Guzm\u00e1n laundered more than US$14 billion in drug proceeds along with several other high-ranking drug lords.<ref name='Forbes2017'/><ref name='FoxLatino'>{{cite news |title=Notorious Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n indicted in New York, opening door to possible extradition| url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2014/10/07/notorious-mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-indicted-in-new-york-opening-door/| accessdate=8 October 2014| publisher=[[Fox News]]| date=8 October 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008014044/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2014/10/07/notorious-mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-indicted-in-new-york-opening-door/| archivedate=8 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 November 2014, a federal court in Sinaloa granted Guzm\u00e1n an injunction for weaponry charges after the judge determined that the arrest was not carried out the way the Mexican Navy reported it.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ram\u00edrez de Aguilar|first1=Fernando| title=Otorgan un amparo al \"Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n|url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/sociedad/otorgan-un-amparo-al-chapo-guzman.html| accessdate=13 November 2014| publisher=El Financiero| date=13 November 2014| language=Spanish}}</ref> According to law enforcement, the Navy apprehended Guzm\u00e1n after they received an anonymous tip on an armed individual in the hotel where he was staying. However, no evidence of the anonymous tip was provided. The judge also determined that the investigations leading to his arrest were not presented in court. He determined that law enforcement's version of the arrest had several irregularities because the Navy did not have a raid warrant when they entered the premises and arrested Guzm\u00e1n (when he was not the subject matter of the anonymous tip in the first place).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mosso |first1=Rub\u00e9n |title=Tribunal ampara a 'El Chapo' |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-captura_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_407959393.html |accessdate=13 November 2014 |publisher=[[Milenio]] |date=13 November 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113103315/http://www.milenio.com/policia/Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-captura_Chapo_Guzman-Cartel_de_Sinaloa_0_407959393.html |archivedate=13 November 2014 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2015, Guzm\u00e1n requested another injunction through his lawyer Andr\u00e9s Granados Flores to prevent his extradition to the U.S.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vela| first1=David Sa\u00fal| title='El Chapo' tramita amparo ante posible extradici\u00f3n a EU| url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/el-chapo-tramita-amparo-ante-posible-extradicion-a-eu.html| accessdate=24 January 2015| publisher=El Financiero| date=23 January 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> His defense argued that if he were to be extradited and judged in a foreign court, his constitutional rights expressed in [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 1|Articles 1]], [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 14|14]], [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 16|16]], [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 17|17]], [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 18|18]] and [[Constitution of Mexico#Article 20|20]] of the Constitution of Mexico would be violated.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alzaga| first1=Ignacio|title=Promueve El Chapo amparo para evitar extradici\u00f3n a EU| url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/promueve_amparo_chapo-amparo_extradicion_chapo-el_chapo_guzman_0_451155237.html| accessdate=24 January 2015| publisher=[[Milenio]]| date=23 January 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> The decision of his defense was made after Attorney General Murillo Karam said at a press conference that the U.S. was pushing to formally request his extradition.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuevo amparo del \"Chapo\" contra extradici\u00f3n| url=http://zetatijuana.com/noticias/generalez/17105/nuevo-amparo-del-chapo-contra-extradicion| accessdate=24 January 2015| magazine=[[Zeta (magazine)|Zeta]]| date=23 January 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> The PGR and Mexico's [[Secretariat of Foreign Affairs (Mexico)|Secretariat of Foreign Affairs]] stated that Guzm\u00e1n had a provisional arrest with extradition purposes from the U.S. government since 17 February 2001, but that the formal proceedings to officiate the extradition were not realized because investigators considered that the request was outdated and believed it would have been difficult to gather potential witnesses.<ref>{{cite news |title=Busca 'El Chapo' amparo para evitar extradici\u00f3n a Estados Unidos|url=http://diario.mx/Nacional/2015-01-23_995ad1a0/busca-el-chapo-amparo-para-evitar-extradicion-a-estados-unidos-|accessdate=24 January 2015|publisher=Diario de Ju\u00e1rez|date=23 January 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Murillo Karam said that the Mexican government would process the request when they deemed it appropriate.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Estevez|first1=Dolia|title=Confirmed: U.S. Will Request That Mexico Extradite Drug Lord Joaqu\u00edn El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/doliaestevez/2015/01/21/confirmed-u-s-will-request-that-mexico-extradite-drug-lord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman/|accessdate=24 January 2015|work=[[Forbes]]|date=21 January 2015}}</ref> He asked for a second injunction preventing his extradition on 26 January. Mexico City federal judge Fabricio Villegas asked federal authorities to confirm in 24 hours if there was a pending extradition request against Guzm\u00e1n.<ref>{{cite news|last1=M\u00e9ndez|first1=Alfredo|title=Otorgan a 'El Chapo' segundo amparo contra extradici\u00f3n a EU|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2015/01/26/otorgan-suspension-de-amparo-a-el-chapo-contra-extradicion-a-eu-594.html|accessdate=29 January 2015|publisher=[[La Jornada]]|date=26 January 2015|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801102231/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2015/01/26/otorgan-suspension-de-amparo-a-el-chapo-contra-extradicion-a-eu-594.html|archive-date=1 August 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a press conference the following day, Murillo Karam said that he was expecting a request from Washington, but said that they would not extradite him until he faces charges and completes his sentences in Mexico. If all the charges are added up, Guzm\u00e1n may receive a sentence between 300 and 400 years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Verza|first1=Maria |title=Mexico: Captured drug lord 'Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n to stay put |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/0fbcdfcab6f94b268c74cd651a35b932/mexico-ag-captured-drug-lord-chapo-guzman-stay-put |accessdate=29 January 2015 |work=Associated Press |date=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=reuters-2nd-escape>{{cite news |last1=Stargardter|first1=Gabriel |title=Mexico says drug lord 'Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n escapes from prison |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/12/us-mexcio-guzman-idUSKCN0PM07020150712 |accessdate=12 July 2015 |publisher=Reuters |date=12 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Second escape and third arrest ==\n\n=== Second escape: 2015 ===\nOn 11 July 2015, Guzm\u00e1n escaped from [[Federal Social Readaptation Center No. 1]], a maximum-security prison.<ref name=reuters-2nd-escape /> After receiving medication,<ref name=reformafuga>{{cite news|last1=Mart\u00ednez|first1=C\u00e9sar|title=Escap\u00f3 'Chapo' por t\u00fanel de 1.5 km|url=http://www.reforma.com/aplicacioneslibre/articulo/default.aspx?id=589370&md5=fff66622e1862e9b295ee653b4ff13be&ta=0dfdbac11765226904c16cb9ad1b2efe#ixzz3fggfMYlD|publisher=[[Reforma]]|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n was last seen by security cameras at 20:52 hours near the shower area in his cell. The shower area was the only part of his cell that was not visible through the security camera.<ref name=laescape>{{cite news|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Tracy|title=Drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzman escapes from Mexico prison -- again|url=https://latimes.com/world/mexico-americas/la-fg-drug-lord-escapes-mexico-prison-20150711-story.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> After the guards did not see him for twenty-five minutes on surveillance video, personnel went looking for him.<ref name=CNNElChapo>{{cite news|last1=Hanna|first1=Jason|title=Seven prison workers charged in connection with 'El Chapo' escape|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/07/17/americas/mexico-el-chapo-escape/|publisher=CNN|date=18 July 2015|language=}}</ref> When they reached his cell, Guzm\u00e1n was gone. It was discovered he had [[Escape tunnel|escaped through a tunnel]] leading from the shower area to a house construction site {{convert|1.5|km|abbr=on}} away in a Santa Juanita neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news| title=Se escapa \"El Chapo\" por un t\u00fanel de 1.5 kil\u00f3metros| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=410392| magazine=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=12 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Castillo| first1=Eduardo E. |last2=Corcoran| first2=Katherine| title=Mexico: Drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzman escapes through tunnel| url=https://news.yahoo.com/mexico-top-drug-lord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-064113154.html |agency=[[The Associated Press]]| publisher=Yahoo News| date=12 July 2015}}</ref> The tunnel lay {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}} deep underground, and Guzm\u00e1n used a ladder to climb to the bottom. The tunnel was {{convert|1.7|m|abbr=on}} tall and {{convert|75|cm|abbr=on}} in width. It was equipped with artificial light, air ducts, and high-quality construction materials.<ref name=reformafuga /> In addition, a [[motorcycle]] was found in the tunnel, which authorities think was used to transport materials and possibly Guzm\u00e1n himself.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dudley|first1=Steven|title=El Chapo's 2nd Escape Could Paralyze Mexico's National Security Plans|url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-analysis/el-chapo-s-2nd-escape-could-paralyze-mexico-s-already-reeling-security-strategy|publisher=[[InSight Crime]]|date=12 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Notorious Mexican Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Escapes Prison for Second Time|url = https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/mexican-drug-lord-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-escapes-prison-second-n390706|website = NBC News| accessdate = 9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Second runaway and manhunt: 2015\u20132016 ===\nThe escape of Guzm\u00e1n triggered a wide-range manhunt.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Partlow| first1=Joshua| last2=Miroff| first2=Nick|title=Huge manhunt in Mexico as drug lord Chapo Guzm\u00e1n tunnels out of prison| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/drug-lord-chapo-guzman-tunnels-out-of-maximum-security-prison/2015/07/12/90279efe-666a-49fb-aba4-4177bb36f0a0_story.html| newspaper=The Washington Post| date=12 July 2015}}</ref> According to Mexico's National Security Commissioner Monte Alejandro Rubido&nbsp;Garc\u00eda, the manhunt was instituted immediately in the surrounding area by putting up several checkpoints and air searches by helicopter.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Alzag |first1=Ignacio| title=El Chapo se fug\u00f3 \u2026 otra vez| url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/fuga-nuevamente-Chapo-Guzman-Altiplano-Penal-Federal-CNS-Joaquin_0_553144682.html| publisher=[[Milenio]]| date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> The entire prison was put on lockdown and no one was allowed to enter or leave.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Partlow| first1=Joshua| last2=Miroff| first2=Nick| title=Drug lord Chapo Guzman tunnels out of maximum-security Mexico prison| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/drug-lord-chapo-guzman-tunnels-out-of-maximum-security-prison/2015/07/12/90279efe-666a-49fb-aba4-4177bb36f0a0_story.html| newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> The search was then extended to other federal entities: Mexico City, the State of Mexico, [[Morelos]], [[Puebla]], [[Guerrero]], [[Michoac\u00e1n]], [[Quer\u00e9taro]], [[Hidalgo (state)|Hidalgo]] and [[Tlaxcala]]. However, most of the military officers involved in the search were sent to the State of Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jim\u00e9nez|first1=Benito|title=Buscan al 'Chapo' en 9 entidades|url=http://www.reforma.com/aplicacioneslibre/articulo/default.aspx?id=589374&md5=1c521e6ad138567d1f7521e754eb78e7&ta=0dfdbac11765226904c16cb9ad1b2efe#ixzz3fgpNCJQQ|publisher=[[Reforma]]|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> The Mexican government also issued an international warning to prevent Guzm\u00e1n from escaping the country through airports, border checkpoints, or ports. Interpol and other security organizations were alerted to the possibility of him escaping into another country.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mosso|first1=Rub\u00e9n|title=Emiten alerta internacional por fuga de El Chapo|url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/alerta_internacional_chapo-fuga_el_chapo_guzman-joaquin_chapo_guzman_0_553144757.html|publisher=[[Milenio]]|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Flights at the [[Toluca International Airport]] were cancelled, while soldiers occupied parts of [[Mexico City International Airport]].<ref name=laescape /> Out of the 120 employees that were working at the prison that night, eighteen that worked in the area of Guzm\u00e1n's cell were initially detained for questioning.<ref name=procesofuga1>{{cite news| last1=Mendoza| first1=Veneranda| title=\"El Chapo\" tuvo dos horas para escapar; sobrevol\u00f3 la zona un \"helic\u00f3ptero peque\u00f1o\"| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=410421| magazine=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=12 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> By the afternoon, a total of 31 people had been called in for questioning. The director of the prison, Valent\u00edn C\u00e1rdenas Lerma, was among those detained.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Mosso| first1=Rub\u00e9n| title=Declaran 31 por fuga de el Chapo, entre ellos el director del penal |url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/arely_gomex_penal_altiplano-fuga_chapo_guzman-joaquin_chapo_guzman_0_553144770.html| accessdate=12 July 2015|publisher=[[Milenio]]| date=12 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nWhen the news of the escape broke, President Pe\u00f1a Nieto was heading to a state visit in France along with several top officials from his cabinet and many others.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harrup|first1=Anthony|last2=Althaus|first2=Dudley|title=Mexican Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Escapes From Prison|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-escapes-from-prison-1436703513|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> The [[Secretariat of the Interior (Mexico)|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Osorio Chong]], who was already in France waiting for them, returned to Mexico after learning of Guzm\u00e1n's prison break.<ref>{{cite news|title=Una noticia congel\u00f3 el vuelo presidencial a Francia|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/articulo/nacion/politica/2015/07/12/una-noticia-congelo-el-vuelo-presidencial-francia|publisher=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]]|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Osorio Chong regresa a M\u00e9xico por fuga del Chapo|url=http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/osorio-chong-regresa-a-mexico-por-fuga-del-chapo.html|publisher=El Financiero|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> Pe\u00f1a Nieto returned to Mexico on 17 July.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rivera|first1=Carolina|title=Osorio Chong regresa a M\u00e9xico por fuga de 'El Chapo'|url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/Osorio_Chong_regresa_Mexico_fuga_-El_Chapo-fuga_chapo_guzman-guzman_loera_0_553144725.html|publisher=[[Milenio]]|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> In a press conference, Pe\u00f1a Nieto said he was shocked by Guzm\u00e1n's escape, and promised that the government would carry out an intensive investigation to see if officials had collaborated in the prison break. In addition, he claimed that Guzm\u00e1n's escape was an \"affront\" to the Mexican government, and that they would not spare any resources in trying to recapture him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fuga de 'el Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n es una \"afrenta\" al Estado mexicano: Pe\u00f1a|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2015/07/12/la-fuga-de-el-chapo-guzman-es-lamentable-e-indigna-pena|agency=[[Turner Broadcasting System]]|publisher=CNNM\u00e9xico|date=12 July 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Pe\u00f1a Nieto, however, was severely criticized for the incident, and media outlets pointed out that this incident was among the administration's most embarrassing episodes. Critics stated that Guzm\u00e1n's escape highlighted the high levels of corruption within the government, and questioned the government's ability to combat the country's organized crime groups.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Neuman|first1=William|last2=Ahmed|first2=Azam|title=Stunning Escape of Joaqu\u00edn 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Fuels Mexicans' Cynicism|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/14/world/americas/mexico-joaquin-guzman-loera-el-chapo-prison-escape.html|work=The New York Times|date=13 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Barrett|first1=Devlin|title=U.S. Officials Cite Intelligence Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n Was Plotting Escape|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-officials-cite-intelligence-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzman-was-plotting-escape-1436807234|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=13 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July 2015, Osorio Chong met with members of the cabinet that specialize in security and law enforcement intelligence to discuss the escape of Guzm\u00e1n, and scheduled a press conference that day. The objective of the meeting and the conference was to analyze the actions the government employed to recapture him. Among them were Rubido Garc\u00eda, [[Arely G\u00f3mez Gonz\u00e1lez]], the Attorney General of Mexico and Eugenio Imaz Gispert, head of the [[Centro de Investigaci\u00f3n y Seguridad Nacional (M\u00e9xico)|Center for Research and National Security]].<ref>{{cite news| title=Osorio Chong encabeza reuniones para recapturar a Guzm\u00e1n| url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=410463| magazine=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]| date=13 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Osorio encabezar\u00e1 reuni\u00f3n de seguridad para buscar a 'El Chapo'| url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/El_Chapo-Chapo_Guzman-Joaquin_Chapo_Guzman-fuga_Chapo_Guzman_0_553744723.html| publisher=[[Milenio]]| date=13 July 2015| language=Spanish}}</ref> At the press conference, the government placed a $60 million MXN bounty (approximately US$3.8 million) for information that leads to Guzm\u00e1n's arrest.<ref>{{cite news| title=PGR ofrece 60 mdp de recompensa por 'El Chapo'| url=http://noticieros.televisa.com/coberturas/chapo-guzman/1507/pgr-ofrece-60-mdp-recompensa-chapo/| publisher=[[Televisa]]| date=13 July 2015| location=Mexico City| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nA number of officials were indicted; of these, three were police officers employed within the Division of Intelligence, and another two were employed by [[CISEN]].<ref>Business Insider \u2013 [http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/world/heres-why-el-chapo-probably-wont-be-recaptured-any-time-soon/ar-AAdIhbM news] published by [[msn]] 30 July 2015 [Retrieved 1 August 2015]</ref>\n\n==== Colombian assistance ====\nOfficials of the Mexican government appealed to three Colombian Police retired generals for assistance in the closure of issues relating to Guzm\u00e1n, according to a report dated to 1 August 2015.<ref name=\"Manhunters\">A. Dawber \u2013 [http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/world/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-manhunters-who-caught-pablo-escobar-are-tasked-with-tracking-down-escaped-mexican-drug-lord/ar-BBlgTbI Article:''Manhunters tasked with capture''] published by [[The Independent]] via msn [Retrieved 1 August 2015]</ref> Among them is [[Rosso Jos\u00e9 Serrano]], a decorated officer and one of the masterminds behind the dismantling of the [[Cali Cartel]] and [[Medell\u00edn Cartel]] and Luis Enrique Montenegro, protagonist in the arrests of [[Miguel Rodr\u00edguez Orejuela|Miguel]] and [[Gilberto Rodr\u00edguez Orejuela]]. They suggested particular Colombian strategies like creation of special search units (\"Bloques de B\u00fasqueda\" or [[Search Bloc]]s), specialized investigation and intelligence units, like [[DIJIN]] (Directorate of Criminal Investigation and Interpol) and DIPOL (Directorate of Police Intelligence) and new laws about [[money laundering]] and [[asset forfeiture]].<ref name=\"Manhunters\"/><ref>{{cite web|title = Luis Enrique Montenegro Rinco|url = http://www.semana.com/enfoque/articulo/luis-enrique-montenegro-rinco/126394-3|website = www.semana.com|accessdate = 9 January 2016}}</ref> After the third capture of Guzm\u00e1n, it was revealed that the [[Government of Colombia]] had sent a team of 12 officials to assist the Mexican authorities on tracking down Guzm\u00e1n.<ref>{{cite web| title=La asesor\u00eda en Colombia para la captura de 'El Chapo'| url=http://cnnespanol.cnn.com/video/cnnee-pkg-ramos-colombian-expertise-help-mexico-chapo/| accessdate=9 January 2016| date=9 January 2016}} (Spanish)</ref>\n\n==== Kate del Castillo meeting ====\nMexican actress [[Kate del Castillo]] was first approached by Guzm\u00e1n's lawyers in 2014,<ref name=Littleton10Jan>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2016/biz/news/kate-del-castillo-el-chapo-sean-penn-1201676183/| title=Kate del Castillo: Meet the Star Playing a Big Part in El Chapo's Real-Life Drama| first1=Cynthia| last1=Littleton| first2=John| last2=Hopewell| work=Variety| date=10 January 2016| accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref> after having published an open letter to Guzm\u00e1n in 2012 in which she expressed her sympathy and requested him to \"traffic in love\" instead of in drugs; Guzm\u00e1n reached out again to del Castillo after his 2015 escape,<ref name=\"extradition 2016\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/11/chapo-guzman-kate-del-castillo-letter_n_1199024.html |title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n, 'World's Most Powerful Drug Trafficker,' Receives Special Request From Mexican Actress, Kate Del Castillo |work=The Huffington Post |date=1 November 2012 |accessdate=2016-01-11 }}</ref> and allegedly sought to cooperate with her in making a film about his life.<ref name=Littleton10Jan/><ref name=Penn9Jan/> American actor [[Sean Penn]] heard about the connection with Ms. del Castillo through a mutual acquaintance, and asked if he might come along to do an interview.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/world/americas/el-chapo-mexican-drug-lord-interview-with-sean-penn.html Sean Penn Met With \u2018El Chapo\u2019 for Interview in His Hide-Out].  Ravi Somaiya, ''The New3 York Times''. 9 January 2016.</ref>\n\nOn 2 October, del Castillo and Penn visited Guzm\u00e1n for seven hours at his hideout in the mountains, with Penn interviewing the fugitive for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine.<ref name=Penn9Jan>{{cite news| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/el-chapo-speaks-40784/| title=El Chapo Speaks| work=Rolling Stone| first=Sean| last=Penn| date=9 January 2016| accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n, who had never before acknowledged his drug trafficking to a journalist, told Penn he had a \"fleet of [[narco-submarine]]s, airplanes, trucks and boats\" and that he supplied \"more heroin, methamphetamine, cocaine and marijuana than anybody else in the world\".<ref name=Penn9Jan />\n\nGuzm\u00e1n had a close call in early October 2015, several days after the meeting with Penn and Kate del Castillo.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan/><ref name=\"extradition 2016\"/> An unnamed Mexican official confirmed that the meeting helped authorities locate Guzm\u00e1n,<ref name=BBC10Jan>{{cite news| work=BBC| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-35276894| title='El Chapo' Guzman: Sean Penn interview provokes US scorn| date=10 January 2016| accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref> with cell phone interceptions and information from American authorities<ref name=Ahmed16Jan/> directing Mexican Marines to a ranch near [[Tamazula de Victoria|Tamazula]], [[Durango]], in the [[Sierra Madre Occidental|Sierra Madre]] mountains in western Mexico.<ref name=Castillo10Jan>{{cite news| url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/L/LT_MEXICO_DRUG_LORD?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-01-10-01-33-52| title= Sean Penn interview helped locate drug lord |date=10 January 2016| accessdate=10 January 2016| work=Associated Press| first1=E. Eduardo| last1=Castillo| first2=Katherine| last2=Corcoran}}</ref> The raid on the ranch was met with heavy gunfire and Guzm\u00e1n was able to flee. The [[Attorney General of Mexico|Attorney General of M\u00e9xico]] declared that \"El Chapo ran away through a gully and, although he was found by a helicopter, he was with two women and a girl and it was decided not to shoot\".<ref>{{cite web| title = Cellphone Signals Suggest 'El Chapo' Hid in Mexican Mountains: Sources| url = https://www.nbcnews.com/news/mexico/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-may-have-hid-mexican-mountains-sources-n444206| website = NBC News| accessdate = 9 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = 'El Chapo' en el momento de la detenci\u00f3n: \"\u00a1Pinches federales, ya nos atraparon!\"| url = http://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2016/01/09/56909b6e46163f45048b4591.html| website = El Mundo |accessdate =10 January 2016| date = 9 January 2016}}</ref> The two women were later revealed to be Guzm\u00e1n's personal chefs, who had traveled with him to multiple safe houses. At one point, Guzm\u00e1n reportedly carried a child on his arms \"obscuring himself as a target\".<ref name=Ahmed16Jan>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/17/world/americas/mexico-el-chapo-sinaloa.html| title=The Manhunt for the Drug Kingpin El Chapo|work=The New York Times|date=16 January 2016|accessdate=16 January 2016| first=Azam| last=Ahmed}}</ref>\n\n=== Third arrest: 2016 ===\n[[File:Mensaje a los medios de comunicaci\u00f3n, 8 Enero 2016.jpg|thumbnail|President [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]], accompanied by [[Cabinet of Mexico|Cabinet members]], holds a press conference in the [[National Palace (Mexico)|Palacio Nacional]] announcing the capture of Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n]]\nAccording to the official report published by the [[Mexican Navy]], citizens reported \"armed people\" in a house at the coastal city of [[Los Mochis]] in northern Sinaloa, which was then placed under surveillance for one month.<ref name=\"surveillance\">{{cite news |last=Martinez |first=Michael |last2=Karimi |first2=Faith |last3=Romo |first3=Rafael |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/09/americas/el-chapo-captured-mexico/index.html |title='El Chapo' dreamed of biopic; it helps lead to recapture, extradition process |publisher=CNN |date=9 January 2016 |accessdate=10 January 2016 }}</ref> Monitored communications indicated the home was being prepared for the arrival of \"Grandma\" or \"Aunt\", which authorities suspected was code for a high-priority potential target.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan /> After the gunmen returned to the house, placing a large order for tacos at a nearby restaurant and picking up the order in a white van after midnight,<ref name=Ahmed16Jan /> the residence was raided in the early hours of 8 January 2016,<ref name=\"surveillance\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Marina de M\u00e9xico emite comunicado oficial sobre \"El Chapo\" |url=http://www.latribuna.hn/?p=11707853 |website=Diario La Tribuna Honduras |accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> in [[Operation Black Swan]], by 17 marines from the [[Fuerzas Especiales|Mexican Navy's Special Forces]] with support from the Mexican Army and the Federal Police<ref name=\"2016 capture\">{{cite news |last=Schuppe |first=Jon |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/el-chapo-notorious-mexican-drug-kingpin-captured-authorities-n492956 |title=El Chapo: Notorious Mexican Drug Kingpin Captured by Authorities |publisher=NBC News |date=8 January 2016 |accessdate=8 January 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Recapturan a \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/especiales/nacion/2016/01/8/260967/nota/261085/0/capturan-el-cholo-junto-el-chapo#info |website=El Universal |accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> \u2013 but Guzm\u00e1n and a lieutenant escaped through a secret tunnel, emerging 1.5&nbsp;km away and stealing a vehicle at gunpoint.\n\nA statewide alert was issued for the stolen vehicle, and the Federal Police located and intercepted it about 20&nbsp;km south of Los Mochis near the town of [[Juan Jos\u00e9 R\u00edos, Sinaloa|Juan Jos\u00e9 R\u00edos]].<ref name=\"bribe offered\">{{cite news |last=Valencia |first=Alejandro |url=http://tamaulipaszonadeguerra.com/cartel-de-sinaloa/se-van-a-morir-todos-ustedes-no-saben-quien-soy-dijo-el-chapo-a-federales-hasta-selfies-se-tomaron/ |title=\"\u00a1Se van a morir todos ustedes! \u00bfNo saben qui\u00e9n soy?\" dijo El Chapo a Federales, hasta selfies se tomaron |work=Zona de Guerra |language=Spanish |date=11 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115090448/http://tamaulipaszonadeguerra.com/cartel-de-sinaloa/se-van-a-morir-todos-ustedes-no-saben-quien-soy-dijo-el-chapo-a-federales-hasta-selfies-se-tomaron/ |archive-date=15 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n attempted to bribe the officers with offers of cash, properties, and offers of jobs.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan /><ref name=\"bribe offered\" /> When the officers refused, Guzm\u00e1n told them \"you are all going to die\". The four police officers sent pictures of Guzm\u00e1n to their superiors, who were tipped that 40 assassins were on their way to free Guzm\u00e1n.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan /> To avoid this counter-attack by cartel members, the policemen were told to take their prisoners to a motel on the outskirts of town to wait for reinforcements,<ref name=\"bribe offered\" /><ref>{{cite web| title=As\u00ed se captur\u00f3 a Joaqu\u00edn Loera Guzm\u00e1n, 'El Chapo', el pr\u00f3fugo m\u00e1s buscado del mundo| url=http://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2016/01/09/56909b6e46163f45048b4591.html| publisher=El Mundo| accessdate=9 January 2016| date=9 January 2016}}</ref> and later, hand over the prisoners to the marines.<ref>{{cite news |last=P\u00e1ez |first=Hugo |url=http://impacto.mx/opinion/policia-federal-enfrenta-a-marinos-y-entrega-al-chapo |title=Polic\u00eda Federal enfrenta a marinos y entrega al 'Chapo' |language=Spanish |work=Impacto |date=13 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117175816/http://impacto.mx/opinion/policia-federal-enfrenta-a-marinos-y-entrega-al-chapo |archive-date=17 January 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> They were subsequently taken to Los Mochis airport for transport to Mexico City, where Guzm\u00e1n was presented to the press at the Mexico City airport and then flown by a Navy helicopter to the same maximum-security prison from which he escaped in July 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-captured-1452278572 |title=Mexican Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Recaptured |date=9 January 2016 |access-date=9 January 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\nDuring the raid, five gunmen were killed, six others arrested, and one Marine was wounded.<ref name=\"2016 capture\" /> The Mexican Navy said that they found two [[Armored car (VIP)|armored cars]], eight assault rifles, including two [[Barrett M82]] sniper rifles, two [[M16 rifle]]s with [[grenade launchers]] and a loaded [[rocket-propelled grenade]] launcher.<ref>{{cite web| title=Recapturan a \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n| url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/especiales/nacion/2016/01/8/260967/nota/261004/0/incautan-vehiculos-en-recaptura-del-el-chapo#info| website=El Universal| accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Reactions ====\nSecretary of the Interior [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Osorio Chong]] was hosting a reunion with Mexico's ambassadors and consuls when he received a notice from the President on Guzm\u00e1n's capture.<ref name=\"Noticieros Televisa 2016\">{{cite web|last1=Madrigal|first1=Guadalupe|title=Osorio Chong recibi\u00f3 una tarjeta, se apart\u00f3 y llam\u00f3 a EPN|url=http://noticieros.televisa.com/mexico/1601/osorio-chong-recibio-tarjeta-se-aparto-llamo-epn/|publisher=Noticieros Televisa|accessdate=9 January 2016|date=8 January 2016}}</ref> He returned a few moments later with Secretary of National Defense [[Salvador Cienfuegos Zepeda]], Secretary of Navy [[Vidal Francisco Sober\u00f3n Sanz]] and Secretary of Foreign Affairs [[Claudia Ruiz Massieu]].<ref name=\"Noticieros Televisa 2016\" /> Osorio Chong then announced the capture to the diplomats by reading the President's tweet which resulted in applause and chants of ''Viva M\u00e9xico'', ''Viva el Presidente Pe\u00f1a'' and ''Viva las Fuerzas Armadas'' (Long live Mexico, Long live President Pe\u00f1a, Long live our Military Forces).<ref name=\"Once Noticias 2016\">{{cite web|title=Once Noticias \u2013 Embajadores y c\u00f3nsules aplauden la reaprehensi\u00f3n de \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=sv2XLeCBRrE|via=YouTube|publisher=[[Canal Once (Mexico)|Canal Once]]|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> This was followed by a spontaneous rendition of the [[Himno Nacional Mexicano|National Anthem]] by the crowd.<ref name=\"Noticieros Televisa 2016\" /><ref name=\"Once Noticias 2016\" />\n\nColombian President [[Juan Manuel Santos]] congratulated Mexican President [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]] for the capture of Guzm\u00e1n. Santos stated that \"Guzm\u00e1n's capture is a success, a great blow against organized crime, and drug trafficking\", adding that \"finally, this individual (Guzm\u00e1n), like all criminals, will find what he deserves in the eyes of justice, and we celebrate that the Mexican authorities have recaptured this criminal\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Santos felicita a Pe\u00f1a Nieto por recaptura de \"El Chapo\", importante socio de las Farc| url=http://www.elespectador.com/noticias/elmundo/santos-felicita-pena-nieto-recaptura-de-el-chapo-import-articulo-609603|work=El Espectador|accessdate=9 January 2016| date=9 January 2016}} (Spanish)</ref> [[Loretta Lynch]], United States Attorney General, praised Mexican authorities \"who have worked tirelessly in recent months to bring Guzm\u00e1n to justice\".\n\n== United States extradition and prosecution ==\n{{Main|United States of America v. Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera}}\n\n[[File:El Chapo in U.S. 1.jpg|thumb|Guzm\u00e1n in U.S. custody when extradited on 19 January 2017.]]\n[[File:Booking photo of Joaquin \u201cEl Chapo\u201c Guzman (side and front).jpg|thumb|[[Mugshot]] taken shortly after Guzm\u00e1n was extradited.]]\nMexico formally launched a renewed process of extradition to the United States two days after Guzm\u00e1n was recaptured on 8 January 2016 after his second prison escape.<ref name=\"extradition 2016\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35278176 |title=El Chapo Guzman: Extradition to US could take 'at least year' |work=CNN News |date=11 January 2015 |accessdate=2016-01-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world |title=Mexico moves to extradite 'El Chapo' |work=BBC News |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=9 January 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Almasy |first=Steve |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/08/us/el-chapo-us-extradition/index.html |title=U.S. indicates Washington wants 'El Chapo' extradited |work=CNN News |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=9 January 2016 }}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n's lawyers mounted \"numerous and creative injunctions\" to prevent extradition.<ref name=Ahmed16Jan/><ref>{{cite news |last=Pestano |first=Andrew V. |url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/01/11/Mexico-El-Chapo-extradition-could-take-up-to-six-years/7891452529818/ |title=Mexico: 'El Chapo' extradition could take up to six years |work=UPI |date=11 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-13 }}</ref> [[Murder of Vicente Berm\u00fadez Zacar\u00edas|Vicente Antonio Berm\u00fadez Zacar\u00edas]] was a federal judge involved in Guzm\u00e1n's extradition proceedings, and he was assassinated on 17 October 2016 while jogging near Mexico City.<ref>{{cite news |title=A federal judge who ruled on some of Mexico's highest profile criminal cases was gunned down in broad daylight |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=18 October 2016 |author=Patrick J. McDonnell |url=https://latimes.com/world/mexico-americas/la-fg-mexico-judge-20161018-snap-story.html |accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n was wanted in Chicago, San Diego, New York City, New Hampshire, Miami, and Texas, in addition to having indictments in at least seven different U.S. federal courts.<ref name=\"Process 2016\">{{cite news |url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-briefs/el-chapo-the-extradition-process-briefly-explained |title='El Chapo': Mexico's Extradition Process Briefly Explained |work=InSight Crime |date=11 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-13 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.businessinsider.com/ap-a-look-at-the-extradition-process-for-el-chapo-guzman-2016-1 A look at the extradition process for 'El Chapo' Guzman]. Eric Tucker and Alicia A. Caldwell, ''Business Insider''. 12 January 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2016/01/11/coming-america-el-chapo-could-fight-extradition-years/78622760/ Coming to America: Why the El Chapo extradition could take years]. John Bacon, ''USA Today''. 13 January 2016.</ref> Charges in the United States include drug trafficking with intent to distribute, conspiracy association, organized crime against health, money laundering, homicide, illegal possession of firearms,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/el-chapos-extradition-process-set-to-begin/ |title=El Chapo's extradition process set to begin |work=Mexico News Daily |date=12 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-13 }}</ref> kidnapping, and murder in Chicago, Miami, New York, and other cities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-faces-life-sentence-u-s-n709556|title=Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' faces life sentence in U.S. prison|publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-court-york/story?id=44915563|title='El Chapo' Pleads Not Guilty in 1st Appearance in New York Courtroom|date=20 January 2017|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/opa/legacy/2009/08/20/chapo-mayo-indictment.pdf|title=Chapo-Mayo Superseding Infictment|last=News|date=20 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref> A critical requirement for extradition was that the U.S. must guarantee that they would not sentence Guzm\u00e1n to death if he were found guilty of homicide charges.<ref name=\"Process 2016\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Estados Unidos no ejecutar\u00e1 a El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n si es extraditado |url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/actualidad/estados-unidos-ejecutara-chapo-guzman-extraditado-208432 |website=El Comercio |language=es |date=12 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo, if convicted, would likely do time in 'Supermax' prison|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mexico-crime-chapo-prison-idUSKBN1550E0?il=0|accessdate=21 January 2017|work=Reuters|date=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 January 2017, Guzm\u00e1n was extradited to the U.S. to face the charges and turned over to the custody of HSI and DEA agents.<ref name=\"ChapoExtradited\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/el-chapo-mexico-extradites-drug-lord-joaquin-guzman-to-us/|title=Mexico says it has extradited drug lord Joaquin \"El Chapo\" Guzman to U.S.|publisher=CBS News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://europe.newsweek.com/el-chapo-mexico-drug-lord-mexican-drug-cartels-544940|title=Top Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' extradited to U.S.|magazine=Newsweek}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/mexico-drug-lord-el-chapo-guzaman-extradited-us-44900272|title=Mexico Says Drug Lord 'El Chapo' Guzman Extradited to US|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> He was housed at the maximum-security wing of the [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York]] located in Manhattan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-headed-new-york-jail-article-1.2950794|title=Drug lord 'El Chapo' headed to New York jail from Mexico|newspaper=New York Daily News}}</ref> He pled not guilty on 20 January to a 17-count indictment in the United States District Court in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/20/us/el-chapo-guzman-extradition/index.html|title='El Chapo' Guzman pleads not guilty in US to 17 counts|author1=Ray Sanchez |author2=Phil Gast |author3=Catherine E. Shoichet |author4=Evan Perez|publisher=CNN}}</ref> U.S. District Judge [[Brian Cogan]] scheduled his trial for 5 November 2018, when jury selection began.<ref>[https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2018/07/16/Judge-delays-start-of-El-Chapo-trial-by-two-months/9811531782964/ Judge delays start of 'El Chapo' trial by two months]. Daniel Uria, UPI. July 16, 2018.</ref> According to the prosecutors, juror anonymity and an armed escort are necessary even if Guzm\u00e1n is in isolation due to his history of having jurors and witnesses murdered.<ref name=lawyer>[http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/01/25/el-chapo-promises-not-to-kill-any-jurors.html 'El Chapo' promises not to kill any jurors, lawyer says]. ''Fox News''. January 25, 2018</ref><ref>[http://www.ladbible.com/news/news-el-chapo-promises-he-wont-have-jurors-swimming-with-the-fishes-20180125 El Chapo Promises He Won\u2019t Have Jurors Swimming With The Fishes]. Mischa Pearlman. 25 January 2018.</ref> The judge agreed to keep jurors anonymous and to have Guzm\u00e1n transported to and from the courthouse by U.S. Marshals and sequestered from the public while in the courthouse.<ref>[http://www.businessinsider.com/juror-identities-el-chapo-guzman-federal-trial-secret-2018-2 The identities of the jurors in Mexican cartel kingpin 'El Chapo' Guzman's federal trial will be kept secret]. Christopher Woody. ''Business Insider''. 7 February 2018.</ref> Opening arguments began Tuesday November 13,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/05/nyregion/el-chapo-trial-jury.html Wanted: 12 People Willing to Serve as Jurors in El Chapo Trial]. Alan Feuer, ''The New York Times''. November 2018.</ref> and closing arguments took place on 31 January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/01/31/690468846/closing-arguments-heard-in-trial-of-joaquin-el-chapo-guzm-n|title=Closing Arguments Heard In Trial Of Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> Guzm\u00e1n was found guilty of all counts on 12 February 2019, and was sentenced on 17 July 2019 to life in prison plus 30 years<ref name=\"SentenceBBC\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/1d5b01e6b8ee4dd29319349bcebc1dcd|title=Mexico's El Chapo sentenced to life in prison|website=apnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=El Chapo trial: Mexican drug lord Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n gets life in prison|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-49022208|work=BBC News|date=17 July 2019 |accessdate=17 July 2019 }}</ref> and ordered to forfeit more than $12.6 billion.<ref name=\"Hong\"/> He is now serving his sentence at [[ADX Florence]], the nation's most secure supermax prison under Federal Register Number 89914-053.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wkzo.com/news/articles/2019/jul/19/mexican-drug-lord-el-chapo-at-supermax-prison-in-colorado/919764/|title=Mexican drug lord 'El Chapo' begins life term in Colorado 'Supermax' prison|first=Midwest Communications|last=Inc|website=WKZO}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=After two escapes, 'El Chapo' may go to 'Supermax' prison to avoid a third|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-mexico-el-chapo-supermax/after-two-escapes-el-chapo-may-go-to-supermax-prison-to-avoid-a-third-idUSKCN1UC142|work=Reuters|date=17 July 2019 |accessdate=17 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal and family criminal activities ==\nGuzm\u00e1n's family is heavily involved in drug trafficking. Several members of his family, including his brother, one of his sons, and a nephew were killed by Sinaloa's archrival cartels, [[Los Zetas]] and the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Organization.<ref name=insight />\n\nIn 1977, Guzm\u00e1n married Alejandrina Mar\u00eda Salazar Hern\u00e1ndez in a small ceremony in the town of Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda, Sinaloa. The couple had at least three children: C\u00e9sar, Iv\u00e1n Archivaldo, and Jes\u00fas Alfredo. He set them up in a ranch home in Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda.\n\nWhen he was 30 years old, El Chapo fell in love with a bank clerk, Estela Pe\u00f1a of [[Nayarit]], whom he kidnapped and with whom he had sexual relations. They later married.\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Guzm\u00e1n married once more, to Griselda L\u00f3pez P\u00e9rez, with whom he had four more children: \u00c9dgar, Joaqu\u00edn, [[Ovidio Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez|Ovidio]], and Griselda Guadalupe.<ref name=\"LastNarco\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Women, the Achilles heel of 'El Chapo' Guzman |url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/2014/02/22/945140 |accessdate=12 January 2016 |newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n's sons followed him into the drug business, and his third wife, L\u00f3pez P\u00e9rez, was arrested in 2010, in [[Culiac\u00e1n]].<ref name=\"LAT daughter\">{{cite news| title=Wife of Fugitive Mexican Drug Lord Arrested, Press Says| url=http://www.laht.com/article.asp?CategoryId=14091&ArticleId=356911| accessdate=22 February 2012|newspaper=[[Latin American Herald Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, Guzm\u00e1n married an 18-year-old American beauty queen, [[Emma Coronel Aispuro]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dailyentertainmentnews.com/breaking-news/emma-coronel-guzman-joaquin-el-chapo-guzmans-wife/| title=Emma Coronel- El Chapo's young American Wife |accessdate=22 February 2014|date=February 2014}}</ref> the daughter of one of his top deputies, In\u00e9s Coronel Barreras, in Canelas, Durango.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7938904.stm |work=BBC News| title=Mexican 'drug lord' on rich list|date=12 March 2009| accessdate=6 May 2010| first=Stephen|last=Gibbs}}</ref><ref name=\"In\u00e9s Coronel\">{{cite news|last=Barros |first=Guillermo |title=Mexican police detain drug kingpin's father-in-law |url=http://uk.news.yahoo.com/mexican-police-detain-drug-kingpins-father-law-001528438.html#DOt3euy |accessdate=2 May 2013 |newspaper=[[Yahoo! News]] |date=1 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714170607/https://uk.news.yahoo.com/mexican-police-detain-drug-kingpins-father-law-001528438.html |url-status=live |archivedate= 14 July 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>Revista Proceso, Mexico DF, 2007</ref> In August 2011, she gave birth to twin girls, Maria Joaquina and Emali Guadalupe, in [[Los Angeles County Hospital]], in California.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2011/09/mexico-el-chapo-guzman-emma-coronel-twins-lancaster-antelope-valley.html |work=Los Angeles Times| title=Drug lord's wife has twins in Los Angeles County hospital| date=26 September 2011| accessdate=27 September 2011| first=Tracy| last=Wilkinson}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/quienes-son-las-esposas-e-hijos-de-el-chapo-guzman-fotos-y-videos,76b9ca117d14c179a815cc4306f99530gzy9RCRD.html| work=Terra Networks| title=Mujeres de 'El Chapo': Las seduce con dinero y amenaza con armas\n| date=12 July 2015| accessdate=12 January 2016| first=Anna| last=Lagos| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2013, Guzm\u00e1n's father-in-law, [[In\u00e9s Coronel Barreras]], was captured by Mexican authorities in [[Agua Prieta]], Sonora, with no gunfire exchanged. U.S. authorities believe Coronel Barreras was a \"key operative\" of the Sinaloa Cartel who grew and smuggled marijuana through the Arizona border area.<ref name=\"In\u00e9s Coronel\" />\n\nOn 15 February 2005, Guzm\u00e1n's son Iv\u00e1n Archivaldo, known as \"El Chapito\", was arrested in Guadalajara on [[money laundering]] charges.<ref name=\"Beltran Leon\">{{cite news|last=Gomez Licon|first=Adriana|title=Jesus Alfredo Guzm\u00e1n Salazar Arrested? Identity Of Capo's Son Questioned In Mexico|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/22/jesus-alfredo-guzman-salazar-arrested_n_1619373.html|accessdate=23 February 2014|work=The Huffington Post|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=22 June 2012}}</ref> He was sentenced to five years in a federal prison but released in April 2008, after a Mexican federal judge, Jes\u00fas Guadalupe Luna, ruled that there was no proof his cash came from drugs other than that he was a drug lord's son.<ref name=\"Mexican judges\">{{cite news| last=Gomez Licon|first=Adriana| title=Mexico Drug Cases Federal Judges Suspended For Possible Irregularities |url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/02/mexico-drug-cases-judges-_n_1565262.html |accessdate=22 February 2014|work=The Huffington Post| agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=6 June 2012}}</ref> Luna and another judge were later suspended on suspicion of unspecified irregularities in their decisions, including Luna's decision to release \"El Chapito\".<ref name=\"Mexican judges\" />\n\nGuzm\u00e1n's son \u00c9dgar Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez died after a 2008 ambush in a shopping center parking lot, in Culiac\u00e1n, Sinaloa.<ref name=\"AP El Gordo\">{{cite news |title=Mexico marines detain suspected son of drug lord| url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/story/2012-06-22/mexico-detains-drug-lord-son/55754648/1| accessdate=22 February 2012| newspaper=[[USA Today]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=22 June 2012}}</ref> Afterwards, police found more than 500 [[AK-47]] bullet casings at the scene.<ref name=\"AP El Gordo\" /> Guzm\u00e1n's brother Arturo, known as \"El Pollo\", was killed in prison in 2004.<ref name=insight />\n\nAnother of Guzm\u00e1n's sons, Jes\u00fas Alfredo Guzm\u00e1n Salazar, known as \"El Gordo\" (\"The Fat One\"), then 23 years old, was suspected of being a member of the cartel and was indicted on federal charges of drug trafficking in 2009 with Guzm\u00e1n, by the U.S. District Court of Northern Illinois, which oversees Chicago.<ref name=\"Beltran Leon\" /><ref name=\"BBC El Gordo\">{{cite news| title=Mexico arrests son of top drug lord 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-18543635| accessdate=22 February 2012 |newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=22 June 2012}}</ref> Authorities described Guzm\u00e1n Salazar as a growing force within his father's organization and directly responsible for Sinaloa's drug trade between the U.S. and Mexico and for managing his billionaire father's growing list of properties. Guzm\u00e1n Salazar and his mother, Guzm\u00e1n's former wife Mar\u00eda Alejandrina Salazar Hern\u00e1ndez, were both described as key operatives in the Sinaloa Cartel and added to the U.S.'s financial sanction list under the [[Kingpin Act]] on 7 June 2012.<ref name=\"BBC El Gordo\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Otero|first=Silvia|title=Esposa e hijo de 'El Chapo' en lista de narcos de EU| url=http://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/852073.html| accessdate=7 June 2012| newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]| date=7 June 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=\"salazar sanctions\">{{cite web|url= http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg1609.aspx|title=Treasury Targets Operatives of Sinaloa Cartel|author=Staff |date=7 June 2012| publisher=United States Department of the Treasury| accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. Treasury Department described Salazar as Guzm\u00e1n's wife, in its sanction against her, and described Guzm\u00e1n as her husband.<ref name=\"salazar sanctions\" /> The month before, the U.S. Treasury Department had announced sanctions against Guzm\u00e1n's sons Iv\u00e1n Guzm\u00e1n Salazar and [[Ovidio Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez]] under the Kingpin Act.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/world/2012/05/08/us-targets-2-sons-sinaloa-cartel-leader US targets 2 sons of Sinaloa cartel leader] ''Fox News''; 8 May 2012.</ref> Guzm\u00e1n's second wife, Griselda L\u00f3pez P\u00e9rez, was also sanctioned by the U.S. under the Kingpin Act and described as Guzm\u00e1n's wife.<ref name=\"Forbes daughter\">{{cite news| last=Carlyle|first=Erin|title=Alleged Daughter Of Mexican Billionaire Druglord El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n Arrested Trying To Cross Border, Won't Talk |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erincarlyle/2012/10/17/alleged-daughter-of-mexican-billionaire-druglord-el-chapo-guzman-arrested-trying-to-cross-border-wont-talk| accessdate=22 February 2012 |newspaper=[[Forbes]]| date=17 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nJes\u00fas Guzm\u00e1n Salazar was reported to have been detained by Mexican Marines in an early morning raid, in the western state of [[Jalisco]] on 21 June 2012.<ref>{{cite news| last=Allen|first=Nick| title=Son of Sinaloa drug cartel's Joaquin 'El Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n captured| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/9347880/Son-of-Sinaloa-drug-cartels-Joaquin-El-Chapo-Guzman-captured.html |accessdate=22 February 2014 |newspaper=[[The Sunday Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=21 June 2012}}</ref> Months later, however, the Mexican Attorney General's Office announced the Marines had arrested the wrong man and that the man captured was actually F\u00e9lix Beltr\u00e1n Le\u00f3n, who said he was a used-car dealer, not the drug lord's son.<ref name=\"Beltran Leon\" /> U.S. and Mexican authorities blamed each other for providing the inaccurate information that led to the arrest.<ref name=\"Beltran Leon\" />\n\nIn 2012, Alejandrina Gisselle Guzm\u00e1n Salazar, a 31-year-old pregnant physician and Mexican citizen from Guadalajara, was said to have claimed she was Guzm\u00e1n's daughter as she crossed the U.S. border into San Diego.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|last1=Marosi|first1=Richard|last2=Wilkinson|first2=Tracy|title=Woman claiming to be drug trafficker's daughter is arrested| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/16/local/la-me-chapo-daughter-20121016|accessdate=22 February 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=16 October 2012}}</ref> She was arrested on fraud charges for entering the country with a false visa.<ref name=\"LAT daughter\" /> Unnamed officials said the woman was the daughter of Mar\u00eda Alejandrina Salazar Hern\u00e1ndez but did not appear to be a major figure in the cartel. She had planned to meet the father of her child in Los Angeles and give birth in the United States.<ref name=\"LAT daughter\" />\n\nOn the night of 17 June 2012, Obied Cano Zepeda, a nephew of Guzm\u00e1n's, was gunned down by unknown assailants at his home in the state capital of [[Culiac\u00e1n]], while hosting a [[Father's Day]] celebration.<ref name=diadelpadre /> The gunmen, who were reportedly carrying [[AK-47]] rifles, also killed two other guests and left another seriously injured.<ref name=diadelpadre>{{cite news|title=Asesinan a sobrino de El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=311451|accessdate=20 June 2012|newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=19 June 2012|language=es}}</ref>\n\nObied was a brother of Luis Alberto Cano Zepeda (''alias'' \"El Blanco\")'s, another nephew of Guzm\u00e1n's who worked as a pilot drug transporter for the Sinaloa cartel.<ref name=elblanco>{{cite news| last=Torres|first=Rub\u00e9n| title=Asesinan al sobrino de El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n |url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/seguridad-publica/2012/06/19/ejecutan-sobrino-chapo-sinaloa|accessdate=20 June 2012|newspaper=[[El Economista (Mexico)|El Economista]]|date=19 June 2012|language=es}}</ref> The latter was arrested by the Mexican military in August 2006.<ref name=elblanco /> ''InSight Crime'' notes that Obied's murder may have been either a retaliation attack by [[Los Zetas]], for Guzm\u00e1n's incursions into their territory, or a brutal campaign heralding Los Zetas' presence in [[Sinaloa]].<ref>{{cite news| last=Knott|first=Tracey| title=El Chapo Nephew Gunned Down at Family Party| url=http://www.insightcrime.org/news-briefs/el-chapo-nephew-gunned-down-at-family-party| accessdate=2 March 2014| newspaper=[[InSight Crime]]|date=20 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nEven after Guzman's arrest, the Sinaloa Cartel remained the primary drug distributor (in 2018) in the U.S. among Mexican cartels, according to the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/ny-mexico-guzman-sentence-1.5214643 |title=Drug kingpin Joaquin (El Chapo) Guzman gets life sentence, says jail has been 'mental torture' |date=July 17, 2019 |work=Fortune |access-date=July 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n=== Literature ===\nMartin Corona, the chief assassin for a rival cartel of Sinaloa's who mistakenly killed a priest when aiming at Guzm\u00e1n, published a tell-all memoir titled ''Confessions of a Cartel Hit Man'' in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|author=Connelly, Sherryl|date=15 July 2017|work=New York Daily News|title=Executioner for Sinaloa rival details how he almost took out El Capo in 'Confessions of a Cartel Hit Man'}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nSeveral Mexican ''[[narcocorrido]]s'' (narco ballads) narrate the exploits of Guzm\u00e1n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnnmexico.com/nacional/2015/07/13/la-segunda-fuga-de-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman-ya-tiene-dos-narcocorridos|title=La segunda fuga de Joaqu\u00edn 'el Chapo' Guzm\u00e1n ya tiene dos narcocorridos|date=13 July 2015|work=CNN|language=Spanish|location=Mexico|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/2015/07/13/1034501|title=De Lupillo Rivera a Regulo\u2026 los corridos sobre la fuga de 'El Chapo'|work=Exc\u00e9lsior|language=Spanish|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chilango.com/cultura/nota/2014/02/24/11-narcos-y-sus-corridos|title=12 narcos y sus corridos (Canciones de sangre, violencia y crimen)|language=Spanish|date=9 October 2014|website=chilango.com|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/el-regreso-del-chapo-mt0003041507|title=El Regreso del Chapo|website=AllMusic|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/11-narcocorridos-que-inspiro-joaquin-el-chapo-guzman|language=Spanish||title=11 narcocorridos que inspir\u00f3 Joaqu\u00edn \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n|work=People en Espanol|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/el-comandante-antrax-mt0048963603|title=El Comandante Antrax|website=AllMusic|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> and his organization. Additionally, some [[Americans|American]] artists have made songs with references to Guzm\u00e1n, such as the rappers [[Uncle Murda]], [[Skrillex]], [[YG (rapper)|YG]], [[Gucci Mane]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/12/world/americas/mexico-el-chapo-profile/|title=The legend of 'El Chapo': Hiding in plain sight? | author1=Shoichet, Catherine E. |author2=Melvin, Don  |author3=Castillo, Mariano  |date=12 July 2015|work=CNN| accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref> and [[The Game (rapper)|The Game]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://noisey.vice.com/es_mx/blog/the-game-acaba-de-lanzar-una-cancin-dedicada-al-chapo|title=The Game y Skrillex acaban de lanzar una canci\u00f3n dedicada al Chapo|work=NOISEY|language=Spanish|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://espectaculos.televisa.com/musica/noticias/865919/chapo-joaquin-guzman-loera-tambien-tiene-hip-hop-corridos/|title=No s\u00f3lo corridos, 'El Chapo' tambi\u00e9n tiene su hip hop|author=Televisa TIM|language=Spanish|work=Televisa Entretenimiento|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\nIn 2017, [[Netflix]] and [[Univision]] began co-producing the series ''[[El Chapo (TV series)|El Chapo]]'' about the life of Guzm\u00e1n.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/univision-netflix-el-chapo-series-sets-april-premiere-w463155|title=Univision, Netflix 'El Chapo' Series Sets April Premiere|first=Jon|last=Blistein|date=26 January 2017|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> The series premiered on Sunday, 23 April 2017 at 8PM/7C on Univision and was followed by a 20-minute [[Facebook]] Live after-show titled \"El Chapo Ilimitado\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elchapotheseries.kinja.com/the-story-of-el-chapo-comes-to-univision-1794468954|title=The story of \"El Chapo\" comes to Univision|last=|first=|date=|website=kinja.com|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fmg.kinja.com/univision-launches-el-chapo-ilimitado-first-live-a-1794544950|title=Univision Launches 'El Chapo Ilimitado' -- First Live After-Show for New Series 'El Chapo'|last=|first=|date=|website=kinja.com|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n is also portrayed by Alejandro Edda in the [[Netflix]] television series ''[[Narcos: Mexico]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of Mexico's 37 most-wanted drug lords]]\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}<!-- NB. When indent option is used,  please use a colon (:) instead of asterisk (*) for bullet markers in the references list -->\n\n: {{cite book|author=Bagley, Bruce  |title=Drug trafficking and organized crime in the Americas & he was the drug lord: Major trends in the twenty-first century|year=2012|publisher=Woodrow Wilson Center Latin American 