 the customers crave something creepier than usual.\n| LineColor       = 31dfb5\n}}\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|SpongeBob SquarePants (season 11)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 240a\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 25a\n| Title           = Bubbletown\n| DirectedBy      = Alan Smart and Tom Yasumi\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|ex1label=Written by|ex1=Andrew Goodman and John Trabbic|ex2label=Storyboarded by|ex2=John Trabbic, Dave Cunningham <small>(director)</small>}}\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|28}}\n| Viewers         = 1.25<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-10-28-2018.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 10.28.2018 - Showbuzz Daily|author=|date=|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = SpongeBob visits his old friend Bubble Buddy in his new hometown.\n\n''Guest appearance:'' Brad Abrell as Bubble Buddy.\n| LineColor       = 31dfb5\n}}\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|SpongeBob SquarePants (season 11)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 240b\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 25b\n| Title           = Girls' Night Out\n| DirectedBy      = Bob Jaques\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|ex1label=Written by|ex1=Mr. Lawrence|ex2label=Storyboarded by|ex2=Brian Morante, Sherm Cohen <small>(director)</small>}}\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|11|4}}\n| Viewers         = 1.20<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-4-2018.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.4.2018 - Showbuzz Daily|author=|date=|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|accessdate=6 November 2018}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Sandy invites Karen and Mrs. Puff out for a night on the town, so the ladies decide to blow off some steam.\n| LineColor       = 31dfb5\n}}\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|SpongeBob SquarePants (season 11)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 241a\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 26a\n| Title           = Squirrel Jelly\n| DirectedBy      = Tom Yasumi\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|ex1label=Written by|ex1=Kaz  and Zeus Cervas|ex2label=Storyboarded by|ex2=Brian Morante, Sherm Cohen <small>(director)</small>}}\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|11|18}}\n| Viewers         = 1.38<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-18-2018.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.18.2018 - Showbuzz Daily|author=|date=|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = SpongeBob and Patrick have their peaceful day of jellyfishing disturbed by Sandy's competitive nature.\n| LineColor       = 31dfb5\n}}\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|SpongeBob SquarePants (season 11)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 241b\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 26b\n| Title           = The String\n| DirectedBy      = Alan Smart and Tom Yasumi\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|ex1label=Written by|ex1=Fred Osmond|ex2label=Storyboarded by|ex2=Fred Osmond, Adam Paloian <small>(director)</small>}}\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|11|18}}\n| Viewers         = 1.38<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-18-2018.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.18.2018 - Showbuzz Daily|author=|date=|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = SpongeBob pulls a loose string from Squidward's shirt that never seems to end.\n| LineColor       = 31dfb5\n}}\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n== DVD release ==\nThe DVD boxset for season ten was released by [[Paramount Home Media Distribution|Paramount Home Entertainment]] and Nickelodeon in the United States and Canada in October 2019, 1 year and 10 months after the season had completed broadcast on television. The DVD release features bonus materials, including the animated short \"Clam Up!\"\n\n{|border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 1em 0 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#31dfb5; color:#000;\"\n|colspan=\"4\" | '''''SpongeBob SquarePants: The Complete Eleventh Season'''''\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:400px;\" colspan=\"3\"| '''Set details'''\n|style=\"width:300px; text-align:center;\"|'''Special features'''\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:left; width:400px;\"|\n* 26 episodes (50 segment episodes)\n* 3-disc set\n* [[Aspect ratio (image)#16:9 standard|1.78:1 aspect ratio]]\n* Languages:\n** English ([[Dolby Digital]] 5.1)\n** Spanish (Dolby Stereo)\n** French (Dolby Stereo)\n|rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:left; width:300px;\"|\n* Animated short:\n** \"Plankton's Color Nullifer\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Release dates'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[DVD region code#Region codes and countries|Region 1]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[DVD region code#Region codes and countries|Region 2]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[DVD region code#Region codes and countries|Region 4]]\n|-\n|| March 31, 2020\n|| TBA\n|| TBA\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:400px;\" colspan=\"4\"| '''Episodes'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:400px;\" colspan=\"4\"| \n* '''Disc 1''': \"Cave Dwelling Sponge\", \"The Clam Whisperer\", \"Spot Returns\", \"The Check-Up\", \"Spin the Bottle\", \"There's a Sponge in My Soup\", \"Man Ray Returns\", \"Larry the Floor Manager\", \"The Legend of Boo-Kini Bottom\", \"No Pictures Please\", \"Stuck on the Roof\", \"Krabby Patty Creature Feature\", \"Teacher's Pests\", \"Sanitation Insanity\", \"Bunny Hunt\", \"Squid Noir\", and \"Scavenger Pants\"\n* '''Disc 2''': \"Cuddle E. Hugs\", \"Pat the Horse\", \"Chatterbox Gary\", \"Don't Feed the Clowns\", \"Drive Happy\", \"Old Man Patrick\", \"Fun-Sized Friends\", \"Grandmum's the Word\", \"Doodle Dimension\", \"Moving Bubble Bass\", \"High Sea Diving\", \"Bottle Burglars\", \"My Leg!\", \"Ink Lemonade\", \"Mustard O' Mine\", \"Shopping List\", \"Whale Watching\", and \"Krusty Kleaners\"\n* '''Disc 3''': \"Patnocchio\", \"ChefBob\", \"Plankton Paranoia\", \"Library Cards\", \"Call the Cops\", \"Surf N' Turf\", \"Goons on the Moon\", \"Appointment TV\", \"Karen's Virus\", \"The Grill is Gone\", \"The Night Patty\", \"Bubbletown\", \"Girls' Night Out\", \"Squirrel Jelly\", and \"The String\"\n|}\n\n{{Notelist|group=lower-alpha|refs=\n<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"credits\">Information is taken from the opening credits of each episode.</ref>\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|40em|group=nb}}\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{SpongeBob SquarePants}}\n\n[[Category:SpongeBob SquarePants seasons]]\n[[Category:2017 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:2018 American television seasons]]\n", "name_user": "Ilovededede", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SpongeBob_SquarePants_(season_11)"}
{"title_page": "Manuel Boutoumites", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Manuel Boutoumites\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_date=mid-11th century\n|death_date=after 1112\n|birth_place=\n|death_place=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance=[[Byzantine Empire]]\n|rank=\n|battles=[[Siege of Nicaea]], [[Byzantine\u2013Seljuk Wars]], Byzantine\u2013Latin Wars\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Manuel Boutoumites''' or '''Butumites''' ({{lang-el|\u039c\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u1f74\u03bb \u0392\u03bf\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03bc\u03af\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2}}, ''[[floruit|fl.]]'' 1086\u20131112) was a leading [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] general and diplomat during the reign of Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos]] (r. 1081\u20131118), and one of the emperor's most trusted aides. He was instrumental in the Byzantine recovery of [[Nicaea]] from the [[Seljuk Turks]], in the reconquest of [[Cilicia]], and acted as the emperor's envoy in several missions to [[First Crusade|Crusader]] princes.\n\n==Early campaigns against the Seljuks==\n[[File:Alexius I.jpg|thumb|right|130px|Miniature of the Emperor Alexios I Komnenos (r. 1081\u20131118).]]\n\nBoutoumites appears in [[Anna Komnene]]'s ''[[Alexiad]]'' in 1086, when he was appointed as the ''[[dux|doux]]'' of the Byzantine fleet by Alexios, and sent against [[Abu'l Qasim (Seljuk governor of Nicaea)|Abu'l Qasim]], the semi-independent [[Seljuk Turks|Seljuk Turkish]] governor of [[Nicaea]].<ref name=\"ODB\">{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Boutoumites\" (A. Kazhdan), pp. 318\u2013319}}.</ref><ref name=\"Skoulatos181\">{{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|p=181}}.</ref> Abu'l Qasim was preparing to launch a fleet into the [[Sea of Marmara]] to challenge the [[Byzantine navy]]. Alexios, determined to prevent this, sent against him Boutoumites with the fleet, while [[Tatikios]] would move against his base by land. The two generals successfully destroyed the Seljuk fleet and forced Abu'l Qasim to withdraw to Nicaea, whence he concluded a truce with Byzantium.<ref name=\"Skoulatos181\"/><ref>[[Anna Komnene]], ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=202\u2013203}}.</ref>\n\nLater, in 1092, after Alexios's ''[[megas doux]]'', [[John Doukas (megas doux)|John Doukas]], defeated the emir [[Tzachas]] of [[Smyrna]], Boutoumites, along with Alexander Euphorbenos, were given as hostages to the emir to guarantee his peaceful evacuation of the island of [[Lesbos]].<ref name=\"Skoulatos181\"/><ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=270\u2013271}}.</ref> Soon after, Doukas and Boutoumites were sent against the rebellions of [[Karykes]] at [[Crete]] and [[Rhapsomates]] at [[Cyprus]]. After subduing Karykes's revolt, they headed to Cyprus, where [[Kyrenia]] fell quickly. Rhapsomates came out to meet them and occupied the heights above the city, but Boutoumites enticed many of his men to desert, and the rebel had to flee the battle. Boutoumites pursued and caught up with him at the church of the Holy Cross, where the rebel had sought refuge. Promising to spare his life, he captured him and brought him back to Doukas.<ref name=\"Skoulatos181\"/><ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=272\u2013274}}.</ref> According to tradition, while in Cyprus, he founded the [[Kykkos Monastery]] there.\n\n==First Crusade and the Siege of Nicaea==\nBoutoumites was highly regarded and trusted by Alexios; Anna Komnene calls him \"Alexios' sole confidant\". Hence he played an important role in the delicate dealings with the [[First Crusade]]: in 1096, Boutoumites was sent to escort the ship-wrecked [[Hugh I, Count of Vermandois|Hugh of Vermandois]] from [[Dyrrhachium]] to [[Constantinople]], and in 1097, he was dispatched, at the head of a small detachment, to accompany the Crusader army as it marched against the Turks in [[Anatolia]].<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=315, 331}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|pp=144, 177}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Siege of Nicaea.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The siege of Nicaea, from a Western European illuminated manuscript.]]\n\nThe first great obstacle on the Crusaders' path was Nicaea, the Seljuk capital, prompting the [[Siege of Nicaea]] in 1097. Boutoumites had been instructed by Alexios to secure the surrender of the city to imperial forces, and not to the Crusaders. Already from the outset of the siege, Boutoumites, through numerous letters, tried to entice the Seljuks to surrender to him, whether through promises of amnesty or threats of a wholesale massacre should the Crusaders capture the city by force. The Turks had entered negotiations, allowing Boutoumites to enter the city. Two days later, at the news of the approach of a relief force under Sultan [[Kilij Arslan I]] (r. 1092\u20131107), they forced him to leave.<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=331\u2013334}}; {{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|p=182}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1969|p=289}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|p=179}}.</ref> After the relief force was defeated by the Crusaders, however, and as an imperial squadron under Boutoumites gained control of the city's open supply route through the [[Ascanian Lake]] and 2,000 Byzantines under Tatikios joined the Crusaders in the siege, the city's inhabitants determined to accept Alexios's terms: Boutoumites entered Nicaea and showed them the Byzantine emperor's [[chrysobull]], offering generous terms and honours for the Sultan's wife and sister, who were in the city. Boutoumites, however, kept the deal a secret, and arranged with Tatikios for a renewed assault by the Crusaders and Tatikios's men, in which the city would ostensibly be captured by the Byzantines. The ruse worked: the day of the final assault was set for June 19, but when the assault began at dawn, the Byzantines, allowed in through the lake-ward gates, raised their standards on the battlements, leaving the Crusaders outside.<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=334\u2013338}}; {{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|pp=182\u2013183}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1969|p=290}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|p=180}}.</ref>\n\nAlthough by and large the Crusaders accepted the outcome, the event soured relations. The Crusader leaders felt cheated at having been left out of the loop after the casualties they suffered in defeating the Turkish relief force, but the resentment was greater among the Crusader rank and file, who were deprived of the prospect of plunder and outraged at the Byzantines' respectful treatment of the Muslim captives.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1969|pp=290\u2013291}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|pp=180\u2013181}}.</ref> In the aftermath of the city's fall, Boutoumites was named by Alexios as ''[[dux|doux]]'' of Nicaea. He was successful both in keeping the Crusader rank and file, still eager for pillage, in check \u2013 they were not allowed into the city except in groups of ten \u2013 and in soothing their leaders through gifts and securing their pledge of allegiance to Alexios. He also persuaded some of the Crusaders to enroll in the Byzantine army. They were then employed in garrisoning Nicaea and repairing its walls.<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=339\u2013340}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|p=184}}.</ref><ref name=\"Skoulatos183\">{{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|p=183}}.</ref>\n\n==Envoy and general against Bohemund and Tancred==\n[[File:South-eastern Europe 1105.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Byzantine Empire and the Eastern Mediterranean circa 1105.]]\n\nIn 1099, he was sent by the Byzantine commanders at Cyprus as a peace envoy to [[Bohemond I of Antioch]], but he was detained by him for a fortnight before being released, and no negotiations were begun.<ref name=\"Skoulatos183\"/><ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=362\u2013363}}.</ref> A few years later ({{circa|1103}}), Boutoumites was placed at the head of a large army sent to secure [[Cilicia]] against Bohemund. After taking [[Attaleia]], the Byzantines took [[Kahramanmara\u015f|Mara\u015f]] and its surrounding region. Boutoumites left behind a large force under Monastras to garrison the province, and returned to Constantinople.<ref name=\"ODB\"/><ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=358\u2013360}}; {{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|pp=183\u2013184}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|pp=300\u2013301}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1111/12, he was sent as an envoy to the Latin [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]] to secure aid against [[Tancred, Prince of Galilee|Tancred]], Bohemond's regent at Antioch, who refused to comply with the [[Treaty of Devol]] of 1108, which turned Antioch into a Byzantine vassal state.<ref>{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Bohemund\" (C. M. Brand), pp. 301\u2013302; \"Boutoumites\" (A. Kazhdan), pp. 318\u2013319; \"Devol\" (A. Kazhdan), pp. 616\u2013617; \"Tancred\" (C. M. Brand), p. 2009}}; {{harvnb|Finck|1969|p=400}}.</ref> From Cyprus, Boutoumites first sailed to [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]]. According to the ''Alexiad'', the local count, [[Bertrand, Count of Toulouse|Bertrand of Toulouse]], readily assented to assist the imperial forces against Tancred, and even to come and pay homage to Alexios when he would arrive to besiege Antioch.<ref>{{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|p=184}}; Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=440\u2013441}}.</ref> Next the Byzantine envoys set out to meet with the King of Jerusalem, [[Baldwin I of Jerusalem|Baldwin I]], who was besieging [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]. Boutoumites tried to persuade Baldwin by offering a substantial reward in gold, and making various exaggerated statements, including that Alexios was supposedly already on his way and had reached Seleucia. Baldwin, however, advised of the untruth of Boutoumites's claims, lost confidence in him. He feigned willingness to attack Tancred provided that he received the promised subsidies beforehand. Boutoumites, however, perceived the king's intentions, and refused to do so. Thus the mission ended in failure, and Boutoumites left Jerusalem, returning to Constantinople via Tripoli.<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=441\u2013441}}; {{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|pp=184\u2013185}}; {{harvnb|Finck|1969|pp=400\u2013401}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Setton-A History of the Crusades | volume = 1 | last = Finck | first = Harold S. | chapter = The Foundation of the Latin States, 1099-1118 | pages = 368-409 | chapterurl=http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/History/History-idx?type=article&did=History.CrusOne.i0027&id=History.CrusOne }}\n*{{Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium}}\n*{{Setton-A History of the Crusades | volume = 1 | last = Runciman | first = Sir Steven | chapter = The First Crusade: Constantinople to Antioch | pages = 280-307 | chapterurl=http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/History/History-idx?type=turn&entity=History.CrusOne.p0010&id=History.CrusOne }}\n*{{cite book|last=Runciman|first=Steven|authorlink=Steven Runciman|title=A History of the Crusades, Volume 1: The First Crusade and the Foundation of the Kingdom of Jerusalem|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1987|origyear=1951|isbn=978-0-521-34770-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uDj9sNezWzEC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|editor-last=Sewter|editor-first=E. R. A.| title=The Alexiad|location=London and New York|publisher=Penguin Classics|year=2003|origyear=1969|isbn=978-0-14-044958-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mcGJLXOzOU4C|ref=harv}}\n* {{Les personnages byzantins de l'Alexiade}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boutoumites, Manuel}}\n[[Category:11th-century births]]\n[[Category:12th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:11th-century Byzantine military personnel]]\n[[Category:12th-century Byzantine military personnel]]\n[[Category:Byzantine admirals]]\n[[Category:Byzantine diplomats]]\n[[Category:Byzantine generals]]\n[[Category:Christians of the First Crusade]]\n[[Category:Generals of Alexios I Komnenos]]\n[[Category:Byzantine people of the Byzantine\u2013Seljuq Wars]]\n[[Category:12th-century diplomats]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Manuel Boutoumites\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_date=mid-11th century\n|death_date=after 1112\n|birth_place=\n|death_place=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance=[[Byzantine Empire]]\n|rank=\n|battles=[[Siege of Nicaea]], [[Byzantine\u2013Seljuk Wars]], Byzantine\u2013Latin Wars\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Manuel Boutoumites''' or '''Butumites''' ({{lang-el|\u039c\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u1f74\u03bb \u0392\u03bf\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03bc\u03af\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2}}, ''[[floruit|fl.]]'' 1086\u20131112) was a leading [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] general and diplomat during the reign of Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos]] (r. 1081\u20131118), and one of the emperor's most trusted aides. He was instrumental in the Byzantine recovery of [[Nicaea]] from the [[Seljuk Turks]], in the reconquest of [[Cilicia]], and acted as the emperor's envoy in several missions to [[First Crusade|Crusader]] princes.\n\n==Early campaigns against the Seljuks==\n[[File:Alexius I.jpg|thumb|right|130px|Miniature of the Emperor Alexios I Komnenos (r. 1081\u20131118).]]\n\nBoutoumites appears in [[Anna Komnene]]'s ''[[Alexiad]]'' in 1086, when he was appointed as the ''[[dux|doux]]'' of the Byzantine fleet by Alexios, and sent against [[Abu'l Qasim (Seljuk governor of Nicaea)|Abu'l Qasim]], the semi-independent [[Seljuk Turks|Seljuk Turkish]] governor of [[Nicaea]].<ref name=\"ODB\">{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Boutoumites\" (A. Kazhdan), pp. 318\u2013319}}.</ref><ref name=\"Skoulatos181\">{{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|p=181}}.</ref> Abu'l Qasim was preparing to launch a fleet into the [[Sea of Marmara]] to challenge the [[Byzantine navy]]. Alexios, determined to prevent this, sent against him Boutoumites with the fleet, while [[Tatikios]] would move against his base by land. The two generals successfully destroyed the Seljuk fleet and forced Abu'l Qasim to withdraw to Nicaea, whence he concluded a truce with Byzantium.<ref name=\"Skoulatos181\"/><ref>[[Anna Komnene]], ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=202\u2013203}}.</ref>\n\nLater, in 1092, after Alexios's ''[[megas doux]]'', [[John Doukas (megas doux)|John Doukas]], defeated the emir [[Tzachas]] of [[Smyrna]], Boutoumites, along with Alexander Euphorbenos, were given as hostages to the emir to guarantee his peaceful evacuation of the island of [[Lesbos]].<ref name=\"Skoulatos181\"/><ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=270\u2013271}}.</ref> Soon after, Doukas and Boutoumites were sent against the rebellions of [[Karykes]] at [[Crete]] and [[Rhapsomates]] at [[Cyprus]]. After subduing Karykes's revolt, they headed to Cyprus, where [[Kyrenia]] fell quickly. Rhapsomates came out to meet them and occupied the heights above the city, but Boutoumites enticed many of his men to desert, and the rebel had to flee the battle. Boutoumites pursued and caught up with him at the church of the Holy Cross, where the rebel had sought refuge. Promising to spare his life, he captured him and brought him back to Doukas.<ref name=\"Skoulatos181\"/><ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=272\u2013274}}.</ref> According to tradition, while in Cyprus, he founded the [[Kykkos Monastery]] there.\n\n==First Crusade and the Siege of Nicaea==\nBoutoumites was highly regarded and trusted by Alexios; Anna Komnene calls him \"Alexios' sole confidant\". Hence he played an important role in the delicate dealings with the [[First Crusade]]: in 1096, Boutoumites was sent to escort the ship-wrecked [[Hugh I, Count of Vermandois|Hugh of Vermandois]] from [[Dyrrhachium]] to [[Constantinople]], and in 1097, he was dispatched, at the head of a small detachment, to accompany the Crusader army as it marched against the Turks in [[Anatolia]].<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=315, 331}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|pp=144, 177}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Siege of Nicaea.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The siege of Nicaea, from a Western European illuminated manuscript.]]\n\nThe first great obstacle on the Crusaders' path was Nicaea, the Seljuk capital, which they proceeded to [[Siege of Nicaea|besiege]]. Boutoumites had been instructed by Alexios to secure the surrender of the city to imperial forces, and not to the Crusaders. Already from the outset of the siege, Boutoumites, through numerous letters, tried to entice the Seljuks to surrender to him, whether through promises of amnesty or threats of a wholesale massacre should the Crusaders capture the city by force. The Turks had entered negotiations, allowing Boutoumites to enter the city. Two days later, at the news of the approach of a relief force under Sultan [[Kilij Arslan I]] (r. 1092\u20131107), they forced him to leave.<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=331\u2013334}}; {{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|p=182}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1969|p=289}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|p=179}}.</ref> After the relief force was defeated by the Crusaders, however, and as an imperial squadron under Boutoumites gained control of the city's open supply route through the [[Ascanian Lake]] and 2,000 Byzantines under Tatikios joined the Crusaders in the siege, the city's inhabitants determined to accept Alexios's terms: Boutoumites entered Nicaea and showed them the Byzantine emperor's [[chrysobull]], offering generous terms and honours for the Sultan's wife and sister, who were in the city. Boutoumites, however, kept the deal a secret, and arranged with Tatikios for a renewed assault by the Crusaders and Tatikios's men, in which the city would ostensibly be captured by the Byzantines. The ruse worked: the day of the final assault was set for June 19, but when the assault began at dawn, the Byzantines, allowed in through the lake-ward gates, raised their standards on the battlements, leaving the Crusaders outside.<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=334\u2013338}}; {{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|pp=182\u2013183}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1969|p=290}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|p=180}}.</ref>\n\nAlthough by and large the Crusaders accepted the outcome, the event soured relations. The Crusader leaders felt cheated at having been left out of the loop after the casualties they suffered in defeating the Turkish relief force, but the resentment was greater among the Crusader rank and file, who were deprived of the prospect of plunder and outraged at the Byzantines' respectful treatment of the [[Islam|Muslim]] captives.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1969|pp=290\u2013291}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|pp=180\u2013181}}.</ref> In the aftermath of the city's fall, Boutoumites was named by Alexios as ''[[dux|doux]]'' of Nicaea. He was successful both in keeping the Crusader rank and file, still eager for pillage, in check \u2013 they were not allowed into the city except in groups of ten \u2013 and in soothing their leaders through gifts and securing their pledge of allegiance to Alexios. He also persuaded some of the Crusaders to enroll in the Byzantine army. They were then employed in garrisoning Nicaea and repairing its walls.<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=339\u2013340}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|p=184}}.</ref><ref name=\"Skoulatos183\">{{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|p=183}}.</ref>\n\n==Envoy and general against Bohemund and Tancred==\n[[File:South-eastern Europe 1105.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Byzantine Empire and the Eastern Mediterranean circa 1105.]]\n\nIn 1099, he was sent by the Byzantine commanders at Cyprus as a peace envoy to [[Bohemond I of Antioch]], but he was detained by him for a fortnight before being released, and no negotiations were begun.<ref name=\"Skoulatos183\"/><ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=362\u2013363}}.</ref> A few years later ({{circa|1103}}), Boutoumites was placed at the head of a large army sent to secure [[Cilicia]] against Bohemund. After taking [[Attaleia]], the Byzantines took [[Kahramanmara\u015f|Mara\u015f]] and its surrounding region. Boutoumites left behind a large force under Monastras to garrison the province, and returned to Constantinople.<ref name=\"ODB\"/><ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=358\u2013360}}; {{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|pp=183\u2013184}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1987|pp=300\u2013301}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1111/12, he was sent as an envoy to the Latin [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]] to secure aid against [[Tancred, Prince of Galilee|Tancred]], Bohemund's regent at Antioch, who refused to comply with the [[Treaty of Devol]] of 1108, which turned Antioch into a Byzantine vassal state.<ref>{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Bohemund\" (C. M. Brand), pp. 301\u2013302; \"Boutoumites\" (A. Kazhdan), pp. 318\u2013319; \"Devol\" (A. Kazhdan), pp. 616\u2013617; \"Tancred\" (C. M. Brand), p. 2009}}; {{harvnb|Finck|1969|p=400}}.</ref> From Cyprus, Boutoumites first sailed to [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]]. According to the ''Alexiad'', the local count, [[Bertrand, Count of Toulouse|Bertrand of Toulouse]], readily assented to assist the imperial forces against Tancred, and even to come and pay homage to Alexios when he would arrive to besiege Antioch.<ref>{{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|p=184}}; Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=440\u2013441}}.</ref> Next the Byzantine envoys set out to meet with the King of Jerusalem, [[Baldwin I of Jerusalem|Baldwin I]], who was besieging [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]. Boutoumites tried to persuade Baldwin by offering a substantial reward in [[gold]], and making various exaggerated statements, including that Alexios was supposedly already on his way and had reached Seleucia. Baldwin, however, advised of the untruth of Boutoumites's claims, lost confidence in him. He feigned willingness to attack Tancred provided that he received the promised subsidies beforehand. Boutoumites, however, perceived the king's intentions, and refused to do so. Thus the mission ended in failure, and Boutoumites left Jerusalem, returning to Constantinople via Tripoli.<ref>Anna Komnene, ''The Alexiad'', ed. {{harvnb|Sewter|2003|pp=441\u2013441}}; {{harvnb|Skoulatos|1980|pp=184\u2013185}}; {{harvnb|Finck|1969|pp=400\u2013401}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Setton-A History of the Crusades | volume = 1 | last = Finck | first = Harold S. | chapter = The Foundation of the Latin States, 1099-1118 | pages = 368-409 | chapterurl=http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/History/History-idx?type=article&did=History.CrusOne.i0027&id=History.CrusOne }}\n*{{Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium}}\n*{{Setton-A History of the Crusades | volume = 1 | last = Runciman | first = Sir Steven | chapter = The First Crusade: Constantinople to Antioch | pages = 280-307 | chapterurl=http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/History/History-idx?type=turn&entity=History.CrusOne.p0010&id=History.CrusOne }}\n*{{cite book|last=Runciman|first=Steven|authorlink=Steven Runciman|title=A History of the Crusades, Volume 1: The First Crusade and the Foundation of the Kingdom of Jerusalem|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1987|origyear=1951|isbn=978-0-521-34770-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uDj9sNezWzEC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|editor-last=Sewter|editor-first=E. R. A.| title=The Alexiad|location=London and New York|publisher=Penguin Classics|year=2003|origyear=1969|isbn=978-0-14-044958-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mcGJLXOzOU4C|ref=harv}}\n* {{Les personnages byzantins de l'Alexiade}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boutoumites, Manuel}}\n[[Category:11th-century births]]\n[[Category:12th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:11th-century Byzantine military personnel]]\n[[Category:12th-century Byzantine military personnel]]\n[[Category:Byzantine admirals]]\n[[Category:Byzantine diplomats]]\n[[Category:Byzantine generals]]\n[[Category:Christians of the First Crusade]]\n[[Category:Generals of Alexios I Komnenos]]\n[[Category:Byzantine people of the Byzantine\u2013Seljuq Wars]]\n[[Category:12th-century diplomats]]\n", "name_user": "Dr. Grampinator", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manuel_Boutoumites"}
{"title_page": "Ion Iliescu", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Iliescu|other people with the surname|Iliescu (surname)}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = PORC COMUNIST infect \n| honorific-suffix = <small>[[Istiglal Order|IO]], [[Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana|OCTM]], [[Grand Order of King Tomislav|GOKT]], [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|OWE]], [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|OMIR]]</small>\n| image = Ion Iliescu (2).JPG\n| order = 2nd\n| office = President of Romania\n| primeminister = [[Petre Roman]]<br />[[Theodor Stolojan]]<br />[[Nicolae V\u0103c\u0103roiu]]\n| term_start = 26 December 1989\n| term_end = 29 November 1996<br /><small>Acting to 20 May 1990</small>\n| predecessor = [[List of members of the National Salvation Front Council|National Salvation Front Council]] (interim)\n| successor = [[Emil Constantinescu]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Mugur Is\u0103rescu]]<br />[[Adrian N\u0103stase]]\n| term_start2 = 20 December 2000\n| term_end2 = 20 December 2004\n| predecessor2 = [[Emil Constantinescu]]\n| successor2 = [[Traian B\u0103sescu]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1930|3|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Olteni\u021ba]], [[C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County|C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i]], Romania\n| party = [[Romanian Communist Party|Romanian Communist]]<br />{{small|(1953\u20131989)}}<br />[[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]]<br />{{small|(1989\u20131992)}}<br />[[Democratic National Salvation Front]]<br />{{small|(1992)}}<br />[[Independent politician|Independent]]<br />{{small|(1992\u20131996; 2000\u20132004; FDSN/PDSR membership suspended while president)}}<br />[[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic]]<br />{{small|(1996\u20132000; 2004\u2013present)}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Nina Iliescu]]|1951}}\n| alma_mater = [[Bucharest Polytechnic Institute]]<br />[[Moscow State University]]\n| profession = [[Engineer|Hydroelectric Engineer]]\n| signature = Signature of Ion Iliescu.png\n}}\n\n'''Ion Iliescu''' ({{IPA-ro|i\u02c8on ili\u02c8esku|-|Ro-Ion Iliescu.ogg}}; born 3 March 1930) is a Romanian [[politician]] who served as [[President of Romania]] from 1996 to 2000 and from 2004 until his retirement in 2008. Iliescu was a [[Senate of Romania|senator]] for the [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party]] (PSD), of which he is the founder and honorary president.\n\nHe joined the Communist Party in 1953 and became a member of its Central Committee in 1965. However, beginning with 1971, he was gradually marginalized by [[Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu]]. He had a leading role in the [[Romanian Revolution]], becoming the country's president in December 1989. In May 1990, he became Romania's first freely elected head of state. After a new constitution was approved by popular referendum, he served a further two terms as president, from 1992 to 1996, and from 2000 to 2004, separated by the presidency of [[Emil Constantinescu]], who defeated him in 1996.\n\nIliescu is widely recognized as a predominant figure in the first fifteen years of post-revolution politics. During his presidency, Romania joined [[NATO]]. In April 2018, Ion Iliescu was charged in Romania with committing [[crimes against humanity]] during the deadly aftermath of the country's 1989 revolution.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://stirileprotv.ro/justitie/ion-iliescu-asteptat-la-parchetul-general-fostul-presedinte-este-urmarit-penal-in-dosarul-revolutiei.html |title=Dosarul \"Revolu\u021biei\". Ion Iliescu este, oficial, urm\u0103rit penal pentru infrac\u021biuni contra umanit\u0103\u021bii |work=\u0218tirile Pro TV |date=17 April 2018 |language=Romanian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418161216/https://stirileprotv.ro/justitie/ion-iliescu-asteptat-la-parchetul-general-fostul-presedinte-este-urmarit-penal-in-dosarul-revolutiei.html |archivedate=18 April 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and entering politics==\n{{Expand section|date=June 2013}}\nIliescu's father, Alexandru Iliescu, was a railroad worker with [[Communism|Communist]] views during the period in which the [[Romanian Communist Party]] was banned by the authorities. In 1931, he went to the [[Soviet Union]] to take part in the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]] Congress of [[Moscow]]. He remained in the USSR for the next four years and was arrested upon his return. He was imprisoned from June 1940 to August 1944 and died in August 1945. During his time in the Soviet Union, Alexandru Iliescu divorced and married Mari\u021ba, a chambermaid.\n\nIliescu married Nina \u0218erb\u0103nescu in 1951; they have no children, not by choice but because they could not, as Nina had three [[miscarriage]]s.<ref>[http://ziua.net/news.php?data=2008-09-06&id=12256 \"De ce nu a avut Ion Iliescu urmasi\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Ziua'', 5 September 2008</ref> Born in [[Olteni\u021ba]], Iliescu studied [[fluid mechanics]] at the [[Bucharest Polytechnic Institute]] and then as a foreign student at the Energy Institute of the [[Moscow University]]. During his stay in Moscow, he was the secretary of the \"Association of Romanian Students\" it is alleged that he met [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], although Iliescu always denied this.<ref name=\"risingstar\">[[New York Times]], \"Upheaval in the East: A Rising Star; A Man Who Could Become Rumania's Leader\", 23 December 1989, p. 15</ref> However, years later, president [[Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu]] probably believed that there was a connection between the two, since during Gorbachev's visit to Romania in July 1989, Iliescu was sent outside of Bucharest to prevent any contact.<ref>''[[Rom\u00e2nia Liber\u0103]]''. \"Gura lumii despre Rom\u00e2nia\", 8 May 1990, quoting [[Paris Match]]</ref>\n\nIon Iliescu speaks fluently [[Romanian language|Romanian]], [[English language|English]] and [[Russian language|Russian]] languages.\n\n[[File:016.Vacanta-pentrecuta-in-Moldova-1976.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Ion Iliescu in 1976 with [[Elena Ceau\u0219escu]]]]\nHe joined the [[Union of Communist Youth]] in 1944 and the Communist Party in 1953 and made a career in the Communist [[nomenklatura]], becoming a secretary of the [[Central Committee]] of the Union of Communist Youth in 1956 and a member of the Central Committee of the [[Romanian Communist Party]] in 1965. At one point, he served as the head of the Central Committee's Department of Propaganda.<ref name=\"risingstar\"/> Iliescu later served as Minister for Youth-related Issues between 1967 and 1971.\n\nHowever, in 1971, Ceau\u0219escu felt threatened by Iliescu, who was seen as Ceau\u0219escu's heir apparent. He was marginalized and removed from all major political offices, becoming vice-president of the [[Timi\u0219 County]] Council (1971\u20131974), and later president of the [[Ia\u0219i County|Ia\u0219i]] Council (1974\u20131979). Until 1989, he was in charge of the Editura Tehnic\u0103 publishing house. For most of the 1980s (if not before), he was tailed by the [[Securitate]] (secret police), as he was known to oppose Ceau\u0219escu's harsh rule.<ref name=Revolution1989>{{cite book|last=Sebetsyen|first=Victor|title=Revolution 1989: The Fall of the Soviet Empire|publisher=[[Pantheon Books]]|location=New York City|year=2009|isbn=0-375-42532-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/revolution1989fa00sebe}}</ref>\n\n==Romanian Revolution==\n{{Main|Romanian Revolution}}\nThe Romanian Revolution began as a popular revolt in [[Timi\u0219oara]]. After Ceau\u0219escu was overthrown on 22 December, the political vacuum was filled by an organization named [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]] (FSN: ''Frontul Salv\u0103rii Na\u021bionale''), formed spontaneously by second-rank communist party members opposed to the policies of Ceau\u0219escu and non-affiliated participants in the revolt. Iliescu was quickly acknowledged as the leader of the organization and therefore of the provisional authority. He first learned of the revolution when he noticed the Securitate was no longer tailing him.<ref name=Revolution1989/>\n\nThe Ceau\u0219escus were captured, haled before a [[Trial and execution of Nicolae and Elena Ceau\u0219escu|drumhead court-martial]], and executed on Christmas Day. Years later, Iliescu conceded that the trial and execution were \"quite shameful, but necessary\" to end the chaos that had riven the country since Ceau\u0219escu's overthow.<ref name=dem25dec>{{cite news|last=Demian|first=Sinziana|title=In Romania, Ceausescu's death haunts Christmas|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/europe/091224/romania-nicolae-elena-ceausescu|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=Global Post|date=25 December 2009|location=Cluj Napoca}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CFSN Revolution Roumaine.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Three men are walking side-by-side holding papers. The first two are wearing a suit and the third is wearing a red sweater. The first man is smiling and flashing a V sign.|Iliescu (center) with FSN members [[Dumitru Mazilu]] (left) and [[Petre Roman]] (right) on 23 December 1989, one day after the formation of the FSN.]]\nIliescu proposed multi-party elections and an \"original democracy\". This is widely held to have meant the adoption of ''[[Perestroika]]''-style reforms rather than the complete removal of existing institutions; it can be linked to the warm reception the new regime was given by Mikhail Gorbachev and the rest of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] leadership, and the fact that the first post-revolutionary international agreement signed by Romania was with that country.\n\nIliescu did not renounce Communist ideology and the program he initially presented during the revolution included restructuring the agriculture and the reorganization of trade, but not a switch to capitalism.<ref name=\"risingstar\"/> These views were held by other members of the FSN as well, such as [[Silviu Brucan]], who claimed in early 1990 that the revolution was against Ceau\u0219escu, not against communism.<ref>http://eprints-phd.biblio.unitn.it/74/1/PhDThesisSGI.pdf</ref> Iliescu later evoked the possibility of trying a \"[[Sweden|Swedish]] model\" of socialism.\n\nRumours abounded for years that Illiescu and other second-rank Communists had been planning to overthrow Ceau\u0219escu, but the events of December 1989 overtook them. For instance, [[Nicolae Militaru]], the new regime's first [[Ministry of National Defense (Romania)|defense minister]], said that Illiescu and others had planned to take Ceau\u0219escu prisoner in February 1990 while he was out of the capital. However, Illiescu denies this, saying that the nature of the Ceau\u0219escu regime\u2014particularly the Securitate's ubiquity\u2014made advance planning for a coup all but impossible.<ref name=Revolution1989/>\n\n==Presidency==\n{{expand section|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox President styles\n | image = Coat of arms of Romania.svg\n | size = 50px\n | name = Ion Iliescu\n | dipstyle = Pre\u0219edintele (President)\n | offstyle = Pre\u0219edintele (President)\n | altstyle = Domnia Sa/Excelen\u021ba Sa (His Excellency)\n}}\nThe [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]] decided to organize itself as a party and run in the [[1990 Romanian general election|1990 general election]]\u2014the first free election held in the country in 53 years\u2013with Illiescu as its presidential candidate. The FSN won a sweeping victory, taking strong majorities in both chambers.<ref>Nohlen & St\u00f6ver, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120205171131/http://www2.essex.ac.uk/elect/database/indexElections.asp?country=ROMANIA&election=ro90cd University of Essex]</ref> In the separate presidential election, Iliescu won handily, taking 85 percent of the vote, still the largest vote share for a free presidential election. He thus became Romania's first democratically elected head of state, and the first since 1947 who was not a Communist or [[fellow traveler]]. To date, it is the only time since the end of Communism that a president has been elected in a single round.\n\nIliescu and his supporters split from the Front and created the Democratic National Salvation Front (NSDF), which later evolved into the Party of Social Democracy in Romania (PDSR), then the Social Democratic Party (PSD) (see [[Social Democratic Party of Romania]]). Progressively, the Front lost its character as a [[Central government|national government]] or generic coalition, and became vulnerable to criticism for using its appeal as the first institution involved in power sharing, while engaging itself in political battles with forces that could not enjoy this status, nor the credibility.\n\nUnder the pressure of the events that led to the [[Mineriad]]s, his political stance has veered with time: from a proponent of ''Perestroika'', Iliescu recast himself as a Western European [[social democracy|social democrat]]. The main debate around the subject of his commitment to such ideals is linked to the special conditions in Romania, and especially to the strong [[Romanian nationalism|nationalist]] and autarkic attitude visible within the Ceau\u0219escu regime. Critics have pointed out that, unlike most communist-to-social democrat changes in the [[Eastern bloc]], Romania's tended to retain various cornerstones.\n\n[[File:Ion Iliescu (2004).jpg|thumb|165px|Iliescu in 2004]]\n[[File:Iliescu si Bush.jpg|thumb|250px|Iliescu and U.S. President George W. Bush in 2002]]\nRomania adopted its first [[Constitution of Romania|post-Communist Constitution]] in 1991. In 1992, Iliescu [[1992 Romanian general election|won a second term]] when he received 61% of the vote in the second round. He immediately suspended his NSDF membership; the Constitution does not allow the president to be a formal member of a political party during his term. He ran for a third time in [[1996 Romanian general election|1996]] but, stripped of media monopoly, he lost in the second round to [[Emil Constantinescu]], his second-round opponent in 1992. Over 1,000,000 votes were cancelled, leading to accusations of widespread fraud. Nevertheless, Iliescu conceded defeat within hours of polls closing, making him the only incumbent president to lose a bid for re-election since the end of Communism.\n\nIn the [[2000 Romanian general election|2000 presidential election]] Iliescu ran again and won in the run-off against the ultra-nationalist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitatea.net/preda-antonescu-il-secondeaza-pe-vadim-tudor-cu-discursul-ultranationalist_718413.html|title=Preda: Antonescu \u00eel secondeaz\u0103 pe Vadim Tudor cu discursul ultrana\u0163ionalist|publisher=Realitatea|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927232910/http://www.realitatea.net/preda-antonescu-il-secondeaza-pe-vadim-tudor-cu-discursul-ultranationalist_718413.html|archivedate=27 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfbaytimes.com/index.php?sec=article&article_id=4066|title=Article|publisher=SF Bay Times|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016063611/http://www.sfbaytimes.com/index.php?sec=article&article_id=4066|archivedate=16 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/romania/tudor.html|title=House of Tudor|publisher=PBS|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106052244/http://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/romania/tudor.html|archivedate=6 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Corneliu Vadim Tudor]]. He began his third term on 20 December of that year, ending on 20 December 2004. The center-right was severely defeated during the 2000 elections due largely to public dissatisfaction with the harsh economic reforms of the previous four years as well as the political instability and infighting of the multiparty coalition. Tudor's extreme views also ensured that most urban voters either abstained or chose Iliescu.\n\nIn the PSD elections of 21 April 2005, Iliescu lost the Party presidency to [[Mircea Geoan\u0103]], but was elected as honorary president of the party in 2006, a position without official executive authority in the party.\n\n==Controversies==\nThough enjoying a certain popularity due to his opposition to Ceau\u0219escu and image as a revolutionary, his political career after 1989 was characterized by multiple controversies and scandals. Public opinion regarding his tenure as president is still divided.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfin.ro/articol_13481/al_cincilea_iliescu.html?action=print|title=Al Cincilea Iliescu|publisher=Income Magazine|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323014416/http://www.sfin.ro/articol_13481/al_cincilea_iliescu.html?action=print|archivedate=23 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged KGB connections===\nSome alleged Iliescu had connections to the [[KGB]], the allegations continued during 2003\u20132008, when Russian dissident [[Vladimir Bukovsky]], who had been granted access to Soviet archives, declared that Iliescu and some of the NSF members were KGB agents, that Iliescu had been in close connection with Mikhail Gorbachev ever since they had allegedly met during Iliescu's stay in Moscow, and that the Romanian Revolution of 1989 was a plot organized by the KGB to regain control of the country's policies (gradually lost under Ceau\u0219escu's rule).<ref>[http://english.hotnews.ro/stiri-top_news-6209804-russian-dissident-who-copied-the-gorbachev-foundations-archive-mitterrand-and-gorbachev-wanted-the-european-socialist-union-thatcher-opposed-germanys-reunification.htm Russian dissident who copied the Gorbachev Foundation's archive: Mitterrand and Gorbachev wanted the European Socialist Union, Thatcher opposed Germany's reunification] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111130233603/http://english.hotnews.ro/stiri-top_news-6209804-russian-dissident-who-copied-the-gorbachev-foundations-archive-mitterrand-and-gorbachev-wanted-the-european-socialist-union-thatcher-opposed-germanys-reunification.htm |date=30 November 2011 }}</ref> The only hard evidence published was a discussion between Gorbachev and Bulgaria's [[Aleksandar Lilov]] from 23 May 1990 (after Iliescu's victory in the 20 May elections) in which Gorbachev says that Iliescu holds a \"calculated position\", and that despite sharing common views with Iliescu, Gorbachev wanted to avoid sharing this impression with the public.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.ziua.ro/display.php?id=199569&data=15-05-2006 Dovada Bukovski] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201102614/http://www.ziua.ro/display.php?id=199569&data=15-05-2006 |date=1 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Mineriads===\n{{Main|Mineriad}}\nHe, along with other figures in the leading [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]], was allegedly responsible for calling the [[Jiu Valley]] miners to Bucharest on 28 January and 14 June 1990 to end the protests of the citizens gathered in [[University Square, Bucharest]], protests aimed against the ex-communist leaders of Romania (like himself). The pejorative term for this demonstration was the [[Golaniad]] (from the [[Romanian language|Romanian]] ''golan'', rascal). On 13 June, an attempt of the authorities to remove from the square around 100 protesters, which had remained in the street even after the [[1990 Romanian presidential election|May elections]] had confirmed Iliescu and the FSN, resulted in attacks against several state institutions, such as the Ministry of Interior, the Bucharest Police Headquarters and the National Television. Iliescu issued a call to the Romanian people to come and defend the government, prompting several groups of miners to descend on the capital, armed with wooden clubs and bats. They trashed the [[University of Bucharest]], some newspaper offices and the headquarters of opposition parties, claiming that they were havens of decadence and immorality \u2013 drugs, firearms and munitions, \"an automatic typewriter\", and fake currency. The [[June 1990 Mineriad]] in particular was widely criticized both at home and internationally, with one historian (Andrei Pippidi) comparing the events to Nazi Germany's [[Kristallnacht]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Constantin Petre|url=http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/mineriadele-anului-1990-democratia-sub-bate-898037.html|title=Mineriadele anului 1990, democra\u0163ia sub b\u00e2te|publisher=EVZ|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010083428/http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/mineriadele-anului-1990-democratia-sub-bate-898037.html|archivedate=10 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.romanialibera.ro/exclusiv-rl/investigatii/minerii-au-terorizat-capitala-30479.html|title=Minerii au terorizat Capitala|publisher=Romania Libera|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008110518/http://www.romanialibera.ro/exclusiv-rl/investigatii/minerii-au-terorizat-capitala-30479.html|archivedate=8 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Government inquiries later established that the miners were infiltrated and instigated by former [[Securitate]] operatives.<ref name=\"Baleanu\">[http://www.fas.org/irp/world/romania/g43.html Baleanu, V. G. ''The Enemy Within: The Romanian Intelligence Service in Transition''. January 1995. Conflict Studies Research Centre, The Royal Military Academy Sandhurst: Camberley, Surrey GU15 4PQ.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016030538/http://fas.org/irp/world/romania/g43.html |date=16 October 2015 }}</ref> In February 1994 a Bucharest court \"found two security officers, Colonel Ion Nicolae and warrant officer Corneliu Dumitrescu, guilty of ransacking the house of [[Ion Ra\u021biu]], a leading figure in the [[Christian Democratic National Peasants' Party]], during the miners\u2019 incursion and stealing $100,000.\"<ref name=\"Deletant\">[http://d.yimg.com/kq/groups/21010417/803473086/name/Carey_final.pdf Deletant, Dennis. \"Chapter 25: The Security Services since 1989: Turning over a new leaf.\" 2004. Carey, Henry F., ed. ''Romania since 1989: politics, economics, and society.'' Lexington Books: Oxford. pp. 507\u2013510.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105090207/http://d.yimg.com/kq/groups/21010417/803473086/name/Carey_final.pdf |date=5 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===King Michael===\nIn 1992, three years after the revolution which overthrew the Communist dictatorship, the Romanian government allowed [[Michael I of Romania|King Michael]] to return to his country for Easter celebrations, where he drew large crowds{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}. In Bucharest over a million people turned out to see him{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}. Michael's popularity alarmed the government of President Ion Iliescu, so Michael was forbidden to visit Romania again for five years{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}. In 1997, after Iliescu's defeat by Emil Constantinescu, the Romanian Government restored Michael's citizenship and again allowed him to visit the country{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}.\n\n===Pardons===\nIn December 2001, Iliescu pardoned three inmates convicted for [[bribery]], including George T\u0103nase, former [[Garda Financiara|Financial Guard]] head commissioner for [[Ialomi\u021ba County|Ialomi\u021ba]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www2.gds.ro/Actualitate/2002-01-04/Presedintele+Ion+Iliescu+a+acordat+gratieri Presedintele Ion Iliescu a acordat gratieri] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619125248/http://www2.gds.ro/Actualitate/2002-01-04/Presedintele+Ion+Iliescu+a+acordat+gratieri |date=19 June 2009 }}</ref> Iliescu had to revoke T\u0103nase's pardon a few days later due to the media outcry, claiming that \"a legal adviser was superficial in analyzing the case\".<ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-49352551.html Romania's president to cancel pardon, pledges to fight corruption] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106062029/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-49352551.html |date=6 November 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{in lang|ro}}[http://www2.gds.ro/Opinii/2002-01-14/Colaboratorii+presedintelui Colaboratorii presedintelui. Opinii \u2013 de Octavian PALER]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Later, the humanitarian reasons invoked in the pardon were contradicted by another medical expert opinion.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.ziaruldeiasi.ro/national-extern/gratierea-lui-iliescu-miroase-suspect-de-la-o-posta~ni2ch4 Gratierea lui Iliescu miroase suspect de la o posta] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716064745/http://www.ziaruldeiasi.ro/national-extern/gratierea-lui-iliescu-miroase-suspect-de-la-o-posta~ni2ch4 |date=16 July 2011 }}</ref> Another controversial pardon was that of Dan Tartag\u0103\u2014a businessman from [[Bra\u0219ov]] that, while drunk, had run over and killed two people on a pedestrian crossing. He was sentenced to three years and a half but was pardoned after only a couple of months.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1248257-ambasada-sua-nu-inceput-anchetarea-puscasului-marin.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925231808/http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1248257-ambasada-sua-nu-inceput-anchetarea-puscasului-marin.htm |archivedate=25 September 2012 |df=dmy-all |language=ro}} Ambasada SUA: Nu a inceput anchetarea puscasului marin] (in the background section)</ref> Tartag\u0103 was later sentenced to a two-year sentence for [[fraud]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20050118074925/http://www.phg.ro/stire.php?id=7335&cat_id=10 Afacere imobiliara cu iz de TBC la Brasov] (in the background section)</ref>\n\nMost controversial of all, on 15 December 2004, a few days before the end of his last term, Iliescu [[pardon]]ed 47 convicts, including [[Miron Cozma]], the leader of the miners during the early 1990s, who had been sentenced in 1999 to 18 years in prison in conjunction with the [[September 1991 Mineriad]]. This has attracted harsh criticism from all Romanian media.<ref name=evz46>{{in lang|ro}} [https://archive.is/20130416115702/http://www.evz.ro/articole/detalii-articol/669963/Gratiatii-lui-Iliescu-Nastase-corupti-tilhari-violatori-tepari/ Gratiatii lui Iliescu-Nastase: corupti, tilhari, violatori, tepari]</ref> Many of the pardoned had been convicted for corruption or other economic crimes, while one had been imprisoned for his involvement in the attempts at suppressing the 1989 Revolution.<ref name=evz46/>\n\n===Decorating Vadim Tudor===\nIn the last days of his President mandate, he awarded the National Order ''[[Steaua Rom\u00e2niei]]'' (rank of ceremonial knighthood) to the ultra-nationalist controversial politician [[Corneliu Vadim Tudor]], a gesture which drew criticism in the press and prompted [[Nobel Peace Prize]] winner [[Elie Wiesel]], fifteen [[Radio Free Europe]] journalists, [[Timi\u0219oara]] mayor [[Gheorghe Ciuhandu]], songwriter [[Alexandru Andrie\u0219]], and historian [[Randolph Braham]] to return their Romanian honours in protest. The leader of the Democratic Union of Hungarians in Romania, [[B\u00e9la Mark\u00f3]], did not show up to claim the award he received on the same occasion. President Traian B\u0103sescu revoked the award granted to Tudor on 24 May 2007, but a lawsuit is ongoing even after B\u0103sescu's decree was declared constitutional.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.ziua.ro/news.php?data=2009-01-20&id=19614 Curtea Constitu\u021bional\u0103 a respins excep\u021bia invocat\u0103 de Vadim Tudor in procesul privind Ordinul \"Steaua Romaniei\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927095437/http://www.ziua.ro/news.php?data=2009-01-20&id=19614 |date=27 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Black sites===\nIon Iliescu is mentioned in the report of the [[Council of Europe]] investigator into illegal activities of the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] in Europe, [[Dick Marty]]. He is pointed out as one of the people who authorized or at least knew about and have to stand accountable for [[Black site|torture prisons]] at [[Mihail Kog\u0103lniceanu International Airport|Mihail Kog\u0103lniceanu]] airbase from 2003 to 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://assembly.coe.int/CommitteeDocs/2007/EMarty_20070608_NoEmbargo.pdf|title=Secret detentions and illegal transfers of detainees involving Council of Europe member states: second report|author=Committee on Legal Affairs and Human Rights|date=7 June 2007|work=Parliamentary Assembly|publisher=Council of Europe|accessdate=11 March 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606232511/http://assembly.coe.int/CommitteeDocs/2007/EMarty_20070608_NoEmbargo.pdf|archivedate=6 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In April 2015, Iliescu confirmed that he had granted a CIA request for a site in Romania, but was not aware of the nature of the site, describing it as a small gesture of goodwill to an ally in advance of Romania's eventual accession to NATO. Iliescu further stated that had he known of the intended use of the site, he would certainly not have approved the request.<ref name=\"Spiegel 2015-04-22\">{{cite journal |last=Verseck |first=Keno |date=2015-04-22 |title=Folter in Rum\u00e4nien: Ex-Staatschef Iliescu gibt Existenz von CIA-Gef\u00e4ngnis zu |trans-title=Torture in Romania: Former Head of State Iliescu Acknowledges Existence of CIA Prison |language=German |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/cia-foltergefaengnisse-in-rumaenien-ion-iliescu-gibt-existenz-zu-a-1028917.html |journal=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg, Germany |publisher=Spiegel-Verlag |access-date=2015-04-22 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423154042/http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/cia-foltergefaengnisse-in-rumaenien-ion-iliescu-gibt-existenz-zu-a-1028917.html |archivedate=23 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Revolution of 1989 and Subsequent Trial===\nIn 2016, a previously closed legal case regarding Crimes Against Humanity committed by the interim government headed by Iliescu during the [[Romanian Revolution]] was reopened.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\">https://trialinternational.org/latest-post/iliescu-ion/</ref> Authorities had, in 2015, after 26 years of prolonged investigation, concluded that there was no evidence with which they could prosecute.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> However, in 2016, the case was ordered to be re-examined by the interim General Prosecutor.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> By 2017, military prosecutors had alleged that the events of 1989 were orchestrated by a misinformation campaign on the part of Iliescu's government, which were disseminated through broadcasting media.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47858664</ref> Reportedly, this investigation lead to speculation of whether the conflict of 1989 could be classified as a revolution, or conversely, as a [[Coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/>\n\nIn April 2018, the General Prosecutor asked that Iliescu be put on trial. President [[Klaus Iohannis]] approved this request, as well as the proceeding of the prosecution of [[Petre Roman]].<ref>Voiculescu</ref>\n\nIliescu was charged for his alleged role in the killing of 862 people during the revolution, at which time he headed the [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]] interim government, as well as the spreading of misinformation.<ref name=\"bbc.com\"/> Allegations included Iliescu's apparent involvement in the \"Mineriad\" case, in which miners quashed protests against the government. The initial charges, brought forward in 2005, were shortly dropped, until 2014 when the European Court of Human Rights found Iliescu's lack of investigation into the events of Mineriad to be in violation of human rights to life, freedom from inhumane and degrading treatment and demonstration<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> and again in 2015 when the Military Prosecutor's Section within the Prosecutor's Office and the Justice Office reopened investigations into the Mineriad protests, accusing Iliescu, along with other accused perpetrators, of coordinating a general and systematic attack against the civilian population during the events from 13 until 15 June 1990 in Bucharest.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> Finally, on 13 June 2017, the Prosecutor's office indicted Iliescu for crimes against humanity for actions taken by Iliescu during the Mineriad protests. The statement released by the office claimed that the attack illegally involved forces of the Interior Ministry, Defence Ministry, Romanian Intelligence service, as well as the miners and other workers from various areas of the country.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> The office further alleged that attacks were also carried out against peaceful residents.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/>\n\n[[File:1989 Iliescu television.jpg|thumb|Ion Iliescu at the Romanian Television during the Romanian Revolution of 1989, the broadcast was one of the key points of accusation against Iliescu.]]\n\nOn 8 April 2019, Ion Iliescu was officially charged with crimes against humanity<ref>https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-former-romanian-president-to-stand-trial/av-48297216</ref><ref name=\"actmedia.eu\">https://www.actmedia.eu/daily/1990-miners-riot-file-returned-to-the-prosecutor-s-office/80815</ref> Iliescu's lawyer, Adrian Georgescu, complained that the file was illegitimate,<ref>https://www.g4media.ro/ion-iliescu-plangere-la-sectia-speciala-pentru-magistrati-pentru-modul-in-care-a-fost-trimis-in-judecata-dosarul-revolutiei.html</ref> due to its lack of a prosecutor.<ref name=\"actmedia.eu\"/> In December of the same year, Iliescu's trial began to focus on allegations that he had intentionally spread disinformation through the use of broadcast media with the aid of [[Aurel-Drago\u0219 Munteanu]], a member of the National Salvation Front and the director of [[Romanian Television|TVR]] during the revolution of 1989, meaning that he was greatly influential  in the Nation Salvation Front's ability to foster support in the Romanian public.<ref>{{cite news |date=2019-09-29 |title=Proc\u00e8s historique pour l\u2019ex-pr\u00e9sident roumain Ion Iliescu, jug\u00e9 pour \" crimes contre l\u2019humanit\u00e9\"|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/international/article/2019/11/29/proces-historique-pour-l-ex-president-roumain-ion-iliescu-juge-pour-crimes-contre-l-humanite_6020988_3210.html|work=[La Monde] |location=France}}</ref> Among the claims investigated were Iliescu's broadcast claim that \"unknown terrorists\" were responsible for the deaths of Elena and Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu.<ref>{{cite news |date=2019-09-29 |title=Proc\u00e8s historique pour l\u2019ex-pr\u00e9sident roumain Ion Iliescu, jug\u00e9 pour \" crimes contre l\u2019humanit\u00e9 \"|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/international/article/2019/11/29/proces-historique-pour-l-ex-president-roumain-ion-iliescu-juge-pour-crimes-contre-l-humanite_6020988_3210.html |work=[La Monde] |location=France}}</ref>\n\nAmid candlelit vigils and other memorial services during the 30th anniversary of the [[Romanian Revolution]], several survivors of the conflict spoke out against Iliescu's trial, with many claiming it is a publicity stunt on the part of [[Klaus Iohannis]] to gain popularity from the Romanian population that still seek the truth about the revolution.<ref name=\"The Article\">{{cite news |date=2020-01-04 |title=Romania \u2014 a country fighting for its past|url=https://www.thearticle.com/romania-a-country-fighting-for-its-past |work=The Article}}</ref> Currently, Iliescu's trial is not expected to reach a definitive conclusion.<ref name=\"The Article\"/> The trial has been postponed to February 2020 due to Iliescu's declining health and the slow pace of legal proceedings.<ref>{{cite news |date=2019-12-24 |title=Executing a dictator: Open wounds of Romania's Christmas revolution|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50821546 |work=[BBC] |location=United Kingdom}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* The Order \"The Star of the Romanian Socialist Republic First Class\" (Ordinul Steaua Republicii Socialiste Rom\u00e2nia clasa I) (1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lege5.ro/Gratuit/gu4tqoju/decretul-nr-157-1971-privind-conferirea-unor-ordine-ale-republicii-socialiste-romania/2|title=Decretul nr. 157/1971 privind conferirea unor ordine ale Republicii Socialiste Rom\u00e2nia|language=Romanian|accessdate=13 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221210938/http://lege5.ro/Gratuit/gu4tqoju/decretul-nr-157-1971-privind-conferirea-unor-ordine-ale-republicii-socialiste-romania/2|archivedate=21 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Iliescu was awarded with Azerbaijani [[Istiglal Order]] for his contributions to development of [[Azerbaijan-Romania relations]] and strategic cooperation between the states by [[President of Azerbaijan]] [[Ilham Aliyev]] on 6 October 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://e-qanun.az/print.php?internal=view&target=1&docid=5771&doctype=0|title= \u0130on \u0130liyeskonun \"\u0130stiqlal\" ordeni il\u0259 t\u0259ltif edilm\u0259si haqq\u0131nda AZ\u018fRBAYCAN RESPUBL\u0130KASI PREZ\u0130DENT\u0130N\u0130N F\u018fRMANI|trans-title= Order of the President of Azerbaijan Republic on awarding President of Romania Ion Iliescu with Istiglal Order|accessdate= 20 January 2011|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120330111128/http://e-qanun.az/print.php?internal=view&target=1&docid=5771&doctype=0|archivedate= 30 March 2012|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Estonia}}: Collar of the [[Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]]\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: Grand Cross (or 1st Class) of the [[Order of the White Double Cross]] (2002)<ref>Slovak republic website, [http://www.slovak-republic.org/symbols/honours/ State honours] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413004835/http://www.slovak-republic.org/symbols/honours/ |date=13 April 2016 }}: 1st Class in 2002 (click on \"Holders of the Order of the 1st Class White Double Cross\" to see the holders' table)</ref>\n* {{flag|Croatia}}: Knight Grand Cross of the [[Grand Order of King Tomislav]] (\"For outstanding contribution to the promotion of friendship and development co-operation between the Republic of Croatia and the Republic of Romania.\" \u2013 12 May 2003)\n* {{flag|Italy}}: Knight Grand Cross with Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] \u2013 15 October 2003<ref>[http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=132635 Quirinale web site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030094721/http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=132635 |date=30 October 2013 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Poland}}: [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]] (2003)\n* {{flag|Denmark}}: Knight of the [[Order of the Elephant]] (2004)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kongehuset.dk/modtagere-af-danske-dekorationer|title=Modtagere af danske dekorationer|website=kongehuset.dk|accessdate=5 May 2019|language=Danish}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Romania}}: Emblema de Onoare an Armatei Rom\u00e2niei (\"The Romanian Army's Badge of Honor\") \u2013 24 October 2012<ref>{{cite web|title=Iliescu si Constantinescu au primit Emblema de Onoare a Armatei|url=http://www.ziare.com/ion-iliescu/presedinte/iliescu-si-constantinescu-au-primit-emblema-de-onoare-a-armatei-1197560|accessdate=24 October 2012|language=ro|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025234702/http://www.ziare.com/ion-iliescu/presedinte/iliescu-si-constantinescu-au-primit-emblema-de-onoare-a-armatei-1197560|archivedate=25 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Serbia and Montenegro}}: [[Order of the Yugoslav Star]] (2004)<ref>[http://www.blic.rs/stara_arhiva/politika/68682/Odlikovanja-sakom-i-kapom Odlikovanja \u0161akom i kapom] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054500/http://www.blic.rs/stara_arhiva/politika/68682/Odlikovanja-sakom-i-kapom |date=21 September 2013 }} at [[Blic]], 9-9-2004 {{in lang|sr}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n===Presidential elections===\n{| class=wikitable width=100%\n! rowspan=2|Election\n! rowspan=2|Affiliation\n! colspan=3|First round\n! colspan=3|Second round\n|-\n!Votes\n!Percentage\n!Position\n!Votes\n!Percentage\n!Position\n|-align=center\n! [[1990 Romanian general election|1990]]\n| {{yes2|'''[[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]'''}} || 12,232,498 || {{Percentage bar|85.07|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}} || bgcolor=lightgrey colspan=3|\n|-align=center\n! [[1992 Romanian general election|1992]]\n| {{yes2|'''[[Democratic National Salvation Front|FDSN]]'''}} || 5,633,465|| {{Percentage bar|47.5|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}} || 7,393,429|| {{Percentage bar|61.4|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}}\n|-align=center\n! [[1996 Romanian general election|1996]]\n| {{no2|[[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PDSR]]}} || 4,081,093 || {{Percentage bar|32.3|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}} || 5,914,579 || {{Percentage bar|45.6|c=red}} || {{color box|silver|2nd}}\n|-align=center\n![[2000 Romanian general election|2000]]\n| {{yes2|'''[[Social Democratic Pole of Romania|PDSR]]'''}} || 4,076,273 || {{Percentage bar|36.4|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}} || 6,696,623 || {{Percentage bar|66.8|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.ziaristionline.ro/2011/01/27/foaie-nationala-si-ziaristi-online-ofera-biografia-secreta-a-lui-ion-iliescu-candidatul-manciurian-pdf/ Vladimir Alexe\u2014''Ion Iliescu \u2013 biografia secret\u0103: \"Candidatul manciurian\"'' (Ion Iliescu \u2013 The Secret Biography: \"The Manchurian Candidate\")] (in Romanian), published by [[Ziaristi Online]], 2000; {{ISBN|973-581-036-0}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041230220851/http://www.catavencu.ro/pdf/supliment_Iliescu.pdf The supplement dedicated to Iliescu] (in Romanian), published by [[Academia Ca\u021bavencu]], 22 December 2004\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|ro}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041021002732/http://www.presidency.ro/index.php?_RID=htm&id=4 |date=21 October 2004 |title=Ion Iliescu official biography }}\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://ioniliescu.wordpress.com/ Ion Iliescu's blog]\n{{Ion Iliescu}}\n{{Presidents of Romania}}\n{{PSDHeads}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iliescu, Ion}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People of the Romanian Revolution]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian communists]]\n[[Category:Romanian atheists]]\n[[Category:Romanian bloggers]]\n[[Category:Romanian dissidents]]\n[[Category:Members of the Great National Assembly]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Romania]]\n[[Category:People from Olteni\u021ba]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Politehnica University of Bucharest alumni]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Social Democratic Party (Romania)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Collar of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Istiglal Order]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross with Collar of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:Grand Order of King Tomislav recipients]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the White Double Cross]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Vytautas the Great]]\n[[Category:Romanian propagandists]]\n[[Category:Moscow Power Engineering Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Romanian democracy activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Iliescu|other people with the surname|Iliescu (surname)}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Ion Iliescu\n| honorific-suffix = <small>[[Istiglal Order|IO]], [[Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana|OCTM]], [[Grand Order of King Tomislav|GOKT]], [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|OWE]], [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|OMIR]]</small>\n| image = Ion Iliescu (2).JPG\n| order = 2nd\n| office = President of Romania\n| primeminister = [[Petre Roman]]<br />[[Theodor Stolojan]]<br />[[Nicolae V\u0103c\u0103roiu]]\n| term_start = 26 December 1989\n| term_end = 29 November 1996<br /><small>Acting to 20 May 1990</small>\n| predecessor = [[List of members of the National Salvation Front Council|National Salvation Front Council]] (interim)\n| successor = [[Emil Constantinescu]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Mugur Is\u0103rescu]]<br />[[Adrian N\u0103stase]]\n| term_start2 = 20 December 2000\n| term_end2 = 20 December 2004\n| predecessor2 = [[Emil Constantinescu]]\n| successor2 = [[Traian B\u0103sescu]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1930|3|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Olteni\u021ba]], [[C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County|C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i]], Romania\n| party = [[Romanian Communist Party|Romanian Communist]]<br />{{small|(1953\u20131989)}}<br />[[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]]<br />{{small|(1989\u20131992)}}<br />[[Democratic National Salvation Front]]<br />{{small|(1992)}}<br />[[Independent politician|Independent]]<br />{{small|(1992\u20131996; 2000\u20132004; FDSN/PDSR membership suspended while president)}}<br />[[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic]]<br />{{small|(1996\u20132000; 2004\u2013present)}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Nina Iliescu]]|1951}}\n| alma_mater = [[Bucharest Polytechnic Institute]]<br />[[Moscow State University]]\n| profession = [[Engineer|Hydroelectric Engineer]]\n| signature = Signature of Ion Iliescu.png\n}}\n\n'''Ion Iliescu''' ({{IPA-ro|i\u02c8on ili\u02c8esku|-|Ro-Ion Iliescu.ogg}}; born 3 March 1930) is a Romanian [[politician]] who served as [[President of Romania]] from 1996 to 2000 and from 2004 until his retirement in 2008. Iliescu was a [[Senate of Romania|senator]] for the [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party]] (PSD), of which he is the founder and honorary president.\n\nHe joined the Communist Party in 1953 and became a member of its Central Committee in 1965. However, beginning with 1971, he was gradually marginalized by [[Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu]]. He had a leading role in the [[Romanian Revolution]], becoming the country's president in December 1989. In May 1990, he became Romania's first freely elected head of state. After a new constitution was approved by popular referendum, he served a further two terms as president, from 1992 to 1996, and from 2000 to 2004, separated by the presidency of [[Emil Constantinescu]], who defeated him in 1996.\n\nIliescu is widely recognized as a predominant figure in the first fifteen years of post-revolution politics. During his presidency, Romania joined [[NATO]]. In April 2018, Ion Iliescu was charged in Romania with committing [[crimes against humanity]] during the deadly aftermath of the country's 1989 revolution.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://stirileprotv.ro/justitie/ion-iliescu-asteptat-la-parchetul-general-fostul-presedinte-este-urmarit-penal-in-dosarul-revolutiei.html |title=Dosarul \"Revolu\u021biei\". Ion Iliescu este, oficial, urm\u0103rit penal pentru infrac\u021biuni contra umanit\u0103\u021bii |work=\u0218tirile Pro TV |date=17 April 2018 |language=Romanian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418161216/https://stirileprotv.ro/justitie/ion-iliescu-asteptat-la-parchetul-general-fostul-presedinte-este-urmarit-penal-in-dosarul-revolutiei.html |archivedate=18 April 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and entering politics==\n{{Expand section|date=June 2013}}\nIliescu's father, Alexandru Iliescu, was a railroad worker with [[Communism|Communist]] views during the period in which the [[Romanian Communist Party]] was banned by the authorities. In 1931, he went to the [[Soviet Union]] to take part in the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]] Congress of [[Moscow]]. He remained in the USSR for the next four years and was arrested upon his return. He was imprisoned from June 1940 to August 1944 and died in August 1945. During his time in the Soviet Union, Alexandru Iliescu divorced and married Mari\u021ba, a chambermaid.\n\nIliescu married Nina \u0218erb\u0103nescu in 1951; they have no children, not by choice but because they could not, as Nina had three [[miscarriage]]s.<ref>[http://ziua.net/news.php?data=2008-09-06&id=12256 \"De ce nu a avut Ion Iliescu urmasi\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Ziua'', 5 September 2008</ref> Born in [[Olteni\u021ba]], Iliescu studied [[fluid mechanics]] at the [[Bucharest Polytechnic Institute]] and then as a foreign student at the Energy Institute of the [[Moscow University]]. During his stay in Moscow, he was the secretary of the \"Association of Romanian Students\" it is alleged that he met [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], although Iliescu always denied this.<ref name=\"risingstar\">[[New York Times]], \"Upheaval in the East: A Rising Star; A Man Who Could Become Rumania's Leader\", 23 December 1989, p. 15</ref> However, years later, president [[Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu]] probably believed that there was a connection between the two, since during Gorbachev's visit to Romania in July 1989, Iliescu was sent outside of Bucharest to prevent any contact.<ref>''[[Rom\u00e2nia Liber\u0103]]''. \"Gura lumii despre Rom\u00e2nia\", 8 May 1990, quoting [[Paris Match]]</ref>\n\nIon Iliescu speaks fluently [[Romanian language|Romanian]], [[English language|English]] and [[Russian language|Russian]] languages.\n\n[[File:016.Vacanta-pentrecuta-in-Moldova-1976.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Ion Iliescu in 1976 with [[Elena Ceau\u0219escu]]]]\nHe joined the [[Union of Communist Youth]] in 1944 and the Communist Party in 1953 and made a career in the Communist [[nomenklatura]], becoming a secretary of the [[Central Committee]] of the Union of Communist Youth in 1956 and a member of the Central Committee of the [[Romanian Communist Party]] in 1965. At one point, he served as the head of the Central Committee's Department of Propaganda.<ref name=\"risingstar\"/> Iliescu later served as Minister for Youth-related Issues between 1967 and 1971.\n\nHowever, in 1971, Ceau\u0219escu felt threatened by Iliescu, who was seen as Ceau\u0219escu's heir apparent. He was marginalized and removed from all major political offices, becoming vice-president of the [[Timi\u0219 County]] Council (1971\u20131974), and later president of the [[Ia\u0219i County|Ia\u0219i]] Council (1974\u20131979). Until 1989, he was in charge of the Editura Tehnic\u0103 publishing house. For most of the 1980s (if not before), he was tailed by the [[Securitate]] (secret police), as he was known to oppose Ceau\u0219escu's harsh rule.<ref name=Revolution1989>{{cite book|last=Sebetsyen|first=Victor|title=Revolution 1989: The Fall of the Soviet Empire|publisher=[[Pantheon Books]]|location=New York City|year=2009|isbn=0-375-42532-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/revolution1989fa00sebe}}</ref>\n\n==Romanian Revolution==\n{{Main|Romanian Revolution}}\nThe Romanian Revolution began as a popular revolt in [[Timi\u0219oara]]. After Ceau\u0219escu was overthrown on 22 December, the political vacuum was filled by an organization named [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]] (FSN: ''Frontul Salv\u0103rii Na\u021bionale''), formed spontaneously by second-rank communist party members opposed to the policies of Ceau\u0219escu and non-affiliated participants in the revolt. Iliescu was quickly acknowledged as the leader of the organization and therefore of the provisional authority. He first learned of the revolution when he noticed the Securitate was no longer tailing him.<ref name=Revolution1989/>\n\nThe Ceau\u0219escus were captured, haled before a [[Trial and execution of Nicolae and Elena Ceau\u0219escu|drumhead court-martial]], and executed on Christmas Day. Years later, Iliescu conceded that the trial and execution were \"quite shameful, but necessary\" to end the chaos that had riven the country since Ceau\u0219escu's overthow.<ref name=dem25dec>{{cite news|last=Demian|first=Sinziana|title=In Romania, Ceausescu's death haunts Christmas|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/europe/091224/romania-nicolae-elena-ceausescu|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=Global Post|date=25 December 2009|location=Cluj Napoca}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CFSN Revolution Roumaine.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Three men are walking side-by-side holding papers. The first two are wearing a suit and the third is wearing a red sweater. The first man is smiling and flashing a V sign.|Iliescu (center) with FSN members [[Dumitru Mazilu]] (left) and [[Petre Roman]] (right) on 23 December 1989, one day after the formation of the FSN.]]\nIliescu proposed multi-party elections and an \"original democracy\". This is widely held to have meant the adoption of ''[[Perestroika]]''-style reforms rather than the complete removal of existing institutions; it can be linked to the warm reception the new regime was given by Mikhail Gorbachev and the rest of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] leadership, and the fact that the first post-revolutionary international agreement signed by Romania was with that country.\n\nIliescu did not renounce Communist ideology and the program he initially presented during the revolution included restructuring the agriculture and the reorganization of trade, but not a switch to capitalism.<ref name=\"risingstar\"/> These views were held by other members of the FSN as well, such as [[Silviu Brucan]], who claimed in early 1990 that the revolution was against Ceau\u0219escu, not against communism.<ref>http://eprints-phd.biblio.unitn.it/74/1/PhDThesisSGI.pdf</ref> Iliescu later evoked the possibility of trying a \"[[Sweden|Swedish]] model\" of socialism.\n\nRumours abounded for years that Illiescu and other second-rank Communists had been planning to overthrow Ceau\u0219escu, but the events of December 1989 overtook them. For instance, [[Nicolae Militaru]], the new regime's first [[Ministry of National Defense (Romania)|defense minister]], said that Illiescu and others had planned to take Ceau\u0219escu prisoner in February 1990 while he was out of the capital. However, Illiescu denies this, saying that the nature of the Ceau\u0219escu regime\u2014particularly the Securitate's ubiquity\u2014made advance planning for a coup all but impossible.<ref name=Revolution1989/>\n\n==Presidency==\n{{expand section|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox President styles\n | image = Coat of arms of Romania.svg\n | size = 50px\n | name = Ion Iliescu\n | dipstyle = Pre\u0219edintele (President)\n | offstyle = Pre\u0219edintele (President)\n | altstyle = Domnia Sa/Excelen\u021ba Sa (His Excellency)\n}}\nThe [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]] decided to organize itself as a party and run in the [[1990 Romanian general election|1990 general election]]\u2014the first free election held in the country in 53 years\u2013with Illiescu as its presidential candidate. The FSN won a sweeping victory, taking strong majorities in both chambers.<ref>Nohlen & St\u00f6ver, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120205171131/http://www2.essex.ac.uk/elect/database/indexElections.asp?country=ROMANIA&election=ro90cd University of Essex]</ref> In the separate presidential election, Iliescu won handily, taking 85 percent of the vote, still the largest vote share for a free presidential election. He thus became Romania's first democratically elected head of state, and the first since 1947 who was not a Communist or [[fellow traveler]]. To date, it is the only time since the end of Communism that a president has been elected in a single round.\n\nIliescu and his supporters split from the Front and created the Democratic National Salvation Front (NSDF), which later evolved into the Party of Social Democracy in Romania (PDSR), then the Social Democratic Party (PSD) (see [[Social Democratic Party of Romania]]). Progressively, the Front lost its character as a [[Central government|national government]] or generic coalition, and became vulnerable to criticism for using its appeal as the first institution involved in power sharing, while engaging itself in political battles with forces that could not enjoy this status, nor the credibility.\n\nUnder the pressure of the events that led to the [[Mineriad]]s, his political stance has veered with time: from a proponent of ''Perestroika'', Iliescu recast himself as a Western European [[social democracy|social democrat]]. The main debate around the subject of his commitment to such ideals is linked to the special conditions in Romania, and especially to the strong [[Romanian nationalism|nationalist]] and autarkic attitude visible within the Ceau\u0219escu regime. Critics have pointed out that, unlike most communist-to-social democrat changes in the [[Eastern bloc]], Romania's tended to retain various cornerstones.\n\n[[File:Ion Iliescu (2004).jpg|thumb|165px|Iliescu in 2004]]\n[[File:Iliescu si Bush.jpg|thumb|250px|Iliescu and U.S. President George W. Bush in 2002]]\nRomania adopted its first [[Constitution of Romania|post-Communist Constitution]] in 1991. In 1992, Iliescu [[1992 Romanian general election|won a second term]] when he received 61% of the vote in the second round. He immediately suspended his NSDF membership; the Constitution does not allow the president to be a formal member of a political party during his term. He ran for a third time in [[1996 Romanian general election|1996]] but, stripped of media monopoly, he lost in the second round to [[Emil Constantinescu]], his second-round opponent in 1992. Over 1,000,000 votes were cancelled, leading to accusations of widespread fraud. Nevertheless, Iliescu conceded defeat within hours of polls closing, making him the only incumbent president to lose a bid for re-election since the end of Communism.\n\nIn the [[2000 Romanian general election|2000 presidential election]] Iliescu ran again and won in the run-off against the ultra-nationalist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitatea.net/preda-antonescu-il-secondeaza-pe-vadim-tudor-cu-discursul-ultranationalist_718413.html|title=Preda: Antonescu \u00eel secondeaz\u0103 pe Vadim Tudor cu discursul ultrana\u0163ionalist|publisher=Realitatea|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927232910/http://www.realitatea.net/preda-antonescu-il-secondeaza-pe-vadim-tudor-cu-discursul-ultranationalist_718413.html|archivedate=27 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfbaytimes.com/index.php?sec=article&article_id=4066|title=Article|publisher=SF Bay Times|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016063611/http://www.sfbaytimes.com/index.php?sec=article&article_id=4066|archivedate=16 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/romania/tudor.html|title=House of Tudor|publisher=PBS|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106052244/http://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/romania/tudor.html|archivedate=6 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Corneliu Vadim Tudor]]. He began his third term on 20 December of that year, ending on 20 December 2004. The center-right was severely defeated during the 2000 elections due largely to public dissatisfaction with the harsh economic reforms of the previous four years as well as the political instability and infighting of the multiparty coalition. Tudor's extreme views also ensured that most urban voters either abstained or chose Iliescu.\n\nIn the PSD elections of 21 April 2005, Iliescu lost the Party presidency to [[Mircea Geoan\u0103]], but was elected as honorary president of the party in 2006, a position without official executive authority in the party.\n\n==Controversies==\nThough enjoying a certain popularity due to his opposition to Ceau\u0219escu and image as a revolutionary, his political career after 1989 was characterized by multiple controversies and scandals. Public opinion regarding his tenure as president is still divided.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfin.ro/articol_13481/al_cincilea_iliescu.html?action=print|title=Al Cincilea Iliescu|publisher=Income Magazine|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323014416/http://www.sfin.ro/articol_13481/al_cincilea_iliescu.html?action=print|archivedate=23 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged KGB connections===\nSome alleged Iliescu had connections to the [[KGB]], the allegations continued during 2003\u20132008, when Russian dissident [[Vladimir Bukovsky]], who had been granted access to Soviet archives, declared that Iliescu and some of the NSF members were KGB agents, that Iliescu had been in close connection with Mikhail Gorbachev ever since they had allegedly met during Iliescu's stay in Moscow, and that the Romanian Revolution of 1989 was a plot organized by the KGB to regain control of the country's policies (gradually lost under Ceau\u0219escu's rule).<ref>[http://english.hotnews.ro/stiri-top_news-6209804-russian-dissident-who-copied-the-gorbachev-foundations-archive-mitterrand-and-gorbachev-wanted-the-european-socialist-union-thatcher-opposed-germanys-reunification.htm Russian dissident who copied the Gorbachev Foundation's archive: Mitterrand and Gorbachev wanted the European Socialist Union, Thatcher opposed Germany's reunification] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111130233603/http://english.hotnews.ro/stiri-top_news-6209804-russian-dissident-who-copied-the-gorbachev-foundations-archive-mitterrand-and-gorbachev-wanted-the-european-socialist-union-thatcher-opposed-germanys-reunification.htm |date=30 November 2011 }}</ref> The only hard evidence published was a discussion between Gorbachev and Bulgaria's [[Aleksandar Lilov]] from 23 May 1990 (after Iliescu's victory in the 20 May elections) in which Gorbachev says that Iliescu holds a \"calculated position\", and that despite sharing common views with Iliescu, Gorbachev wanted to avoid sharing this impression with the public.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.ziua.ro/display.php?id=199569&data=15-05-2006 Dovada Bukovski] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201102614/http://www.ziua.ro/display.php?id=199569&data=15-05-2006 |date=1 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Mineriads===\n{{Main|Mineriad}}\nHe, along with other figures in the leading [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]], was allegedly responsible for calling the [[Jiu Valley]] miners to Bucharest on 28 January and 14 June 1990 to end the protests of the citizens gathered in [[University Square, Bucharest]], protests aimed against the ex-communist leaders of Romania (like himself). The pejorative term for this demonstration was the [[Golaniad]] (from the [[Romanian language|Romanian]] ''golan'', rascal). On 13 June, an attempt of the authorities to remove from the square around 100 protesters, which had remained in the street even after the [[1990 Romanian presidential election|May elections]] had confirmed Iliescu and the FSN, resulted in attacks against several state institutions, such as the Ministry of Interior, the Bucharest Police Headquarters and the National Television. Iliescu issued a call to the Romanian people to come and defend the government, prompting several groups of miners to descend on the capital, armed with wooden clubs and bats. They trashed the [[University of Bucharest]], some newspaper offices and the headquarters of opposition parties, claiming that they were havens of decadence and immorality \u2013 drugs, firearms and munitions, \"an automatic typewriter\", and fake currency. The [[June 1990 Mineriad]] in particular was widely criticized both at home and internationally, with one historian (Andrei Pippidi) comparing the events to Nazi Germany's [[Kristallnacht]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Constantin Petre|url=http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/mineriadele-anului-1990-democratia-sub-bate-898037.html|title=Mineriadele anului 1990, democra\u0163ia sub b\u00e2te|publisher=EVZ|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010083428/http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/mineriadele-anului-1990-democratia-sub-bate-898037.html|archivedate=10 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.romanialibera.ro/exclusiv-rl/investigatii/minerii-au-terorizat-capitala-30479.html|title=Minerii au terorizat Capitala|publisher=Romania Libera|accessdate=28 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008110518/http://www.romanialibera.ro/exclusiv-rl/investigatii/minerii-au-terorizat-capitala-30479.html|archivedate=8 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Government inquiries later established that the miners were infiltrated and instigated by former [[Securitate]] operatives.<ref name=\"Baleanu\">[http://www.fas.org/irp/world/romania/g43.html Baleanu, V. G. ''The Enemy Within: The Romanian Intelligence Service in Transition''. January 1995. Conflict Studies Research Centre, The Royal Military Academy Sandhurst: Camberley, Surrey GU15 4PQ.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016030538/http://fas.org/irp/world/romania/g43.html |date=16 October 2015 }}</ref> In February 1994 a Bucharest court \"found two security officers, Colonel Ion Nicolae and warrant officer Corneliu Dumitrescu, guilty of ransacking the house of [[Ion Ra\u021biu]], a leading figure in the [[Christian Democratic National Peasants' Party]], during the miners\u2019 incursion and stealing $100,000.\"<ref name=\"Deletant\">[http://d.yimg.com/kq/groups/21010417/803473086/name/Carey_final.pdf Deletant, Dennis. \"Chapter 25: The Security Services since 1989: Turning over a new leaf.\" 2004. Carey, Henry F., ed. ''Romania since 1989: politics, economics, and society.'' Lexington Books: Oxford. pp. 507\u2013510.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105090207/http://d.yimg.com/kq/groups/21010417/803473086/name/Carey_final.pdf |date=5 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===King Michael===\nIn 1992, three years after the revolution which overthrew the Communist dictatorship, the Romanian government allowed [[Michael I of Romania|King Michael]] to return to his country for Easter celebrations, where he drew large crowds{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}. In Bucharest over a million people turned out to see him{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}. Michael's popularity alarmed the government of President Ion Iliescu, so Michael was forbidden to visit Romania again for five years{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}. In 1997, after Iliescu's defeat by Emil Constantinescu, the Romanian Government restored Michael's citizenship and again allowed him to visit the country{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}.\n\n===Pardons===\nIn December 2001, Iliescu pardoned three inmates convicted for [[bribery]], including George T\u0103nase, former [[Garda Financiara|Financial Guard]] head commissioner for [[Ialomi\u021ba County|Ialomi\u021ba]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www2.gds.ro/Actualitate/2002-01-04/Presedintele+Ion+Iliescu+a+acordat+gratieri Presedintele Ion Iliescu a acordat gratieri] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619125248/http://www2.gds.ro/Actualitate/2002-01-04/Presedintele+Ion+Iliescu+a+acordat+gratieri |date=19 June 2009 }}</ref> Iliescu had to revoke T\u0103nase's pardon a few days later due to the media outcry, claiming that \"a legal adviser was superficial in analyzing the case\".<ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-49352551.html Romania's president to cancel pardon, pledges to fight corruption] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106062029/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-49352551.html |date=6 November 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{in lang|ro}}[http://www2.gds.ro/Opinii/2002-01-14/Colaboratorii+presedintelui Colaboratorii presedintelui. Opinii \u2013 de Octavian PALER]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Later, the humanitarian reasons invoked in the pardon were contradicted by another medical expert opinion.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.ziaruldeiasi.ro/national-extern/gratierea-lui-iliescu-miroase-suspect-de-la-o-posta~ni2ch4 Gratierea lui Iliescu miroase suspect de la o posta] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716064745/http://www.ziaruldeiasi.ro/national-extern/gratierea-lui-iliescu-miroase-suspect-de-la-o-posta~ni2ch4 |date=16 July 2011 }}</ref> Another controversial pardon was that of Dan Tartag\u0103\u2014a businessman from [[Bra\u0219ov]] that, while drunk, had run over and killed two people on a pedestrian crossing. He was sentenced to three years and a half but was pardoned after only a couple of months.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1248257-ambasada-sua-nu-inceput-anchetarea-puscasului-marin.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925231808/http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1248257-ambasada-sua-nu-inceput-anchetarea-puscasului-marin.htm |archivedate=25 September 2012 |df=dmy-all |language=ro}} Ambasada SUA: Nu a inceput anchetarea puscasului marin] (in the background section)</ref> Tartag\u0103 was later sentenced to a two-year sentence for [[fraud]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20050118074925/http://www.phg.ro/stire.php?id=7335&cat_id=10 Afacere imobiliara cu iz de TBC la Brasov] (in the background section)</ref>\n\nMost controversial of all, on 15 December 2004, a few days before the end of his last term, Iliescu [[pardon]]ed 47 convicts, including [[Miron Cozma]], the leader of the miners during the early 1990s, who had been sentenced in 1999 to 18 years in prison in conjunction with the [[September 1991 Mineriad]]. This has attracted harsh criticism from all Romanian media.<ref name=evz46>{{in lang|ro}} [https://archive.is/20130416115702/http://www.evz.ro/articole/detalii-articol/669963/Gratiatii-lui-Iliescu-Nastase-corupti-tilhari-violatori-tepari/ Gratiatii lui Iliescu-Nastase: corupti, tilhari, violatori, tepari]</ref> Many of the pardoned had been convicted for corruption or other economic crimes, while one had been imprisoned for his involvement in the attempts at suppressing the 1989 Revolution.<ref name=evz46/>\n\n===Decorating Vadim Tudor===\nIn the last days of his President mandate, he awarded the National Order ''[[Steaua Rom\u00e2niei]]'' (rank of ceremonial knighthood) to the ultra-nationalist controversial politician [[Corneliu Vadim Tudor]], a gesture which drew criticism in the press and prompted [[Nobel Peace Prize]] winner [[Elie Wiesel]], fifteen [[Radio Free Europe]] journalists, [[Timi\u0219oara]] mayor [[Gheorghe Ciuhandu]], songwriter [[Alexandru Andrie\u0219]], and historian [[Randolph Braham]] to return their Romanian honours in protest. The leader of the Democratic Union of Hungarians in Romania, [[B\u00e9la Mark\u00f3]], did not show up to claim the award he received on the same occasion. President Traian B\u0103sescu revoked the award granted to Tudor on 24 May 2007, but a lawsuit is ongoing even after B\u0103sescu's decree was declared constitutional.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.ziua.ro/news.php?data=2009-01-20&id=19614 Curtea Constitu\u021bional\u0103 a respins excep\u021bia invocat\u0103 de Vadim Tudor in procesul privind Ordinul \"Steaua Romaniei\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927095437/http://www.ziua.ro/news.php?data=2009-01-20&id=19614 |date=27 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Black sites===\nIon Iliescu is mentioned in the report of the [[Council of Europe]] investigator into illegal activities of the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] in Europe, [[Dick Marty]]. He is pointed out as one of the people who authorized or at least knew about and have to stand accountable for [[Black site|torture prisons]] at [[Mihail Kog\u0103lniceanu International Airport|Mihail Kog\u0103lniceanu]] airbase from 2003 to 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://assembly.coe.int/CommitteeDocs/2007/EMarty_20070608_NoEmbargo.pdf|title=Secret detentions and illegal transfers of detainees involving Council of Europe member states: second report|author=Committee on Legal Affairs and Human Rights|date=7 June 2007|work=Parliamentary Assembly|publisher=Council of Europe|accessdate=11 March 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606232511/http://assembly.coe.int/CommitteeDocs/2007/EMarty_20070608_NoEmbargo.pdf|archivedate=6 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In April 2015, Iliescu confirmed that he had granted a CIA request for a site in Romania, but was not aware of the nature of the site, describing it as a small gesture of goodwill to an ally in advance of Romania's eventual accession to NATO. Iliescu further stated that had he known of the intended use of the site, he would certainly not have approved the request.<ref name=\"Spiegel 2015-04-22\">{{cite journal |last=Verseck |first=Keno |date=2015-04-22 |title=Folter in Rum\u00e4nien: Ex-Staatschef Iliescu gibt Existenz von CIA-Gef\u00e4ngnis zu |trans-title=Torture in Romania: Former Head of State Iliescu Acknowledges Existence of CIA Prison |language=German |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/cia-foltergefaengnisse-in-rumaenien-ion-iliescu-gibt-existenz-zu-a-1028917.html |journal=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg, Germany |publisher=Spiegel-Verlag |access-date=2015-04-22 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423154042/http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/cia-foltergefaengnisse-in-rumaenien-ion-iliescu-gibt-existenz-zu-a-1028917.html |archivedate=23 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Revolution of 1989 and Subsequent Trial===\nIn 2016, a previously closed legal case regarding Crimes Against Humanity committed by the interim government headed by Iliescu during the [[Romanian Revolution]] was reopened.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\">https://trialinternational.org/latest-post/iliescu-ion/</ref> Authorities had, in 2015, after 26 years of prolonged investigation, concluded that there was no evidence with which they could prosecute.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> However, in 2016, the case was ordered to be re-examined by the interim General Prosecutor.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> By 2017, military prosecutors had alleged that the events of 1989 were orchestrated by a misinformation campaign on the part of Iliescu's government, which were disseminated through broadcasting media.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47858664</ref> Reportedly, this investigation lead to speculation of whether the conflict of 1989 could be classified as a revolution, or conversely, as a [[Coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/>\n\nIn April 2018, the General Prosecutor asked that Iliescu be put on trial. President [[Klaus Iohannis]] approved this request, as well as the proceeding of the prosecution of [[Petre Roman]].<ref>Voiculescu</ref>\n\nIliescu was charged for his alleged role in the killing of 862 people during the revolution, at which time he headed the [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]] interim government, as well as the spreading of misinformation.<ref name=\"bbc.com\"/> Allegations included Iliescu's apparent involvement in the \"Mineriad\" case, in which miners quashed protests against the government. The initial charges, brought forward in 2005, were shortly dropped, until 2014 when the European Court of Human Rights found Iliescu's lack of investigation into the events of Mineriad to be in violation of human rights to life, freedom from inhumane and degrading treatment and demonstration<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> and again in 2015 when the Military Prosecutor's Section within the Prosecutor's Office and the Justice Office reopened investigations into the Mineriad protests, accusing Iliescu, along with other accused perpetrators, of coordinating a general and systematic attack against the civilian population during the events from 13 until 15 June 1990 in Bucharest.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> Finally, on 13 June 2017, the Prosecutor's office indicted Iliescu for crimes against humanity for actions taken by Iliescu during the Mineriad protests. The statement released by the office claimed that the attack illegally involved forces of the Interior Ministry, Defence Ministry, Romanian Intelligence service, as well as the miners and other workers from various areas of the country.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/> The office further alleged that attacks were also carried out against peaceful residents.<ref name=\"trialinternational.org\"/>\n\n[[File:1989 Iliescu television.jpg|thumb|Ion Iliescu at the Romanian Television during the Romanian Revolution of 1989, the broadcast was one of the key points of accusation against Iliescu.]]\n\nOn 8 April 2019, Ion Iliescu was officially charged with crimes against humanity<ref>https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-former-romanian-president-to-stand-trial/av-48297216</ref><ref name=\"actmedia.eu\">https://www.actmedia.eu/daily/1990-miners-riot-file-returned-to-the-prosecutor-s-office/80815</ref> Iliescu's lawyer, Adrian Georgescu, complained that the file was illegitimate,<ref>https://www.g4media.ro/ion-iliescu-plangere-la-sectia-speciala-pentru-magistrati-pentru-modul-in-care-a-fost-trimis-in-judecata-dosarul-revolutiei.html</ref> due to its lack of a prosecutor.<ref name=\"actmedia.eu\"/> In December of the same year, Iliescu's trial began to focus on allegations that he had intentionally spread disinformation through the use of broadcast media with the aid of [[Aurel-Drago\u0219 Munteanu]], a member of the National Salvation Front and the director of [[Romanian Television|TVR]] during the revolution of 1989, meaning that he was greatly influential  in the Nation Salvation Front's ability to foster support in the Romanian public.<ref>{{cite news |date=2019-09-29 |title=Proc\u00e8s historique pour l\u2019ex-pr\u00e9sident roumain Ion Iliescu, jug\u00e9 pour \" crimes contre l\u2019humanit\u00e9\"|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/international/article/2019/11/29/proces-historique-pour-l-ex-president-roumain-ion-iliescu-juge-pour-crimes-contre-l-humanite_6020988_3210.html|work=[La Monde] |location=France}}</ref> Among the claims investigated were Iliescu's broadcast claim that \"unknown terrorists\" were responsible for the deaths of Elena and Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu.<ref>{{cite news |date=2019-09-29 |title=Proc\u00e8s historique pour l\u2019ex-pr\u00e9sident roumain Ion Iliescu, jug\u00e9 pour \" crimes contre l\u2019humanit\u00e9 \"|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/international/article/2019/11/29/proces-historique-pour-l-ex-president-roumain-ion-iliescu-juge-pour-crimes-contre-l-humanite_6020988_3210.html |work=[La Monde] |location=France}}</ref>\n\nAmid candlelit vigils and other memorial services during the 30th anniversary of the [[Romanian Revolution]], several survivors of the conflict spoke out against Iliescu's trial, with many claiming it is a publicity stunt on the part of [[Klaus Iohannis]] to gain popularity from the Romanian population that still seek the truth about the revolution.<ref name=\"The Article\">{{cite news |date=2020-01-04 |title=Romania \u2014 a country fighting for its past|url=https://www.thearticle.com/romania-a-country-fighting-for-its-past |work=The Article}}</ref> Currently, Iliescu's trial is not expected to reach a definitive conclusion.<ref name=\"The Article\"/> The trial has been postponed to February 2020 due to Iliescu's declining health and the slow pace of legal proceedings.<ref>{{cite news |date=2019-12-24 |title=Executing a dictator: Open wounds of Romania's Christmas revolution|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50821546 |work=[BBC] |location=United Kingdom}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* The Order \"The Star of the Romanian Socialist Republic First Class\" (Ordinul Steaua Republicii Socialiste Rom\u00e2nia clasa I) (1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lege5.ro/Gratuit/gu4tqoju/decretul-nr-157-1971-privind-conferirea-unor-ordine-ale-republicii-socialiste-romania/2|title=Decretul nr. 157/1971 privind conferirea unor ordine ale Republicii Socialiste Rom\u00e2nia|language=Romanian|accessdate=13 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221210938/http://lege5.ro/Gratuit/gu4tqoju/decretul-nr-157-1971-privind-conferirea-unor-ordine-ale-republicii-socialiste-romania/2|archivedate=21 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Iliescu was awarded with Azerbaijani [[Istiglal Order]] for his contributions to development of [[Azerbaijan-Romania relations]] and strategic cooperation between the states by [[President of Azerbaijan]] [[Ilham Aliyev]] on 6 October 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://e-qanun.az/print.php?internal=view&target=1&docid=5771&doctype=0|title= \u0130on \u0130liyeskonun \"\u0130stiqlal\" ordeni il\u0259 t\u0259ltif edilm\u0259si haqq\u0131nda AZ\u018fRBAYCAN RESPUBL\u0130KASI PREZ\u0130DENT\u0130N\u0130N F\u018fRMANI|trans-title= Order of the President of Azerbaijan Republic on awarding President of Romania Ion Iliescu with Istiglal Order|accessdate= 20 January 2011|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120330111128/http://e-qanun.az/print.php?internal=view&target=1&docid=5771&doctype=0|archivedate= 30 March 2012|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Estonia}}: Collar of the [[Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]]\n* {{flag|Slovakia}}: Grand Cross (or 1st Class) of the [[Order of the White Double Cross]] (2002)<ref>Slovak republic website, [http://www.slovak-republic.org/symbols/honours/ State honours] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413004835/http://www.slovak-republic.org/symbols/honours/ |date=13 April 2016 }}: 1st Class in 2002 (click on \"Holders of the Order of the 1st Class White Double Cross\" to see the holders' table)</ref>\n* {{flag|Croatia}}: Knight Grand Cross of the [[Grand Order of King Tomislav]] (\"For outstanding contribution to the promotion of friendship and development co-operation between the Republic of Croatia and the Republic of Romania.\" \u2013 12 May 2003)\n* {{flag|Italy}}: Knight Grand Cross with Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] \u2013 15 October 2003<ref>[http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=132635 Quirinale web site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030094721/http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=132635 |date=30 October 2013 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Poland}}: [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]] (2003)\n* {{flag|Denmark}}: Knight of the [[Order of the Elephant]] (2004)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kongehuset.dk/modtagere-af-danske-dekorationer|title=Modtagere af danske dekorationer|website=kongehuset.dk|accessdate=5 May 2019|language=Danish}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Romania}}: Emblema de Onoare an Armatei Rom\u00e2niei (\"The Romanian Army's Badge of Honor\") \u2013 24 October 2012<ref>{{cite web|title=Iliescu si Constantinescu au primit Emblema de Onoare a Armatei|url=http://www.ziare.com/ion-iliescu/presedinte/iliescu-si-constantinescu-au-primit-emblema-de-onoare-a-armatei-1197560|accessdate=24 October 2012|language=ro|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025234702/http://www.ziare.com/ion-iliescu/presedinte/iliescu-si-constantinescu-au-primit-emblema-de-onoare-a-armatei-1197560|archivedate=25 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Serbia and Montenegro}}: [[Order of the Yugoslav Star]] (2004)<ref>[http://www.blic.rs/stara_arhiva/politika/68682/Odlikovanja-sakom-i-kapom Odlikovanja \u0161akom i kapom] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054500/http://www.blic.rs/stara_arhiva/politika/68682/Odlikovanja-sakom-i-kapom |date=21 September 2013 }} at [[Blic]], 9-9-2004 {{in lang|sr}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n===Presidential elections===\n{| class=wikitable width=100%\n! rowspan=2|Election\n! rowspan=2|Affiliation\n! colspan=3|First round\n! colspan=3|Second round\n|-\n!Votes\n!Percentage\n!Position\n!Votes\n!Percentage\n!Position\n|-align=center\n! [[1990 Romanian general election|1990]]\n| {{yes2|'''[[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]'''}} || 12,232,498 || {{Percentage bar|85.07|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}} || bgcolor=lightgrey colspan=3|\n|-align=center\n! [[1992 Romanian general election|1992]]\n| {{yes2|'''[[Democratic National Salvation Front|FDSN]]'''}} || 5,633,465|| {{Percentage bar|47.5|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}} || 7,393,429|| {{Percentage bar|61.4|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}}\n|-align=center\n! [[1996 Romanian general election|1996]]\n| {{no2|[[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PDSR]]}} || 4,081,093 || {{Percentage bar|32.3|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}} || 5,914,579 || {{Percentage bar|45.6|c=red}} || {{color box|silver|2nd}}\n|-align=center\n![[2000 Romanian general election|2000]]\n| {{yes2|'''[[Social Democratic Pole of Romania|PDSR]]'''}} || 4,076,273 || {{Percentage bar|36.4|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}} || 6,696,623 || {{Percentage bar|66.8|c=red}} || {{color box|gold|1st}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.ziaristionline.ro/2011/01/27/foaie-nationala-si-ziaristi-online-ofera-biografia-secreta-a-lui-ion-iliescu-candidatul-manciurian-pdf/ Vladimir Alexe\u2014''Ion Iliescu \u2013 biografia secret\u0103: \"Candidatul manciurian\"'' (Ion Iliescu \u2013 The Secret Biography: \"The Manchurian Candidate\")] (in Romanian), published by [[Ziaristi Online]], 2000; {{ISBN|973-581-036-0}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041230220851/http://www.catavencu.ro/pdf/supliment_Iliescu.pdf The supplement dedicated to Iliescu] (in Romanian), published by [[Academia Ca\u021bavencu]], 22 December 2004\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|ro}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041021002732/http://www.presidency.ro/index.php?_RID=htm&id=4 |date=21 October 2004 |title=Ion Iliescu official biography }}\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://ioniliescu.wordpress.com/ Ion Iliescu's blog]\n{{Ion Iliescu}}\n{{Presidents of Romania}}\n{{PSDHeads}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iliescu, Ion}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People of the Romanian Revolution]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian communists]]\n[[Category:Romanian atheists]]\n[[Category:Romanian bloggers]]\n[[Category:Romanian dissidents]]\n[[Category:Members of the Great National Assembly]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Romania]]\n[[Category:People from Olteni\u021ba]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Politehnica University of Bucharest alumni]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Social Democratic Party (Romania)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Collar of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Istiglal Order]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross with Collar of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:Grand Order of King Tomislav recipients]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the White Double Cross]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Vytautas the Great]]\n[[Category:Romanian propagandists]]\n[[Category:Moscow Power Engineering Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Romanian democracy activists]]\n", "name_user": "213.233.85.115", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion_Iliescu"}
{"title_page": "Charles Surtees", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name         = Charles Surtees\n| honorific_suffix = [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] [[Justice of the Peace|JP]] [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]]\n| office       = [[High Sheriff of Durham]]\n| term_start   = 1873\n| term_end     = 1873\n| predecessor  = [[Rowland Burdon (Sedgefield MP)|Rowland Burdon]]\n| successor    = [[John Fogg Elliot]] \n| office1      = [[Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[South Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|South Durham]]\n| term_start1  = 1865\n| term_end1    = 1868\n| alongside1   = [[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Henry Pease (MP)|Henry Pease]]<br />[[James Farrer]]\n| successor1   = [[Frederick Beaumont]]<br />[[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]]\n| birth_name   = Charles Freville Surtees\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1823|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Heighington, County Durham]]\n| death_date   = {{dda|1906|12|22|1823|11|13|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Charing Cross Hotel]], [[London]]\n| education    = [[Harrow College]]\n| alma_mater   =\n| party        = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| parents      =\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Bertha Chauncey<br>|25 August 1855|5 November 1882|reason=her death}}\n| children     = Sir [[Herbert Conyers Surtees]]\n| relations    = [[Henry Surtees (MP)|Henry Surtees]] (brother)\n}}\n'''Charles Freville Surtees''' [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] [[Justice of the Peace|JP]] [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] (13 November 1823 \u2013 22 December 1906)<ref name=\"rayment\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Dcommons4.htm|title=House of Commons constituencies beginning with \"D\" (Part 4)|work=Leigh Rayment's House of Commons page|accessdate=2009-04-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407130329/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Dcommons4.htm|archive-date=7 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> was a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician in [[England]].\n\n==Early life==\nSurtees was born on 13 November 1823 at [[Heighington, County Durham]]. He was the youngest son of four children born to the former Elizabeth Cookson (1783\u20131847) and Robert Surtees of [[Redworth Hall]] (1782\u20131857).<ref name=\"Burke1863\"/>  His eldest brother, Robert Lambton Surtees, inherited the Redworth Hall after their father's in 1857.  When his brother died unmarried with no children six years later in 1863, the property passed to another brother, [[Henry Surtees (MP)|Henry Edward Surtees]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for [[Hertfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hertfordshire]] (who married Eliza Snell Chauncey in 1843).<ref name=\"craig1832\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Craig|editor1-first=F. W. S.|editor-link=F. W. S. Craig|title=British Parliamentary Election Results 1832-1885|date=1977|publisher=Macmillan Press|location=London|isbn=978-1-349-02349-3|edition=1st|format=e-book}}</ref>\n\nHis paternal grandparents were first cousins Jane Surtees and Lt. Crosier Surtees, who died in 1803 when returning from a banquet with [[William Vane, 1st Duke of Cleveland|Lord Barnard]] at [[Raby Castle]] when he drunkenly fell into the moors and froze to death.<ref name=\"1984Journal\">{{cite book |title=Journal of the Society for Army Historical Research |date=1984 |publisher=Society for Army Historical Research. |page=188 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=eEciAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>  His grandmother's sister, Dorothy Surtees (co-heiresses of William Steele, a director of the [[East India Company]]),<ref name=\"Burke1846\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=John |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland: M to Z |date=1846 |publisher=Henry Colburn |page=1334 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FlI4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1334&lpg=PA1334 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> also married a first cousin, Robert Surtees, and they were the parents of antiquarian [[Robert Surtees (antiquarian)|Robert Surtees]] of [[Mainsforth]].<ref name=\"reed\">{{cite web |title=Durham Cathedral Library: Catalogue of the Surtees Manuscripts |url=http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ark/32150_s2rr171x22v.xml |website=reed.dur.ac.uk |publisher=[[Durham Cathedral]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"RSdoi\">{{cite web |title=Surtees, Robert (1779\u20131834), historian |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/26790 |website=doi.org |publisher=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/26790}}</ref>  Charles became a member of the [[Surtees Society]] in 1859.<ref name=\"SS1884\">{{cite book |title=Publications of the Surtees Society |date=1884 |publisher=Surtees Society |page=15 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dvNaAAAAIAAJ&pg=PT15&lpg=PT15 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe was educated at [[Harrow College|Harrow]] before entering the [[British Army]] in 1842.<ref name=\"Fox-Davies1910\">{{cite book |last1=Fox-Davies |first1=Arthur Charles |title=Armorial Families: A Directory of Gentlemen of Coat-armour |date=1910 |publisher=T.C. & E.C. Jack |pages=1549-1550 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M2VHAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1550&lpg=PA1550 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSurtees was a member of the [[10th Royal Hussars]], reaching the rank of Lieutenant in 1845,<ref>{{cite news |title=War Office |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fRhKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA358&lpg=PA358 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The London Gazette]] |publisher=T. Neuman |date=1845 |page=358 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Captain]] in 1847.<ref name=\"Colburn1848\">{{cite book |title=The United Service Magazine |date=1848 |publisher=H. Colburn |page=472 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ft4RAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA472&lpg=PA472 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> From 1873 he was Colonel of the 3rd Battalion of the [[Durham Light Infantry]].<ref name=\"Fox-Davies1910\"/>\n\nHe served as a director of the [[Great Central Railway]] and was chairman of the Universal Life Assurance Society when it merged with [[North British and Mercantile Insurance|North British and Mercantile Insurance Company]] in 1903.<ref name=\"HMSO1903\">{{cite book |last1=Commons |first1=Great Britain Parliament House of |title=Parliamentary Papers |date=1903 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Office |page=167 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c2UOAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA167&lpg=RA3-PA167 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\n===Political career===\nHe was elected  as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|South Durham]] at the [[1865 United Kingdom general election|1865 general election]] and served alongside [[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]], but was defeated by [[Frederick Beaumont]] at the [[1868 United Kingdom general election|1868 general election]]. He did not stand in the [[1874 United Kingdom general election|1874 general election]], but failed to win a seat when he stood again in [[1880 United Kingdom general election|1880]].<ref name=\"craig1832-1885\">{{cite book  |last=Craig |first=F. W. S.  |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig |title=British parliamentary election results 1832\u20131885 |origyear=1977 |edition= 2nd |year=1989 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-26-4 |page = 384}}</ref>\n\nIn 1873, as Charles Freville Surtees of [[Mainsforth]], [[Ferryhill]] he succeeded [[Rowland Burdon (Sedgefield MP)|Rowland Burdon]] of [[The Castle, Castle Eden|The Castle at Castle Eden]] as [[High Sheriff of Durham]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=23945|page=513|date=6 February 1873}}</ref>  Surtees was himself succeeded by John Fogg Elliot of Elvet Hill.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=24061|page=481|date=2 February 1874}}</ref> He also served as [[List of deputy lieutenants of Durham|Deputy Lieutenant of Durham]].<ref name=\"Fox-Davies1910\"/> \n\n==Personal life==\nOn 25 August 1855, Surtees was married to Bertha Chauncey (1833\u20131882), a daughter of Nathaniel Snell Chauncey, Esq. of Green End.<ref name=\"ucl.ac\">{{cite web |title=Summary of Individual {{!}} Nathaniel Snell Chauncy |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/27133 |website=www.ucl.ac.uk |publisher=[[Centre for the Study of the Legacies of British Slave-ownership|Legacies of British Slave-ownership database]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Bertha was relative of Charles' older brother Henry's first wife, Eliza Snell Chauncey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pelhamwest.plus.com/grpf311.html|title=Herbert Conyers Surtees & Madeline Augusta Crabbe|website=www.pelhamwest.plus.com}}</ref> Together, they were the parents of one son:<ref name=\"Burke1863\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Sir Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain and Ireland |date=1863 |publisher=Harrison |page=1459 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ni4BAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA1459&lpg=PA1459 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n* [[Herbert Conyers Surtees]] (1858\u20131933), who in 1887 married Madeline Augusta Crabbe (d. 1957), daughter of Edward Crabbe and his wife [[Ruth Herbert]], a stage actress and the artist's model to [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]].<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |last1=Dorment |first1=Richard |title=Virginia Surtees obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2017/dec/05/virginia-surtees-obituary |work=The Guardian |date=5 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Fox-Davies|first=Arthur Charles|title=Armorial Families|edition=7th|year=1929\u201330|publisher=Hurst & Blackett|location=London|page=1242|volume=}}</ref>\n\nHe was a member of several of London's most prestigious [[gentlemen's club]]s, including the [[Army and Navy Club]], the [[Carlton Club]], the [[United Service Club]], the [[Cavalry Club]] and the [[Ranelagh Club]].<ref name=\"Walford1869\">{{cite book |last1=Walford |first1=Edward |title=The County Families of the United Kingdom Or, Royal Manual of the Titled and Untitled Aristocracy of Great Britain and Ireland ... |date=1869 |publisher=R. Hardwicke |page=931 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9EkzFlBgz0C&pg=PA931&lpg=PA931 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He was also made a [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society]].<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Mainsforth, in Sedgefield and County Durham {{!}} Map and description |url=https://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/1909 |website=www.visionofbritain.org.uk |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis wife died on 5 November 1882. Surtess died on 22 December 1906 at the [[Charing Cross Hotel]] in London.<ref name=\"rayment\"/> His funeral was held on 27 December at [[Long Ditton]] and was attended by [[Walburga, Lady Paget|Lady Paget]], Col. Surtees, Horace Avery K.C., Mr. Sheath (Secretary of the [[South Eastern Railway Company]]), and [[Cosmo Bonsor]] among others.<ref name=\"1906Funeral\">{{cite news |title=Court Circular |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48344812/court-circular/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=28 December 1906 |pages=7}}</ref>\n\n===Descendants===\nThrough his only son, he was a grandfather of Dorothy Cynthia Surtees (1890\u20131957), who married Sir [[Patrick Ramsay]] (the second son of [[John Ramsay, 13th Earl of Dalhousie]] and a brother-in-law of [[Princess Patricia of Connaught]] (through her husband [[Alexander Ramsay (Royal Navy officer)|Sir Alexander Ramsay]]), a granddaughter of [[Queen Victoria]]);<ref name=\"EarlDalhousie\">{{cite web |title=Dalhousie, Earl of (S, 1633) |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/dalhousie1633.htm |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> and Etelka Bertha Surtees (1891\u20131974), who married the American diplomat Edward J. Bell,<ref name=\"1914Engagement\">{{cite news |last1=TIMES |first1=Special Cable to THE NEW YORK |title=EDWARD BELL ENGAGED.; Attache of American Embassy in London to Marry Miss Surtees. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1914/01/19/archives/edward-bell-engaged-attache-of-american-embassy-in-london-to-marry.html?searchResultPosition=2 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=19 January 1914}}</ref> and after his death,<ref name=\"EBObit1924\">{{cite news |title=SUDDEN STROKE KILLS EDWARD BELL IN PEKING; Death of the Legation's Charge Shocks Washington -- F.L. Mayer Succeeds Him. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1924/10/29/archives/sudden-stroke-kills-edward-bell-in-peking-death-of-the-legations.html?searchResultPosition=4 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=29 October 1924}}</ref> [[James Dodds (diplomat)|Sir James Leishman Dodds]].<ref name=\"1927Engagement\">{{cite news |title=MRS. ETELKA BELL TO WED; U.S. Diplomat's Widow Engaged to J. L. Dodds, British Official. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/06/05/archives/mrs-etelk__aa-bel____l-to-wed-i-u-s-diplomats-widow-engaged-i-to-j.html?searchResultPosition=6 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=5 June 1927}}</ref> During [[World War II]], Dodds was the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Bolivia|British Minister to Bolivia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U153942|title=DODDS, Sir James Leishman|work=Who Was Who |publisher=A & C Black |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | colonel-charles-surtees | Charles Surtees }}\n*[http://www.19thcenturyphotos.com/Captain-Charles-Freville-Surtees-125880.htm Captain Charles Freville Surtees] at The Library of Nineteenth-Century Photography.\n*{{findagrave|145762188|Brigadier General Sir Herbert Conyers Surtees, CB, CMG, DSO, MVO, DL}} (his son)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[South Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|South Durham]]\n| years  = [[1865 United Kingdom general election|1865]] \u2013 [[1868 United Kingdom general election|1868]]\n| with   = [[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]]\n| before = [[Henry Pease (MP)|Henry Pease]]<br />[[James Farrer]]\n| after  = [[Frederick Beaumont]]<br />[[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surtees, Charles F}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow College]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1865\u20131868]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Durham]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Durham]]\n[[Category:Directors of the Great Central Railway]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Geographical Society]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name         = Charles Surtees\n| honorific_suffix = [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] [[Justice of the Peace|JP]] [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]]\n| office       = [[High Sheriff of Durham]]\n| term_start   = 1873\n| term_end     = 1873\n| predecessor  = [[Rowland Burdon (Sedgefield MP)|Rowland Burdon]]\n| successor    = [[John Fogg Elliot]] \n| office1      = [[Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[South Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|South Durham]]\n| term_start1  = 1865\n| term_end1    = 1868\n| alongside1   = [[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Henry Pease (MP)|Henry Pease]]<br />[[James Farrer]]\n| successor1   = [[Frederick Beaumont]]<br />[[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]]\n| birth_name   = Charles Freville Surtees\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1823|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Heighington, County Durham]]\n| death_date   = {{dda|1906|12|22|1823|11|13|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Charing Cross Hotel]], [[London]]\n| education    = [[Harrow College]]\n| alma_mater   =\n| party        = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| parents      =\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Bertha Chauncey<br>|25 August 1855|5 November 1882|reason=her death}}\n| children     = Sir [[Herbert Conyers Surtees]]\n| relations    = [[Henry Surtees (MP)|Henry Surtees]] (brother)\n}}\n'''Charles Freville Surtees''' [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] [[Justice of the Peace|JP]] [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] (13 November 1823 \u2013 22 December 1906)<ref name=\"rayment\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Dcommons4.htm|title=House of Commons constituencies beginning with \"D\" (Part 4)|work=Leigh Rayment's House of Commons page|accessdate=2009-04-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407130329/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Dcommons4.htm|archive-date=7 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> was a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician in [[England]].\n\n==Early life==\nSurtees was born on 13 November 1823 at [[Heighington, County Durham]]. He was the youngest son of four children born to the former Elizabeth Cookson (1783\u20131847) and Robert Surtees of [[Redworth Hall]] (1782\u20131857).<ref name=\"Burke1863\"/>  His eldest brother, Robert Lambton Surtees, inherited the Redworth Hall after their father's in 1857.  When his brother died unmarried with no children six years later in 1863, the property passed to another brother, [[Henry Surtees (MP)|Henry Edward Surtees]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for [[Hertfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hertfordshire]] (who married Eliza Snell Chauncey in 1843).<ref name=\"craig1832\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Craig|editor1-first=F. W. S.|editor-link=F. W. S. Craig|title=British Parliamentary Election Results 1832-1885|date=1977|publisher=Macmillan Press|location=London|isbn=978-1-349-02349-3|edition=1st|format=e-book}}</ref>\n\nHis paternal grandparents were first cousins Jane Surtees and Lt. Crosier Surtees, who died in 1803 when returning from a banquet with [[William Vane, 1st Duke of Cleveland|Lord Barnard]] at [[Raby Castle]] when he drunkenly fell into the moors and froze to death.<ref name=\"1984Journal\">{{cite book |title=Journal of the Society for Army Historical Research |date=1984 |publisher=Society for Army Historical Research. |page=188 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=eEciAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>  His grandmother's sister, Dorothy Surtees (co-heiresses of William Steele, a director of the [[East India Company]]),<ref name=\"Burke1846\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=John |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland: M to Z |date=1846 |publisher=Henry Colburn |page=1334 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FlI4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1334&lpg=PA1334 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> also married a first cousin, Robert Surtees, and they were the parents of antiquarian [[Robert Surtees (antiquarian)|Robert Surtees]] of [[Mainsforth]].<ref name=\"reed\">{{cite web |title=Durham Cathedral Library: Catalogue of the Surtees Manuscripts |url=http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ark/32150_s2rr171x22v.xml |website=reed.dur.ac.uk |publisher=[[Durham Cathedral]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"RSdoi\">{{cite web |title=Surtees, Robert (1779\u20131834), historian |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/26790 |website=doi.org |publisher=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/26790}}</ref>  Charles became a member of the [[Surtees Society]] in 1859.<ref name=\"SS1884\">{{cite book |title=Publications of the Surtees Society |date=1884 |publisher=Surtees Society |page=15 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dvNaAAAAIAAJ&pg=PT15&lpg=PT15 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe was educated at [[Harrow College|Harrow]] before entering the [[British Army]] in 1842.<ref name=\"Fox-Davies1910\">{{cite book |last1=Fox-Davies |first1=Arthur Charles |title=Armorial Families: A Directory of Gentlemen of Coat-armour |date=1910 |publisher=T.C. & E.C. Jack |pages=1549-1550 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M2VHAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1550&lpg=PA1550 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSurtees was a member of the [[10th Royal Hussars]], reaching the rank of Lieutenant in 1845,<ref>{{cite news |title=War Office |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fRhKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA358&lpg=PA358 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The London Gazette]] |publisher=T. Neuman |date=1845 |page=358 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Captain]] in 1847.<ref name=\"Colburn1848\">{{cite book |title=The United Service Magazine |date=1848 |publisher=H. Colburn |page=472 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ft4RAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA472&lpg=PA472 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> From 1873 he was Colonel of the 3rd Battalion of the [[Durham Light Infantry]].<ref name=\"Fox-Davies1910\"/>\n\nHe served as a director of the [[Great Central Railway]] and was chairman of the Universal Life Assurance Society when it merged with [[North British and Mercantile Insurance|North British and Mercantile Insurance Company]] in 1903.<ref name=\"HMSO1903\">{{cite book |last1=Commons |first1=Great Britain Parliament House of |title=Parliamentary Papers |date=1903 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Office |page=167 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c2UOAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA167&lpg=RA3-PA167 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\n===Political career===\nHe was elected  as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|South Durham]] at the [[1865 United Kingdom general election|1865 general election]] and served alongside [[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]], but was defeated by [[Frederick Beaumont]] at the [[1868 United Kingdom general election|1868 general election]]. He did not stand in the [[1874 United Kingdom general election|1874 general election]], but failed to win a seat when he stood again in [[1880 United Kingdom general election|1880]].<ref name=\"craig1832-1885\">{{cite book  |last=Craig |first=F. W. S.  |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig |title=British parliamentary election results 1832\u20131885 |origyear=1977 |edition= 2nd |year=1989 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-26-4 |page = 384}}</ref>\n\nIn 1873, as Charles Freville Surtees of [[Mainsforth]], [[Ferryhill]] he succeeded [[Rowland Burdon (Sedgefield MP)|Rowland Burdon]] of [[The Castle, Castle Eden|The Castle at Castle Eden]] as [[High Sheriff of Durham]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=23945|page=513|date=6 February 1873}}</ref>  Surtees was himself succeeded by John Fogg Elliot of Elvet Hill.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=24061|page=481|date=2 February 1874}}</ref> He also served as [[List of deputy lieutenants of Durham|Deputy Lieutenant of Durham]].<ref name=\"Fox-Davies1910\"/> \n\n==Personal life==\nOn 25 August 1855, Surtees was married to Bertha Chauncey (1833\u20131882), a daughter of Nathaniel Snell Chauncey, Esq. of Green End.<ref name=\"ucl.ac\">{{cite web |title=Summary of Individual {{!}} Nathaniel Snell Chauncy |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/27133 |website=www.ucl.ac.uk |publisher=[[Centre for the Study of the Legacies of British Slave-ownership|Legacies of British Slave-ownership database]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Bertha was relative of Charles' older brother Henry's first wife, Eliza Snell Chauncey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pelhamwest.plus.com/grpf311.html|title=Herbert Conyers Surtees & Madeline Augusta Crabbe|website=www.pelhamwest.plus.com}}</ref> Together, they were the parents of one son:<ref name=\"Burke1863\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Sir Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain and Ireland |date=1863 |publisher=Harrison |page=1459 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ni4BAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA1459&lpg=PA1459 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n* [[Herbert Conyers Surtees]] (1858\u20131933), who in 1887 married Madeline Augusta Crabbe (d. 1957), daughter of Edward Crabbe and his wife [[Ruth Herbert]], a stage actress and the artist's model to [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]].<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |last1=Dorment |first1=Richard |title=Virginia Surtees obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2017/dec/05/virginia-surtees-obituary |work=The Guardian |date=5 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Fox-Davies|first=Arthur Charles|title=Armorial Families|edition=7th|year=1929\u201330|publisher=Hurst & Blackett|location=London|page=1242|volume=}}</ref>\n\nHe was a member of several of London's most prestigious [[gentlemen's club]]s, including the [[Army and Navy Club]], the [[Carlton Club]], the [[United Service Club]], the [[Cavalry Club]] and the [[Ranelagh Club]].<ref name=\"Walford1869\">{{cite book |last1=Walford |first1=Edward |title=The County Families of the United Kingdom Or, Royal Manual of the Titled and Untitled Aristocracy of Great Britain and Ireland ... |date=1869 |publisher=R. Hardwicke |page=931 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9EkzFlBgz0C&pg=PA931&lpg=PA931 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He was also made a [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society]].<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Mainsforth, in Sedgefield and County Durham {{!}} Map and description |url=https://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/1909 |website=www.visionofbritain.org.uk |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis wife died on 5 November 1882. Surtess died on 22 December 1906 at the [[Charing Cross Hotel]] in London.<ref name=\"rayment\"/> His funeral was held on 27 December at [[Long Ditton]] and was attended by [[Walburga, Lady Paget|Lady Paget]], Col. Surtees, Horace Avery K.C., Mr. Sheath (Secretary of the [[South Eastern Railway Company]]), and [[Cosmo Bonsor]] among others.<ref name=\"1906Funeral\">{{cite news |title=Court Circular |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48344812/court-circular/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=28 December 1906 |pages=7}}</ref>\n\n===Descendants===\nThrough his only son, he was was a grandfather of Dorothy Cynthia Surtees (1890\u20131957), who married Sir [[Patrick Ramsay]] (the second son of [[John Ramsay, 13th Earl of Dalhousie]] and a brother-in-law of [[Princess Patricia of Connaught]] (through her husband [[Alexander Ramsay (Royal Navy officer)|Sir Alexander Ramsay]]), a granddaughter of [[Queen Victoria]]);<ref name=\"EarlDalhousie\">{{cite web |title=Dalhousie, Earl of (S, 1633) |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/dalhousie1633.htm |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> and Etelka Bertha Surtees (1891\u20131974), who married the American diplomat Edward J. Bell,<ref name=\"1914Engagement\">{{cite news |last1=TIMES |first1=Special Cable to THE NEW YORK |title=EDWARD BELL ENGAGED.; Attache of American Embassy in London to Marry Miss Surtees. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1914/01/19/archives/edward-bell-engaged-attache-of-american-embassy-in-london-to-marry.html?searchResultPosition=2 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=19 January 1914}}</ref> and after his death,<ref name=\"EBObit1924\">{{cite news |title=SUDDEN STROKE KILLS EDWARD BELL IN PEKING; Death of the Legation's Charge Shocks Washington -- F.L. Mayer Succeeds Him. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1924/10/29/archives/sudden-stroke-kills-edward-bell-in-peking-death-of-the-legations.html?searchResultPosition=4 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=29 October 1924}}</ref> [[James Dodds (diplomat)|Sir James Leishman Dodds]].<ref name=\"1927Engagement\">{{cite news |title=MRS. ETELKA BELL TO WED; U.S. Diplomat's Widow Engaged to J. L. Dodds, British Official. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/06/05/archives/mrs-etelk__aa-bel____l-to-wed-i-u-s-diplomats-widow-engaged-i-to-j.html?searchResultPosition=6 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=5 June 1927}}</ref> During [[World War II]], Dodds was the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Bolivia|British Minister to Bolivia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U153942|title=DODDS, Sir James Leishman|work=Who Was Who |publisher=A & C Black |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | colonel-charles-surtees | Charles Surtees }}\n*[http://www.19thcenturyphotos.com/Captain-Charles-Freville-Surtees-125880.htm Captain Charles Freville Surtees] at The Library of Nineteenth-Century Photography.\n*{{findagrave|145762188|Brigadier General Sir Herbert Conyers Surtees, CB, CMG, DSO, MVO, DL}} (his son)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[South Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|South Durham]]\n| years  = [[1865 United Kingdom general election|1865]] \u2013 [[1868 United Kingdom general election|1868]]\n| with   = [[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]]\n| before = [[Henry Pease (MP)|Henry Pease]]<br />[[James Farrer]]\n| after  = [[Frederick Beaumont]]<br />[[Sir Joseph Pease, 1st Baronet|Joseph Whitwell Pease]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surtees, Charles F}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow College]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1865\u20131868]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Durham]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Durham]]\n[[Category:Directors of the Great Central Railway]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Geographical Society]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Surtees"}
{"title_page": "Zaro Aga", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Zaro Aga\n| image                     = Zaro Agha, de oudste Turk ooit Zaro Agha, the oldest Turk ever.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       =\n| caption                   =\n| birth_date                = {{Tooltip|c.|circa}} 1777\n| birth_place               = [[Mutki]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_date                = 29 June 1934 (aged 157)\n| death_place               = [[Istanbul Province]], Turkey\n| death_cause               = \n| resting_place             = \n| citizenship               = Ottoman Empire, Turkey\n| nationality               = [[Ottoman Turks|Ottoman]], [[Turkey|Turkish]]\n| occupation                = [[Porter (carrier)|Porter]], [[laborer]], [[Doorman (profession)|doorman]]\n| known_for                 = Longevity\n| children                  = 36\n}}\n\n'''Zaro Aga''' ({{lang-tr|Zaro A\u011fa}}, {{lang-ku|Zaro Axa}}) was a Kurdish man who claimed to be one of the longest-living humans ever. He claimed birth between 1774 and 1777, and died on 29 June 1934<ref>Mecid Efendi (one of the [[son-in-law]] of Zaro Aga), ''[[Cumhuriyet]]'', 1 July 1934.</ref> in [[Istanbul Province|Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]. He was allegedly aged 157 when he died, and thus [[Longevity myths|claimed to be]] one of the longest-living humans ever.\n\n==Debate==\nThere is a debate as to his actual age when he died.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicagotribune.newspapers.com/|title=Chicago Tribune - Historical Newspapers|website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Zaro Agha, The legendary Kurdish supercentenarian|first1=Ali Yavuz|last1=Karahan|first2=\u0130brahim|last2=Batmaz|date=27 December 2018|journal=International Journal on Disability and Human Development|volume=14|issue=2|pages=201\u2013202|doi=10.1515/ijdhd-2014-0015}}</ref> According to the death certificate provided by his Turkish doctor, Zaro Aga's age was 157. He died in [[Istanbul Province|Istanbul]], although some confusion about the place of death exists, probably because the body was sent to the US right after his death. However, an investigative report published by Walter Bowerman in 1939 indicated that Zaro Aga was around 97, not 157.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isgeschiedenis.nl/nieuws/oudste-man-ter-wereld-zaro-aga|title=Oudste man ter wereld: Zaro A\u011fa|date=24 August 2012|website=IsGeschiedenis}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gahetna.nl/actueel/nieuws/2012/zaro-a%C4%9Fa-oudste-man-ter-wereld|title=Nieuws en pers \u00bb Zaro A\u011fa, de oudste man ter wereld? - gahetNA|website=www.gahetna.nl}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAga was born in Medan village (present-day: Meydan ){{citation needed|date=February 2013}} in [[Mutki]] ([[Bitlis Province]], [[Ottoman Empire]]), worked as a construction worker when he was young, and then moved to [[Istanbul Province|Istanbul]], where he worked as a porter and finally retired as a janitor. He was a major attraction to popular press during his last years as allegedly the world's oldest living man and one who had traveled to many countries, including the [[United States]],<ref>{{cite web |title=WORLD'S OLDEST MAN DEAD |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/35117181 |website=Advertiser (Adelaide, SA : 1931 - 1954) |pages=21 |date=30 June 1934}}</ref> the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]], [[French Third Republic|France]] and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]]. His body was sent to the US for research purposes after he died.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nZaro Aga had come into [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]]'s presence twice and called him \"Sultan\". Turkish newspaper Taraf claimed that when Zaro met with Mustafa Kemal, he mentioned his having done very good jobs, but he allegedly criticized his giving much freedom to the women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arsiv.taraf.com.tr/yazilar/ayse-hur/modern-methuselah-zaro-aga/16715|title='Modern Methuselah' Zaro A\u011fa - Ay\u015fe H\u00fcr - Taraf.com.tr - D\u00fc\u015f\u00fcnmek Taraf Olmakt\u0131r|date=14 February 2015|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214010832/http://arsiv.taraf.com.tr/yazilar/ayse-hur/modern-methuselah-zaro-aga/16715|archive-date=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring his lifetime surgeons treating Aga for an internal complaint examined X-Rays of his bones and cast doubt on his claimed age, suggesting he was not more than 120 years old. The old man was, according to Reuter from Istanbul, very angry and flourished his birth certificate under the noses of the doubting doctors.<ref name=\"auto\">Bournemouth Echo 30 June 1934 \u2018World\u2019s Oldest Man Dead\u2019</ref>\n\nHe claimed to have met [[Napoleon]], to have fought in six wars, and to have fought in the [[Battle of Plevna]], when he was 100. He was not sure if he had been married eleven or twelve times, but claimed to have roughly 36 children.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn 1931, he toured England and enjoyed a flight from Brooklands. He did not drink, or smoke, and was largely vegetarian. He held conservative views, feeling that women should have long hair and skirts, and in Turkey they should remain indoors, out of the view of strangers.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAga had 14 children, however their names were never recorded. His wife, a Turk, was highly looked upon. She was viewed as a person above most people, but died at 60 years old.\n\nAga himself refused to believe the claims of a man in [[China]] who was said to be 252 years old. Aga lived in relative anonymity until 1930, when someone, hearing his stories about meeting Napoleon and the Sultan of Turkey, pointed out that he had a claim to be the world\u2019s oldest man, and he began a public life with a tour of the USA. He said that he lost his teeth soon after [[Napoleon III]] [[Battle of Sedan|lost Sedan]]. He became prosperous through his fame and toured circus shows as the \u2018Eighth Wonder of the World\u2019.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nEventually Aga had to return home, as his wife Kudret was threatening to sue him for maintenance. He resumed his \u00a38 a month job as a coffee brewer for the local city council. For the remainder of his life he told stories to the coffee house patrons not of meeting Napoleon, but of his travels to New York and London.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Zaro Agha 148.jpg|Zaro Aga in [[Istanbul]].\nFile:Zaro Agha. (ca. 1923-1939).jpg|Mitchell's [[cigarette pack]].\nFile:Death of Zaro A\u011fa.JPG|Death of Zaro Aga.\nFile:Zaro A\u011fa Mezar Ta\u015f\u0131.jpg|thumb|Tombstone of Zaro Aga at Ey\u00fcp Sultan Cemetery\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Rohat Alakom, ''D\u00fcnyan\u0131n En Ya\u015fl\u0131 Adam\u0131: Zaro Aga (1774-1934)'', Avesta, 2009.\n* Rohat Alakom, ''Eski \u0130stanbul K\u00fcrtleri (1453-1925)'', Avesta Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, 1998; {{ISBN|975-7112-47-X}}, s. 155-161.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aga, Zaro}}\n[[Category:1770s births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:Kurdish Alevis]]\n[[Category:Turkish Alevis]]\n[[Category:People from Mutki]]\n[[Category:Civil servants of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Military personnel of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Kurdish people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Turkish Kurdish people]]\n[[Category:Kurdish people]]\n[[Category:Longevity myths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Zaro Aga\n| image                     = Zaro Agha, de oudste Turk ooit Zaro Agha, the oldest Turk ever.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       =\n| caption                   =\n| birth_date                = {{Tooltip|c.|circa}} 1777\n| birth_place               = [[Mutki]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_date                = 29 June 1934 (aged 157)\n| death_place               = [[Istanbul Province]], Turkey\n| death_cause               = \n| resting_place             = \n| citizenship               = Ottoman Empire, Turkey\n| nationality               = [[Ottoman Turks|Ottoman]], [[Turkey|Turkish]]\n| occupation                = [[Porter (carrier)|Porter]], [[laborer]], [[Doorman (profession)|doorman]]\n| known_for                 = Longevity\n| children                  = 36\n}}\n\n'''Zaro Aga''' ({{lang-tr|Zaro A\u011fa}}, {{lang-ku|Zaro Axa}}) was a Turkish man who claimed to be one of the longest-living humans ever. He claimed birth between 1774 and 1777, and died on 29 June 1934<ref>Mecid Efendi (one of the [[son-in-law]] of Zaro Aga), ''[[Cumhuriyet]]'', 1 July 1934.</ref> in [[Istanbul Province|Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]. He was allegedly aged 157 when he died, and thus [[Longevity myths|claimed to be]] one of the longest-living humans ever.\n\n==Debate==\nThere is a debate as to his actual age when he died.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicagotribune.newspapers.com/|title=Chicago Tribune - Historical Newspapers|website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Zaro Agha, The legendary Kurdish supercentenarian|first1=Ali Yavuz|last1=Karahan|first2=\u0130brahim|last2=Batmaz|date=27 December 2018|journal=International Journal on Disability and Human Development|volume=14|issue=2|pages=201\u2013202|doi=10.1515/ijdhd-2014-0015}}</ref> According to the death certificate provided by his Turkish doctor, Zaro Aga's age was 157. He died in [[Istanbul Province|Istanbul]], although some confusion about the place of death exists, probably because the body was sent to the US right after his death. However, an investigative report published by Walter Bowerman in 1939 indicated that Zaro Aga was around 97, not 157.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isgeschiedenis.nl/nieuws/oudste-man-ter-wereld-zaro-aga|title=Oudste man ter wereld: Zaro A\u011fa|date=24 August 2012|website=IsGeschiedenis}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gahetna.nl/actueel/nieuws/2012/zaro-a%C4%9Fa-oudste-man-ter-wereld|title=Nieuws en pers \u00bb Zaro A\u011fa, de oudste man ter wereld? - gahetNA|website=www.gahetna.nl}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAga was born in Medan village (present-day: Meydan ){{citation needed|date=February 2013}} in [[Mutki]] ([[Bitlis Province]], [[Ottoman Empire]]), worked as a construction worker when he was young, and then moved to [[Istanbul Province|Istanbul]], where he worked as a porter and finally retired as a janitor. He was a major attraction to popular press during his last years as allegedly the world's oldest living man and one who had traveled to many countries, including the [[United States]],<ref>{{cite web |title=WORLD'S OLDEST MAN DEAD |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/35117181 |website=Advertiser (Adelaide, SA : 1931 - 1954) |pages=21 |date=30 June 1934}}</ref> the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]], [[French Third Republic|France]] and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]]. His body was sent to the US for research purposes after he died.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nZaro Aga had come into [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]]'s presence twice and called him \"Sultan\". Turkish newspaper Taraf claimed that when Zaro met with Mustafa Kemal, he mentioned his having done very good jobs, but he allegedly criticized his giving much freedom to the women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arsiv.taraf.com.tr/yazilar/ayse-hur/modern-methuselah-zaro-aga/16715|title='Modern Methuselah' Zaro A\u011fa - Ay\u015fe H\u00fcr - Taraf.com.tr - D\u00fc\u015f\u00fcnmek Taraf Olmakt\u0131r|date=14 February 2015|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214010832/http://arsiv.taraf.com.tr/yazilar/ayse-hur/modern-methuselah-zaro-aga/16715|archive-date=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring his lifetime surgeons treating Aga for an internal complaint examined X-Rays of his bones and cast doubt on his claimed age, suggesting he was not more than 120 years old. The old man was, according to Reuter from Istanbul, very angry and flourished his birth certificate under the noses of the doubting doctors.<ref name=\"auto\">Bournemouth Echo 30 June 1934 \u2018World\u2019s Oldest Man Dead\u2019</ref>\n\nHe claimed to have met [[Napoleon]], to have fought in six wars, and to have fought in the [[Battle of Plevna]], when he was 100. He was not sure if he had been married eleven or twelve times, but claimed to have roughly 36 children.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn 1931, he toured England and enjoyed a flight from Brooklands. He did not drink, or smoke, and was largely vegetarian. He held conservative views, feeling that women should have long hair and skirts, and in Turkey they should remain indoors, out of the view of strangers.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAga had 14 children, however their names were never recorded. His wife, a Turk, was highly looked upon. She was viewed as a person above most people, but died at 60 years old.\n\nAga himself refused to believe the claims of a man in [[China]] who was said to be 252 years old. Aga lived in relative anonymity until 1930, when someone, hearing his stories about meeting Napoleon and the Sultan of Turkey, pointed out that he had a claim to be the world\u2019s oldest man, and he began a public life with a tour of the USA. He said that he lost his teeth soon after [[Napoleon III]] [[Battle of Sedan|lost Sedan]]. He became prosperous through his fame and toured circus shows as the \u2018Eighth Wonder of the World\u2019.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nEventually Aga had to return home, as his wife Kudret was threatening to sue him for maintenance. He resumed his \u00a38 a month job as a coffee brewer for the local city council. For the remainder of his life he told stories to the coffee house patrons not of meeting Napoleon, but of his travels to New York and London.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Zaro Agha 148.jpg|Zaro Aga in [[Istanbul]].\nFile:Zaro Agha. (ca. 1923-1939).jpg|Mitchell's [[cigarette pack]].\nFile:Death of Zaro A\u011fa.JPG|Death of Zaro Aga.\nFile:Zaro A\u011fa Mezar Ta\u015f\u0131.jpg|thumb|Tombstone of Zaro Aga at Ey\u00fcp Sultan Cemetery\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Rohat Alakom, ''D\u00fcnyan\u0131n En Ya\u015fl\u0131 Adam\u0131: Zaro Aga (1774-1934)'', Avesta, 2009.\n* Rohat Alakom, ''Eski \u0130stanbul K\u00fcrtleri (1453-1925)'', Avesta Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, 1998; {{ISBN|975-7112-47-X}}, s. 155-161.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aga, Zaro}}\n[[Category:1770s births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:Kurdish Alevis]]\n[[Category:Turkish Alevis]]\n[[Category:People from Mutki]]\n[[Category:Civil servants of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Military personnel of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Kurdish people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Turkish Kurdish people]]\n[[Category:Kurdish people]]\n[[Category:Longevity myths]]\n", "name_user": "Spivorg", "label": "safe", "comment": "All the sources refer to him as ethnically Kurdish", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zaro_Aga"}
{"title_page": "The Mister", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 novel by E. L. James}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name             = The Mister\n| image            = The Mister.jpg\n| author           = [[E. L. James]]\n| illustrator      = \n| cover_artist     =  \n| country          = United Kingdom\n| pages            = 512\n| language         = English\n| media_type     = Print: paperback\n| series           =  \n| published        = 16 April 2019, [[Vintage Books]]\n| preceded_by      =  \n| isbn             = 978-1984898326\n|genre=[[Romantic fiction|romance]]\n| followed_by      =\n|set_in= [[London]], [[Cornwall]] and [[Albania]], 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eljamesauthor.com/books/the-mister/|title=The Mister|website=www.eljamesauthor.com}}</ref> \n| audio_read_by     =  Dominic Thorburn, Jessica O'Hara-Baker<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Mister/dp/B07N317VDS/ref=tmm_aud_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=|title=The Mister|publisher=|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n| dewey             = \t823.92\n| congress          = \n| website           = {{URL|https://www.eljamesauthor.com/books/the-mister/}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Mister''''' is a 2019 [[Romantic fiction|romance]] novel by [[E. L. James]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cccadvocate.com/10860/scene/the-mister-fails-to-address-human-trafficking/|title=\u201cThe Mister\u201d fails to address human trafficking|first=Cindy|last=Pantoja|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.virginmediatelevision.ie/xpose/article/lifestyle/288349/Fifty-Shades-Of-Grey-author-EL-James-has-a-new-book-out--our-verdict-on-The-Mister|title=Fifty Shades Of Grey author E.L James has a new book out - our verdict on The Mister - Lifestyle from Xpos\u00e9 - Virgin Media Television|website=Virgin Media Television - Xpos\u00e9 Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-gb/the-mister-e-l-james-review|title=The Most Frustratingly Unsexy Things About 'The Mister' \u2013 The Follow Up To 'Fifty Shades'|first=Jazmin|last=Kopotsha|website=www.refinery29.com}}</ref><ref>https://variety.com/2020/film/news/fifty-shades-of-grey-el-james-new-movie-book-mister-1203513863/</ref><ref>https://deadline.com/2020/02/fifty-shades-of-grey-the-mister-author-e-l-james-universal-1202868038/</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nEnglish aristocrat Maxim Trevethick inherits his brother's titles and estate. He keeps on having fall offs with his sister-in-law Caroline who was his lover and had chosen his brother, Kit instead of him. He falls for his [[Albanian people|Albanian]] undocumented immigrant housemaid, Alessia Demachi. He finds out about her many talents and her past life. He takes her to his place in Cornwall when two unauthorised people came to his apartment searching whereabouts of Alessia. He introduces Alessia to sexual pleasure and enjoys her company. She has no idea of Maxim's title but gets to know and decides to run away. Maxim stops her and reveals his affections for her and they reconcile. Alessia reveals of her abusive betrothed who kidnaps her when they are in England. Alarmed, Maxim confronts Caroline and goes after Alessia to Albania. Due to the absence of her documents and passport, she travels with her fianc\u00e9e through another route. Maxim reaches her home and asks for her hand in marriage and Alessia enters soon after where she reveals about her fianc\u00e9e to her father and tries to get Maxim to be married to her. The novel ends with Alessia's father threatening Maxim to marry his daughter and them being together.\n\n==Reception==\n''The Mister'' was panned by literary critics, with review aggregator [[Book Marks]] reporting three negative and one mixed reviews among 6 total.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-mister/|title=Book Marks reviews of The Mister by E. L. James|publisher=Book Marks|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' described it as \"A coked-up lord bonks a trafficked Albanian immigrant as the ''Fifty Shades of Grey'' author swaps BDSM for dispiritingly creepy power games\" and adding that \"There is a complete dearth of emotional maturity that is genuinely unsettling.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/apr/17/el-james-the-mister-fifty-shades-of-grey-sex-romance-immigrant|title=EL James's The Mister \u2013 turns out books and sex can be this bad|first=Sian|last=Cain|date=17 April 2019|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> [[Jezebel (website)|Jezebel]] wrote \"the narrative is so committed to sexualizing Aleissa\u2019s vulnerability and powerlessness that the result is offensive.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jezebel.com/e-l-jamess-the-mister-fucks-a-duck-1834456299|title=E.L. James's The Mister Fucks a Duck|first=Kelly|last=Faircloth|website=Jezebel}}</ref> ''[[The Atlantic]]'' said it was \"hopelessly retrograde and dismally unentertaining.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/04/e-l-james-the-mister-review/587515/|title=The Indelible Awfulness of E. L. James's 'The Mister'|first=Sophie|last=Gilbert|date=18 April 2019|website=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n\nIt featured on the podcast series ''[[372 Pages We'll Never Get Back]]'', which mocks literature of low quality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://372pages.com/episode-41-handsome-buttocks|title=Episode 41 \u2013 Handsome Buttocks \u2013 372 Pages We'll Never Get Back}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.eljamesauthor.com/books/the-mister/ Official site]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mister, The}}\n[[Category:2019 British novels]]\n[[Category:Vintage Books books]]\n[[Category:British romance novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 novel by E. L. James}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name             = The Mister\n| image            = The Mister.jpg\n| author           = [[E. L. James]]\n| illustrator      = \n| cover_artist     =  \n| country          = United Kingdom\n| pages            = 512\n| language         = English\n| media_type     = Print: paperback\n| series           =  \n| published        = 16 April 2019, [[Vintage Books]]\n| preceded_by      =  \n| isbn             = 978-1984898326\n|genre=[[Romantic fiction|romance]]\n| followed_by      =\n|set_in= [[London]], [[Cornwall]] and [[Albania]], 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eljamesauthor.com/books/the-mister/|title=The Mister|website=www.eljamesauthor.com}}</ref> \n| audio_read_by     =  Dominic Thorburn, Jessica O'Hara-Baker<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Mister/dp/B07N317VDS/ref=tmm_aud_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=|title=The Mister|publisher=|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n| dewey             = \t823.92\n| congress          = \n| website           = {{URL|https://www.eljamesauthor.com/books/the-mister/}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Mister''''' is a 2019 [[Romantic fiction|romance]] novel by [[E. L. James]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cccadvocate.com/10860/scene/the-mister-fails-to-address-human-trafficking/|title=\u201cThe Mister\u201d fails to address human trafficking|first=Cindy|last=Pantoja|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.virginmediatelevision.ie/xpose/article/lifestyle/288349/Fifty-Shades-Of-Grey-author-EL-James-has-a-new-book-out--our-verdict-on-The-Mister|title=Fifty Shades Of Grey author E.L James has a new book out - our verdict on The Mister - Lifestyle from Xpos\u00e9 - Virgin Media Television|website=Virgin Media Television - Xpos\u00e9 Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-gb/the-mister-e-l-james-review|title=The Most Frustratingly Unsexy Things About 'The Mister' \u2013 The Follow Up To 'Fifty Shades'|first=Jazmin|last=Kopotsha|website=www.refinery29.com}}</ref><ref>https://variety.com/2020/film/news/fifty-shades-of-grey-el-james-new-movie-book-mister-1203513863/</ref><ref>https://deadline.com/2020/02/fifty-shades-of-grey-the-mister-author-e-l-james-universal-1202868038/</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nEnglish aristocrat Maxim Trevethick inherits his brother's titles and estate. He keeps on having fall offs with his sister-in-law Caroline who was his lover and had chosen his brother, Kit instead of him. He falls for his [[Albanian people|Albanian]] undocumented immigrant housemaid, Alessia Demachi. He finds out about her many talents and her past life. He takes her to his place in Cornwall when two unauthorised people came to his apartment searching whereabouts of Alessia. He introduces Alessia to sexual pleasure and enjoys her company. She has no idea of Maxim's title but gets to know and decides to run away. Maxim stops her and reveals his affections for her and they reconcile. Alessia reveals of her abusive betrothed who kidnaps her when they are in England. Alarmed, Maxim confronts Caroline and goes after Alessia to Albania. Due to the absence of her documents and passport, she travels with her fiancee through another route. Maxim reaches her home and asks for her hand in marriage and Alessia enters soon after where she reveals about her fiancee to her father and tries to get Maxim to be married to her. The novel ends with Alessia's father threatening Maxim to marry his daughter and them being together.\n\n==Reception==\n''The Mister'' was panned by literary critics, with review aggregator [[Book Marks]] reporting three negative and one mixed reviews among 6 total.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-mister/|title=Book Marks reviews of The Mister by E. L. James|publisher=Book Marks|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' described it as \"A coked-up lord bonks a trafficked Albanian immigrant as the ''Fifty Shades of Grey'' author swaps BDSM for dispiritingly creepy power games\" and adding that \"There is a complete dearth of emotional maturity that is genuinely unsettling.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/apr/17/el-james-the-mister-fifty-shades-of-grey-sex-romance-immigrant|title=EL James's The Mister \u2013 turns out books and sex can be this bad|first=Sian|last=Cain|date=17 April 2019|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> [[Jezebel (website)|Jezebel]] wrote \"the narrative is so committed to sexualizing Aleissa\u2019s vulnerability and powerlessness that the result is offensive.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jezebel.com/e-l-jamess-the-mister-fucks-a-duck-1834456299|title=E.L. James's The Mister Fucks a Duck|first=Kelly|last=Faircloth|website=Jezebel}}</ref> ''[[The Atlantic]]'' said it was \"hopelessly retrograde and dismally unentertaining.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/04/e-l-james-the-mister-review/587515/|title=The Indelible Awfulness of E. L. James's 'The Mister'|first=Sophie|last=Gilbert|date=18 April 2019|website=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n\nIt featured on the podcast series ''[[372 Pages We'll Never Get Back]]'', which mocks literature of low quality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://372pages.com/episode-41-handsome-buttocks|title=Episode 41 \u2013 Handsome Buttocks \u2013 372 Pages We'll Never Get Back}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.eljamesauthor.com/books/the-mister/ Official site]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mister, The}}\n[[Category:2019 British novels]]\n[[Category:Vintage Books books]]\n[[Category:British romance novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in London]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: fiancee \u2192 fianc\u00e9e (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Mister"}
