aro Cathedral| publisher =The News Today: Online Edition | date = [[1 February]] [[2008]] | url =https://www.thenewstoday.info/2008/02/01/jaro.cathedral.html\n  | accessdate = 2020-04-09 }}</ref>\n}}\n|\n*Katipunan\n*First Philippine Republic\n*\"Estados Federal de Bisayas\" (Federal States of Visayas)\n|Jaro,Iloilo\n|-\n|[[Payat Lucino]]<ref>{{Harvnb| Halili|2004|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=gUt5v8ET4QYC&pg=PA144 144]}}</ref>\n|\n|data-sort-value=\"1\"|\n*Katipunan General\n|Magdiwang-Katipunan\n|?\n|-\n|[[Mateo Luga]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Neutral\n|Cebu\n|-\n|[[Vicente Lukb\u00e1n]][[File:General Vicente Lukban.tif|thumb|General Vicente Lukban]]\n|\n|data-sort-value=\"1\"|\n*Member of the Hong Kong Junta (Emilio Aguinaldo's Exile Government in Hong Kong) along with brother, Justo Lukban (1897)\n*Brigadier-General-Philippine Revolutionary Army (1898-1901)<ref>{{Harvnb| Halili|2004|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=gUt5v8ET4QYC&pg=PA181 181]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lukban.org/vicente-lukban.php |title=VICENTE R. LUKBAN |last=Zampaga |first=Dr. Sarah Lukban|website=LUKBAN (Family Heritage) \n|publisher=Lukban Family Heritage |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n*Comandante Militar -Civil Governor - Bicol Region, Leyte (took over after General Ambrosio Mojica's surrender in May 18, 1901 and Samar (1898-1901)\n*Lieutenant General-Comandante Militar -Visayas and Mindanao (1901)\n*Tayabas Province - Governor (1913-1916)\n|\n*Pro-Emilio Aguinaldo- Staff member of Aguinaldo's Government\n*First Philippine Republic\n\n|[[Lobo,Camarines]]\n|-\n|[[Antonio Luna]] \n|\n|{{sort|4|[[Captain General]] (Director of War, Malolos Republic)<ref>{{Harvnb|Nakpil|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=fV0Ro1qPjXAC&pg=PA140 140]}}</ref>}}\n|Neutral\n|Manila (Ilocos Norte)\n|-\n|[[Elias Magbanua]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Neutral\n|Iloilo\n|-\n|[[Pascual Magbanua]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Neutral\n|Iloilo\n|-\n|[[Teresa Magbanua]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Bernard A. Cook|title=Women and War: A Historical Encyclopedia from Antiquity to the Present|year=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lyZYS_GxglIC|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-770-8|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=lyZYS_GxglIC&pg=PA465&dq=general 465]}}</ref>\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}} (disputed)\n|Neutral\n|Iloilo\n|-\n|[[Francisco Macabulos]]\n|\n|{{sort|2|Major General- also noted as Francisco Makabulos, Francisco Soliman}}\n|Pro-Emilio Aguinaldo, First Philippine Republic, Provisional Government of Central Luzon<ref name=\"RicarteCommission1963\">{{cite book|author1=Artemio Ricarte|author2=National Heroes Commission|title=Memoirs: With a Pref. by Alejandro R. Roces and an Introd. by Armando J. Malay. Selected and Edited from Mss. in the Watson Collection|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ozK7xgEACAAJ|year=1963|publisher=National Heroes Commission}}</ref>\n|Tarlac\n|-\n|[[Luis Malinis]][[File:General Luis Malinis.tif|thumb|One of the early Katipunero general who fought in Manila]]\n|\n|{{sort|2|Brigadier General<ref>{{cite news|url=http://balita.ph/2011/11/30/metro-news-novaliches-folks-honor-bonifacio-on-his-148th-birth-anniversary|title=(Metro News) Novaliches folks honor Bonifacio on his 148th birth anniversary|newspaper=Balita|date=November 30, 2011}}</ref>}}\n|Magdiwang\n|Polo (present-Valenzuela City)\n|-\n|[[Miguel Malvar]] \n|\n|{{sort|2|Major General<ref>{{Harvnb| Halili|2004|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=gUt5v8ET4QYC&pg=PA151 151]}} (confirms General Officer status, but not specific grade).</ref>}}\n|\n*Magdiwang\n*President of the Tagalog Republic after Emilio Aguinaldo's capture\n*Commanding General of Batangas Province\n|\n*Military campaigns in Manila, Laguna, Batangas and Quezon provinces with the First Philippine Republic\n|-\n|[[Roman Manalang]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Morey |first=Michael |date=February 5, 2019 |title=Fagen: An African American Renegade in the Philippine-Ameri