adier General<ref>{{cite book|last=Dept|first=United States. War|title=Annual Reports of the Secretary of War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cAoSAAAAYAAJ|year=1904|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=cAoSAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA41&dq=%22Luciano+San+Miguel%22 41]}}</ref>\n*Commander of the rebel lines in San Francisco de Malabon\n*\u201cCaptain-General\u201d and Supreme commander of the remaining revolutionary forces (1902)\n|Katipunan-Magdiwang, \n|\n*Noveleta, Cavite\n*March 27, 1903 - Killed in action during the Battle of Corral-na-Bato in Morong (now Rizal)\n|-\n|[[Sinforoso San Pedro]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Pro-Andr\u00e9s Bonifacio\n|Manila\n|-\n|[[Pedro Sason]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|General \"Consejero\" -War Counselor<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.geni.com/projects/Members-of-the-Revolutionary-Katipunan/10821\n |title= Members of the Revolutionary Katipunan |access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>}}\n|Katipunan\n|Bulacan\n|-\n|[[Gavino Sepulveda]]\n||\n|{{sort|1|General- also noted as Gabino Sepulveda<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2017/06/02/visayan-revolutionary-forces-during-our-wars-of-independence-2/|title=Visayan revolutionary forces during our wars of independence \n|author=Elinando B. Cinco|date=June 2, 2017|newspaper=Manila Bulletin|access-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>}}\n|First Philippine Republic, Federal State of the Visayas\n|Cebu, Bohol\n|-\n|[[Pablo Tecson]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Pro-Emilio Aguinaldo\n|Bulacan\n|-\n|[[Trinidad Tecson]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Pro-Emilio Aguinaldo\n|Bulacan\n|-\n|[[Manuel Tinio]][[File:General Manuel Tinio.tif|thumb|General Manuel Tinio-leader of the Northern brigade that operated in the Ilocos region against American forces]]\n|\n|data-sort-value=\"1\"|\n*Brigadier General<ref>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-5WOrmt_VxcC&pg=PA182 182]}}</ref>\n*Commander of \"The Tinio Brigade\"\n|\n*Katipunan\n*Pro-Emilio Aguinaldo\n*First Philippine Republic\n|\n*Nueva Ecija\n*Campaigns in Ilocos Norte Region\n|-\n|[[Candido Tirona]]\n|\n|{{sort|2|Major General}}\n|Magdalo\n|Cavite\n|-\n|[[Daniel Tirona]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Magdalo\n|Cavite\n|-\n|[[Lazaro Toledo]]\n|\n|data-sort-value=\"1\"|\n*Post-'''Brigandage Act of 1902''' Brigadier General - took over after General Simeon Ola's surrender (September 25, 1903)\n*Colonel under General Simeon Ola's guerrilla brigade \n*Officer under General Vito Belarmino's Command in the Bicol Region\n|Pro-Emilio Aguinaldo\n|?\n|-\n|[[Glicerio Topacio]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Magdalo\n|Cavite\n|-\n|[[Isidro Torres]]\n|\n|data-sort-value=\"1\"|\n*Also noted as \"Isidoro\"\n*\"Matang Lawin\" - Katipunan code name and nom de guerre\n*Brigadier General\n|\n*First Philippine Republic\n*Philippine Revolutionary Government\n*[[Republic of Kakarong Sili]]\n*Katipunan-Magdiwang\n|Bulacan\n|-\n|[[Mariano Tr\u00edas]]\n|\n|{{sort|3|Lieutenant General<ref>{{Harvnb| Halili|2004|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=gUt5v8ET4QYC&pg=PA162 162]}} (confirms General Officer status, but not specific grade).</ref>}}\n|Magdiwang to Magdalo\n|Cavite\n|-\n|[[P\u00edo Valenzuela]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Pro-Andr\u00e9s Bonifacio\n|Bulacan\n|-\n|[[Pantale\u00f3n Valmonte]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General-also noted as Pantale\u00f3n Belmonte}}\n|Neutral\n|[[Nueva Ecija]]\n|-\n|[[Miguel Valmoria]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Neutral\n|[[Bohol]]\n|-\n|[[Pantaleon Villegas]][[File:General Pantaleon Villegas.tif|thumb|General Pantaleon Villegas- celebrated hero of the Revolutionary movement in the Visayas]]\n|\n|data-sort-value=\"1\"|\n*Brigadier General\n* His nom de guerre was \"Leon Kilat\" (Lightning Lion)\n*Assassinated on Good Friday, April 8, 1898, in Carcar, Cebu by his own aide-de-camp, Apolinario Alcuitas\n|\n*Katipunan\n*First Philippine Republic\n|\n*Bacong, Negros Oriental\n*Cebu\n|-\n|[[Saturnino Echavez Teves]]\n|\n|{{sort|3|General}}\n|\n*First Philippine Republic\n*Federal State of the Visayas\n|Dumaguete, Negros Oriental, Cebu\n|-\n|[[Emilio Verdeflor]][[File:General Emilip Verdeflor.tif|thumb|General Emilio Verdeflor- one of the most effective guerrilla commander in Cebu]]\n|\n|data-sort-value=\"3\"|\n*Brigadier General<ref name=\"Dept1900\">{{cite book|author=United States. War Dept|title=Annual Reports of the War Department|url=https://archive.org/details/annualreportswa82deptgoog|year=1900|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|pages=[https://archive.org/details/annualreportswa82deptgoog/page/n39 23]\u2013}}</ref>\n*Colonel under General Arcadio Maxilom\n*Katipunan Lieutenant\n|\n*Katipunan in Cebu\n*Revolutionary Republic of Cebu\n*First Philippine Republic\n\n|Insurgent campaigns in Cebu- Tuburan and Balamban\n|-\n|[[Flaviano Yengko]]\n|\n|{{sort|1|Brigadier General}}\n|Magdalo\n|Manila\n|}\n\n==Table Legend==\n\n#{{Note|a}}'''''Grade''''' here refers to military, organizational, or leadership rank with regards to the [[Katipunan]] movement, governments of [[First Philippine Republic]], and regional Federated states and provincial republics. Second, it also includes guerrilla-structured Post-Republic campaign during the [[Philippine-American War]] that includes \"de facto\" leadership, guerrilla leadership, \"cacique\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Shaw |first1=Angel Velasco |last2=Francia |first2=Luis |date=2002 |title=Vestiges of War: the Philippine-American War and the Aftermath of an Imperial Dream 1899-1999 |publisher=New York University Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/vestigesofwarphi0000unse/page/8 8] |isbn=0814797911 |url=https://archive.org/details/vestigesofwarphi0000unse/page/8 }}</ref> or chieftain leadership. Third,  leaders who are categorized as part of \"''bandolerisimo''\" leadership after '''''Brigandage Act of Nov. 12, 1902''''' (American-influenced Philippine legislature changed status of all Philippine Revolutionary Republican soldiers from enemy insurgent to \"''ladrones''\", \"''bandoleros''\" or \"''tulisanes''\" (bandits and outlaws), effectively criminalizing all resistance activities or revolts) are also described in this section. Fourth, Kolorum (Colorum)<ref>{{Harvnb| Alvarez|1992|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=F3q\u2013krDckHwC&pg=PA207 207]}}</ref> leaders and \"generals\" who heads religious and fanatic based rebel groups are also noted in this section.\n\n#{{Note|b}}'''''Affiliation''''' here refers to support of political fractions or individuals in the [[Katipunan]] movement, government of [[First Philippine Republic]], or guerrilla-structured Post-Republic campaign during the [[Philippine-American War]].\n\n#{{Note|c}}'''''Province''''' here refers to provinces or regions within the individual's areas of operational responsibilities.\n\n==Addendum==\nThe Philippine American War or \"Philippine Insurrection\" has two phases. First phase was the conventional military warfare \nbetween two organized armies: The US Forces and the First Philippine Republican Army. This was period was from February to November \n1899. The second phase started from November 1899 when the Revolutionary army was dissipated into \"guerrilla\" -style warfare. This was based on smaller organized units of soldiers and local civilian supporters. Leadership became arbitrary with succession of \"generals\" and \"commanders\" based on who was second in command from the hierarchy of the old republic or who has more supporters or people under one's command. The remnants of the First Philippine Republic continued the struggle for independence into local regional and provincial levels as late as 1915.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://history.state.gov/milestones/1899-1913/war |title=The Philippine-American War, 1899\u20131902 |publisher=Office of the Historian, Foreign Service Institute |website=United States Department of State |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n===Works cited in footnotes===\n* Almario, Virgilio (1998) *Rebolusyong Filipino, Intimas Memorias, memoirs of  Colonel Sityar, in Spanish, page 197,  translated to Tagalog by Almario\n* {{cite book|last= Alvarez|first=Santiago V.|title=The katipunan and the revolution: memoirs of a general : with the original Tagalog text|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F3q-krDckHwC|year=1992|publisher=Ateneo de Manila University Press|isbn=978-971-550-077-7|ref=harv}}<!--note: also mentions \n\na General Mariano Alvarez (Apoy) on p.43, \na Lieutenant General Artemio Ricarte (Vibora) on p. 80, \na General Emilio Aguinaldo (Magdalo) on p.132, \na General Ramon Bernardo (Salogo) on p.145 & 163, \na General Luis Malinis on p.147,157 \na General Lucino de la Cruz (Ipo-Ipo) on p.150,\na General Francisco de Asis (Labe, Heneral Kiko) on p.152-153, 155-156, & 164-169\na General Vincente Leyba (Kalentong) on p.159 \na General Felipe Estrella on p. 182-189\na General Eusebio Roque  (Maestrong Sebio,Dimabunggo) on p. 182-189\na General Julian Santos on p. 195\na General Salvador Estrella on p. 197\na General Modesto Ritual on p.201-202 \na Information about \"Kolorum\" (Colorum) and religious-insurrection movements on p. 207\n-->\n\n* {{cite book|last= Halili|first=M.c.|title=Philippine history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gUt5v8ET4QYC|year=2004|publisher=Rex Bookstore, Inc.|isbn=978-971-23-3934-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last= Linn|first=Brian McAllister|authorlink=Brian McAllister Linn|title=The U.S. Army and Counterinsurgency in the Philippine War, 1899-1902|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-5WOrmt_VxcC|year=2000|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=978-0-8078-4948-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Nakpil|first=Carmen Guerrero |title=Whatever: a new collection of later essays, 1987-2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fV0Ro1qPjXAC|year=2002|publisher=Ateneo de Manila University Press|isbn=978-971-550-417-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news |url=http://opinion.inquirer.net/98377/king-of-the-philippines |title=King of the Phi